<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="[1], A-text">
<HEAD>[Prologus.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Prologus; <I>not in any of the</I> MSS.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN A somer sesun &middot; whon softe was &thorn;e sonne,<MILESTONE N="394b:2" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>whon softe was &thorn;e sonne</I>] as y south wente U.</NOTE></L>
<L>I schop me in-to a schroud &middot; A scheep as I were;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>into</I>] vndur H; in U; to D. <I>A scheep, &amp;c</I>.] as I a shep were TH UH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Habite of an Hermite &middot; vn-holy of werkes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] as TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">Wende I wydene in &thorn;is world &middot; wondres to here.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wende I wydene</I>] Wente wyde TH<SUB>2</SUB>D; I wente wide UH.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote in a Mayes Morwnynge &middot; on Maluerne hulles</L>
<L>Me bi-fel a ferly &middot; A Feyrie me &thorn;ouhte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A Feyrie</I>] of fairie THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>I was weori of wandringe &middot; and wente me to reste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of wandring and</I>] of-wandrit &amp; T; forwandred H<SUB>2</SUB>, forwandryd y U; for wandryng &amp; D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">Vndur a brod banke &middot; bi a Bourne syde,</L>
<L>And as I lay and leonede &middot; and lokede on &thorn;e watres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leonede</I>] lened me U.</NOTE></L>
<L>I slumberde in A slepyng &middot; hit sownede so murie.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sownede</I>] swi&yogh;ede T; swyed H<SUB>2</SUB>; schewed D. <I>hit sownede</I>] I swe|uenyd U.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;enne gon I Meeten &middot; A Meruelous sweuene,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at I was in A Wildernesse &middot; wuste I neuer where,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wuste I</I>] y wyste UH.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as I beo-heold in-to &thorn;e Est &middot; an-hei&yogh; to &thorn;e sonne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] Ac TD; H <I>omits;</I> But U. <I>an hei&yogh;</I>] up U.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sauh a Tour on A Toft &middot; [tri&yogh;ely] I-maket;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>tri&yogh;ely</I> T; triely U; tryelyche H<SUB>2</SUB>] wonderliche VH; trewliche D. <I>imaket</I>] a-tired U.</NOTE></L>
<L>A Deop Dale bi-neo&thorn;e &middot; A dungun &thorn;er-Inne,</L>
<L N="16">With deop dich and derk &middot; and dredful of siht.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dich</I>] dikes T; diches UH<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>and dredful, &amp;c</I>.] &thorn;at dredeful was of syghte H.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="2, A-text"></L>
<L>&para; A Feir feld ful of folk &middot; fond I &thorn;er bi-twene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fond I</I>] I fonde H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of alle maner of men &middot; &thorn;e mene and &thorn;e riche,</L>
<L>Worchinge and wondringe &middot; as &thorn;e world aske&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H. <I>omits</I> this line. <I>wondringe</I>] wandringe TUDH<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>as</I>] so D.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="20">Summe putten hem to &thorn;e plou&yogh; &middot; and pleiden hem ful seldene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and pleiden hem</I>] plei&yogh;ede TUD. <I>hem ful</I>] but H.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Eringe and in Sowynge &middot; swonken ful harde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eringe</I>] settyng TH<SUB>2</SUB>D; seed tyme U. <I>harde</I>] sore HH<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at monie of &thorn;eos wasturs &middot; In Glotonye distruen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at monie of</I>] whom that T; And wonnen &thorn;at U; whanne &thorn;at D. <I>In</I>] wi&thorn; TUDH<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And summe putten hem to pruide &middot; apparaylden hem &thorn;er-after,</L>
<L N="24">In Cuntinaunce of clo&thorn;inge &middot; queinteliche de-Gyset;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cuntinaunce</I>] quoyntyse H. <I>queinteliche degyset</I>] comen disgisid TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D; &thorn;ei conen hem disgyse H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To preyere and to penaunce &middot; putten heom monye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To</I>] In THD. <I>preyere</I>] preyers HTUD. <I>to</I>] HD <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For loue of vr lord &middot; liueden ful harde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ful harde</I>] wel streite TD; ful strayte HUH<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Hope for to haue &middot; Heuene-riche blisse;</L>
<L N="28">As Ancres and Hermytes &middot; &thorn;at holde&thorn; hem in heore Celles,</L>
<L>Coueyte not in Cuntre &middot; to carien a-boute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>carien</I>] cairen T; cayren H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For non likerous lyflode &middot; heore licam to plese.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>non</I>] no THU. <I>licam</I>] lykames U; lyke hem (!) D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And summe chosen Chaffare &middot; to cheeuen &thorn;e bettre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Chaffare</I>] to chaffare TUD. <I>to cheeuen</I>] &thorn;ei cheuide TU; to preue H; &thorn;ey cheuen D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">As hit seme&thorn; to vre siht &middot; &thorn;at suche men scholden;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hit seme&thorn; to</I>] es seen in U. <I>suche men</I>] &thorn;ei so H. <I>scholden</I>] &thorn;riuen TH<SUB>2</SUB>U; &thorn;ryueth D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And summe Mur&thorn;hes to maken &middot; as Munstrals cunne,</L>
<L>[And gete gold wi&thorn; here gle &middot; giltles, I trowe.]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> T: <I>also in</I> HUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>giltles</I>] synles HUD; synfullyche H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Bote Iapers and Iangelers &middot; Iudas Children,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Iudas</I>] Iudases U.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">Founden hem Fantasyes &middot; and fooles hem maaden,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Founden</I>] &thorn;a faynen H; Gon fynden U; fynden H<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>maaden</I>] maken HUTD.</NOTE></L>
<L>And habbe&thorn; wit at heor wille &middot; to worchen &yogh;if hem luste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;if hem luste</I>] &yogh;if &thorn;ei wolde H; what hem liketh U.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="3, A-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Poul preche&thorn; of hem &middot; I dar not preouen heere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dar</I>] wol U. <I>preouen</I>] proue it TH<SUB>2</SUB>; sey H; proue yt D.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Qui loquitur turpiloquium</I> &middot; Hee is Luciferes hyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Qui, &amp;c</I>.] <I>Qui turpe loquitur</I> D. <I>Hee is</I>] is HUH<SUB>2</SUB>D; his T.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="40">Bidders and Beggers &middot; faste a-boute eoden,<MILESTONE N="395a:1" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bidders and beggers</I>] beggeris and bydderes U. <I>eoden</I>] &yogh;ede TH<SUB>2</SUB>; &yogh;eden H; &yogh;edyn U.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til heor Bagges and heore Balies &middot; weren [bratful] I-crommet;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bagges&mdash;Balies</I>] bely &amp; here bagge TH<SUB>2</SUB>D; belyes and here bagges U. [<I>bratful</I> T; bretful H<SUB>2</SUB>; bredful UD] faste VH.</NOTE></L>
<L>Feyneden hem for heore foode &middot; fou&yogh;ten atte alle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Feyneden hem</I>] Flite &thorn;anne T; &thorn;ei fliten U; Fayteden H; Faytours H<SUB>2</SUB>; Flytteden &amp; D. <I>atte alle</I>] at &thorn;e ale TD; at &thorn;e nale UH; at nale H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Glotonye, God wot &middot; gon heo to Bedde,</L>
<L N="44">And ryseth vp wi&thorn; ribaudye &middot; &thorn;is Roberdes knaues;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>] as TUD; tho H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sleep and Sleu&yogh;&thorn;e &middot; suwe&thorn; hem euere.</L>
<L>&para; Pilgrimes and Palmers &middot; Plihten hem to-gederes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Plihten</I>] pyghten H.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to seche seint Ieme &middot; and seintes at Roome;</L>
<L N="48">Wenten for&thorn; in heore wey &middot; with mony wyse tales,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyse</I>] vayn H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hedden leue to ly&yogh;en &middot; al heore lyf [aftir].<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>aftir</I> THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D] tyme V.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Ermytes on an hep &middot; wi&thorn; hokide staues,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> T; <I>also in</I> UH<SUB>2</SUB>D; <I>not in</I> VH.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wenten to Walsyngham &middot; &amp; here wenchis aftir;]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> T; <I>also in</I> UH<SUB>2</SUB>D; <I>not in</I> VH.</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">&para; Grete lobres and longe &middot; &thorn;at lo&thorn; weore to swynke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lobres</I>] lobies TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D; loburs H. <I>&thorn;at lo&thorn; weore</I>] loth for U.</NOTE></L>
<L>Clo&thorn;eden hem in Copes &middot; to beo knowen for bre&thorn;eren;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for bre&thorn;eren</I>] from o&thorn;ere TU H<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And summe schopen [hem] to hermytes &middot; heore ese to haue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>om. the whole line</I> U. <I>And summe</I>] TH<SUB>2</SUB>D <I>om.;</I> summe H. [<I>hem</I> THD.] V <I>omits</I>.</P><P>OBS. <I>After l</I>. 54 <I>the two following lines occur, in</I> H<SUB>2</SUB> <I>only;</I></P><P>Who-so &yogh;eueth for godes loue &middot; wyl nat &yogh;eue his &thorn;ankis</P><P>But &thorn;ere his mede may be most &middot; and most merytorye.</P></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I Font &thorn;ere Freres &middot; all &thorn;e Foure Ordres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Font</I>] fond TUH<SUB>2</SUB>H; But I fonde D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="56">Prechinge &thorn;e peple &middot; for profyt of heore wombes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heore wombes</I>] &thorn;e wombe TH<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Glosynge &thorn;e Gospel &middot; as hem good like&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Glosynge</I>] gloside TUH<SUB>2</SUB>; gloseth D. <I>good</I>] silf H. <I>like&thorn;</I>] likide TUH<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="4, A-text"></L>
<L>For Couetyse of Copes &middot; Construe&thorn; hit ille;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ille</I>] ful yuel H; as &thorn;ei wolde TUH<SUB>2</SUB>; at wille D.</NOTE></L>
<L>For monye of &thorn;is Maistres &middot; mowen clo&thorn;en hem at lyking,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>clo&thorn;en&mdash;lyking</I>] be clothed the better H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">For Moneye and heore Marchaundie &middot; meeten ofte to-gedere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For moneye</I>] For here mony TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>oft</I>] THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D <I>omit</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e charite ha&thorn; be chapmon &middot; [and] cheef to schriuen lordes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>charite&mdash;chapmon</I>] freeris han ben chapmen H. [<I>and</I> THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D] V <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mony ferlyes han bi-falle &middot; in a fewe &yogh;eres.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bifalle</I>] fallen TUD; falle ry&yogh;t H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>But holychirche bi-ginne &middot; holde bet to-gedere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>biginne</I>] and &thorn;ei T; and he U H<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>holde&mdash;togedere</I>] &thorn;e better to holde togedre H; holde togidre U.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">&THORN;e moste Mischeef on molde &middot; mounte&thorn; vp faste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mounte&thorn;, &amp;c</I>.] is mountyng up faste T; is mowntynge vp wel faste H. H<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;er prechede a pardoner &middot; as he a prest were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as&mdash;were</I>] a prest as he were U; a prest as it were H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t vp a Bulle &middot; with Bisschopes seles,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vp</I>] forth THUH<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at him-self mihte &middot; a-soylen hem alle</L>
<L N="68">Of Falsnesse and Fastinge &middot; and of vouwes I-broken.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lewede Men likede him wel &middot; and leeue&thorn; his speche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>likede</I>] leuide T; leued HD; lyueden U. <I>him</I>] DH <I>om. wel</I>] U <I>om. leeue&thorn;</I>] likide TU; lykeden H; liked D; leued H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And comen vp knelynge &middot; and cusseden his Bulle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and cusseden</I>] to kissen TU H<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>He bonchede hem with his Breuet &middot; and blered heore ei&yogh;en,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bonchede</I>] bunchi&thorn; T; bunched H<SUB>2</SUB>; blessid UH; bonches D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">And rauhte with his Ragemon &middot; Ringes and Broches.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And rauhte</I>] Raughte hym U. <I>Ringes and broches</I>] broches and rynges UD.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;us &yogh;e &yogh;iue&thorn; oure gold &middot; Glotonye to helpen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;us&mdash;gold</I>] &thorn;us &thorn;ei &yogh;ouen here geld TD; &thorn;us &yogh;e &yogh;yuen &yogh;oure goodus H. <I>Glotonye</I>] glotonis THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>And leue&thorn; hit to losels &middot; &thorn;at lecherie haunten.</L>
<L>Weore &thorn;e Bisschop I-blesset &middot; and wor&thorn; bo&thorn;e his Eres,</L>
<L>Heo scholde not beo so hardi &middot; to deceyue so &thorn;e peple.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Heo&mdash;hardi</I>] His sel shulde not be sent TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>to deceyue so</I>] to bigyle so H; TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D <I>omit</I> so.</NOTE></L>
<L>Saue hit nis not bi &thorn;e Bisschop &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e Boye preche&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Saue&mdash;bi</I>] It is not al be TH; y trowe it is noght for U; It is nou&yogh;t be H<SUB>2</SUB>; He is nou&yogh;t al by D. <I>&thorn;e Boye</I>] &thorn;ey bo&thorn;e D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="5, A-text"></L>
<L N="78">Bote &thorn;e Parisch prest and he de-parte &thorn;e seluer,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] &thorn;e pardoner THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>departe</I>] parte THU; departid H<SUB>2</SUB>; parteth D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at haue schulde &thorn;e pore parisschens &middot; &yogh;if &thorn;at heo ne weore.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>haue&mdash;parisschens</I>] &thorn;e pore peple of &thorn;e parissh shulde haue TH<SUB>2</SUB>D; &thorn;e poore of &thorn;e parysche schuld haue H; &thorn;e pore peple schuld haue U.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">&para; Persones and parisch prestes &middot; playne&thorn; to heore Bis|schops,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>parisch prestes</I>] prouenders H. <I>playne&thorn;</I>] playned H; pleynide hem TD; playnen hem U. <I>Bisschops</I>] bisshop TU.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at heore Parisch ha&thorn; ben pore &middot; se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e Pestilence [tyme],<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Parisch</I>] parischens HU. <I>ha&thorn; ben</I>] was T; ben U; were H<SUB>2</SUB>D. [<I>tyme</I> THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D] V <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And aske&thorn; leue and lycence &middot; at londun to dwelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And&mdash;lycence</I>] To haue a licence &amp; leue TUH<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>aske&thorn;</I>] han H. D <I>omits this line</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To singe &thorn;er for Simonye &middot; for seluer is swete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="84">&THORN;Er houe&thorn; an Hundret &middot; In Houues of selk,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>houe&thorn;</I>] houide THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seriauns hit seme&thorn; &middot; to seruen atte Barre;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hit seme&thorn;</I>] it semide THH<SUB>2</SUB>; &thorn;ei semeden U; it semedyn D. <I>to seruen atte</I>] &thorn;at seruide at &thorn;e T; pletiden at &thorn;e U.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pleden for pons &middot; and poundes &thorn;e lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pleden&mdash;poundes</I>] Pleten for penis &amp; poynte&thorn; T; For penyes &amp; for powndis pladden H; &thorn;ei pletide for pens and poundide U; plededen for pens &amp; poundes D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Not for loue of vr lord &middot; vn-lose&thorn; heore lippes ones.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vnlose&thorn;&mdash;ones</I>] openyd his lippes U; not open her lyppus oonus H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ow mihtest beter meten &thorn;e Myst &middot; on Maluerne hulles,</L>
<L N="89">&THORN;en geten a Mom of heore Mou&thorn; &middot; til moneye weore schewed.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>weore</I>] be TH<SUB>2</SUB>UD.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I sauh &thorn;er Bisschops Bolde &middot; and Bachilers of diuyn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bisschops</I>] erchebisschopes U.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi-coome Clerkes of A-Counte &middot; &thorn;e kyng for to seruen;</L>
<L N="92">Erchedekenes and Deknes &middot; &thorn;at Dignite hauen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Erchedekenes</I>] I saw <I>&thorn;ere</I> erchedeknes U. <I>Deknes</I>] denis THUD; dekenes H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To preche &thorn;e peple &middot; and pore men to feede,</L>
<L>Beon lopen to londun &middot; bi leue of heore Bisschopes,</L>
<L>To ben Clerkes of &thorn;e kynges Benche &middot; &thorn;e Cuntre to schende.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="6, A-text"></L>
<L N="96">&para; Barouns and Burgeis &middot; and Bonde-men also<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and Burgeis</I>] TU <I>omit</I> and. <I>Bondemen</I>] bondage TH<SUB>2</SUB>; bondeage D; bondages U.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sau&yogh; in &thorn;at Semble &middot; as &yogh;e schul heren her-aftur.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>semble</I>] semele T. <I>heren her|aftur</I>] heer aftir TU; seen aftur H; here after D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Bakers, Bochers &middot; and Breusters monye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bakers</I>] Baxteris &amp; T; bakeris and HH<SUB>2</SUB>U; Baksteres &amp; D.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Wollene websteris &middot; and weueris of lynen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> T; <I>also in</I> UH<SUB>2</SUB>D. [<I>tanneris &amp; tokkeris</I>] toucheris and tolleris U; towkers and tollers H<SUB>2</SUB>; &amp; souters and tokkeres D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">Taillours, tanneris &middot; &amp; tokkeris bo&thorn;e,]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> T; <I>also in</I> UH<SUB>2</SUB>D. [<I>tanneris &amp; tokkeris</I>] toucheris and tolleris U; towkers and tollers H<SUB>2</SUB>; &amp; souters and tokkeres D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Masons, Minours &middot; and mony o&thorn;er craftes,</L>
<L>Dykers, and Deluers &middot; &thorn;at don heore dedes ille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heore dedes</I>] here dede T. here werk U. <I>ille</I>] yuol H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="103">And driue&thorn; for&thorn; &thorn;e longe day &middot; with "deu vous saue, dam Emme!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vous</I>] THU <I>om. with&mdash;saue</I>] dieu gard D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Cookes and heore knaues &middot; Cryen "hote pies, hote!</L>
<L>Goode gees and grys &middot; Gowe dyne, [Gowe]!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Gowe</I> THUH<SUB>2</SUB>; V <I>has</I> Gouwe]</NOTE></L>
<L>Tauerners to hem &middot; tolde &thorn;e same tale<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to hem</I>] tollid hem U. <I>Tolde&mdash;tale</I>] and tolde hem &thorn;e same U; tolde &thorn;e same TD; tolde hem the same H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; good wyn of Gaskoyne &middot; And wyn of Oseye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wi&thorn; wyn of osay &amp; wyn of gascoyne TH<SUB>2</SUB>D (<I>but D reads</I> Asay); wi&thorn; white wyn of oseye &middot; and gas|coyne U.</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">Of Ruyn a[n]d of Rochel &middot; &thorn;e Rost to defye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ruyn</I>] &thorn;e ryn THDUH<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>Rochel</I>] &thorn;e rochel THUH<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Al &thorn;is I sau&yogh; slepynge &middot; &amp; seue si&thorn;es more.]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> T. <I>Also in</I> UD <I>and</I> H<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

