<L>For &thorn;e same Mesure &thorn;at &yogh;e Meten &middot; A-mis o&thorn;er elles,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at &yogh;e meten</I>] &thorn;at &thorn;ou metest (<I>over erasure</I>) H; &yogh;e metyn here U. <I>Amis</I>] a-ri&yogh;t (<I>over erasure</I>) H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e schul be weyen &thorn;er-with &middot; whon &yogh;e wenden hennes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e wenden</I>] &thorn;at &yogh;e gon U.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;au&yogh; &yogh;e ben trewe of tonge &middot; and treweliche winne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For&mdash;&yogh;e</I>] For &thorn;i TH<SUB>2</SUB>; For &thorn;y D. <I>of</I>] of &yogh;oure TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="154">And eke as chast as a child &middot; &thorn;at in Chirche wepe&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as chast</I>] U <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &yogh;e liuen trewely &middot; and eke loue &thorn;e pore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>liuen trewely</I>] loue lelly T; loue lely UH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>eke loue</I>] lene (<I>or</I> leue) TU; &yogh;eue to loue H<SUB>2</SUB>; loue D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="156">And such good as God sent &middot; Treweliche parten,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] Of TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>sent</I>] ha&thorn; sent U. <I>Treweliche parten</I>] goodliche parteth UTH<SUB>2</SUB>; godliche parte D.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="15, A-text"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e naue no more merit &middot; In Masse ne In houres<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>naue</I>] ne haue TUH<SUB>2</SUB>; haue D. <I>Masse</I>] Matynes TUH<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>houres</I>] masse TH<SUB>2</SUB>; oures UD.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en Malkyn of hire Maydenhod &middot; &thorn;at no Mon desyre&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>desyre&thorn;</I>] desired U.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For Iames &thorn;e gentel &middot; bond hit in his Book,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bond hit</I>] ioynide TH<SUB>2</SUB>; Iug|gid U; hath wryten D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at [Fey] withouten [fait] &middot; Is febelore &thorn;en nou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Fey</I>] fei&thorn; THUH<SUB>2</SUB>; fay D. [<I>fait</I> TH<SUB>2</SUB>; <I>feet</I> D] werk U; warkis H. V <I>misreads</I>, &thorn;at Treu&thorn;e withouten Fey.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ded as a dore-nayl &middot; but &thorn;e deede folewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>ded</I>] as ded TH<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>but &thorn;e</I>] but &yogh;if &thorn;e THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</P><P>OBS. <I>After</I> folewe H <I>inserts the weak line</I>, &thorn;at is, to sokoure &thorn;e sorow|ful &middot; &amp; haue charite to alle.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>Chastite withouten Charite &middot; (wite &thorn;ou forso&thorn;e),<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wite&mdash;forso&thorn;e</I>] worth cheynide in helle TH<SUB>2</SUB>; wur&thorn; schryned in helle U; worth shewed in helle D. (<I>See</I> l. 168.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="163">Is as lewed as a Laumpe &middot; &thorn;at no liht is Inne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Is</I>] &thorn;at is U; Hit is DT.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Moni Chapeleyns ben chast &middot; but Charite is aweye;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Moni</I>] Now many U.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beo no men hardore &thorn;en &thorn;ei &middot; whon heo beo&thorn; avaunset;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Beo no men</I>] Arn none TUH<SUB>2</SUB>; &thorn;er beo&thorn; noon H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vn-kuynde to heore kun &middot; and to alle cristene;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Transposed in</I> H.</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and to</I>] and ek to TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Chewen heore charite &middot; and chiden after more!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Transposed in</I> H.</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Chewen</I>] &thorn;ei chewen H; Chiwen U.</NOTE></L>
<L N="168">Such [Chastite] withouten [Charite] &middot; wor&thorn; claymed in helle!<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Chastite</I>, &amp;c.] chastite with|oute charite THUH<SUB>2</SUB>D; V <I>absurdly transposes</I> chastite <I>and</I> charite; see l. 162. <I>claymed</I>] cheynid TH<SUB>2</SUB>; schryned U; shewed D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Curatours &thorn;at schulden kepe hem &middot; clene of heore bodies,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Curatours</I>] &yogh;e curatours TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>schulden&mdash;hem</I>] kepe &yogh;ow TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D; schulden &yogh;ou kepe H. <I>of heore</I>] of &yogh;our TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. H <I>has</I>, in &yogh;oure soules.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei beo&thorn; cumbred in care &middot; and cunnen not out-crepe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei&mdash;care</I>] &yogh;e ben acumbrid wi&thorn; couetise TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D. <I>&amp; cunnen</I>] &yogh;e mowe T; &yogh;e cunne UH<SUB>2</SUB>; &yogh;e can D; &thorn;ei con H.</NOTE></L>
<L>So harde heo beo&thorn; with Auarice &middot; I-haspet to-gedere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>harde&mdash;wi&thorn;</I>] faste ha&thorn; TH<SUB>2</SUB>D; harde ha&thorn; U. <I>I-haspet</I>] haspide &yogh;ow TUH<SUB>2</SUB>D.</NOTE></L>
<L N="172">&THORN;at nis no treu&thorn;e of Trinite &middot; but tricherie of helle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &thorn;e trewe tresoure of trou&thorn;e &middot; is almost for&yogh;ete H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And a leornyng for lewed men &middot; &thorn;e latere forte dele.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>latere forte</I>] lattere to THUH<SUB>2</SUB>; latter for to D.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;eos be&thorn; wordes I-writen &middot; In &thorn;e Ewangelye,
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="16, A-text"></L>
<L><I>Date et dabitur vobis</I> &middot; for I dele ow alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>After <I>vobis</I>, &yogh;eue&thorn; to myne of &yogh;oure goodus for I dele, &amp;c. H.</P><P>OBS. <I>The rest is not in</I> V.</P></NOTE></L>
<L N="176">[&YOGH;oure grace &amp; &yogh;oure good happe &middot; &yogh;oure wel&thorn;e for to wynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>These two lines are in</I> H <I>only</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; knowe&thorn; me kyndely &middot; of &thorn;at I &yogh;ou sende.]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>These two lines are in</I> H <I>only</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>[&THORN;at is &thorn;e lok of loue &middot; &thorn;at leti&thorn; out my grace<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leti&thorn;&mdash;my</I>] lyth in &yogh;oure H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To counforte &thorn;e carful &middot; Acumbrid wi&thorn; synne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">U <I>omits. wi&thorn;</I>] in H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">Loue is &thorn;e leueste &thorn;inge &middot; &thorn;at our lord aski&thorn;,</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;e grai&thorn; gate &middot; &thorn;at go&thorn; into heuene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>grai&thorn; gate</I>] redyest waye H; greytheste gate U.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I sei&yogh;e as I seide er &middot; be si&yogh;te of &thorn;ise tixtes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For-&thorn;i</I>] &thorn;erfore U. <I>seide er</I>] er seyde H; sayde here D.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan alle tresouris arn tri&yogh;ede &middot; treu&thorn;e is &thorn;e beste.</L>
<L N="184">Now haue I tolde &thorn;e what treu&thorn;e is &middot; &thorn;at no tresour is betere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] H <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>I may no lengere lenge &middot; now loke &thorn;e oure lord."]<NOTE PLACE="foot">178&mdash;185. <I>from</I> T; <I>with which</I> D <I>and</I> H<SUB>2</SUB> <I>very closely agree; also found in</I> H; <I>and</I> (<I>partly</I>) <I>in</I> U.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lenge</I>] lende H; duellen U; lengen D. <I>now</I>] but H; D <I>om. &thorn;e</I>] &thorn;ou loue H; by D.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

