<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000189.tif" N="137*">
<HEAD>PASSUS XII. SUPPLEMENT TO "PIERS PLOWMAN," PART I. TEXT A. [<I>MS. Rawl. Poet</I>. 137. <I>fol.</I> 40]<NOTE PLACE="foot">[NOTE. See the account at the end of the Passus, shewing whence this Twelfth Passus is derived.]</NOTE></HEAD>

<HEAD><I>Passus tercius de dowel</I>.<NOTE>Pass. XII. <I>Called</I> Passus tercius de dowel <I>in</I> MS. U and MS. Rawlinson 137. See the note to Pass. XI. l. 303, on p. 154.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Crist wot," quod clergie &middot; "knowe hit &yogh;if &thorn;e lyke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] ye U; <I>but the</I> y <I>represents</I> &thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>I haue do my deuer &middot; &thorn;e dowel to teche;</L>
<L>And who-so coueyte&thorn; don betere &middot; &thorn;an &thorn;e boke telle&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>coueyte&thorn; don</I>] coueite to don U.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">He passe&thorn; &thorn;e apostolis lyf &middot; and put him to aungelys!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] U <I>om. him</I>] hem U; <I>cor|ruptly</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>But I se now as I seye &middot; as me so&thorn; thinkyt&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e were lef to lerne &middot; but lo&thorn; for to stodie.<NOTE PLACE="foot">U <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou woldest konne &thorn;at I can &middot; and carpen hit after.</L>
<L N="8">Presumptuowsly, parauenture &middot; a-pose so manye,</L>
<L>That [hit] my&yogh;the turne men to tene &middot; &amp; theologie bo&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hit</I>] it U; MS. Rawlinson <I>omits. men</I>] me U.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if I wiste witterly &middot; &thorn;ou woldest don &thorn;er-after,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;ou askest &middot; a-soylen I wolde."</L>
<L N="12">Skornfully &thorn;o scripture &middot; [set vp here] browes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>] <I>miswritten</I> &thorn;e <I>in</I> MS. Raw|linson; U <I>has</I> yo = &thorn;o. [<I>set vp here</I>] <I>So in</I> U; MS. Rawlinson <I>has</I> sherte vp his, <I>where at least</I> his <I>is wrong</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And on clergie crie&thorn; &middot; on cristes holy name,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crie&thorn;</I>] cryede U. <I>cristes</I>] godis U.</NOTE></L>
<L>That he shewe me hit ne sholde &middot; but &yogh;if [hit] stryf were<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shewe me hit</I>] schewi&yogh;t U (<I>cor|ruptly</I>). [<I>hit</I>] it U; MS. Rawl. <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kynde cardinal wit &middot; and cristned in a font;&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kynde</I>] U <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="16">And seyde [hit] so loude &middot; &thorn;at shame me thou&yogh;the,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hit</I>] it U; MS. Rawl. <I>om. me</I>] me it U.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;at hit were bo&thorn;e ska&thorn;e &middot; and sklaundre to holy cherche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bo&thorn;e</I>] U <I>om</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="138*"></L>
<L>Sitthe theologie &thorn;e trewe &middot; to tellen hit defende&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sitthe</I>] Sciho&thorn; (<I>sic</I>) U. <I>&thorn;e trewe</I>] yat trewe is U. <I>to</I>] U <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dauid godes derling &middot; defendy&thorn; hit al-so:<Q><I>Vidi</I> [<I>preuaricantes</I>] <I>et tabescebam:</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>preuaricantes</I>] <I>So in</I> U; MS. Rawl. <I>corruptly has</I> preuaricationes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">I saw synful, he seyde &middot; &thorn;er-fore I seyde no-&thorn;ing,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. U <I>ends with</I> tabescebam; <I>and from this line to the end, we have only</I> MS. Rawl. <I>to trust to. seyde no|&thorn;ing</I>] It is clear that the poet con|strues <I>tabescebam</I> as if it were <I>tacebam</I>. The same idea recurs in ll. 23 and 29.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til &thorn;o wrecches ben in wil &middot; here synne to lete.</L>
<L>And poul preche&thorn; hit often &middot; prestes hit redyn,<Q><I>Audiui archane que non licet homini loqui:</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Audiui</I>, &amp;c. Quoted again in Text B. Pass. XVIII.</NOTE></L>
<L>I am not hardy, quod he &middot; &thorn;at I herde with erys,</L>
<L N="24">Telle hit with tounge &middot; to synful wrecches.</L>
<L>And god graunted hit neuere &middot; &thorn;e gospel hit witnesse&thorn;,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e passioun, whan pilat &middot; a-posed god al-my&yogh;thi,</L>
<L>And asked Ihesu on hy &middot; &thorn;at herden hit an hundred,<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="28"><I>Quid est ueritas?</I> quod he &middot; verilyche tel vs;</L>
<L>God gaf him non answere &middot; but gan his tounge holde.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so I rede," quod she &middot; "red &thorn;ou no fer&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he wolde wite &middot; wis him no betere.</L>
<L N="32">For he cam not by cause &middot; to lerne to dowel,</L>
<L>But as he sey&thorn;, such I am &middot; when he with me carpe&thorn;."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>such I am</I>] i. e. I am not to be commended; alluding to Pass. XI. l. 286.</NOTE></L>
<L>And when scripture &thorn;e skolde &middot; hadde &thorn;us wyt y-sheued,</L>
<L>Clergie in-to a caban &middot; crepte anon after,</L>
<L N="36">And drow &thorn;e dore after him &middot; and bad me go dowel,</L>
<L>Or wycke, &yogh;if I wolde &middot; whe&thorn;er me lyked!</L>
<L>&THORN;an held I vp myn handes &middot; to scripture &thorn;e wise,</L>
<L>To be hure man &yogh;if I most &middot; for euere-more after,</L>
<L N="40">With &thorn;at she wolde me wisse &middot; wher &thorn;e toun were,</L>
<L>Kynde wit hure confessour &middot; hure cosyn was Inne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wit</I>.] <I>The</I> MS. <I>has</I> wt, <I>the usual contraction for</I> with; <I>but see</I> ll. 43 <I>and</I> 53; <I>and</I> hit <I>for</I> hit, l. 25.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at lady &thorn;an low &middot; and lau&yogh;the me in here armes,</L>
<L>And sayde, "my cosyn kynde wit &middot; knowen is wel wide,</L>
<L N="44">And his loggyng is with lyf &middot; &thorn;at lord is of er&thorn;e.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou desyre &middot; with him for to a-byde,
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="139*"></L>
<L>I shal &thorn;e wisse &middot; where &thorn;at he dwelle&thorn;."</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne I kneled on my knes &middot; and kyste her wel sone,</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;anked hure a &thorn;ousand sy&thorn;es &middot; with &thorn;robbant herte.</L>
<L>She called [to ken] me &middot; a clerioun &thorn;at hy&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>These two lines are written as one in the MS. Some such phrase as</I> to ken me <I>seems to have been lost; see</I> l. 53.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Omnia-probate</I> &middot; a pore &thorn;ing with alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>These two lines are written as one in the MS. Some such phrase as</I> to ken me <I>seems to have been lost; see</I> l. 53.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Omnia probate</I>] <I>Compare</I> Text B. Pass. III. l. 335.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou shalt wende with wil," quod she &middot; "whiles &thorn;at him lyky&thorn;,</L>
<L N="52">Til &yogh;e come to &thorn;e burghe &middot; <I>quod-bonum-est-tenete</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>burghe</I>]? burgher MS. <I>But</I> burghe = borough <I>is meant; it is call|ed</I> a court <I>in</I> l. 57.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ken him to my cosenes hous &middot; &thorn;at kinde wit hy&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Sey I sente him &thorn;is segge &middot; and &thorn;at he shewe hym dowel."</L>
<L>&THORN;us we lau&yogh;&thorn;e oure leue &middot; lowtyng at onys,</L>
<L N="56">And wente for&thorn; on my way &middot; with <I>omnia-probate</I>,</L>
<L>And ere I cam to &thorn;e court &middot; <I>quod-bonum-est-tenete</I>,</L>
<L>Many ferlys me by-fel &middot; in a fewe &yogh;eris.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. Prologue; l. 62. <I>Here fol|lows the catchword&mdash;&thorn;e</I> ferste ferly.</NOTE></L>
<L>The fyrste ferly I fond &middot; a-fyngrid me made;<MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="60">As I &yogh;ede thurgh &yogh;ou&thorn;e &middot; a-&yogh;en prime dayes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ou&thorn;e</I>] <I>miswritten</I> &yogh;ou &middot; <I>&thorn;e in</I> MS.; <I>the metrical dot being inserted by mistake after the letter</I> u. <I>But the reading is certain; cf</I>. Text B. Pass. XI. 17, 34, 59; <I>and especially observe the whole drift of</I> Text B. Pass. XI.</NOTE></L>
<L>I stode stille in a stodie &middot; and stared a-bowte;</L>
<L>"Al hayl," quod on &thorn;o, and I answered "welcome &middot; and with whom be &yogh;e?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A half-line has probably been lost here</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"I am dwellyng with deth &middot; and hunger I hatte,</L>
<L N="64">To lyf in his lordshepe &middot; longyt my weye,</L>
<L>I shal felle &thorn;at freke &middot; in a fewe dayes!"</L>
<L>"I wolde folwe &thorn;e fayn &middot; but fentesye me hende&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. Pass. V. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me folwe&thorn; such a fentyse &middot; I may no fer&thorn;er walke."</L>
<L N="68">"Go we for&thorn;," quod &thorn;e gom &middot; "I haue a gret boyste</L>
<L>At my bak, of broke bred &middot; &thorn;i bely for to fylle;
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="140*"></L>
<L>A bagge ful, of a beggere &middot; I bou&yogh;&thorn;e hit at onys."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bou&yogh;&thorn;e</I>] <I>cf</I>. wrou&yogh;&thorn;, l. 87; lau&yogh;&thorn;e, l. 55; &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than maunged I wit &middot; vp at &thorn;e fulle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Corrupt; probably two half|lines lost</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">For &thorn;e myssyng of mete &middot; no mesour I coude.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at cam a knaue &middot; with a confessoures face,</L>
<L>He halsed me and I &middot; asked him after,</L>
<L>Of when &thorn;at he were &middot; and wheder &thorn;at he wolde.</L>
<L N="76">"With de&thorn; I duelle," quod he &middot; "dayes and ny&yogh;tes;</L>
<L>Mi name is feuere, on &thorn;e fer&thorn;e day &middot; I am a-&thorn;rest euere;</L>
<L>I am masager of de&thorn; &middot; men haue I tweyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fevers <I>and</I> Death <I>appear in</I> Text B. Pass. XX.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at on is called cotidian &middot; a courour of oure hous,</L>
<L N="80">Tercian &thorn;at o&thorn;er &middot; trewe drinkeres bo&thorn;e!</L>
<L>We han letteres of lyf &middot; he shal his lyf [tyne;]<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>tyne</I>] <I>The</I> MS. <I>has</I> tyme, <I>cor|ruptly</I>. See Pass. XI. 233.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro de&thorn;, &thorn;at is oure duk &middot; swyche dedis we brynge."</L>
<L>"My&yogh;th I so, god wot &middot; &yogh;oure gates wolde I holden."</L>
<L N="84">"Nay, wil!" quod &thorn;at wy&yogh;th &middot; "wend &thorn;ou no ferther,</L>
<L>But lyue as &thorn;is lyf &middot; is ordeyned for the,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou tomblest wi&thorn; a trepget &middot; &yogh;if &thorn;ou my tras folwe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ou</I>] <I>miswritten</I> &thorn;e <I>in the</I> MS.; the <I>being the preceding word</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And mannes mer&thorn;e wrou&yogh;&thorn; no mor &middot; &thorn;an he deseruy&thorn; here,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wrou&yogh;&thorn;</I>] = wrou&yogh;te. Cf. l. 70. <I>The reading</I> wor&thorn;e <I>would make better sense</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">Whil his lyf and his lykhame &middot; lesten to-gedere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-fore do after do-wel &middot; whil &thorn;i dayes duren,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i play be plentevous &middot; in paradys with aungelys.<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt be lau&yogh;th into ly&yogh;th &middot; with loking of an eye,</L>
<L N="92">So &thorn;at &thorn;ou werke &thorn;e word &middot; &thorn;at holy wryt teche&thorn;,</L>
<L>And be prest to preyeres &middot; and profitable werkes."</L>
<L>Wille [wiste] &thorn;urgh in-wit&mdash; &middot; &thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;e so&thorn;e&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The word</I> wiste <I>has evidently been dropped here, probably on account of</I> wost <I>following</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is speche was spedelich &middot; and sped him wel faste,</L>
<L N="96">And wrou&yogh;the &thorn;at here is wryten &middot; and o&thorn;er werkes bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>This means that, besides the</I> Vita de Do-wel, Do-bet, et Do-best, <I>the author wrote</I> Peres the Plowman.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="141*"></L>
<L>Of peres &thorn;e plowman &middot; and mechel puple al-so;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is werk was wrou&yogh;t &middot; ere wille my&yogh;te a-spie,</L>
<L>De&thorn; delt him a dent &middot; and drof him to &thorn;e er&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="100">And is closed vnder clom &middot; crist haue his soule!<NOTE PLACE="foot">98&mdash;100. These are the author's own words; he kills himself off, by way of finishing his poem, but he lived to re-write it, nevertheless.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so bad Iohan but &middot; busily wel ofte,</L>
<L>When he saw &thorn;es sawes &middot; busyly a-legged<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>busyly</I>] <I>Read</I> sothely? Busyly <I>is repeated from the line above</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>By Iames and by Ierom &middot; by Iop and by o&thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="104">And for he medle&thorn; of makyng &middot; he made &thorn;is ende.</L>
<L>Now alle kenne creatures &middot; &thorn;at cristene were euere,</L>
<L>God for his goudnesse &middot; gif hem swyche happes,</L>
<L>To lyue as &thorn;at lord lyky&thorn; &middot; &thorn;at lyf in hem putte.</L>
<L N="108">Furst to rekne Richard &middot; kyng of &thorn;is rewme,</L>
<L>And alle lordes &thorn;at louyn him &middot; lely in herte,</L>
<L>God saue hem sound &middot; by se and by land;</L>
<L>Marie moder and may &middot; for man &thorn;ou by-seke;</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at barn bryng vs to blys &middot; &thorn;at bled vp-on &thorn;e rode! Amen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">101&mdash;112. Obviously added, as stated, by another hand, viz. that of John But, who made a second "end," because he was accustomed to "meddle with makyng," i. e. to compose verses.</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Explicit do-Wel.<LB><I>Nomen scriptoris &middot; tisot plenus amoris</I>.</TRAILER>
</LG>
