<HEAD>Incipit liber de Petro Plowman.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="prologue">
<HEAD>[Prologus.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">OBS. L=MS. Laud 581; W=MS. <I>printed by</I> Wright; O=MS. Oriel; R=MS. Rawlinson; C=Camb. MS. Dd. 1. 17; C2=Camb. MS. Ll. 4. 14. <I>Readings from the last of these are given only occasionally</I>.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In a somer seson &middot; whan soft was the sonne,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="1"><MILESTONE UNIT="L folio" N="1"></L>
<L>I shope me in shroudes &middot; as I a shepe were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] into W. <I>shepe</I>] sheep W; scheep C2; <I>but</I> C <I>has</I> schepe (<I>with a final</I> e).</NOTE></L>
<L>In habite as an heremite &middot; vnholy of workes,</L>
<L N="4">Went wyde in &thorn;is world &middot; wondres to here.</L>
<L>Ac on a May mornynge &middot; on Maluerne hulles<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And CC2.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me byfel a ferly &middot; of fairy me thou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>I was wery forwandred &middot; and went me to reste</L>
<L N="8">Vnder a brode banke &middot; bi a bornes side,</L>
<L>And as I lay and lened &middot; and loked in &thorn;e wateres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] on W.</NOTE></L>
<L>I slombred in a slepyng &middot; it sweyued so merye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] in-to W. <I>sweyued</I>] sweyed W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thanne gan I to meten &middot; a merueilouse sweuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] <I>so in</I> W (<I>but not printed</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">That I was in a wildernesse &middot; wist I neuer where,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] WO <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>As I bihelde in-to &thorn;e est &middot; an hiegh to &thorn;e sonne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As</I>] And as W; And C. <I>an hiegh</I>] on hy&yogh; O; on hie C2.</NOTE></L>
<L>I seigh a toure on a toft &middot; trielich ymaked;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seigh</I>] saw&yogh; O. <I>trielich</I>] rie|liche (<I>with</I> t <I>erased</I>) C; triedliche O.</NOTE></L>
<L>A depe dale binethe &middot; a dongeon &thorn;ere-Inne,</L>
<L N="16">With depe dyches &amp; derke &middot; and dredful of sight.
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="2, B-text"></L>
<L>A faire felde ful of folke &middot; fonde I there bytwene,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="2"></L>
<L>Of alle maner of men &middot; &thorn;e mene and &thorn;e riche,</L>
<L>Worchyng and wandryng &middot; as &thorn;e worlde asketh.</L>
<L N="20">Some [putten] hem to &thorn;e plow &middot; pleyed ful selde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>putten</I> W] putte C<SUB>2</SUB>; put LC. <I>See</I> l. 23. <I>hem</I>] him C. <I>pleyed</I>] plei|den W; pleyede O; plaiden C; pleyed LC<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>selde</I>] seelde O; seeld C<SUB>2</SUB>; sel|den C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In settyng and in sowyng &middot; swonken ful harde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in sowyng</I>] WOC<SUB>2</SUB> <I>omit</I> in. <I>swonken</I>] swynken C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wonnen that wastours &middot; with glotonye destruyeth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>] in OC<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>destruyeth</I>] dis|troys C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And some putten hem to pruyde &middot; apparailed hem &thorn;ere-after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>apparailed</I>] apparayleden OC<SUB>2</SUB>; apparailed LWC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">In contenaunce of clothyng &middot; comen disgised.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>disgised</I>] degised W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; In prayers and in penance &middot; putten hem manye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>prayers</I>] preyere O. <I>in pe|nance</I>] penaunces W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al for loue of owre lorde &middot; lyueden ful streyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>loue</I>] &thorn;e loue W.</NOTE></L>
<L>In hope forto haue &middot; heueneriche blisse;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>forto haue</I>] to haue after W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">As ancres and heremites &middot; that holden hem in here selles,</L>
<L>And coueiten nought in contre &middot; to kairen aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kairen</I>] cayren O; carien WC<SUB>2</SUB>; walken C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For no likerous liflode &middot; her lykam to plese.</L>
<L>&para; And somme chosen chaffare &middot; they cheuen the bettere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chosen</I>] chesen C. <I>cheuen</I>] cheueden W.</NOTE></L>
<L>As it semeth to owre sy&yogh;t &middot; that suche men thryueth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>suche</I>] swilke C. <I>men</I>] OC<SUB>2</SUB> <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And somme murthes to make &middot; as mynstralles conneth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>conneth</I>] konne W; knaueth C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="34">And geten gold with here glee &middot; synneles, I leue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>synneles</I>] Mr Wright prints <I>giltles</I> (cf. Text A); but we find <I>syn|neles</I> in LWC; <I>not synles</I> in OC<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac iapers &amp; iangelers &middot; Iudas chylderen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] As COC<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Feynen hem fantasies &middot; and foles hem maketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Feynen</I>] &thorn;at feynen OC<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And han here witte at wille &middot; to worche &yogh;if &thorn;ei sholde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>at wille</I>] at her wille OC<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>sholde</I>] wolde W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="38">That Poule precheth of hem &middot; I nel nought preue it here;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="3"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nel</I>] wol W. <I>In the margin of</I> O <I>is written</I>, Qui non laborat non manducet.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="3, B-text"></L>
<L><I>Qui turpiloquium loquitur</I> &middot; [is luciferes hyne].<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Qui</I>] But <I>Qui</I> W. <I>The readings are&mdash;Qui turpiloquium loquitur, &amp;c</I>. LC; But <I>Qui lcquitur turpiloquium</I> &middot; is Luciferes hyne W; O <I>resembles</I> W, <I>with</I> knaue <I>instead of</I> hyne; C<SUB>2</SUB> <I>has the same as</I> O, <I>with</I> hyne <I>written above</I> knaue. Cf. Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">&para; Bidders and beggeres &middot; fast aboute &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>With her bely and her bagge[s] &middot; of bred ful ycrammed;<MILESTONE N="1b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bely</I>] belies W. <I>bagges</I>] L <I>has</I> bagge; <I>but</I> WCOC<SUB>2</SUB> <I>have the plural</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fayteden for here fode &middot; fou&yogh;ten atte ale;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>atte ale</I>] at &thorn;e ale W; at ale O; at nale C<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In glotonye, god it wote &middot; gon hij to bedde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it</I>] W <I>om. gon</I>] go W; gayt C. <I>hij</I>] &thorn;ei WO; they C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">And risen with ribaudye &middot; tho roberdes knaues;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>] &thorn;e O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Slepe and sori sleuthe &middot; seweth hem eure.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seweth</I>] sheweth C; suen O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Pilgrymes and palmers &middot; pli&yogh;ted hem togidere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pli&yogh;ted</I>] pli&yogh;teden O; pli&yogh;ted L; pli&yogh;ten W; gedir C.</NOTE></L>
<L>To seke seynt Iames &middot; and seyntes in rome.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To</I>] For to W. <I>in</I>] at W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thei went forth in here wey &middot; with many wise tales,</L>
<L N="49">And hadden leue to lye &middot; al here lyf after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to lye</I>] for to lye O; to lee C.</NOTE></L>
<L>I seigh somme that seiden &middot; &thorn;ei had ysou&yogh;t seyntes;</L>
<L>To eche a tale &thorn;at &thorn;ei tolde &middot; here tonge was tempred to lye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To eche</I>] Tho hilke C. <I>here</I>] thayr C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">More &thorn;an to sey soth &middot; it semed bi here speche.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] OC<SUB>2</SUB> <I>om. here</I>] thair C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Heremites on an heep &middot; With hoked staues,</L>
<L>Wenten to Walsyngham &middot; and here wenches after;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here</I>] hire W; thair C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Grete lobyes and longe &middot; that loth were to swynke,</L>
<L>Clotheden hem in copis &middot; to ben knowen fram othere;</L>
<L>And shopen hem heremites &middot; here ese to haue.</L>
<L>&para; I fonde &thorn;ere Freris &middot; alle &thorn;e foure ordres,</L>
<L>Preched &thorn;e peple &middot; for profit of hem-seluen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Preched</I>] Prechynge W; Pre|cheden O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Glosed &thorn;e gospel &middot; as hem good lyked,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="4"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Glosed</I>] Gloseden O.</NOTE></L>
<L>For coueitise of copis &middot; construed it as &thorn;ei wolde,</L>
<L>Many of &thorn;is maistres Freris &middot; mowe clothen hem at lykyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maistres</I>] <I>so also in</I> C; maistre W; maystre O. <I>mowe</I>] now W.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="4, B-text"></L>
<L>For here money and marchandise &middot; marchen togideres.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>marchandise</I>] hire marchaun|di&yogh;e W; mauchaudises (<I>sic</I>) C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">For sith charite ha&thorn; be chapman &middot; and chief to shryue lordes,</L>
<L>Many ferlis han fallen &middot; in a fewe &yogh;eris.</L>
<L>But holychirche and hij &middot; holde better togideres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hij</I>] &thorn;ei O.</NOTE></L>
<L>The moste my[s]chief on molde &middot; is mountyng wel faste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myschief</I>] mychief L; meschief WCO. <I>wel</I>] vp wel OC2.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">&para; &THORN;ere preched a Pardonere &middot; as he a prest were,</L>
<L>Brou&yogh;te forth a bulle &middot; with bishopes seles,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>] wi&thorn; many W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at hym-self my&yogh;te &middot; assoilen hem alle</L>
<L>Of falshed of fastyng &middot; of vowes ybroken.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of vowes</I>] of Auowes W; and of vowes CO.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Lewed men leued hym wel &middot; and lyked his wordes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] it W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="73">Comen vp knelyng &middot; to kissen his bulles;</L>
<L>He bonched hem with his breuet &middot; &amp; blered here eyes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bonched</I>] bunchede O; <I>Mr Wright prints</I> bouched. <I>eyes</I>] ei&yogh;en W; yen O; eyen C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And rau&yogh;te with his ragman &middot; rynges and broches.</L>
<L N="76">Thus &thorn;ey geuen here golde &middot; glotones to kepe,</L>
<L>And leueth such loseles &middot; &thorn;at lecherye haunten.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leueth</I>] leue&thorn; it <I>or</I> lene&thorn; it (<I>misprinted</I> leveth in) W; leuys <I>or</I> lenys C; louen OC2. <I>&thorn;at</I>] as W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were &thorn;e bischop yblissed &middot; and worth bothe his eres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yblissed</I>] yblessed W; Iblessid O.</NOTE></L>
<L>His seel shulde nou&yogh;t be sent &middot; to deceyue &thorn;e peple.</L>
<L N="80">Ac it is nau&yogh;t by &thorn;e bischop &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e boy precheth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>boy</I>] both C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For the parisch prest and &thorn;e pardonere &middot; parten &thorn;e siluer,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="5"><MILESTONE N="2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That &thorn;e poraille of &thorn;e parisch &middot; sholde haue &yogh;if &thorn;ei nere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>poraille</I>] pore porayle O. <I>nere</I>] ne were WO.</NOTE></L>
<L N="83">&para; Persones and parisch prestes &middot; pleyned hem to &thorn;e bischop,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here parisshes were pore &middot; sith &thorn;e pestilence tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>parisshes</I>] parisse C. <I>pore</I>] pouere W. <I>sith &thorn;e</I>] sith C.</NOTE></L>
<L>To haue a lycence and a leue &middot; at London to dwelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a leue</I>] leue WO.</NOTE></L>
<L N="86">And syngen &thorn;ere for symonye &middot; for siluer is swete.</L>
<L>&para; Bischopes and bachelers &middot; bothe maistres and doctours,
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="5, B-text"></L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at han cure vnder criste &middot; and crounyng in tokne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crounyng</I>] crowng (<I>sic</I>) C; crownes C2.</NOTE></L>
<L>And signe &thorn;at &thorn;ei sholden &middot; shryuen here paroschienes,</L>
<L>Prechen and prey for hem &middot; and &thorn;e pore fede,</L>
<L>Liggen in London &middot; in lenten, an elles.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Liggen</I>] Liggand C. <I>in Lon|don</I>] at Londone W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="92">Somme seruen &thorn;e kyng &middot; and his siluer tellen,</L>
<L>In cheker and in chancerye &middot; chalengen his dettes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chancerye</I>] chauncelrie W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of wardes and wardmotes &middot; weyues and streyues.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and wardmotes</I>] and of warde|motes W; of wardemotes OC2. <I>weyues and</I>] of weyues of OC2.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And some seruen as seruantz &middot; lordes and ladyes,</L>
<L N="96">And in stede of stuwardes &middot; sytten and demen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stuwardes</I>] stywardes W; sti|wardes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here messe and here matynes &middot; and many of here oures</L>
<L>Arn don vndeuoutlych; &middot; drede is at &thorn;e laste</L>
<L>Lest crist in cons[is]torie &middot; acorse ful manye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>consistorie</I> WCO] constorie L. <I>acorse</I>] a-curse C; curse O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">I parceyued of &thorn;e power &middot; &thorn;at Peter had to kepe,</L>
<L>To bynde and to vnbynde &middot; as &thorn;e boke telleth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to unbynde</I>] vnbynden W.</NOTE></L>
<L>How he it left wi&thorn; loue &middot; as owre lorde hight,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>left</I>] self (!) OC2.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amonges foure vertues &middot; &thorn;e best of alle vertues,<NOTE PLACE="foot">C <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at cardinales ben called &middot; &amp; closyng &yogh;atis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere crist is in kyngdome &middot; to close and to shutte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crist is</I>] is crist W. <I>in</I>] in his W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to opne it to hem &middot; and heuene blisse shewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>opne</I>] opene W; open C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac of &thorn;e cardinales atte Courte &middot; &thorn;at cau&yogh;t of &thorn;at name,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>atte</I>] at WO.</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">And power presumed in hem &middot; a Pope to make,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] Ac (!) O.</NOTE></L>
<L>To han &thorn;at power &thorn;at peter hadde &middot; inpugnen I nelle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>han</I>] haue CO. <I>inpugnen</I>] impugnen W; Impugne it O.</NOTE></L>
<L>For in loue and letterure &middot; &thorn;e eleccioun bilongeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>letterure</I>] in lettrure W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I can and can nau&yogh;te &middot; of courte speke more.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and can</I>] and I can OC2.</NOTE></L>
<L N="112">&para; &THORN;anne come &thorn;ere a kyng &middot; kny&yogh;thod hym ladde,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t of &thorn;e comunes &middot; made hym to regne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne cam kynde wytte &middot; and clerkes he made,
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="6, B-text"></L>
<L>For to conseille &thorn;e kyng &middot; and &thorn;e comune saue.</L>
<L N="116">&para; The kyng and kny&yogh;thode &middot; and clergye bothe</L>
<L>Casten &thorn;at &thorn;e comune &middot; shulde hem-self fynde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e comune contreued &middot; of kynde witte craftes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>contreued</I>] controued (<I>pro|bably miswritten</I>) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for profit of alle &thorn;e poeple &middot; plowmen ordeygned,</L>
<L N="120">To tilie and trauaile &middot; as trewe lyf aske&thorn;.<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and trauaile</I>] and to trauaille W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kynge and &thorn;e comune &middot; and kynde witte &thorn;e thridde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and kynde</I>] kynde C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shope lawe &amp; lewte &middot; eche man to knowe his owne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lewte</I>] leaute WC; leute O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne loked vp a lunatik &middot; a lene &thorn;ing with-alle,</L>
<L N="124">And knelyng to &thorn;e kyng &middot; clergealy he seyde;</L>
<L>"Crist kepe &thorn;e, sire kyng &middot; and &thorn;i kyngriche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here commences the fragment of</I> MS. R <I>which is now found in</I> MS. Lansdowne 398; <I>see the Preface</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And leue &thorn;e lede &thorn;i londe &middot; so leute &thorn;e louye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leue</I>] leue <I>or</I> lene WCO. <I>lede</I>] to lede OC2.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for &thorn;i ri&yogh;tful rewlyng &middot; be rewarded in heuene!"</L>
<L>&para; And sithen in &thorn;e eyre an hiegh &middot; An angel of heuene</L>
<L>Lowed to speke in latyn&mdash; &middot; for lewed men ne coude</L>
<L N="130">Iangle ne iugge &middot; &thorn;at iustifie hem shulde,</L>
<L>But suffren &amp; seruen&mdash; &middot; for-thi seyde &thorn;e angel,</L>
<L>"<I>Sum Rex, sum Princeps</I> &middot; <I>neutrum fortasse deinceps;</I>&mdash;</L>
<L N="133"><I>O qui iura regis</I> &middot; <I>Christi specialia regis</I>,</L>
<L><I>Hoc quod agas melius</I> &middot; <I>iustus es, esto pius!</I></L>
<L><I>Nudum ius a te</I> &middot; <I>vestiri vult pietate;</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ius</I>] vis R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="136"><I>Qualia vis metere</I> &middot; <I>talia grana sere</I>.</L>
<L><I>Si ius nudatur</I> &middot; <I>nudo de iure metatur</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ius</I>] vis R.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Si seritur pietas</I> &middot; <I>de pietate metas!</I>"</L>
<L>&para; Thanne greued hym a Goliardeys &middot; a glotoun of wordes,</L>
<L N="140">And to &thorn;e angel an hei&yogh; &middot; [answered] after,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>answered</I> C] answerde W; answerede O; answeres LR.</NOTE></L>
<L>"<I>Dum rex a regere</I> &middot; <I>dicatur nomen habere</I>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Dum</I>] <I>so in</I> LWR; Cum CO.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Nomen habet sine re</I> &middot; <I>nisi studet iura tenere</I>."
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="7, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;anne gan alle &thorn;e comune &middot; crye in vers of latin,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And &thorn;anne</I>] Thanne W. <I>co|mune</I>] comunes O. <I>vers</I>] a vers R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">To &thorn;e kynges conseille &middot; construe ho-so wolde&mdash;</L>
<L>"<I>Precepta Regis</I> &middot; <I>sunt nobis vincula legis</I>."</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; &thorn;at ran &thorn;ere a route &middot; of ratones at ones,</L>
<L>And smale mys with hem &middot; mo &thorn;en a &thorn;ousande,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mys</I>] mees W; myce O. <I>with</I>] myd W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="148">And comen to a conseille &middot; for here comune profit;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here</I>] &thorn;e W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For a cat of a courte &middot; cam whan hym lyked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>courte</I>] contree W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ouerlepe hem ly&yogh;tlich &middot; and lau&yogh;te hem at his wille,</L>
<L N="151">And pleyde wi&thorn; hem perilouslych &middot; and possed [hem] aboute.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hem</I> COR] LW <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"For doute of dyuerse dredes &middot; we dar nou&yogh;te wel loke;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dar</I>] doren O; durre C2. <I>wel</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;if we grucche of his gamen &middot; he wil greue vs alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cracche vs, or clowe vs &middot; and in his cloches holde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>] &amp; O. <I>clowe</I>] clawen W; clawe RO; clow C.</NOTE></L>
<L>That vs lotheth &thorn;e lyf &middot; or he lete vs passe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>] er WR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="156">My&yogh;te we wi&thorn; any witte &middot; his wille withstonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wille</I>] wit C (<I>wrongly</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>We my&yogh;te be lordes aloft &middot; and lyuen at owre ese."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aloft</I>] o-lofte W; on lofte R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; A raton of renon &middot; most renable of tonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>renon</I>] renoun WCO. <I>renable</I>] resonable R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seide for a (souereygne &middot; help) to hym-selue;&mdash;<MILESTONE N="3" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym-selue</I>] hem alle R.</NOTE></L>
<L>"I haue ysein segges," quod he &middot; "in &thorn;e cite of london<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ysein</I>] seyn CO; y-seyen W. <I>segges</I>] segthis C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="161">Beren bi&yogh;es ful bri&yogh;te &middot; abouten here nekkes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Beren</I>] Weren C. <I>bi&yogh;es</I>] bei&yogh;es W; behes C; byes O; be&yogh;es R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And some colers of crafty werk; &middot; vncoupled &thorn;ei wenden<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wenden</I>] <I>so in</I> LCOR; wenten W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in wareine &amp; in waste &middot; where hem leue lyketh;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem leue lyketh</I>] hem-self liked W; &thorn;aym lef lyke&thorn; R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="164">And otherwhile &thorn;ei aren elles-where &middot; as I here telle.</L>
<L>Were &thorn;ere a belle on here bei&yogh; &middot; bi Ihesu, as me thynketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bei&yogh;</I>] bighes C; byes O; bye R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men my&yogh;te wite where &thorn;ei went &middot; and awei renne!</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t so," quod &thorn;at ratoun &middot; "reson me sheweth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;e O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="8, B-text"></L>
<L N="168">To bugge a belle of brasse &middot; or of bri&yogh;te syluer,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bugge</I>] bigge CO; bye C<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And knitten on a colere &middot; for owre comune profit,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] it on W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hangen it vp-on &thorn;e cattes hals &middot; &thorn;anne here we mowen<NOTE PLACE="foot">W <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where he ritt or rest &middot; or renneth to playe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>omits. rest</I>] resti&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="172">And &yogh;if him list for to laike &middot; &thorn;enne loke we mowen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And peren in his presence &middot; &thorn;er while hym plaie liketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;er while</I>] &thorn;e while WR.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;if him wrattheth, be ywar &middot; and his weye shonye."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ywar</I>] war W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;is route of ratones &middot; to &thorn;is reson &thorn;ei assented.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I> (1)] &thorn;e R. <I>&thorn;ei</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="176">Ac &thorn;o &thorn;e belle was ybou&yogh;t &middot; and on &thorn;e bei&yogh;e hanged,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>ybou&yogh;t</I>] y-brou&yogh;t W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere ne was ratoun in alle &thorn;e route &middot; for alle &thorn;e rewme of Fraunce,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rewme</I>] reaume W; reem C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at dorst haue ybounden &thorn;e belle &middot; aboute &thorn;e cattis nekke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ybounden</I>] bounden W; bounde O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne hangen [it] aboute &thorn;e cattes hals &middot; al Engelonde to wynne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>it</I>] <I>occurs in</I> WCROC<SUB>2</SUB>; L <I>om. &thorn;e cattes</I>] his R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">And helden hem vnhardy &middot; and here conseille feble,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] Alle W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And leten here laboure lost &middot; &amp; alle here longe studye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alle</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; A mous &thorn;at moche good &middot; couthe, as me thou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Stroke forth sternly &middot; and stode biforn hem alle,</L>
<L N="184">And to &thorn;e route of ratones &middot; reherced &thorn;ese wordes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>route of</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Thou&yogh; we culled &thorn;e catte &middot; &yogh;ut sholde &thorn;er come an|other,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>culled</I>] killen W; kulled C; killeden O; had Iculled R.</NOTE></L>
<L>To cracchy vs and al owre kynde &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; we croupe vnder benches.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cracchy</I>] cracche O; cacchen W; cache C<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>croupe</I>] cropen W, crepe C; crope R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I conseille alle &thorn;e comune &middot; to lat &thorn;e catte worthe,</L>
<L N="188">And be we neuer so bolde &middot; &thorn;e belle hym to shewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For I herde my sire seyn &middot; is seuene &yogh;ere ypassed,
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="9, B-text"></L>
<L N="190">&THORN;ere &thorn;e catte is a kitoun &middot; &thorn;e courte is ful elyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;at witnisseth holiwrite &middot; who-so wil it rede,<Q><I>Ve terre vbi puer rex est, &amp;c</I>.</Q></L>
<L>For may no renke &thorn;ere rest haue &middot; for ratones bi ny&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ere</I>] no R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="193">&THORN;e while he cacche&thorn; conynges &middot; he coueiteth nou&yogh;t owre caroyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>owre</I>] youre W.</NOTE></L>
<L>But fet hym al with venesoun &middot; defame we hym neuere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fet</I>] fede&thorn; W; fedes C. <I>al</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For better is a litel losse &middot; &thorn;an a longe sorwe,</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;e mase amonge vs alle &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; we mysse a schrewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For many mannus malt &middot; we mys wolde destruye,</L>
<L>And also &yogh;e route of ratones &middot; rende mennes clothes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>] the C; &thorn;e O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nere &thorn;at cat of &thorn;at courte &middot; &thorn;at can &yogh;ow ouerlepe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at cat of &thorn;at</I>] &thorn;e cat of &thorn;at W; &thorn;at cat of &thorn;e R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">For had &yogh;e rattes &yogh;owre wille &middot; &yogh;e couthe nou&yogh;t reule &yogh;owre-selue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rattes</I>] ratones R.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sey for me," quod &thorn;e mous &middot; "I se so mykel after,<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for me</I>] it for my-self R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal neuer &thorn;e cat ne &thorn;e kitoun &middot; bi my conseille be greued,</L>
<L>Ne carpyng of &thorn;is coler &middot; &thorn;at costed me neure.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ne</I>] Thoru&yogh; W. <I>costed</I>] cost CO.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh; it had coste me catel &middot; biknowen it I nolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>had coste</I>] hadde costned W; costed R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="205">But suffre as hym-self wolde &middot; to do as hym liketh,</L>
<L>Coupled &amp; vncoupled &middot; to cacche what thei mowe.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i vche a wise wi&yogh;te I warne &middot; wite wel his owne."&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For&thorn;i&mdash;wi&yogh;te</I>] For vche a wyse man R. <I>vche</I>] ech W; ilke C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; What &thorn;is meteles bemeneth &middot; &yogh;e men &thorn;at be merye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bemeneth</I>] bymene R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="209">Deuine &yogh;e, for I ne dar &middot; bi dere god in heuene!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for&mdash;dar</I>] ne dar I nou&yogh;t R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;it houed &thorn;ere an hondreth &middot; in houues of selke,</L>
<L>Seriaunt&yogh; it semed &middot; &thorn;at serueden atte barre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it semed</I>] it bi-semed W; it semeden O; as it semed C. <I>atte</I>] at &thorn;e WOR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="212">Plededen for penyes &middot; and poundes &thorn;e lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Plededen</I>] Pleteden WCRO; Pleded C<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="10, B-text"></L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t for loue of owre lorde &middot; vnlese here lippes onis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vnlese</I>] vnlose (<I>printed</I> un|close) W; vnlose O; vnlouse C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ow my&yogh;test better mete &thorn;e myste &middot; on maluerne hulles,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an gete a momme of here mouthe &middot; but money were shewed.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="6"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>momme</I>] mom W; mumme OR. <I>but</I>&mdash;<I>were</I>] but moneie be O; til moneie be W; er mony hem by R. L <I>has</I> monoy, <I>miswritten for</I> money; <I>cf</I>. Pass. I. l. 44.</NOTE></L>
<L N="216">&para; Barones an burgeis &middot; and bonde-men als<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>burgeis</I>] burgeises W.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sei&yogh; in &thorn;is assemble &middot; as &yogh;e shul here after.</L>
<L>Baxsteres &amp; brewesteres &middot; and bocheres manye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Baxteres</I>] baksteres WR.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wollewebsteres &middot; and weueres of lynnen,</L>
<L N="220">Taillours and tynkeres &middot; &amp; tolleres in marketes,</L>
<L>Masons and mynours &middot; and many other craftes.</L>
<L>Of alkin libbyng laboreres &middot; lopen forth somme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alkin</I>] alle kynne W; alle kyn O; alkyn C; alle R.</NOTE></L>
<L>As dykers &amp; delueres &middot; &thorn;at doth here dedes ille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>doth</I>] doon WO; does C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="224">And dryuen forth &thorn;e [longe] day &middot; with "<I>Dieu vous saue, Dame Emme!</I>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>longe</I>] <I>so in</I> WCO; L <I>has</I> dere. Cf. Text A. <I>&thorn;e</I> &mdash; <I>day</I>] here dayes here R. <I>vous</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cokes and here knaues &middot; crieden, "hote pies, hote!</L>
<L>Gode gris a[nd] gees &middot; gowe dyne, gowe!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] and WRO; an C; L <I>has</I> a.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Tauerners vn-til hem &middot; tolde &thorn;e same,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tolde</I>] trewely tolden W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="228">"White wyn of Oseye &middot; and red wyn of Gascoigne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>red wyn</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Ryne and of &thorn;e Rochel &middot; &thorn;e roste to defye."&mdash;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is sei&yogh; I slepyng &middot; and seuene sythes more.<NOTE PLACE="foot">W <I>omits</I>; but Mr Wright sup|plies the line from MS. T (of the A|class). <I>sei&yogh;</I>] sawe CO.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000293.tif" N="11, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS I.</HEAD>
<HEAD><I>Passus Primus de visione</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. <I>So in</I> LWC; Passus primus de visione petri plowman R; Primus Passus O.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What this montaigne bymeneth &middot; and &thorn;e merke dale,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="7"></L>
<L>And &thorn;e felde ful of folke &middot; I shal &yogh;ow faire schewe.</L>
<L>A loueli ladi of lere &middot; in lynnen yclothed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lere</I>] leere W; lyre C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">Come down fram a castel &middot; and called me faire,</L>
<L>And seide, "Sone, slepestow &middot; sestow &thorn;is poeple,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sestow</I>] sest &thorn;ow R; seest &thorn;ou O.</NOTE></L>
<L>How bisi &thorn;ei ben &middot; abouten &thorn;e mase?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>abouten</I>] alle aboute W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e moste partie of &thorn;is poeple &middot; &thorn;at passeth on &thorn;is erthe,</L>
<L>Haue &thorn;ei worschip in &thorn;is worlde &middot; &thorn;ei wilne no better;</L>
<L N="9">Of other heuene &thorn;an here &middot; holde &thorn;ei no tale."<MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; I was aferd of her face &middot; &thorn;ei&yogh; she faire were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aferd</I>] a-fered CW; a-feerd O. <I>she</I>] scho C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide, "mercy, Madame &middot; what is &thorn;is to mene?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;e toure vp &thorn;e toft," quod she &middot; "treuthe is &thorn;ere-Inne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>toure</I>] thour C. <I>vp</I>] on W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="13">And wolde &thorn;at &yogh;e wrou&yogh;te &middot; as his worde techeth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>techeth</I>] thecheth C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he is fader of feith &middot; fourmed &yogh;ow alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] O <I>om. fourmed</I>] and formed W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bothe with fel and with face &middot; and &yogh;af &yogh;ow fyue wittis</L>
<L>Forto worschip hym &thorn;er-with &middot; &thorn;e while &thorn;at &yogh;e ben here.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="8"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] W <I>om. &thorn;at</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="17">And &thorn;erfore he hy&yogh;te &thorn;e erthe &middot; to help &yogh;ow vchone</L>
<L>Of wollen, of lynnen &middot; of lyflode at nede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of lyflode</I>] o lifode (<I>sic</I>) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In mesurable manere &middot; to make &yogh;ow at ese;</L>
<L N="20">&para; And comaunded of his curteisye &middot; in comune &thorn;ree &thorn;inges;
<PB REF="00000294.tif" N="12, B-text"></L>
<L>Arne none nedful but &thorn;o &middot; and nempne hem I thinke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And rekne hem bi resoun &middot; reherce &thorn;ow hem after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ow</I>] &yogh;e O.</NOTE></L>
<L>That one is vesture &middot; from chele &thorn;e to saue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] W <I>om. vesture</I>] clothinge C<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>chele</I>] chelde C; cold W; colde C<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">And mete atte mele &middot; for myseise of &thorn;i-selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>atte</I>] at W; at &thorn;e R; atte the C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And drynke whan &thorn;ow dryest &middot; ac do nou&yogh;t out of resoun;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>] and CC<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>That &thorn;ow worth &thorn;e werse &middot; whan &thorn;ow worche shuldest.</L>
<L>&para; For loth in his lifdayes &middot; for likyng of drynke,</L>
<L N="28">Dede bi his dou&yogh;tres &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel lyked;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyked</I>] wolde C. <I>But</I> C <I>omits the next line, which ends with</I> wolde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Delited hym in drynke &middot; as &thorn;e deuel wolde,</L>
<L>And lecherye hym lau&yogh;t &middot; and lay bi hem bo&thorn;e;</L>
