<L N="159">Ri&yogh;t so is loue a ledere &middot; and &thorn;e lawe shapeth,</L>
<L>Vpon man for his mysdedes &middot; &thorn;e merciment he taxeth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>] a man C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for to knowe it kyndely &middot; it comseth bi myght,<MILESTONE N="6" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myght</I>] nyght (!) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e herte &thorn;ere is &thorn;e heuede &middot; and &thorn;e hei&yogh; welle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heuede</I>] heed W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For in kynde knowynge in herte &middot; &thorn;ere a my&yogh;te bigynneth.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="14"></L>
<L N="164">And &thorn;at falleth to &thorn;e fader &middot; &thorn;at formed vs alle,</L>
<L>Loked on vs with loue &middot; and lete his sone deye</L>
<L>Mekely for owre mysdedes &middot; to amende vs alle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Mekely</I>] Mekel C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;et wolde he hem no woo &middot; &thorn;at wrou&yogh;te hym &thorn;at peyne,</L>
<L N="168">But mekelich with mouthe &middot; mercy he bisou&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>] bi O. <I>he</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To haue pite of &thorn;at poeple &middot; &thorn;at peyned hym to deth.</L>
<L>&para; Here my&yogh;tow see ensamples &middot; in hym-selue one,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here</I>] Here (<I>printed</I> There) W. <I>my&yogh;tow</I>] myghtestow C. <I>en|samples</I>] ensample W; ensaumpyle C.</NOTE></L>
<L>That he was mi&yogh;tful &amp; meke &middot; and mercy gan graunte</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at hongen him an hei&yogh; &middot; and his herte &thorn;irled.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hongen</I>] hengen W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For-thi I rede &yogh;ow riche &middot; haueth reuthe of &thorn;e pouere;</L>
<L N="174">Thou&yogh; &yogh;e be my&yogh;tful to mote &middot; beth meke in &yogh;owre werkes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Thou&yogh;</I>] Thought C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;e same mesures &thorn;at &yogh;e mete &middot; amys other elles,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shullen ben weyen &thorn;er-wyth &middot; whan &yogh;e wende hennes;<Q><I>Eadem mensura qua mensi fueritis, remecietur vobis</I>.</Q></L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ou&yogh; &yogh;e be trewe of &yogh;owre tonge &middot; and trewliche wynne,</L>
<L>And as chaste as a childe &middot; &thorn;at in cherche wepeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cherche</I>] kerke C</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="19, B-text"></L>
<L>But if &yogh;e louen lelliche &middot; and lene &thorn;e poure,</L>
<L N="180">Such goed as god &yogh;ow sent &middot; godelich parteth,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="15"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>goed</I>] good WCO.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e ne haue na more meryte &middot; in masse ne in houres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>more</I>] C <I>om. ne</I>] nor W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an Malkyn of hire maydenhode &middot; &thorn;at no man desireth.</L>
<L>&para; For Iames &thorn;e gentil &middot; iugged in his bokes,</L>
<L>That faith with-oute &thorn;e faite &middot; is ri&yogh;te no &thorn;inge worthi,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>faite</I>] feet W; feite O; facte <I>or</I> faite C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="185">And as ded as a dore-tre &middot; but &yogh;if &thorn;e dedes folwe;<Q><I>Fides sine operibus mortua est, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot">C <I>om. the second</I> as. <I>&thorn;e</I>] thy C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For-thi chastite with-oute charite &middot; worth cheyned in helle;</L>
<L>It is as lewed as a laumpe &middot; &thorn;at no li&yogh;te is Inne.</L>
<L>&para; Many chapeleynes arne chaste &middot; ac charite is awey;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>] and C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="189">Aren no men auarousere &thorn;an hij &middot; whan &thorn;ei ben auaunced;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hij</I>] &thorn;ei O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnkynde to her kyn &middot; and to alle cristene,</L>
<L>Chewen here charite &middot; and chiden after more.</L>
<L N="192">Such chastite wi&thorn;-outen charite &middot; worth cheyned in helle!</L>
<L>&para; Many curatoures kepen hem &middot; clene of here bodies,</L>
<L>Thei ben acombred wi&thorn; coueitise &middot; &thorn;ei konne nou&yogh;t don it fram hem,</L>
<L>So harde hath auarice &middot; yhasped hem togideres.<MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="196">And &thorn;at is no treuthe of &thorn;e trinite &middot; but treccherye of helle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>] in O (<I>wrongly</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>And lernyng to lewde men &middot; &thorn;e latter for to dele.</L>
<L>&para; For-&thorn;i &thorn;is wordes &middot; ben wryten in &thorn;e gospel,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="16"></L>
<L><I>Date &amp; dabitur vobis</I> &middot; for I dele &yogh;ow alle.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is &thorn;e lokke of loue &middot; and lateth oute my grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lateth</I>] lete&thorn; WC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="201">To conforte &thorn;e careful &middot; acombred wi&thorn; synne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>conforte</I>] counforte O; con|forten W; confort C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Loue is leche of lyf &middot; and nexte owre lorde selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nexte</I>] nexit C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also &thorn;e graith gate &middot; &thorn;at goth in-to heuene;
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="20, B-text"></L>
<L N="204">For-&thorn;i I sey as I seide &middot; ere by &thorn;e textis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ere&mdash;textis</I>] erst &middot; bi &thorn;e trewe textis O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan alle tresores ben ytryed &middot; treuthe is &thorn;e beste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ytryed</I>] tried W</NOTE></L>
<L>Now haue I tolde &thorn;e what treuthe is &middot; &thorn;at no tresore is bettere,</L>
<L N="207">I may no lenger lenge &thorn;e with &middot; now loke &thorn;e owre lorde!"
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000303.tif" N="21, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS II.</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. <I>So in</I> LWC; Secundus Passus O.</NOTE><I>Passus secundus de visione, vt supra</I>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yet I courbed on my knees &middot; and cryed hir of grace,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="17"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>courbed</I>] courred C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide, "mercy, Madame &middot; for Marie loue of heuene,</L>
<L>That bar &thorn;at blisful barne &middot; &thorn;at bou&yogh;te vs on &thorn;e Rode,</L>
<L N="4">Kenne me bi somme crafte &middot; to knowe &thorn;e fals."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] for to O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Loke vppon &thorn;i left half &middot; and lo where he standeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] sche O. <I>standeth</I>] stonde&thorn; W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bothe fals and fauel &middot; and here feres manye!"</L>
<L>&para; I loked on my left half &middot; as &thorn;e lady me taughte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>taughte</I>] thaughte C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">And was war of a womman &middot; wortheli yclothed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>was</I>] whas C. <I>wortheli</I>] wor&thorn;i|liche W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Purfiled with pelure &middot; &thorn;e finest vpon erthe,</L>
<L>Y-crounede with a corone &middot; &thorn;e kyng hath non better.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>corone</I>] croune C. <I>hath</I>] haes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fetislich hir fyngres &middot; were fretted with golde wyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fretted</I>] fettred C; fetrid O. <I>gold</I>] gol C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">And &thorn;ere-on red rubyes &middot; as red as any glede,</L>
<L>And diamantz of derrest pris &middot; and double manere saf|feres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>safferes</I>] saphires W; saphyrs C; saphers O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Orientales and ewages &middot; enuenymes to destroye.</L>
<L>&para; Hire robe was ful riche &middot; of red scarlet engreyned,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="18"></L>
<L N="16">With ribanes of red golde &middot; and of riche stones;</L>
<L>Hire arraye me rauysshed &middot; suche ricchesse saw I neuere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>saw</I>] sau&yogh; W.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="22, B-text"></L>
<L>I had wondre what she was &middot; and whas wyf she were.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>she</I>] scho C. <I>whas</I>] whos WCO.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "What is &thorn;is womman," quod I &middot; "so worthily a|tired?"</L>
<L N="20">&para; "That is Mede &thorn;e Mayde," quod she &middot; "hath noyed me ful oft,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hath</I>] hathes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ylakked my lemman &middot; &thorn;at lewte is hoten,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lewte</I>] leautee W; leaut C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bilowen hire to lordes &middot; &thorn;at lawes han to kepe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>han</I>] hathes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e popis paleys &middot; she is pryue as my-self,<MILESTONE N="7" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24">But sothenesse wolde nou&yogh;t so &middot; for she is a bastarde.</L>
<L>&para; For fals was hire fader &middot; &thorn;at hath a fykel tonge,</L>
<L>And neuere sothe seide &middot; sithen he come to erthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>come</I>] com WC.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And Mede is manered after hym &middot; ri&yogh;te as kynde axeth;<Q><I>Qualis pater, talis filius;</I> [<I>bona</I>] <I>arbor bonum fructum facit</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>axeth</I>] aske&thorn; WO; askes C. [<I>bona</I>] <I>So in</I> CC2; bonus LWO. <I>fructum</I>] fructum (<I>printed</I> fructrum) W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">I au&yogh;te ben herre &thorn;an she &middot; I cam of a better.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>au&yogh;te</I>] ou&yogh;te W. <I>herre</I>] hyere W; heyer O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Mi fader &thorn;e grete god is &middot; and grounde of alle graces,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>graces</I>] grace C.</NOTE></L>
<L>O god with-oute gynnynge &middot; &amp; I his gode dou&yogh;ter,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O</I>] Oo (<I>printed</I> So) W. <I>his</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hath &yogh;oue me mercy &middot; to marye with my-self;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;oue</I>] yeuen W; geue C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">And what man be merciful &middot; and lelly me loue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>loue</I>] loue&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Schal be my lorde and I his leef &middot; in &thorn;e hei&yogh;e heuene.</L>
<L>&para; And what man taketh Mede &middot; myne hed dar I legge,</L>
<L>That he shal lese for hir loue &middot; a lappe of <I>caritatis</I>.</L>
<L N="36">How construeth dauid &thorn;e kynge &middot; of men &thorn;at taketh Mede,</L>
<L>And men of &thorn;is molde &middot; &thorn;at meynteneth treuthe,</L>
<L>And how &yogh;e shal saue &yogh;ow-self &middot; &thorn;e Sauter bereth wit|nesse,<Q><I>Domine, quis habitabit in tabernaculo tuo, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shal</I>] shul W; schul O; sal C. <I>&yogh;ow-self</I>] &yogh;ow-seluen O; &yogh;our-self W; &yogh;owre-self C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="23, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; And now worth &thorn;is Mede ymaried &middot; al to a mansed schrewe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al to</I>] vn-to W. <I>mansed</I>] mansed W (<I>see</I> Mr Wright's note); maysed C; <I>in</I> MS. O mansed <I>is glossed by</I> cursid. <I>schrewe</I>] sherewe W; O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">To one fals fikel-tonge &middot; a fendes bi&yogh;ete;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here</I> MS. R <I>begins again. fikel</I>] fikel of R. <I>a</I>] and C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fauel &thorn;orw his faire speche &middot; hath &thorn;is folke enchaunted,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;orw</I>] thourth C. <I>his</I>] hir C. <I>hath</I>] hayth C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al is lyeres ledyng &middot; &thorn;at she is &thorn;us ywedded.</L>
<L>&para; To-morwe worth ymade &middot; &thorn;e maydenes bruydale,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ymade</I>] ymaked W; ymaad O. <I>maydenes</I>] maydesnesse (!) C. <I>bruy|dale</I>] bridale WC; brydale O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">And &thorn;ere mi&yogh;te &thorn;ow wite, if &thorn;ow wolt &middot; which &thorn;ei ben alle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mi&yogh;te &thorn;ow</I>] my&yogh;tow W; my&yogh;tist &thorn;ou O. <I>wolt</I>] wilt WRO.</NOTE></L>
<L>That longeth to &thorn;at lordeship &middot; &thorn;e lasse and &thorn;e more.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>longeth</I>] longen WO.</NOTE></L>
<L>Knowe hem &thorn;ere if &thorn;ow canst &middot; and kepe &thorn;i tonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kepe</I>] kepe &thorn;ow W; kepe wel O; kepen R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lakke hem nou&yogh;t, but lat hem worth &middot; til lewte be iustice,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lewte</I>] leaute W; leute O; leaut C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">And haue powere to punyschen hem &middot; &thorn;anne put forth &thorn;i resoun.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="19"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;anne</I>] &thorn;at C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Now I bikenne &thorn;e criste," quod she &middot; "and his clene moder,</L>
<L>And lat no conscience acombre &thorn;e &middot; for coueitise of Mede."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lat</I>] at R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thus left me &thorn;at lady &middot; liggyng aslepe,</L>
<L N="52">And how Mede was ymaried &middot; in meteles me &thorn;ou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e riche retenauns &middot; &thorn;at regneth with &thorn;e false<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>retenauns</I>] retenaunce WO; retenaunt&yogh; C; retenawans R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were boden to &thorn;e bridale &middot; on bothe two sydes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>boden</I>] bede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of alle maner of men &middot; &thorn;e mene and &thorn;e riche.</L>
<L N="56">To marie &thorn;is maydene &middot; was many man assembled,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>was</I>] were W. <I>man</I>] men W.</NOTE></L>
<L>As of kni&yogh;tes and of clerkis &middot; and other comune poeple,</L>
<L>As sysours and sompnours &middot; Shireues and here clerkes,<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sompnours</I>] somonours W; sumpnoures RO.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bedelles and Bailliues &middot; and brokoures of chaff[a]re,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chaffare</I> WCO] chaffre L.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="24, B-text"></L>
<L N="60">Forgoeres and vitaillers &middot; and vokates of &thorn;e arches;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vokates</I>] aduokettes W.</NOTE></L>
<L>I can nou&yogh;t rekene &thorn;e route &middot; &thorn;at ran aboute mede.</L>
<L>&para; Ac Symonye and cyuile &middot; and sisoures of courtes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were moste pryue with Mede &middot; of any men, me &thorn;ou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>me</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">Ac fauel was &thorn;e first &middot; &thorn;at fette hire out of boure,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as a brokour brou&yogh;te hir &middot; to be with fals enioigned.<NOTE PLACE="foot">O <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan Symonye and cyuile &middot; sei&yogh; here beire wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>beire</I>] <I>so also</I> C; bo&thorn;er (<I>printed</I> bothe) W; bo&thorn;er O; bethere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thei assented for siluer &middot; to sei as bothe wolde.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="20"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Thei</I>] And R. <I>sei</I>] seggen R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thanne lepe lyer forth, and seide &middot; "lo here! a chartre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lepe</I>] leep W; leup R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="69">That gyle with his gret othes &middot; gaf hem togidere,"</L>
<L>And preide cyuile to se &middot; and symonye to rede it.</L>
<L>Thanne Symonye and cyuile &middot; stonden forth bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stonden</I>] stondeth R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">And vnfoldeth &thorn;e feffement &middot; &thorn;at fals hath ymaked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>feffement</I>] feffament C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us bigynneth &thorn;es gomes &middot; to greden ful hei&yogh;:&mdash;<Q><I>"Sciant presentes &amp; futuri, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gomes</I>] gromes C. <I>to</I>] at R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Witeth and witnesseth &middot; &thorn;at wonieth vpon &thorn;is erthe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Mede is y-maried &middot; more for here goodis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-maried</I>] maried C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">&THORN;an for ani vertue or fairenesse &middot; or any free kynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vertue</I>] vertus C. <I>or</I> (1)] of CO. <I>or</I> (2)] or for O. <I>kynde</I>] kyne C; kende R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Falsenesse is faine of hire &middot; for he wote hire riche;</L>
<L>And fauel with his fikel speche &middot; feffeth bi &thorn;is chartre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>speche</I>] felaw O.</NOTE></L>
<L>To be prynces in pryde &middot; and pouerte to dispise,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>prynces</I>] princesse O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">To bakbite, and to bosten &middot; and bere fals witnesse,</L>
<L>To scorne and to scolde &middot; and sclaundere to make,</L>
<L>Vnboxome and bolde &middot; to breke &thorn;e ten hestes;&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>begins</I>, Bold and vnbuxum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;e Erldome of enuye &middot; and Wratthe togideres,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e chastelet of chest &middot; and chateryng-oute-of-resoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chastelet</I>] chastilet WO. <I>cheste</I>] cleste C; gestes R. <I>resoun</I>] tyme R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">&THORN;e counte of coueitise &middot; and alle &thorn;e costes aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>counte</I>] countee WCRO. <I>costes</I>] coostes O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000307.tif" N="25, B-text"></L>
<L>That is, vsure and auarice &middot; alle I hem graunte,</L>
<L>In bargaines and in brokages &middot; with al &thorn;e [borghe] of theft;&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>borghe</I> CR] burghe WO; L <I>has</I> borgthe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">&para; And al &thorn;e lordeship of lecherye &middot; in lenthe and in brede,</L>
<L>As in werkes and in wordes &middot; and waitynges with eies,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>waitynges</I>] in waitynges W; wattynges C. <I>eies</I>] ei&yogh;es W; yen O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in wedes and in wisshynges &middot; and with ydel thou&yogh;tes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wedes</I>] wedynges R. <I>in</I> (2)] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="91">There as wille wolde &middot; and wer[k]manship failleth."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolde</I>] ne wolde LC; <I>but</I> ne <I>must be omitted, as in</I> WRO; <I>see note. werkmanship</I>] wermanship L (<I>by mis|take;</I> WCRO <I>preserve the</I> k)</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Glotonye he gaf hem eke &middot; and grete othes togydere,</L>
<L>And alday to drynke &middot; at dyuerse tauernes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] with R. <I>ar</I>] er WCO.</NOTE></L>
<L>And there to iangle and to iape &middot; and iugge here euene cristene,</L>
<L N="95">And in fastyng-dayes to frete &middot; ar ful tyme were.</L>
