<L>Tyl pardoneres haued pite &middot; and pulled hym in-to house.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>haued</I>] hadde W; hadden O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">They wesshen hym and wyped hym &middot; and wonden hym in cloutes,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="27"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wonden</I>] wounden WCO. <I>hym</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sente hym with seles &middot; on sondayes to cherches,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sente</I>] senten W; sent R. <I>cherches</I>] kyrkees C; chirche O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gaf pardoun for pens &middot; poundmel aboute.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gaf</I>] yeuen W. <I>pens</I>] pans R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000313.tif" N="31, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; Thanne loured leches &middot; and lettres &thorn;ei sent,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at he sholde wonye with hem &middot; wateres to loke.</L>
<L>Spiceres spoke with hym &middot; to spien here ware,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spoke</I>] spoken O; speken WR; spake C. <I>with</I>] to R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he couth of here craft &middot; and knewe many gommes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of here</I>] on here R; of hir WC. <I>gommes</I>] gummes R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac mynst[r]alles and messageres &middot; mette with hym ones,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And WC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="228">And helden hym an half-&yogh;ere &middot; and elleuene dayes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an half-&yogh;ere</I>] half a &yogh;ere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Freres with faire speche &middot; fetten hym &thorn;ennes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>] with hir C. <I>&thorn;ennes</I>] &thorn;ennes (<I>printed</I> pennes) W; theynnes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for knowyng of comeres &middot; coped hym as a frere.</L>
<L>Ac he hath leue to lepe out &middot; as oft as hym liketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="232">And is welcome whan he wil &middot; and woneth wyth hem oft.</L>
<L>&para; Alle fledden for fere &middot; and flowen in-to hernes,</L>
<L>Saue Mede &thorn;e Mayde &middot; na mo durst abide.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>na mo</I>] nama C; no moo O; no man R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac trewli to telle &middot; she trembled for drede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>she&mdash;drede</I>] heo tremeled for fere R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="236">And ek wept and wronge &middot; whan she was attached.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ek</I>] al-so R. <I>whan</I>] R <I>om. she</I>] heo R.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000314.tif" N="32, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS III.</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>TITLE; Passus tertius O; Passus iijus L; Passus Tertius de visione, C; <I>to which</I> W <I>adds</I> vt supra; <I>and</I> R <I>adds</I> petri plowman, vt supra, &amp;c.</P><P>OBS. <I>Occasional readings from</I> MS. B (Bodley 814) <I>are given in lines</I> 1-86; <I>after which it is more closely collated. See</I> Note.</P></NOTE><I>Passus tertius</I>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">Now is Mede &thorn;e Mayde &middot; and namo of hem alle<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="28"></L>
<L>With bedellus &amp; wi&thorn; bayllyues &middot; brou&yogh;t bifor &thorn;e kyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wi&thorn;</I>] BO <I>om. bayllyues</I>] baillies W; baylis O; baillifs C. <I>brou&yogh;t</I>] ybrou&yogh;t RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>The kyng called a clerke &middot; can I nou&yogh;t his name,</L>
<L N="4">To take Mede &thorn;e mayde &middot; and make hire at ese.</L>
<L>"I shal assaye hir my-self &middot; and sothelich appose<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sothelich</I>] couthliche R.</NOTE></L>
<L>What man of &thorn;is molde &middot; &thorn;at hire were leueste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>] C <I>om. molde</I>] world RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And if she worche bi my witte &middot; and my wille folwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits. my</I> (1)] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">I wil forgyue hir &thorn;is gilte &middot; so me god help!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is gilte</I>] &thorn;is gultes R; &thorn;e gilt B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Curteysliche &thorn;e clerke &thorn;anne &middot; as &thorn;e Kyng hight,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;anne</I>] C <I>om. hight</I>] hym hy&yogh;t B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Toke Mede bi &thorn;e Middel &middot; and brou&yogh;te hir in-to chaumbre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>into</I>] in O; to B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ere was myrthe and mynstralcye &middot; Mede to plese.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] forto B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">&para; They &thorn;at wonyeth in Westmynstre &middot; worschiped hir alle;<MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>worschiped</I>] worschipeden O; worshipe&thorn; WB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gentelliche wi&thorn; ioye &middot; &thorn;e Iustices somme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>somme</I>] comen O; sone B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Busked hem to &thorn;e boure &middot; &thorn;ere &thorn;e birde dwelled,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] hym B. <I>birde</I>] burde W; buyrde R; berde B; bryde O; bred C2.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="33, B-text"></L>
<L>To conforte hire kyndely &middot; by clergise leue,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="29"></L>
<L N="16">And seiden, "mourne nought, Mede &middot; ne make &thorn;ow no sorwe,</L>
<L>For we [wil] wisse &thorn;e kynge &middot; and &thorn;i wey shape,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>wil</I> R] willen B; wol W; LCO <I>om. shape</I>] make B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To be wedded at &thorn;i wille &middot; and where &thorn;e leue liketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits. leue</I>] leef W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For al conscience caste &middot; or craft, as I trowe!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>conscience</I>] Consciences W. <I>caste&mdash;craft</I>] crafte &middot; and cast R; cast a craft B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&para; Mildeliche Mede &thorn;anne &middot; mercyed hem alle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;eire gret goodnesse &middot; and gaf hem vchone<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;eire</I>] hire W; her O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Coupes of clene golde &middot; and coppis of siluer,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>coppis</I>] cuppes RO; pecis B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rynges with rubies &middot; and ricchesses manye,</L>
<L N="24">The leste man of here meyne &middot; a motoun of golde.</L>
<L>Thanne lau&yogh;te &thorn;ei leue &middot; &thorn;is lordes, at Mede.</L>
<L>&para; With that comen clerkis &middot; to conforte hir &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>And beden hire be blithe &middot; "for we beth &thorn;ine owne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>beden</I>] biden C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">For to worche &thorn;i wille &middot; &thorn;e while &thorn;ow my&yogh;te laste."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e&mdash;laste</I>] while our lif laste&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hendeliche heo &thorn;anne &middot; bihight hem &thorn;e same,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heo</I>] sho C; sche O; she B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To "loue &yogh;ow lelli &middot; and lordes to make,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ow</I>] hem WCOB. <I>lelly</I>] lealy C; lely R; leely B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e consistorie atte courte &middot; do calle &yogh;owre names;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] O <I>om. consistorie</I>] con|storie RB. <I>&yogh;owre</I>] hire W. <I>names</I>] name O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">Shal no lewdnesse lette &middot; &thorn;e leode &thorn;at I louye,</L>
<L>That he ne worth first auanced &middot; for I am biknowen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] R <I>om. auanced</I>] vaunsed R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere konnyng clerkes &middot; shul clokke bihynde."<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="30"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>clokke</I>] <I>so in</I> LWCROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne come &thorn;ere a confessoure &middot; coped as a Frere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>come</I>] cam W; com RB. <I>coped</I>] ycoped R; caped C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">To Mede &thorn;e mayde &middot; he mellud &thorn;is wordes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mellud</I>] melled C; mellid B; mened W; medelede O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide ful softly &middot; in shrifte as it were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>softly</I>] sotely R.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Thei&yogh; lewed men and lered men &middot; had leyne by &thorn;e bothe,</L>
<L>And falsenesse haued yfolwed &thorn;e &middot; al &thorn;is fyfty wyntre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits. falsenesse</I>] falsede R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="34, B-text"></L>
<L N="40">I shal assoille &thorn;e my-selue &middot; for a seme of whete,</L>
<L>And also be &thorn;i bedeman &middot; and bere wel &thorn;i message,</L>
<L>Amonges kni&yogh;tes and clerkis &middot; conscience to torne."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>torne</I>] turne ROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thanne Mede for here mysdedes &middot; to &thorn;at man kneled,</L>
<L N="44">And shroue hire of hire shrewednesse &middot; shamelees, I trowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shroue</I>] shrof WR; shroof B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tolde hym a tale &middot; and toke hym a noble,</L>
<L>Forto ben hire bedeman &middot; and hire brokour als.</L>
<L>&para; Thanne he assoilled hir sone &middot; and sithen he seyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he seyde</I>] a sayde R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">"We han a wyndowe a wirchyng &middot; wil sitten vs [ful] heigh;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> (2)] in W. [<I>ful</I>] <I>So in</I> WCROB; L <I>has</I> wel. Cf. Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L>Woldestow glase &thorn;at gable &middot; and graue &thorn;ere-inne &thorn;i name,</L>
<L>Siker sholde &thorn;i soule be &middot; heuene to haue."</L>
<L>"Wist I that," quod &thorn;at womman &middot; "I wolde nou&yogh;t spare<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="52">For to be &yogh;owre frende, frere &middot; and faille &yogh;ow neure</L>
<L>Whil &yogh;e loue lordes &middot; &thorn;at lechery haunte&thorn;,</L>
<L>And lakke&thorn; nou&yogh;t ladis &middot; &thorn;at loue&thorn; wel &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>It is a frelete of flesche &middot; &yogh;e fynde it in bokes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] W <I>retains</I> a, <I>omitted in the printed copy. &yogh;e</I>] &thorn;ei B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="56">And a course of kynde &middot; wher-of we komen alle;</L>
<L>Who may scape &thorn;e sklaundre &middot; &thorn;e ska&thorn;e is sone amended;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (1)] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>It is synne of [&thorn;e] seuene &middot; sonnest relessed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits</I>. [<I>&thorn;e</I>] <I>inserted in</I> WOC<SUB>2</SUB>; LC <I>om. sonnest</I>] is sonnest O. <I>relessed</I>] for-gyuene C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Haue mercy," quod Mede &middot; "of men &thorn;at it haunte,</L>
<L>And I shal keure &yogh;owre kirke &middot; &yogh;owre cloystre do maken,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>keure</I>] keuere O; kouere C; couere W. <I>&yogh;owre</I> (2)] &amp; &yogh;oure O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="61">Wowes do whitten &middot; and wyndowes glasen,</L>
<L>Do peynten and purtraye &middot; and paye for &thorn;e makynge,
<PB REF="00000317.tif" N="35, B-text"></L>
<L>That eury segge shal seyn &middot; I am sustre of &yogh;owre hous."<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="31"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>51&mdash;63. R <I>has only these four lines</I>&mdash;</P><P>Wist I &thorn;at, quat&yogh; mede &middot; &thorn;ere nys wyn|dow no wow&yogh;,</P><P>&thorn;at y ne wolde make and amende &middot; it with of myne,</P><P>And my name write &middot; openliche &thorn;ere|Inne,</P><P>&thorn;at vch a segge schal I-se &middot; Ich am suster to &yogh;ow alle.</P></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seyn</I>] seye WCO.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac god to alle good folke &middot; suche grauynge defendeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">To writen in wyndowes &middot; of here wel dedes,</L>
<L>On auenture pruyde be peynted &thorn;ere &middot; and pompe of &thorn;e worlde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>On</I>] An W; And CR; In B. <I>peynted</I>] ypeynted R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For crist knowe&thorn; &thorn;i conscience &middot; and &thorn;i kynde wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crist</I>] god R. <I>kynde</I>] kende R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;i coste and &thorn;i coueitise &middot; and who &thorn;e catel ou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="69">&para; For-&thorn;i I lere &yogh;ow, lordes &middot; leue&thorn; suche werkes,</L>
<L>To writen in wyndowes &middot; of &yogh;owre wel dedes,</L>
<L>Or to greden after goddis men &middot; whan &yogh;e delen doles;</L>
<L N="72">An auenture &yogh;e han &yogh;owre hire here &middot; and &yogh;oure heuene als;<Q><I>Nesciat sinistra quid faciat dextra</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>An</I>] On WCO; In B. <I>han</I>] haue W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lat nou&yogh;te &thorn;i left half &middot; late [ne] rathe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>ne</I>] <I>so in</I> WCRB; LO <I>have</I> no. Cf. Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyte what &thorn;ow worchest &middot; with &thorn;i ri&yogh;t syde;</L>
<L>For &thorn;us bit &thorn;e gospel &middot; gode men do here almesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] And O. <I>bit</I>] bitt R; bid|di&thorn; B. <I>In</I> W <I>miswritten</I> by, <I>as printed</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">&para; Meires and maceres &middot; that menes ben bitwene</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynge and &thorn;e comune &middot; to kepe &thorn;e lawes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kepe</I>] kepe wel O.</NOTE></L>
<L>To punyschen on pillories &middot; and pynynge stoles<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] vppon R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Brewesteres and bakesteres &middot; bocheres and cokes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bakesteres</I>] baxters C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">For &thorn;ise aren men on &thorn;is molde &middot; &thorn;at moste harme worcheth<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] vppon R; of B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e pore peple &middot; &thorn;at parcel-mele buggen.</L>
<L>&para; For they poysoun &thorn;e peple &middot; priueliche and oft,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="32"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For&mdash;poysoun</I>] And also poy|sene R. <I>poysoun</I>] enpoisone W; punyschen O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thei rychen &thorn;orw regraterye &middot; and rentes hem buggen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>buggen</I>] biggen WO; bieggen B.</NOTE></L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e pore people &middot; shulde put in here wombe;</L>
<L N="85">For toke &thorn;ei on trewly &middot; &thorn;ei tymbred nou&yogh;t so hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Ne bou&yogh;te non burgages &middot; be &yogh;e ful certeyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>burgages</I>] burgage R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="36, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; Ac Mede &thorn;e Mayde &middot; &thorn;e Maire hath bisou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">Of alle suche sellers &middot; syluer to take,</L>
<L>Or present&yogh; with-oute pens &middot; as peces of siluer,<MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>] And B. <I>pens</I>] pans R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ringes or other ricchesse &middot; &thorn;e regrateres to maynetene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or other</I>] other othere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "For my loue," quod that lady &middot; "loue hem vchone,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>loue</I>] lord R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="92">And soffre hem to selle &middot; somdele a&yogh;eins resoun."</L>
<L>&para; Salamon &thorn;e sage &middot; a sarmoun he made,</L>
<L>For to amende Maires &middot; and men &thorn;at kepen lawes,</L>
<L>And tolde hem &thorn;is teme &middot; &thorn;at I telle thynke;<Q><I>Ignis deuorabit tabernacula eorum qui libenter accipiunt munera, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>thynke</I>] <I>written</I> thynko <I>in</I> L; &thorn;ynke W; thenke CRO. <I>accipiunt munera</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="96">Amonge &thorn;is lettered ledes &middot; &thorn;is latyn is to mene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">O <I>omits. ledes</I>] lede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>That fyre shal falle, and [brenne] &middot; al to blo askes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>That</I>] &thorn;at is O. [<I>brenne</I> WCOB] <I>preferable to</I> berne, <I>as in</I> L.</NOTE></L>
<L>The houses and &thorn;e homes &middot; of hem [&thorn;at] desireth<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e homes</I>] homes W. [<I>&thorn;at</I> WCROB] L <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;iftes or &yogh;eres&yogh;yues &middot; bi-cause of here offices.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;eres&yogh;yues</I>] &yogh;ere&yogh;iftes R; yeres|yiftes C. <I>offices</I>] office R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; The kynge fro conseille cam &middot; and called after Mede,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="33"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fro</I>] fro &thorn;e W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="101">And ofsent hir alswythe &middot; with seriauntes manye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alswythe</I>] as swi&thorn;e WC; also swi&thorn;e B. <I>seriauntes</I>] sergeauntz W; sergeauntes CO; seruauntis B.</NOTE></L>
<L>That brou&yogh;ten hir to bowre &middot; with blisse and with ioye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>That</I>] And W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Curteisliche &thorn;e kynge &thorn;anne &middot; comsed to telle,</L>
<L N="104">To Mede &thorn;e mayde &middot; melleth &thorn;ise wordes:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>melleth</I>] he mene&thorn; W.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Vnwittily, womman! &middot; wrou&yogh;te hastow oft,</L>
<L>Ac worse wrou&yogh;testow neure &middot; &thorn;an &thorn;o &thorn;ow fals toke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>But I forgyue [&thorn;e] &thorn;at gilte &middot; and graunte &thorn;e my grace;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;ee WO; &thorn;e R; &thorn;o (<I>by mistake for</I> &thorn;e) CB; L <I>om</I>. Cf. Text A. <I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;is O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">Hennes to &thorn;i deth day &middot; do so namore!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I>] to do R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I haue a kny&yogh;te, conscience &middot; cam late fro bi&yogh;unde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi&yogh;unde</I> LR] biyonde WCO.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if he wilneth &thorn;e to wyf &middot; wyltow hym haue?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyf</I>] wyue RB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="37, B-text"></L>
<L N="111">"&YOGH;e, lorde," quod &thorn;at lady &middot; "lorde forbede elles!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>forbede</I>] forbede it W. <I>lorde&mdash;elles</I>] lord it me forbede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>But I be holely at &yogh;owre heste &middot; lat hange me sone!"</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;anne was conscience calde &middot; to come and appiere<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="34"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>calde</I>] called WCO; Icalled R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e Kynge and his conseille &middot; as clerkes and othere.</L>
<L N="115">Knelynge conscience &middot; to &thorn;e kynge louted,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>louted</I>] a-lowtid B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To wite what his wille were &middot; and what he do shulde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shulde</I>] wolde W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="117">&para; "Woltow wedde &thorn;is womman," quod &thorn;e kynge &middot; "&yogh;if I wil assente,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] she B. <I>Woltow</I>] Wiltow CR; wilt &thorn;ou OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she is fayne of &thorn;i felawship &middot; for to be &thorn;i make?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fayne</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Quod conscience to &thorn;e kynge &middot; "cryst it me forbede!</L>
<L N="120">Ar I wedde suche a wyf &middot; wo me bityde!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ar</I>] Er WCROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she is frele of hir feith &middot; fykel of here speche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fykel</I>] and fykel R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And maketh men mysdo &middot; many score tymes;</L>
<L>Truste of hire tresore &middot; treieth ful manye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>treieth</I>] bitraye&thorn; W; bitraie&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="124">Wyues and widewes &middot; wantounes she techeth,<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wantounes</I>] <I>It may be</I> wanton|nes, <I>the reading being uncertain in</I> W <I>and</I> C; <I>but cf</I>. wantownesse RO.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lereth hem leccherye &middot; that loueth hire &yogh;iftes.</L>
<L>&YOGH;owre fadre she felled &middot; &thorn;orw fals biheste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>she</I>] he R; O <I>om. fals</I>] faire R; hire fals B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hath apoysounde popis &middot; [&amp;] peired holicherche;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>apoysounde</I>] a-poysowned O; apoisunde C; appoysond R; apoisoned B; enpoisoned W. <I>peired</I>] and peired WO; and appayreth R. L <I>omits</I> &amp;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="128">Is nau&yogh;t a better baude &middot; bi hym &thorn;at me made,</L>
<L>Bitwene heuene and helle &middot; in erthe &thorn;ough men sou&yogh;te!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] and R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she is tikil of hire taile &middot; talwis of hir tonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tikil</I>] fikil O. <I>talwis</I>] and talewis W. <I>hir</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>As comune as a cartwey &middot; to eche a knaue &thorn;at walketh,</L>
<L N="132">To monkes, to mynst[r]alles &middot; to meseles in hegges.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="35"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I> (2)] and to R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sisoures and sompnoures &middot; suche men hir preiseth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sompnoures</I>] Somonours W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shireues of shires &middot; were shent &yogh;if she nere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nere</I>] ne were W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she do&thorn; men lese here londe &middot; and here lyf bothe.
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="38, B-text"></L>
<L>She leteth passe prisoneres &middot; and payeth for hem ofte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leteth</I>] lat R; lates C; late&thorn; B. <I>prisoneres</I>] prisons R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="137">And gyueth &thorn;e gailers golde &middot; and grotes togideres,</L>
<L>To vnfettre &thorn;e fals &middot; fle where hym lyketh;</L>
<L>And take&thorn; &thorn;e trewe bi &thorn;e toppe &middot; and tieth hym faste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e trewe</I>] trewthe R. <I>hym</I>] hem W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hangeth hym for hatred &middot; &thorn;at harme dede neure.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] hem W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="141">&para; To be cursed in consistorie &middot; she counteth nou&yogh;te a russhe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>consistorie</I>] constorie RB. <I>she</I>] he R. <I>russhe</I>] resshe C; rische O; reische B; bene W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she copeth &thorn;e comissarie &middot; and coteth his clerkis;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>she</I>] he R.</NOTE></L>
<L>She is assoilled as sone &middot; as hir-self liketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as</I> (1)] al-so B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">And may nei&yogh;e as moche do &middot; in a moneth one[s],<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>neize</I>] nee C. <I>as</I>] al-so B. [<I>ones</I> ROB] one LWC. Cf. Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &yogh;owre secret seel &middot; in syx score dayes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;owre</I>] oure O.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she is priue with &thorn;e pope &middot; prouisoures it knoweth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>she</I>] he R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sire symonye and hir-selue &middot; seleth hire bulles.</L>
<L N="148">&para; She blesseth &thorn;ise bisshopes &middot; &thorn;ei&yogh;e &thorn;ey be lewed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei&yogh;e&mdash;persones</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prouendreth persones &middot; and prestes meynteneth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei&yogh;e&mdash;persones</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To haue lemmannes and lotebies &middot; alle here lif dayes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lif dayes</I>] lyues dayes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bringen forth barnes &middot; a&yogh;ein forbode lawes.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="36"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bringen</I>] brynge&thorn; WB. <I>for|bode</I>] forboden O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="152">There she is wel with &thorn;e kynge &middot; wo is &thorn;e rewme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rewme</I>] reaume W; reame C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For she is fauorable to &thorn;e fals &middot; and fouleth trewthe ofte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] W <I>om. fouleth</I>] defoule&thorn; W; folwe&thorn; CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Bi ihesus, with here ieweles &middot; &yogh;owre iustices she shendeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;owre</I>] &thorn;e R. <I>she</I>] heo R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lith a&yogh;ein &thorn;e lawe &middot; and letteth hym &thorn;e gate,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>letteth</I>] let R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="156">That feith may nou&yogh;te haue his forth &middot; here floreines go so &thorn;ikke.</L>
<L>She ledeth &thorn;e lawe as hire list &middot; and louedayes maketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ledeth</I>] let R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And doth men lese &thorn;orw hire loue &middot; &thorn;at lawe my&yogh;te wynne,
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="39, B-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;e mase for a mene man &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; he mote hir eure.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mote hire</I>] moote heer O; mute here C2.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">Lawe is so lordeliche &middot; and loth to make ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>make</I>] make an O.</NOTE></L>
<L>With-oute present&yogh; or pens &middot; she pleseth wel fewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pens</I>] pans R. <I>she</I>] he R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Barounes and burgeys &middot; she bryngeth in sorwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>burgeys</I>] burgeises W. <I>she</I>] heo R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e comune in kare &middot; &thorn;at coueyten lyue in trewthe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>comune in</I>] comunes into O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="164">For clergye and coueitise &middot; she coupleth togideres.</L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;e lyf of that lady &middot; now lorde &yogh;if hir sorwe!<MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And alle that meynteneth here men &middot; meschaunce hem bityde!</L>
<L>For pore men mowe haue no powere &middot; to pleyne hem &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei smerte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pore</I>] pouere W. <I>hem</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="168">Suche a maistre is Mede &middot; amonge men of gode."</L>
<L>&para; Thanne morned Mede &middot; and mened hire to the kynge,</L>
<L>To haue space to speke &middot; spede if she my&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>she</I>] a R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; The kynge graunted hir grace &middot; with a gode wille;</L>
<L N="172">"Excuse &thorn;e, &yogh;if &thorn;ow canst &middot; I can namore seggen,</L>
<L>For conscience acuseth &thorn;e &middot; to congey &thorn;e for euere."<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="37"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>congey</I>] congeien W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Nay, lorde," quod &thorn;at lady &middot; "leueth hym &thorn;e worse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leueth</I>] leue R; leues C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan &yogh;e wyten witterly &middot; where &thorn;e wronge liggeth;</L>
<L N="176">There &thorn;at myschief is grete &middot; Mede may helpe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ow knowest, conscience &middot; I cam nou&yogh;t to chide,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ow</I>] &thorn;at &thorn;ow R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne depraue &thorn;i persone &middot; with a proude herte.</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;ow wost, wernard &middot; but &yogh;if &thorn;ow wolt gabbe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wost</I>] woost W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">&THORN;ow hast hanged on myne half &middot; elleuene tymes,</L>
<L>And also griped my golde &middot; gyue it where &thorn;e liked;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>griped</I>] Igripe R. <I>gyue</I>] and &yogh;af B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And whi &thorn;ow wratthest &thorn;e now &middot; wonder me thynketh.</L>
<L N="183">&YOGH;it I may as I my&yogh;te &middot; menske &thorn;e with &yogh;iftes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>menske</I>] amende B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And mayntene &thorn;i manhode &middot; more &thorn;an &thorn;ow knoweste.</L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;ow hast famed me foule &middot; bifor &thorn;e Kynge here.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="40, B-text"></L>
<L>For kulled I neuere no kynge &middot; ne conseilled &thorn;er-after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kynge</I>] kni&yogh;t R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="187">Ne dede as &thorn;ow demest &middot; I do [it] on &thorn;e kynge!<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>it</I> WRO; <I>hit</I> B] LC <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; In normandye was he nou&yogh;te &middot; noyed for my sake;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>noyed</I>] Inuyed R; anoied B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ow &thorn;i-self sothely &middot; shamedest hym ofte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Crope in-to a kaban &middot; for colde of &thorn;i nailles,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Crope</I>] And crope B. <I>kabane</I>] Cabane W; caban CO.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wendest &thorn;at wyntre &middot; wolde haue lasted euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>haue lasted</I>] han y-lasted W; a last R. <I>lasted</I>] durid O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="192">And draddest to be ded &middot; for a dym cloude,</L>
<L>And hiedest homeward &middot; for hunger of &thorn;i wombe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hiedest</I>] hyedest &thorn;ee O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn;-out pite, piloure &middot; pore men &thorn;ow robbedest,</L>
<L>And bere here bras at &thorn;i bakke &middot; to caleys to selle.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="38"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bere</I>] bare CO.</NOTE></L>
<L N="196">There I lafte with my lorde &middot; his lyf for to saue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lafte</I>] lefte R.</NOTE></L>
<L>I made his men meri &middot; and mornyng lette.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lette</I>] lettede O.</NOTE></L>
<L>I batered hem on &thorn;e bakke &middot; and bolded here hertis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] And I O. <I>batered</I>] batred W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dede hem hoppe for hope &middot; to haue me at wille.</L>
<L>Had I ben Marschal of his men &middot; bi Marie of heuene!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="201">I durst haue leyde my lyf &middot; and no lasse wedde,</L>
<L>He shulde haue be lorde of &thorn;at londe &middot; a lengthe and a brede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] in (<I>in both places</I>) W. <I>of</I>] of al B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also Kyng of &thorn;at kitthe &middot; his kynne for to helpe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] of al B. <I>kitthe</I>] ki&thorn; WB &middot; kyth R; ki&thorn;&thorn;e O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="204">&THORN;e leste brolle of his blode &middot; a barounes pere!<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brolle</I>] brol WR. <I>blode</I>] kynne CB. <I>pere</I>] piere WC.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Cowardliche &thorn;ow, conscience &middot; conseiledest hym &thorn;ennes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ennes</I>] &thorn;anne O.</NOTE></L>
<L>To leuen his lordeship &middot; for a litel siluer,</L>
<L>That is &thorn;e richest rewme &middot; &thorn;at reyne ouer houeth!</L>
<L N="208">&para; It bicometh to a kynge &middot; &thorn;at kepeth a rewme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> (2)] &thorn;e COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &yogh;iue Mede to men &middot; &thorn;at mekelich hym serueth,</L>
<L>To alienes and to alle men &middot; to honoure hem with &yogh;iftes;</L>
<L>Mede makoth hym biloued &middot; and for a man holden.
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="41, B-text"></L>
<L N="212">Emperoures and Erlis &middot; and al manere lordes</L>
<L>For &yogh;iftes han &yogh;onge men &middot; to renne and to ride.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] &thorn;ur&yogh; R. <I>&yogh;onge men</I>] &yogh;oumen R. <I>renne</I>] &yogh;ernen R.</NOTE></L>
<L>The pope and alle prelatis &middot; present&yogh; vnderfongen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alle</I>] alle &thorn;e W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And medeth men hem-seluen &middot; to meyntene here lawes.</L>
<L N="216">Seruauntz for her seruise &middot; we seth wel &thorn;e sothe,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="39"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Seruauntz</I>] Sergeauntz W. <I>seth</I>] se C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Taken Mede of here maistre &middot; as &thorn;ei mowe acorde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maistre</I>] mayster O; maistres WCB; meystres R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beggeres for here biddynge &middot; bidden men Mede;</L>
<L>Mynstralles for here murthe &middot; mede &thorn;ei aske.</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e kynge hath mede of his men &middot; to make pees in londe;</L>
<L>Men &thorn;at teche chyldren &middot; craue of hem mede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of hem</I>] after W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prestis &thorn;at precheth &thorn;e poeple &middot; to gode, asken mede,</L>
<L>And masse-pans and here mete &middot; at &thorn;e mele tymes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] R <I>om. mele</I>] male O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alkynnes crafty men &middot; crauen Mede for here prentis;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Alkynnes</I>] Alle kynne W; Alle kyns O. <I>crafty</I>] craftes W. <I>prentis</I>] Prentices WO; prentyces R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">Marchauntz and Mede &middot; mote nede go togideres;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mote</I>] most R.</NOTE></L>
<L>No wi&yogh;te as I wene &middot; with-oute Mede may libbe."</L>
<L>&para; [Quod] &thorn;e kynge to conscience &middot; "bi criste! as me thynketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Quod</I> WCROB] Quat&yogh; L.</NOTE></L>
<L N="228">Mede is wel worthi &middot; &thorn;e maistrye to haue!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel</I>] R <I>om.</I> 230. <I>with</I>] by R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Nay," quod conscience to &thorn;e Kynge &middot; and kneled to &thorn;e erthe,</L>
<L>"There aren two manere of Medes &middot; my lorde, with &yogh;owre leue.</L>
<L>&THORN;at one, god of his grace &middot; graunteth in his blisse</L>
<L N="232">To &thorn;o &thorn;at wel worchen &middot; whil &thorn;ei ben here.</L>
<L>The prophete precheth &thorn;er-of &middot; and put it in &thorn;e sautere,<Q><I>Domine quis habitabit in tabernaculo tuo?</I></Q></L>
<L>'Lorde, who shal wonye in &thorn;i wones &middot; and with &thorn;ine holi seyntes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="42, B-text"></L>
<L N="235">Or resten on &thorn;i holy hilles?' &middot; &thorn;is asketh dauid;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] in WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And dauyd assoileth it hym-self &middot; as &thorn;e sauter telleth,<Q><I>Qui ingreditur sine macula, &amp; operatur ius|ticiam</I>,</Q></L>
<L>Tho &thorn;at entren of o colour &middot; and of on wille,</L>
<L>And han wrou&yogh;te werkis &middot; with ri&yogh;te and with reson;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wrou&yogh;te</I>] y-wroght W; Iwrou&yogh;t R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he &thorn;at ne vseth nau&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;e lyf of vsurye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">And enfourmeth pore men &middot; and pursueth treuthe;<Q><I>Qui pecuniam suam non dedit ad vsuram, &amp; munera super innocentem, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>innocentem</I>] innocentem B; innocentes O; innoc: LWCR.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at helpeth &thorn;e innocent &middot; and halt with &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful,<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>helpeth</I>] helpen WO. <I>halt</I>] holt R; hold C; holden W; holdi&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>With-oute mede doth hem gode &middot; and &thorn;e trewthe helpeth&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] O <I>om. trewthe</I>] trewe R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Suche manere men, my lorde &middot; shal haue &thorn;is furst Mede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>] &thorn;e O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="244">Of god at a grete nede &middot; whan &thorn;ei gone hennes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] &thorn;e B; O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>There is an-other Mede mesurelees &middot; &thorn;at maistres de|sireth;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="40"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an-other</I>] and other C.</NOTE></L>
<L>To meyntene mysdoers &middot; Mede &thorn;ei take;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-of seith &thorn;e sauter &middot; in a salmes ende,<Q><I>In quorum manibus iniquitates sunt, dextera eorum repleta est-muneribus;</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ere-of</I>] &thorn;er B. <I>sunt</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="248">And he &thorn;at gripeth her golde &middot; so me god helpe!</L>
<L>Shal abie it bittere &middot; or &thorn;e boke lyeth!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bittere</I>] bittirli O; ful bittere R; ful bytterly B. <I>lyeth</I>] lees C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Prestes and parsones &middot; &thorn;at plesynge desireth,</L>
<L>That taketh Mede and [moneie] &middot; for messes &thorn;at &thorn;ei syngeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>taketh</I>] taken WO; takes C; taked R. [<I>moneie</I> WC] money O; moneye B; <I>this seems preferable to the spelling</I> mone LR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="252">Taketh here mede here &middot; as Mathew vs techeth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Taketh</I>] Taken WO; Takes C. </NOTE>
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="43, B-text"><Q><I>Amen, amen,</I> [<I>receperunt</I>] <I>mercedem suam</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>receperunt</I> O] recipiebant LWCRB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; That laboreres and lowe folke &middot; taketh of her maistres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lowe</I>] lewed R. <I>taketh</I>] taken WO.</NOTE></L>
<L>It is no manere Mede &middot; but a mesurable hire.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] nis R. <I>mesurable</I>] reson|abile CB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">In marchandise is no mede &middot; I may it wel a-vowe</L>
<L>It is a permutacioun apertly &middot; a penyworth for an othre.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac reddestow neuere Regum &middot; &thorn;ow recrayed Mede,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="41"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whi &thorn;e veniaunce fel &middot; on Saul and on his children?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>veniaunce</I>] vengeaunce WC.</NOTE></L>
<L>God sent to Saul &middot; bi Samuel &thorn;e prophete,</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at agage of amaleke &middot; and al his peple aftre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shulde deye for a dede &middot; &thorn;at done had here eldres.</L>
<L>&para; 'For-&thorn;i,' seid Samuel to Saul &middot; 'god hym-self hoteth</L>
<L>The, be boxome at his biddynge &middot; his wille to fulfille:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>] to be O. <I>his</I>] is C. <I>his&mdash;to</I>] &amp; his wille O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="264">Wende to amalec with &thorn;yn oste &middot; and what &thorn;ow fyndest &thorn;ere, slee it;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fyndest</I>] fynst R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Biernes and bestes &middot; brenne hem to ded;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brenne</I>] bren W; brynne C. <I>ded</I>] dede CROB; de&thorn;e W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wydwes and wyues &middot; wommen and children,</L>
<L>Moebles and vnmoebles &middot; and al &thorn;at &thorn;ow my&yogh;te fynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Moebles</I>] Mobles C; Mebles ROB. <I>vnmoebles</I>] vnmobles C; vn|mebles ROB. <I>&thorn;at</I>] WO <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Brenne it, bere it nou&yogh;te awey &middot; be it neuere so riche</L>
<L N="269">For mede ne for [moneie]; &middot; loke &thorn;ow destruye it,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] nor C. [<I>moneie</I> C] money OB; monee W; mone LR.</NOTE></L>
<L>Spille it and spare it nou&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;ow shalt spede &thorn;e bettere.'</L>
<L>&para; And for he coueyted her catel &middot; and &thorn;e kynge spared,</L>
<L N="272">Forbare hym and his bestes bothe &middot; as &thorn;e bible wit|nesseth,</L>
<L>Otherwyse &thorn;an he was &middot; warned of &thorn;e prophete,</L>
<L>God seide to Samuel &middot; &thorn;at Saul shulde deye,</L>
<L>And al his sede for &thorn;at synne &middot; shenfullich ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shenfullich</I>] shendfulliche B; shentfulliche R; shenfuliche C. <I>ende</I>] endede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Such a myschief Mede made &middot; Saul &thorn;e kynge to haue,
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="44, B-text"></L>
<L>That god hated hym for euere &middot; and alle his eyres after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eyres</I>] eires O; heires WCRB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="278">The culorum of &thorn;is cas &middot; kepe I nou&yogh;te to shewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shewe</I>] telle W.</NOTE></L>
<L>An auenture it noyed men &middot; none ende wil I make.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="42"><MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>An</I>] On WO; R <I>om. auen|ture</I>] Aunter R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For so is &thorn;is worlde went &middot; wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at han powere,</L>
<L N="281">That who-so seyth hem sothes &middot; is sonnest yblamed.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sothes</I>] so&thorn;est W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I conscience knowe &thorn;is &middot; for kynde witt me it tau&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] <I>retained in</I> W (<I>but not in the printed copy</I>). <I>me it</I>] it me W. <I>it tau&yogh;te</I>] tau&yogh;te it O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at resoun shal regne &middot; and rewmes gouerne;</L>
<L N="284">And ri&yogh;te as agag hadde &middot; happe shul somme.</L>
<L>Samuel shal sleen hym &middot; and Saul shal be blamed,</L>
<L>And dauid shal be diademed &middot; and daunten hem alle,</L>
<L>And one cristene kynge &middot; kepen hem alle.</L>
<L>&para; Shal na more Mede &middot; be maistre, as she is nouthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>she</I>] he R; scho C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="289">Ac loue and lowenesse &middot; and lewte togederes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>lowenesse</I>] lewed|nese C; lewidnesse B. <I>lewte</I>] leautee W; leaute CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ise shul be maistres on molde &middot; treuthe to saue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] of CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And who-so trespasseth ayein treuthe &middot; or taketh a&yogh;ein his wille,</L>
<L N="292">Leute shal don hym lawe &middot; and no lyf elles.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyf</I>] lif WRB; lief C; lijf O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal no seriaunt for here seruyse &middot; were a silke howue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seriaunt</I>] sergeant W; ser|geant CB. <I>here</I>] his W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no pelure in his cloke &middot; for pledyng atte barre.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>atte</I>] at &thorn;e WOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mede of mys-doeres &middot; maketh many lordes,</L>
<L N="296">And ouer lordes lawes &middot; reuleth &thorn;e rewmes.</L>
<L>&para; Ac kynde loue shal come &yogh;it &middot; and conscience to|gideres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>kynde</I>] kende R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And make of lawe a laborere &middot; suche loue shal arise,</L>
<L>And such a pees amonge &thorn;e peple &middot; and a perfit trewthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at iewes shal wene in here witte &middot; and waxen wonder glade,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Moises or Messie &middot; be come in-to &thorn;is erthe,</L>
<L>And haue wonder in here hertis &middot; &thorn;at men beth so trewe.
<PB REF="00000327.tif" N="45, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;at bereth baslarde &middot; brode swerde or launce,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>baslarde</I>] baslard R; base|larde W; baselard CB; basalard O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="304">Axe [other] hachet &middot; or eny wepne ellis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>other</I> R; <I>o&thorn;er</I> OB] ou&thorn;er WC; orther L (<I>corruptly</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal be demed to &thorn;e deth &middot; but if he do it smythye</L>
<L>In-to sikul or to sithe &middot; to schare or to kulter;<Q><I>Conflabunt gladios suos in vomeres, &amp;c.;</I></Q></L>
<L>Eche man to pleye with a plow &middot; pykoys or spade,<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pykoys</I>] pykoise W; pikeys CO; pycoys R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="308">Spynne, or sprede donge &middot; or spille hym-self with sleuthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I> (2)] other R. <I>spille</I>] lese R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Prestes and parsones &middot; with <I>placebo</I> to hunte,</L>
<L>And dyngen vpon dauid &middot; eche a day til eue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] W <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Huntynge or haukynge &middot; if any of hem vse,</L>
<L>His boste of his benefys &middot; worth bynome hym after.</L>
<L N="313">Shal neither kynge ne kny&yogh;te &middot; constable ne Meire</L>
<L>Ouer-lede &thorn;e comune &middot; ne to &thorn;e courte sompne,</L>
<L>Ne put hem in panel &middot; to don hem pli&yogh;te here treuthe,</L>
<L>But after &thorn;e dede &thorn;at is don &middot; one dome shal rewarde,</L>
<L N="317">Mercy or no mercy &middot; as treuthe wil acorde.<MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; Kynges courte and comune courte &middot; consistorie and chapitele,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>consistorie</I>] constorie R. <I>chapitele</I> LR] Chapitle WCO.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>consistorie&mdash;courte</I>] B <I>omits.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Al shal be but one courte &middot; and one baroun be iustice;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>consistorie&mdash;courte</I>] B <I>omits.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>one</I>] oon WC; on R; o O. <I>baroun</I>] C <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Thanne worth trewe-tonge a tidy man &middot; &thorn;at tened me neuere.</L>
<L N="321">Batailles shal non be &middot; ne no man bere wepne,</L>
<L>And what smyth &thorn;at ony smyt[h]eth &middot; be smyte &thorn;er|with to dethe,<Q><I>Non leuabit gens contra gentem gladium, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>smytheth</I>] smy&thorn;e&thorn; WO; smi|thie R; smyteth LCB. <I>smyte</I>] smiten R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And er &thorn;is fortune falle &middot; fynde men shal &thorn;e worste,</L>
<L>By syx sonnes and a schippe &middot; and half a shef of arwes;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e myddel of a mone &middot; shal make &thorn;e iewes to torne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="46, B-text"></L>
<L N="326">And saracenes for &thorn;at si&yogh;te &middot; shulle synge <I>gloria in excelsis, &amp;c</I>.,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;e R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For Makomet &amp; Mede &middot; myshappe shal &thorn;at tyme;<Q>For, <I>melius est bonum nomen quam diuicie multe</I>."</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] And CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Also wroth as &thorn;e wynde &middot; wex Mede in a while,</L>
<L>"I can no latyn," quod she &middot; "clerkis wote &thorn;e sothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wote</I>] wite W; wyten B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="330">Se what Salamon seith &middot; in Sapience bokes,</L>
<L>That hij &thorn;at &yogh;iueth &yogh;iftes &middot; &thorn;e victorie wynneth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hij</I>] &thorn;ei WB; he O. <I>&yogh;iueth</I>] &yogh;yuen W; &yogh;euen B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; moche worschip had &thorn;er-with &middot; as holiwryt telleth,<Q><I>Honorem adquiret qui dat munera, &amp;c</I>."</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moche</I>] moost W; myche O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="333">&para; "I leue wel, lady," quod conscience &middot; "&thorn;at &thorn;i latyne be trewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] <I>retained in</I> W (<I>but not in the printed copy</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ow art like a lady &middot; &thorn;at redde a lessoun ones,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] An C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was, <I>omnia probate</I> &middot; and &thorn;at plesed here herte,</L>
<L N="336">For &thorn;at lyne was no lenger &middot; atte leues ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>] O <I>om</I>. (!)</NOTE></L>
<L>Had [she] loked &thorn;at other half &middot; and &thorn;e lef torned,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>she</I> WC] sche RO; &yogh;e LB (<I>corruptly</I>). <I>torned</I>] Iturned R.</NOTE></L>
<L>[She] shulde haue founden fele wordis &middot; folwyng &thorn;er|after,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>she</I> WC] sche RO; &yogh;e LB (<I>corruptly</I>). <I>torned</I>] Iturned R.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Quod bonum est tenete</I> &middot; treuthe &thorn;at texte made!</L>
<L N="340">&para; And so ferde &yogh;e, madame! &middot; &yogh;e couthe namore fynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>couthe</I>] koude C; coude RO.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tho &yogh;e loked on sapience &middot; sittynge in &yogh;oure studie.</L>
<L>&THORN;is tixte &thorn;at &yogh;e han tolde &middot; were gode for lordes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>han told</I>] haue Itolde R. <I>couthe</I>] coude R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &yogh;ow failled a cunnyng clerke &middot; &thorn;at couthe &thorn;e lef haue torned!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>haue torned</I>] attorned (<I>contr. from</I> a torned) R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="344">And if &yogh;e seche sapience eft &middot; fynde shal &yogh;e &thorn;at folweth,</L>
<L>A ful teneful tixte &middot; to hem &thorn;at taketh Mede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits. taketh</I>] taken O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at is, <I>animam autem aufert</I> &middot; <I>accipientium, &amp;c.:</I>
<PB REF="00000329.tif" N="47, B-text"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at is &thorn;e taille of &thorn;e tixte &middot; of &thorn;at &thorn;at &yogh;e schewed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>] she W. <I>schewed</I>] scheweden O; schede (!) R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="348">&THORN;at &thorn;ei&yogh;e we wynne worschip &middot; and wi&thorn; mede haue victorie,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mede</I>] me (!) R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e soule &thorn;at &thorn;e sonde taketh &middot; bi so moche is bounde."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sonde</I>] son&yogh;d (<I>miswritten for</I> sondz?) R.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000330.tif" N="48, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS IV.</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. <I>vt supra</I>] petri plowman, vt supra R; CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE><I>Passus quartus de visione, vt supra</I>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Cesseth," seith &thorn;e kynge &middot; "I suffre &yogh;ow no lengere.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="43"><MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cesseth</I>] Cesses C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e shal sau&yogh;tne for sothe &middot; and serue me bothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sau&yogh;tne</I>] sau&yogh;tle OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kisse hir," quod &thorn;e kynge &middot; "conscience, I hote."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hote</I>] &thorn;e hote B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">&para; "Nay, bi criste," quod conscience &middot; "congeye me for euere!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I>] er for W. <I>for euere</I>] rather COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>But resoun rede me &thorn;er-to &middot; rather wil I deye!"</L>
<L>&para; "And I comaunde &thorn;e," quod &thorn;e Kynge &middot; to conscience &thorn;anne,</L>
<L>"Rape &thorn;e to ride &middot; and resoun &thorn;ow fecche;</L>
<L N="8">Comaunde hym &thorn;at he come &middot; my conseille to here.</L>
<L>For he shal reule my rewme &middot; and rede me &thorn;e beste,</L>
<L>And acounte with &thorn;e, conscience &middot; so me cryst helpe,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ow lernest &thorn;e peple &middot; &thorn;e lered and &thorn;e lewede."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e lered</I>] lered R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "I am fayne of &thorn;at forwarde" &middot; seyde &thorn;e freke &thorn;anne,</L>
<L N="13">And ritt ri&yogh;te to resoun &middot; and rowneth in his ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ritt</I>] ryt W; rit CO; ridi&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide as &thorn;e kynge badde &middot; and sithen toke his leue.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="44"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sithen</I>] sithes R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "I shal arraye me to ride, quod resoun &middot; "reste &thorn;e a while"&mdash;</L>
<L N="16">And called catoun his knaue &middot; curteise of speche,</L>
<L>And also tomme trewe-tonge- &middot; telle-me-no-tales|</L>
<L>Ne-lesyng-to-law&yogh;e-of &middot; for-I-loued-hem-neuere&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>law&yogh;e</I>] lau&yogh;en W; laughe C; lawe R; lau&yogh;he O; lau&yogh;ghe B. <I>of</I>] at O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000331.tif" N="49, B-text"></L>
<L>"And sette my sadel vppon suffre- &middot; til-I-se-my-tyme,</L>
<L N="20">And lete warrok it wel &middot; with witty-wordes gerthes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lete</I>] let R; lat W. <I>it</I>] hym W. <I>gerthes</I>] gere B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hange on hym &thorn;e heuy brydel &middot; to holde his hed lowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holde</I>] helde R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he wil make wehe &middot; tweye er he be there."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wehe</I>] wehee W. <I>tweye</I>] twies WB; twyes O; twyees C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thanne conscience vppon his caple &middot; kaireth forth faste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kaireth</I>] carie&thorn; WB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">And resoun with hym ritte &middot; rownynge togideres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ritte</I>] ryt W; rit RO; rydes C; rytt B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whiche maistries Mede &middot; maketh on &thorn;is erthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Mede&mdash;erthe</I>] on eerth &middot; Mede &thorn;e mayde maketh R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; One waryn wisdom &middot; And witty his fere</L>
<L>Folwed hem faste &middot; [for &thorn;ei] haued to done<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] hym W. [<I>for &thorn;ei</I> WOB] for hij C; LR <I>om.; but in</I> L, <I>the line is marked for correction. haued</I>] hadde WC; hadden B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">In &thorn;e cheker and at &thorn;e chauncerie &middot; to be discharged of &thorn;inges;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e cheker</I>] &thorn;escheker W. <I>and</I>] R <I>om. at &thorn;e</I>] in &thorn;e WCOB; atte &thorn;e R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And riden fast, for resoun &middot; shulde rede hem &thorn;e beste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to saue hem, for siluer &middot; fro shame and fram harmes.</L>
<L>&para; And conscience knewe hem wel &middot; &thorn;ei loued coueitise,</L>
<L>And bad resoun ride faste &middot; and recche of her noither,<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>omit. resoun</I>] O <I>om. noither</I>] nei&thorn;er WO; nother R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="33">"&THORN;ere aren wiles in here wordes &middot; and with Mede &thorn;ei dwelleth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ere&mdash;wiles</I>] &thorn;ei arn wyli O.</NOTE></L>
<L>There as wratthe and wranglyng is &middot; &thorn;ere wynne &thorn;ei siluer,</L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;ere is loue and lewte &middot; &thorn;ei wil nou&yogh;te come &thorn;ere;<Q><I>Contricio &amp; infelicitas in vijs eorum, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac &thorn;ere</I>] Ac where W; And &thorn;er C; &thorn;ere R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">&THORN;ei ne gyueth nou&yogh;te of god &middot; one gose wynge,<Q><I>Non est timor dei ante oculos eorum</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gose</I>] goose W; goos O.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For, wot god, &thorn;ei wolde do more &middot; for a dozeine chickenes,</L>
<L>Or as many capones &middot; or for a seem of otes,
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="50, B-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;an for loue of owre lorde &middot; or alle hise leue seyntes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>loue</I>] &thorn;e loue W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i, resoun, lete hem ride &middot; &thorn;o riche, bi hem-seluen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>resoun</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="41">For conscience knoweth hem nou&yogh;te &middot; ne cryst, as I trowe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne resoun rode faste &middot; &thorn;e ri&yogh;te hei&yogh;e gate,</L>
<L>As conscience hym kenned &middot; til &thorn;ei come to &thorn;e kynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei</I>] he O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">&para; Curteisliche &thorn;e kynge &thorn;anne &middot; come a&yogh;ein resoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>come</I>] com W. <I>a&yogh;ein</I>] ayeins W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bitwene hym-self and his sone &middot; sette hym on benche,</L>
<L>And wordeden wel wyseli &middot; a gret while togideres.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] at C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;anne come pees in-to parlement &middot; and put forth a bille,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="45"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>put</I>] puttede O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">How wronge a&yogh;eines his wille &middot; had his wyf taken,</L>
<L>And how he rauisshed Rose &middot; Reginoldes loue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Reginoldes</I>] Reignaldes W; Rey|noldes CO; Reynaldes R; Raynaldis B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Margarete of hir maydenhode &middot; maugre here chekis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maugre</I>] maugree W; maugrey O; magre B.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Bothe my gees &amp; my grys &middot; his gadelynges feccheth;</L>
<L N="52">I dar nou&yogh;te for fere of hym &middot; fy&yogh;te ne chyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] hem W.</NOTE></L>
<L>He borwed of me bayard &middot; he brou&yogh;te hym home neure,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] and R. <I>hym</I>] it R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no ferthynge &thorn;er-fore &middot; for nau&yogh;te I couthe plede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>om. nau&yogh;te</I>] ou&yogh;t W; ou&yogh;t &thorn;at O.</NOTE></L>
<L>He meyneteneth his men &middot; to morther myne hewen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hewen</I>] hennes (!) R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="56">Forstalleth my feyres &middot; and fi&yogh;teth in my chepynge,</L>
<L>And breketh vp my bernes dore &middot; and bereth aweye my whete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>om. bernes dore</I>] berne|dores O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And taketh me but a taile &middot; for ten quarteres of otes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>but</I>] C <I>om. a</I>] o O. <I>taile</I>] taille WC. <I>ten</I>] a ten CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;et he bet me &thorn;er-to &middot; and lyth bi my Mayde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bet</I>] bete&thorn; WB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">I nam nou&yogh;te hardy for hym &middot; vneth to loke."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nam</I>] am WR. <I>vneth</I>] vnne&thorn;e WROB; vnees C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; The kynge knewe he seide sothe &middot; for conscience hym tolde,
<PB REF="00000333.tif" N="51, B-text"></L>
<L N="62">&THORN;at wronge was a wikked luft &middot; and wrou&yogh;te moche sorwe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>luft</I>] lift O; lyft C. <I>wrou&yogh;te&mdash;sorwe</I>] muche sorwe wrou&yogh;te R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Wronge was afered &thorn;anne &middot; and wisdome he sou&yogh;te</L>
<L>To make pees with his pens &middot; and profered hym manye,</L>
<L N="65">And seide, "had I loue of my lorde &thorn;e kynge &middot; litel wolde I recche,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="46"></L>
<L>Thei&yogh;e pees and his powere &middot; pleyned hym eure!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] hem R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o wan wisdome &middot; and sire waryn &thorn;e witty,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wan</I>] whan CB; wente WO.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">For &thorn;at wronge had ywrou&yogh;te &middot; so wikked a dede,</L>
<L>And warned wronge &thorn;o &middot; with such a wyse tale;</L>
<L>"Who-so worcheth bi wille &middot; wratthe maketh ofte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi</I>] my CB; by my O.</NOTE></L>
<L>I seye it bi &thorn;i-self &middot; &thorn;ow shalt it wel fynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;i-self</I>] myself WCB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">But if Mede it make &middot; &thorn;i myschief is vppe,</L>
<L>For bothe &thorn;i lyf and &thorn;i londe &middot; lyth in his grace."</L>
<L>&para; Thanne wowed wronge &middot; wisdome ful &yogh;erne,</L>
<L>To make his pees with his pens &middot; handi-dandi payed.<MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his pees</I>] pees WB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">Wisdome and witte &thorn;anne &middot; wenten togideres,</L>
<L>And toke Mede myd hem &middot; mercy to winne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myd</I>] with C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Pees put for&thorn; his hed &middot; and his panne blody;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>put</I>] putte WR.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Wyth-outen gilte, god it wote &middot; gat I &thorn;is ska&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gilte</I>] gult R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Conscience and &thorn;e comune &middot; knowen &thorn;e sothe."</L>
<L>&para; Ac wisdom and witt &middot; were about faste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>were</I>] weren OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To ouercome &thorn;e kyng &middot; with catel, &yogh;if &thorn;ei my&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kynge swore, bi crist &middot; and bi his crowne bothe,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="47"></L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at wronge for his werkis &middot; sholde wo &thorn;olye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;olye</I>] thole R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And comaunded a constable &middot; to casten hym in yrens,</L>
<L>"And late hym nou&yogh;te &thorn;is seuene &yogh;ere &middot; seen his feet ones."</L>
<L>&para; "God wot," quod wysdom &middot; "&thorn;at were nau&yogh;te &thorn;e beste;
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="52, B-text"></L>
<L>And he amendes mowe make &middot; late meynprise hym haue;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mowe</I>] mowe (<I>printed</I> nowe) W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="89">And be borwgh for his bale &middot; and biggen hym bote,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>borwgh</I>] borgh WCB; boru&yogh; R. <I>biggen</I>] buggen WR; bi&yogh;en B. <I>hym</I>] hem C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so amende &thorn;at is mysdo &middot; and euermore &thorn;e bettere."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>euermore</I>] euere be R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Witt acorded &thorn;er-with &middot; and seide &thorn;e same:</L>
<L N="92">"Bettere is &thorn;at bote &middot; bale adoun brynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bettere</I>] &thorn;at bettere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an bale be ybette &middot; &amp; bote neuere &thorn;e bettere."</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;anne gan Mede to mengen here &middot; and mercy she bisought,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mengen</I>] meken R. <I>she</I>] he R; C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And profred pees a present &middot; al of pure golde:</L>
<L N="96">"Haue &thorn;is, man, of me," quod she &middot; "to amende &thorn;i ska&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For I wil wage for wronge &middot; he wil do so namore."</L>
<L>&para; Pitously pees &thorn;anne &middot; prayed to &thorn;e kynge</L>
<L>To haue mercy on &thorn;at man &middot; &thorn;at mys-did hym so ofte:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] of O.</NOTE></L>
<L>"For he hath waged me wel &middot; as wysdome hym tau&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="101">And I forgyue hym &thorn;at gilte &middot; with a goode wille;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e kynge assent &middot; I can seye no bettere;</L>
<L>For Mede hath made me amendes &middot; I may namore axe."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>made me amendes</I>] me amendes maad W. <I>axe</I>] aske O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="104">&para; "Nay," quod &thorn;e Kynge &thorn;o &middot; "so me cryst helpe!<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="48"></L>
<L>Wronge wendeth nou&yogh;te so awaye &middot; arst wil I wite more;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>arst</I>] erst WCOB. <I>wite</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For loupe he so li&yogh;tly &middot; laughen he wolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>loupe</I>] lope WO; lepe B. <I>laughen</I>] ley&yogh;hen R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And efte &thorn;e balder be &middot; to bete myne hewen;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>balder</I>] boldere WR. <I>hewen</I>] huen O; hewes R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">But resoun haue reuthe on hym &middot; he shal rest in my stokkes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at as longe as he lyueth &middot; but lowenesse hym borwe."</L>
<L>&para; Somme men redde Resoun &thorn;o &middot; to haue reuthe on &thorn;at schrewe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>redde</I>] radde WR; radden O; redden B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for to conseille &thorn;e kynge &middot; and conscience after,<MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000335.tif" N="53, B-text"></L>
<L>That Mede moste be meynpernour &middot; resoun &thorn;ei bisou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moste</I>] muste OB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="113">&para; "Rede me nou&yogh;te," quod resoun &middot; "no reuthe to haue,</L>
<L>Til lordes and ladies &middot; louien alle treuthe,</L>
<L>And haten al harlotrye &middot; to heren it, or to mouthen it;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heren it</I>] heren W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="116">Tyl pernelles purfil &middot; be put in here hucche;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pernelles</I>] Parnelles W; pero|nelles RB; Peronelle C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And childryn cherissyng &middot; be chastyng with &yogh;erdes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>childryn</I>] childrene W; chil|dren COB; childerne R. <I>chastyng</I>] chastysyng O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And harlotes holynesse &middot; be holden for an hyne;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an hyne</I>] vnheende O; nau&yogh;te R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til clerken coueitise be &middot; to clothe &thorn;e pore and to fede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>clerken</I>] clerkene WR; clerkis B. <I>to fede</I>] fede W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">And religious romares &middot; <I>recordare</I> in here cloistres,</L>
<L>As seynt Benet hem bad &middot; Bernarde and Fraunceys;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="49"></L>
<L>And til prechoures prechyng &middot; be preued on hem|seluen;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;e kynges conseille &middot; be &thorn;e comune profyte;</L>
<L N="124">Tyl bisschopes baiardes &middot; ben beggeres chambres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>baiardes</I>] Bayardes WCRO; bayardis B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here haukes and her houndes &middot; helpe to pore Re|ligious;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] &thorn;e CB. <I>pore</I>] pouere WR; <I>Religious</I>] religiouses R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And til seynt Iames be sou&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;ere I shal assigne,</L>
<L>That no man go to Galis &middot; but if he go for euere;</L>
<L N="128">And alle Rome-renneres &middot; for robberes of [by&yogh;onde]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] W <I>om</I>. [<I>by&yogh;onde</I>] bi&yogh;onde COB; biyonde W; <I>preferable to</I> by|&yogh;ende, <I>as in</I> LR.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bere no siluer ouer see &middot; &thorn;at signe of kynge shewe&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>see</I>] sehe O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Noyther graue ne vngraue &middot; golde noither siluer,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Noyther</I>] Nei&thorn;er WCOB; Nother R. <I>noither</I>] nei&thorn;er WCOB; nother R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vppon forfeture of &thorn;at fee &middot; who so fynt hym at Douere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] it W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="132">But if it be marchaunt or his man &middot; or messagere with letteres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>] B <I>om. it</I>] he WCOB; <I>but see</I> Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prouysoure or prest &middot; or penaunt for his synnes.
<PB REF="00000336.tif" N="54, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; And &yogh;et," quod resoun, "bi &thorn;e Rode &middot; I shal no reuthe haue,</L>
<L>While Mede hath &thorn;e maistrye &middot; in &thorn;is moot-halle.</L>
<L N="136">Ac I may shewe ensaumples &middot; as I se other-while,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>as</I>] CB <I>om. other</I>] ou&thorn;er W.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sey it by my-self," quod he &middot; "and it so were<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and&mdash;crowne</I>] B <I>om. crowne</I>] coroune W; corown O.</NOTE></L>
<L>That I were kynge with crowne &middot; to kepen a Rewme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and&mdash;crowne</I>] B <I>om. crowne</I>] coroune W; corown O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shulde neuere wronge in &thorn;is worlde &middot; &thorn;at I wite my&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wite</I>] witt R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ben vnpunisshed in my powere &middot; for peril of my soule!</L>
<L N="141">Ne gete my grace for giftes &middot; so me god saue!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I>] &thorn;oru&yogh; R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne for no Mede haue mercy &middot; but mekenesse it make.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>make</I>] made R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For <I>nullum malum</I> &thorn;e man &middot; mette with <I>inpunitum</I>,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="50"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>inpunitum</I>] impunitum O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">And badde <I>nullum bonum</I> &middot; be <I>irremuneratum</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>badde</I>] bad WRB; bade O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Late &yogh;owre confessoure, sire Kynge &middot; construe &thorn;is vnglosed;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &yogh;e worken it in werke &middot; I wedde myne eres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e worken</I>] he wirke B. <I>myne</I>] bo&thorn;e myne O.</NOTE></L>
<L>That lawe shal ben a laborere &middot; and lede a-felde donge,</L>
<L N="148">And loue shal lede &thorn;i londe &middot; as &thorn;e lief lyketh!"</L>
<L>&para; Clerkes &thorn;at were confessoures &middot; coupled hem to|gideres,</L>
<L>Alle to construe &thorn;is clause &middot; and for &thorn;e kynges profit,<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Alle</I>] Al W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac nou&yogh;te for conforte of &thorn;e comune &middot; ne for &thorn;e kynges soule.</L>
<L N="152">&para; For I sei&yogh;e mede in the moot-halle &middot; on men of lawe wynke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sei&yogh;e</I>] sei&yogh; WC; sey&yogh; R; sy&yogh; O; say B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ei lawghyng lope to hire &middot; and lafte resoun manye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lope</I>] lepe C. <I>lafte</I>] left WR.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Waryn wisdome &middot; wynked vppon Mede,</L>
<L N="155">And seide, "Madame, I am &yogh;owre man &middot; what so my mouth iangleth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>am</I>] C <I>om. iangleth</I>] iangle WR.</NOTE></L>
<L>I falle in floreines," quod &thorn;at freke &middot; "an faile speche ofte."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an</I>] and WCROB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000337.tif" N="55, B-text"></L>
<L N="157">&para; Alle ri&yogh;tful recorded &middot; &thorn;at resoun treuthe tolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ri&yogh;tful</I>] rightfulle W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And witt acorded &thorn;er-with &middot; and comended his wordes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e moste peple in &thorn;e halle &middot; and manye of &thorn;e grete,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] &thorn;is R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">Aud leten mekenesse a maistre &middot; and Mede a mansed schrewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] O <I>om. maistre</I>] mais|tresse B. <I>mansed</I>] mased C; masid B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Loue lete of hir li&yogh;te &middot; and lewte &yogh;it lasse,</L>
<L>And seide it so hei&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;at al &thorn;e halle it herde,</L>
<L>"Who-so wilneth hir to wyf &middot; for welth of her godis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyf</I>] wyue RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>But he be knowe for a koke-wolde &middot; kut of my nose!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kut</I>] bitte (<I>prob. miswritten for</I> kitte) R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">&para; Mede mourned &thorn;o &middot; and made heuy chere,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e moste comune of &thorn;at courte &middot; called hire an hore.</L>
<L>Ac a sysoure and a sompnoure &middot; sued hir faste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>sued</I>] sueden O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="168">And a schireues clerke &middot; byschrewed al &thorn;e route,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I>] al (<I>printed</I> at) W.</NOTE></L>
<L>"For ofte haue I," quod he &middot; "holpe &yogh;ow atte barre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holpe</I>] Ihulpe R. <I>atte</I>] at &thorn;e WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;it &yogh;eue &yogh;e me neuere &middot; &thorn;e worthe of a russhe."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;eue</I>] gaue C. <I>russhe</I>] risshe W; resshe C; rische O; reische B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; The kynge called conscience &middot; and afterwardes resoun,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="51"></L>
<L N="172">And recorded &thorn;at resoun &middot; had ri&yogh;tfullich schewed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ri&yogh;tfullich</I>] reufulliche (!) CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And modilich vppon Mede &middot; with my&yogh;te &thorn;e Kynge loked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with&mdash;loked</I>] mi&yogh;te &thorn;at kyng loke R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gan wax wrothe with lawe &middot; for Mede almoste had shent it,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gan</I>] gand C. <I>wax</I>] wexe W. <I>it</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide, "&thorn;orw &yogh;owre lawe, as I leue &middot; I lese many chetes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;owre</I>] W <I>om. many</I>] myn B. <I>chetes</I>] eschetes W; eschetis B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mede ouer-maistrieth lawe &middot; and moche treuthe letteth.</L>
<L>Ac resoun shal rekene with &yogh;ow &middot; &yogh;if I regne any while,</L>
<L N="178">And deme &yogh;ow bi &thorn;is day &middot; as &yogh;e han deserued.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi &thorn;is</I>] on a O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="56, B-text"></L>
<L>Mede shal nou&yogh;te meynprise &yogh;ow &middot; bi &thorn;e Marie of heuene!</L>
<L N="180">I wil haue leute in lawe &middot; and lete be al &yogh;owre ian|glyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as moste folke witnesseth wel &middot; wronge shal be demed."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moste</I>] alle R. <I>folke</I>] O <I>om. witnesseth</I>] witnesse C. <I>wel</I>] R <I>om. demed</I>] ydemed R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Quod conscience to &thorn;e kynge &middot; "but the comune wil assent,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>the</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>It is ful hard, bi myn hed &middot; here-to to brynge it,</L>
<L N="184">Alle &yogh;owre lige leodes &middot; to lede &thorn;us euene."</L>
<L>&para; "By hym &thorn;at rau&yogh;te on &thorn;e rode" &middot; quod resoun to &thorn;e kynge,</L>
<L>"But if I reule &thorn;us &yogh;owre rewme &middot; rende out my guttes!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>But if</I>] But B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e bidden buxomnes &middot; be of myne assente."<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;if</I>] If WCROB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="188">&para; "And I assent," seith &thorn;e kynge &middot; "by seynte Marie my lady,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seith</I>] saye C; quod O; quat&yogh; R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be my conseille comen &middot; of clerkis and of erlis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">C <I>omits. Be</I>] <I>so in</I> LROB. <I>comen</I>] <I>so in</I> LOB; Icome R. <I>Hence the reading in</I> W, By my counseil commune, <I>is probably corrupt; cf.</I> Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac redili resoun &middot; &thorn;ow shalt nou&yogh;te ride fro me,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For as longe as I lyue &middot; lete &thorn;e I nelle."</L>
<L N="192">&para; "I am aredy," quod resoun &middot; "to reste with &yogh;ow euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aredy</I>] al redy WCB.</NOTE></L>
<L>So conscience be of owre conseille &middot; I kepe no bettere."</L>
<L>"And I graunt," quod the kynge &middot; "goddes forbode it faile,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it</I>] he R. <I>it faile</I>] ellis W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">Als longe as owre lyf lasteth &middot; lyue we togideres."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lasteth</I>] last R. <I>lyue</I>] leue R.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000339.tif" N="57, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS V.</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. Passus Quintus O; Passus quintus de visione LCB; <I>to which</I> W <I>adds</I> vt supra; <I>and</I> R <I>adds</I> petri plowman, vt supra.</NOTE><I>Passus quintus de Visione.</I></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The kyng and his knightes &middot; to the kirke wente<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="52"></L>
<L>To here matynes of &thorn;e day &middot; and &thorn;e masse after.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne waked I of my wynkynge &middot; and wo was with-alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>waked</I>] awaked RB. <I>was</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at I ne hadde sleped sadder &middot; and ysei&yogh;en more.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sleped</I>] slept W. <I>ysei&yogh;en</I>] yseien B; I-sye O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac er I hadde faren a fourlonge &middot; feyntise me hente,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>fourlonge</I>] furlong W; forlong CO; fur&yogh;longe R. <I>feyn|tise</I>] a feyntise O.</NOTE></L>
<L>That I ne my&yogh;te ferther a-foot &middot; for defaute of slepynge;</L>
<L>And sat softly adown &middot; and seide my bileue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sat</I>] sette me B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so I babeled on my bedes &middot; &thorn;ei brou&yogh;te me a-slepe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so I</I>] R <I>om. on</I>] vppon R; of O. <I>&thorn;ei</I>] til &thorn;ei B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9">&para; And &thorn;anne saw I moche more &middot; &thorn;an I bifore tolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moche</I>] myche O; mykile C. <I>tolde</I>] of tolde W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For I say &thorn;e felde ful of folke &middot; &thorn;at I bifore of seyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>say</I>] sei&yogh; W; sey C; saw O; sau&yogh; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And how resoun gan arrayen hym &middot; alle &thorn;e reume to preche,</L>
<L N="12">And with a crosse afor &thorn;e kynge &middot; comsed &thorn;us to techen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>] O <I>om. afor</I>] bifore C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; He preued &thorn;at &thorn;ise pestilences &middot; [were] for pure synne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>preued</I>] preue&thorn; O. <I>pestilences</I>] pestilence C. [<I>were</I> W] was LCROB; <I>but</I> were <I>seems required</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e southwest wynde &middot; on saterday at euene<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>southwest</I>] south westrene W. <I>wynde</I>] wijnd O. <I>on</I>] vppon a B. <I>euene</I>] eue C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="58, B-text"></L>
<L>Was pertliche for pure pryde &middot; and for no poynt elles.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="53"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pure</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="16">Piries and plomtrees &middot; were puffed to &thorn;e erthe,</L>
<L>In ensample, &yogh;e segges &middot; &yogh;e shulden do &thorn;e bettere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e segges</I>] &thorn;at &yogh;e segges (<I>printed</I> that the segges) W. <I>&yogh;e shulden</I>] sholden W; shulden B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beches and brode okes &middot; were blowen to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>Torned vpward her tailles &middot; in tokenynge of drede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tailles</I>] taile R. <I>in tokenynge</I>] to kenynge R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at dedly synne at domesday &middot; shal fordon hem alle.</L>
<L>&para; Of &thorn;is matere I my&yogh;te &middot; mamely ful longe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mamely</I>] mamelen W; mamly B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac I shal seye as I saw &middot; so me god helpe!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>saw</I>] sau&yogh; WB.</NOTE></L>
<L>How pertly afor &thorn;e poeple &middot; resoun gan to preche.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pertly</I>] apertly B. <I>gan</I>] bigan WB; gand C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">&para; He bad wastoure go worche &middot; what he best couthe,</L>
<L>And wynnen his wastyng &middot; with somme manere crafte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crafte</I>] craftys R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And preyed peronelle &middot; her purfyle to lete,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] He W. <I>peronelle</I>] Per|nele WR.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kepe it in hir cofre &middot; for catel at hire nede.<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hir</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">&para; Thomme stowue he tau&yogh;te &middot; to take two staues,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stowue</I>] Stowue C; stouue R; Stowe O; of stowue B; Stowue <I>or</I> Stowne (<I>printed</I> Stowne) W. <I>staues</I>] stones R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fecche [felice] home &middot; fro &thorn;e wyuen pyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>felice</I> WCROB] filice L. <I>fro &thorn;e</I>] fram R. <I>wyuen</I>] wyuen <I>or</I> wynen LWCO; wyuene <I>or</I> wynene RB. <I>See note to</I> Text A; p. 144.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; He warned watt &middot; his wyf was to blame,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He</I>] And O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hire hed was worth halue a marke &middot; his hode nou&yogh;te worth a grote.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] For W. <I>halue a</I>] half a C; half WROB. <I>his</I>] &amp; his W; &amp; is B. <I>hode</I>] hed C; B <I>om. worth</I> (2)] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">And bad bette kut &middot; a bow other tweyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bow</I>] bou&yogh; W; bowghe C. <I>other</I>] outher W; or C. <I>tweyne</I>] tweye WR; tweyen O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bete betoun &thorn;er-with &middot; but if she wolde worche.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>] C <I>om. she</I>] heo R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;anne he charged chapmen &middot; to chasten her chil|deren;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chasten</I>] chasti&yogh;en W; chasti|sen O; chaste R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Late no wynnynge hem forweny &middot; whil &thorn;ei be &yogh;onge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] R <I>om. forweny</I>] for|wanye WB; for-wanyen R. <I>whil</I>] &thorn;e while R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="59, B-text"></L>
<L N="36">Ne for no pouste of pestilence &middot; plese hem nou&yogh;te out of resoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pouste</I>] poustee W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "My syre seyde so to me &middot; and so did my dame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e leuere childe &middot; &thorn;e more lore bihoueth,</L>
<L>And Salamon seide &thorn;e same &middot; &thorn;at Sapience made,<Q><I>Qui parcit virge, odit filium</I>.</Q></L>
<L N="40">&THORN;e Englich of &thorn;is latyn is &middot; who-so wil it knowe,</L>
<L>Who-so spareth &thorn;e sprynge &middot; spilleth his children."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sprynge</I>] &yogh;erde B. <I>spilleth</I>] he spilleth R. <I>children</I>] child B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And sithen he preyed prelat&yogh; &middot; and prestes to-gideres,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="54"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>preyed</I>] prechede W; proued R.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;at &yogh;e prechen to &thorn;e peple &middot; preue it on &yogh;owre-seluen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;owre-seluen</I>] yowselue WR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">And doth it in dede &middot; it shal drawe &yogh;ow to good;</L>
<L>If &yogh;e lyuen as &yogh;e leren vs &middot; we shal leue &yogh;ow &thorn;e bettere."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyuen</I>] leuen WC. <I>leren</I>] lerne R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And sithen he radde Religioun &middot; here reule to holde&mdash;</L>
<L>"Leste &thorn;e kynge and his conseille &middot; &yogh;owre comunes ap|payre,</L>
<L N="48">And ben stuwardes of &yogh;owre stedes &middot; til &yogh;e be ruled bettre."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stuwardes</I>] stywardes WOB; stiwardes CR.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And sithen he conseilled &thorn;e kynge &middot; &thorn;e comune to louye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] his W. <I>comune</I>] comunes O.</NOTE></L>
<L>"It is &thorn;i tresore, if tresoun ne were &middot; and triacle at &thorn;i nede."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tresore&mdash;were</I>] trewe tresor W. <I>ne</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sithen he prayed &thorn;e pope &middot; haue pite on holi|cherche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pope</I>] <I>erased in</I> R. <I>on</I>] of C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">And er he gyue any grace &middot; gouerne firste hym-selue.</L>
<L>&para; "And &yogh;e that han lawes to kepe &middot; late treuthe be &yogh;owre coueytise,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an golde or other gyftes &middot; if &yogh;e wil god plese;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or other</I>] ou&thorn;er W; &amp; o&thorn;er O. <I>&yogh;e</I>] he O.</NOTE></L>
<L>For who-so contrarieth treuthe &middot; he telleth in &thorn;e gospel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>who-so</I>] who B. <I>telleth</I>] telth R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="60, B-text"></L>
<L>That god knoweth hym nou&yogh;te &middot; ne no seynte of heuene,<Q><I>Amen dico vobis, nescio vos</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] hem R. <I>Amen</I>] Amen amen C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="57">&para; And &yogh;e &thorn;at seke seynte James &middot; and seintes of Rome,</L>
<L>Seketh seynt treuthe &middot; for he may saue &yogh;ow alle;</L>
<L><I>Qui cum patre &amp; filio</I> &middot; &thorn;at feire hem bifalle</L>
<L>&THORN;at suweth my sermon;" &middot; and &thorn;us seyde resoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>suweth</I>] seweth W; suen O; sueth R; suwes C. <I>resoun</I>] O <I>adds</I> Amen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="61">Thanne ran repentance &middot; and reherced his teme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] O <I>om. teme</I>] tyme C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gert wille to wepe &middot; water with his eyen.<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eyen</I>] ei&yogh;en WB; ey&yogh;es R; yen O. <I>Superbia</I>. This is here written in the margin of LWCO. Further on, we find the other titles, <I>Luxuria, Inuidia</I>, &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>SUPERBIA.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Peronelle proude-herte &middot; platte hir to &thorn;e erthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Peronelle</I>] Pernele WR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">And lay longe ar she loked &middot; and "lorde, mercy!" cryed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>she</I>] he R. <I>cryed</I>] he criede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And byhi&yogh;te to hym &middot; &thorn;at vs alle made,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>byhi&yogh;te</I>] bisou&yogh;te CB. <I>to</I>] vn|to O.</NOTE></L>
<L>She shulde vnsowen hir serke &middot; and sette &thorn;ere an heyre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heyre</I>] haire RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To affaiten hire flesshe &middot; &thorn;at fierce was to synne:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fierce</I>] fiers W; fers RO; feerse C; firs B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">"Shal neuere hei&yogh;e herte me hente &middot; but holde me lowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holde</I>] holde I wole W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And suffre to be myssayde&mdash; &middot; and so did I neuere.</L>
<L>But now wil I meke me &middot; and mercy biseche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wil I</I>] I wole W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For al &thorn;is I haue &middot; hated in myne herte."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I>] R <I>om. hated</I>] I-hated R; hauntid B.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>LUXURIA.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="72">&para; &THORN;anne lecchoure seyde "allas!" &middot; and on owre lady he cryed,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="55"></L>
<L>To make mercy for his mis-dedes &middot; bitwene god and his soule,
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="61, B-text"></L>
<L>With &thorn;at he shulde &thorn;e saterday &middot; seuene &yogh;ere &thorn;ere-after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e saterday</I>] on &thorn;e day R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Drynke but myd &thorn;e doke &middot; and dyne but ones.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myd</I>] with CR. <I>Inuidia</I>. O has <I>Envie</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>INUIDIA.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="76">&para; Enuye with heuy herte &middot; asked after scrifte,</L>
<L>And carefullich <I>mea culpa</I> &middot; he comsed to shewe.</L>
<L>He was as pale as a pelet &middot; in &thorn;e palsye he semed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as pale</I>] also pale B. <I>&thorn;e</I>] O <I>om. palsye</I>] palacye C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And clothed in a caurimaury &middot; I couthe it nou&yogh;te dis|creue;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>clothed</I>] cluted R. <I>cauri|maury</I>] kaurymaury W; Caurymaury CB; taurimauri (!) R. <I>couthe</I>] coude R. <I>discreue</I>] discryue WCOB; de|scriue R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">In kirtel and kourteby &middot; and a knyf bi his syde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kourteby</I>] courtepy W; curteby R: curtepy B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a freres frokke &middot; were &thorn;e forsleues.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] his R. <I>forsleues</I>] fore sleues WR.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as a leke hadde yleye &middot; longe in &thorn;e sonne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leke</I>] leek &thorn;at W. <I>yleye</I>] y|leyen C.</NOTE></L>
<L>So loked he with lene chekes &middot; lourynge foule.</L>
<L N="84">&para; His body was to-bolle for wratthe &middot; &thorn;at he bote his lippes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to-bolle</I>] to-bollen WCO; to|bolne B. <I>bote</I>] boot W; bot R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wryngynge he &yogh;ede with &thorn;e fiste &middot; to wreke hym|self he &thorn;ou&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wryngynge&mdash;&yogh;ede</I>] wryng&yogh;ed R. <I>&thorn;e</I>] his O. <I>fiste</I>] fust W; fuyst B.</NOTE></L>
<L>With werkes or with wordes &middot; whan he seighe his tyme.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seighe</I>] sey&yogh; R; say B; saw O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eche a worde &thorn;at he warpe &middot; was of an Addres tonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] B <I>om. an Addres</I>] an addre R; a neddres W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of chydynge and of chalangynge &middot; was his chief lyflode,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="89">With bakbitynge and bismer &middot; and beryng of fals wit|nesse;</L>
<L>&THORN;is was al his curteisye &middot; where &thorn;at euere he shewed hym.<NOTE PLACE="foot">W <I>omits. euere</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "I wolde ben yshryue," quod &thorn;is schrewe &middot; "and I for shame durst;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yshryue</I>] schryuen O. <I>schrewe</I>] sherewe W.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wolde be gladder, bi god &middot; &thorn;at gybbe had meschaunce,
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="62, B-text"></L>
<L N="93">Than &thorn;ou&yogh;e I had &thorn;is woke ywonne &middot; a weye of essex chese.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>woke</I>] wouke W; wike B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I haue a neighbore ney&yogh;e me &middot; I haue ennuyed hym ofte,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="56"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ney&yogh;e</I>] by W; ny&yogh; OB. <I>en|nuyed</I>] anoyed W; enuyed CRO; ennyed B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lowen on hym to lordes &middot; to don hym lese his siluer,</L>
<L N="96">And made his frendes ben his foon &middot; thorw my false tonge;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>made</I>] also R.</NOTE></L>
<L>His grace and his good happes &middot; greueth me ful sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>greueth</I>] greuen WOB; greues C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bitwene many and many &middot; I make debate ofte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bothe lyf and lyme &middot; is lost &thorn;orw my speche.</L>
<L N="100">And whan I mete him in market &middot; &thorn;at I moste hate,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hate</I>] hatye R.</NOTE></L>
<L>I hailse hym hendeliche &middot; as I his frende were;<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hailse</I>] haile B. <I>his</I>] is C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he is dou&yogh;tier &thorn;an I &middot; I dar do non other.</L>
<L>Ac hadde I maystrye and my&yogh;te &middot; god wote my wille!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="104">&para; And whan I come to &thorn;e kirke &middot; and sholde knele to &thorn;e Rode,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kirke</I>] cherche R. <I>to</I> (2)] to|for O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And preye for &thorn;e pople &middot; as &thorn;e prest techeth,</L>
<L>For pilgrimes and for palmers &middot; for alle &thorn;e poeple after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and for</I>] and B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;anne I crye on my knees &middot; &thorn;at cryste &yogh;if hem sorwe</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at bar[en] awey my bolle &middot; and my broke schete.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>baren</I>] <I>so in</I> OB; beren W; bare RC; bar L. <I>broke</I>] broken OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Awey fro &thorn;e auter &thorn;anne &middot; turne I myn eyghen,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="57"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eyghen</I>] ey&yogh;es R; yen O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And biholde how Eleyne &middot; hath a newe cote;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>how</I>] W <I>om. Eleyne</I>] heleyne R; Elyne C. <I>hath</I>] has C.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wisshe &thorn;anne it were myne &middot; and al &thorn;e webbe after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] C <I>om. webbe</I>] web WRO; weeb B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="112">&para; And of mennes lesynge I laughe &middot; &thorn;at liketh myn herte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mennes</I>] his R. <I>liketh</I>] werkes C; aki&thorn; B. <I>&thorn;at&mdash;herte</I>] &thorn;at myn herte ake&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for her wynnynge I wepe &middot; and waille &thorn;e tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] Ac R. <I>her</I>] his R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="63, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; And deme &thorn;at hij don ille &middot; &thorn;ere I do wel worse;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] men &thorn;at R. <I>hij</I>] &thorn;ei WO; huy B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Who-so vndernymeth me here-of &middot; I hate hym dedly after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here-of</I>] herof (<I>printed</I> hero) W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="116">I wolde &thorn;at vche a wyght &middot; were my knaue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] And I O. <I>vche a</I>] ech a W; Ilk a C. <I>my</I>] my owne O.</NOTE></L>
<L>For who-so hath more &thorn;an I &middot; &thorn;at angreth me sore.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us I lyue louelees &middot; lyke a luther dogge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>luther</I>] lyther CR; li&thorn;er B.</NOTE></L>
<L>That al my body bolneth &middot; for bitter of my galle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bitter</I>] bytterhed B. <I>of</I>] in R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">&para; I my&yogh;te nou&yogh;te eet many &yogh;eres &middot; as a man ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>For enuye and yuel wille &middot; is yuel to defye;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>defye</I>] diffye CO; diffie B.</NOTE></L>
<L>May no sugre ne swete &thorn;inge &middot; asswage my swellynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sugre</I>] sucre RB; sugure C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no <I>diapenidion</I> &middot; dryue it fro myne herte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>diapenidion</I>] diapendioun CB. <I>Ne&mdash;diapenidion</I>] For no diapendion may B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="124">Ne noyther schrifte ne shame &middot; but ho-so schrape my mawe?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ne</I>] B <I>om. noyther</I>] nei&thorn;er WOB; nou&thorn;er C. <I>ne</I>] no R. <I>schrape</I>] schape O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;us, redili," quod repentaunce &middot; and radde hym to &thorn;e beste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;us</I>] &yogh;is WR; &thorn;is CB; &thorn;is (<I>corrected to</I> &yogh;is) O. <I>redili</I>] rede I O. <I>and</I>] has C; ha&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sorwe of synnes &middot; is sauacioun of soules."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sauacioun</I>] saluacion C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "I am sori," quod &thorn;at segge &middot; "I am but selde other,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="58"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;e B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="128">And &thorn;at maketh me &thorn;us megre &middot; for I ne may me venge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>venge</I>] avenge O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amonges Burgeyses haue I be &middot; dwellynge At Londoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Burgeyses</I>] burgeis C; burgeys R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gert bakbitinge be a brocoure &middot; to blame mennes ware.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gert</I>] gart W; grete C; gret B. <I>bakbitinge</I>] bagbytyng R.</NOTE></L>
