<L>To wey pens with a peys &middot; and pare &thorn;e heuyest,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pens</I>] pans R. <I>peys</I>] pays C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="244">And lene it for loue of &thorn;e crosse &middot; to legge a wedde and lese it;</L>
<L>Suche dedes I did wryte &middot; &yogh;if he his day breke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>breke</I>] broke RB; brook O.</NOTE></L>
<L>I haue mo maneres &thorn;orw rerages &middot; &thorn;an &thorn;orw <I>miseretur &amp; comodat</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maneres</I>] manoirs W. <I>como|dat</I>] <I>so in</I> LCROB; <I>also</I> comodat <I>in</I> W (<I>though printed</I> commodat).</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I haue lent lordes &middot; and ladyes my chaffare,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lent</I>] Ilente R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="248">And ben her brocour after &middot; and bou&yogh;te it my-self.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bou&yogh;te</I>] brou&yogh;t (!) R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eschaunges and cheuesances &middot; with suche chaffare I dele,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chaffare</I>] chaffares R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lene folke &thorn;at lese wol &middot; a lyppe at euery noble.</L>
<L>And with lumbardes lettres &middot; I ladde golde to Rome,</L>
<L>And toke it by taille here &middot; and tolde hem &thorn;ere lasse."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>taille</I>] tale W. <I>hem</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="253">"Len[t]estow euere lordes &middot; for loue of her maynten|aunce?"<MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lentestow</I> W] Lenestow L; Lenedest &thorn;ow R; Lendestow C; Lent|ist &thorn;ou OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;e, I haue lent lordes &middot; loued me neuere after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lordes</I>] to lordes W. <I>loued</I>] &thorn;at loueden O; louede &thorn;ei B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And haue ymade many a kny&yogh;te &middot; bothe mercere &amp; drapere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ymade</I>] maad C; made B. <I>a</I>] CR <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="256">&THORN;at payed neuere for his prentishode &middot; nou&yogh;te a peire gloues."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I>] hir CB. <I>peire</I>] paire of C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Hastow pite on pore men &middot; &thorn;at mote nedes borwe?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hastow</I>] Hast &thorn;ou O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "I haue as moche pite of pore men &middot; as pedlere hath of cattes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as moche</I>] as mikile C; also muche B. <I>of&mdash;men</I>] of hem CB; on hem O. <I>pedlere</I>] &thorn;e pedlere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde kille hem, yf he cacche hem my&yogh;te &middot; for coueitise of here skynnes."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yf</I>] and R. <I>cacche hem</I>] COB <I>om. for&mdash;of</I>] forto haue CB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="71, B-text"></L>
<L N="260">&para; "Artow manlyche amonge &thorn;i nei&yogh;bores &middot; of &thorn;i mete and drynke?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Artow</I>] Art &thorn;ow ROB. <I>&thorn;i mete and</I>] met and of CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "I am holden," quod he, "as hende &middot; as hounde is in kychyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">COB <I>place</I> as hende <I>before</I> quod he. <I>is in</I>] in his R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amonges my neighbores, namelich &middot; such a name ich haue."</L>
<L>&para; "Now god leue neure," quod repentance &middot; "but &thorn;ow repent &thorn;e rather,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Now</I>] O <I>om. leue</I>] leue &thorn;ee <I>or</I> lene &thorn;ee W. <I>neure</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="264">&THORN;e grace on &thorn;is grounde &middot; &thorn;i good wel to bisette,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ine ysue after &thorn;e &middot; haue ioye of &thorn;at &thorn;ow wynnest,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ysue</I>] vssue R; heires WCB; eyres O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;i excecutours wel bisett &middot; &thorn;e siluer &thorn;at &thorn;ow hem leuest;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel</I>] COB <I>om. &thorn;e</I>] &thorn;i O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at was wonne with wronge &middot; with wikked men be despended.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="268">For were I frere of &thorn;at hous &middot; &thorn;ere gode faith and charite is,</L>
<L>I nolde cope vs with &thorn;i catel &middot; ne owre kyrke amende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nolde</I>] wolde nou&yogh;t R. <I>kyrke</I>] cherche R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne haue a peny to my pitaunce &middot; of &thorn;yne, bi my soule hele,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of&mdash;hele</I>] so god my soule saue W. <I>hele</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e best boke in owre hous &middot; &thorn;ei&yogh;e brent golde were &thorn;e leues,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brent</I>] brend RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I wyst wytterly &middot; &thorn;ow were suche as &thorn;ow [tellest,]<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>tellest</I> WCROB] telleth L; <I>but the line is marked for correction</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Or elles &thorn;at I kou&thorn;e knowe it &middot; by any kynnes wise.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">LWRO <I>omit this line, but it is found in</I> CBC<SUB>2</SUB>, <I>and in</I> Crowley's text, <I>which has</I> kindes wyt <I>for</I> kynnes wise. <I>I quote it from</I> C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="274"><I>Seruus es alterius &middot; cum fercula pinguia queris,</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cum</I>] dum W.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Pane tuo pocius &middot; vescere, liber eris</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pocius</I>] pocius (<I>printed</I> potius) W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="276">&para; Thow art an vnkynde creature &middot; I can &thorn;e nou&yogh;te as|soille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e nou&yogh;te</I>] nou&yogh;t &thorn;e CB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="72, B-text"></L>
<L>Til &thorn;ow make restitucioun &middot; and rekne with hem alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>inserts</I> quod repentance <I>after</I> restitucioun.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sithen &thorn;at resoun rolle it &middot; in &thorn;e regystre of heuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it</I>] &thorn;e C; B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="279">That &thorn;ow hast made vche man good &middot; I may &thorn;e nou&yogh;te assoille;<Q><I>Non dimittitur peccatum &middot; donec restituatur abla|tum, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>assoille</I>] saue R. <I>donec</I>] nisi R. <I>ablatum</I>] oblatum WCB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For alle &thorn;at [haue] of &thorn;i good &middot; haue god my trouthe!<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>haue</I> C] hauen B; han WO; hath LR.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Ben] holden at &thorn;e heighe dome &middot; to helpe &thorn;e to restitue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Ben</I> WCOB] Is LR. <I>holden</I>] haldynge R. <I>to</I> (2)] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="282">And who so leueth nou&yogh;te &thorn;is be soth &middot; loke in &thorn;e sauter glose,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nou&yogh;te &thorn;is be</I>] this be nou&yogh;t CB. <I>&thorn;e</I>] a R.</NOTE></L>
<L>In <I>miserere mei deus</I> &middot; where I mene treuthe,<Q><I>Ecce enim veritatem dilexisti, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>After</I> &amp;c. <I>follows, in</I> R <I>only, the curious line</I>, &thorn;ere is no laborere wolde leue with hem &middot; &thorn;at knoweth peres &thorn;e plowman.</NOTE></L>
<L N="284">&para; Shal neuere werkman in &thorn;is worlde &middot; &thorn;ryue wyth &thorn;at &thorn;ow wynnest;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Shal</I>] For schal R.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Cum sancto sanctus eris</I> &middot; construe me &thorn;at on englische."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>construe&mdash;englische</I>] C <I>om. me &thorn;at</I>] me &thorn;is W; &thorn;ou me &thorn;at B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thanne wex &thorn;at shrewe in wanhope &middot; and walde haue hanged him-self,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;e R. <I>him-self</I>] hym W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne hadde repentaunce &thorn;e rather &middot; reconforted hym in &thorn;is manere,<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>reconforted</I>] conforted R. <I>hym</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="288">"Haue mercye in &thorn;i mynde &middot; and with &thorn;i mouth biseche it,</L>
<L>For goddes mercye is more &middot; &thorn;an alle hise other werkes;<Q><I>Misericordia eius super omnia opera eius, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot">LOR <I>preserve</I>, WCB <I>omit, the Latin quotation. eius</I>] domini R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And al &thorn;e wikkednesse in &thorn;is worlde &middot; &thorn;at man my&yogh;te worche or thynke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] O <I>om. in</I>] of O. <I>&thorn;is</I>] C <I>om. worche</I>] do COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne is no more to &thorn;e mercye of god &middot; &thorn;an in &thorn;e see a glede;
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="73, B-text"><Q><I>Omnis iniquitas quantum ad misericordiam dei, est</I> [<I>quasi</I>] <I>sintilla in medio maris</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ne is</I>] Nis WCOB. [<I>quasi</I> WCORB] L <I>om. sintilla</I>] <I>so in</I> W (<I>though printed</I> scintilla).</NOTE></L>
<L N="292">&para; For-&thorn;i haue mercy in &thorn;i mynde &middot; and marchandise, leue it,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ow hast no good grounde &middot; to gete &thorn;e with a wastel,</L>
<L>But if it were with thi tonge &middot; or ellis with &thorn;i two hondes.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;ow hast geten &middot; bigan al with false|hede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bigan</I>] hit began B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="296">And as longe as &thorn;ow lyuest &thorn;er-with &middot; &thorn;ow &yogh;eldest nou&yogh;te, but borwest.</L>
<L>&para; And if &thorn;ow wite neuere to whiche &middot; ne whom to restitue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wite</I>] wost COB. <I>restitue</I>] restitute R; make restitucioun B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bere it to &thorn;e bisschop &middot; and bidde hym of his grace,</L>
<L>Bisette it hym-selue &middot; as best is for &thorn;i soule.</L>
<L N="300">For he shal answere for &thorn;e &middot; at &thorn;e heygh dome,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e and for many mo &middot; &thorn;at man shal &yogh;if a reken|ynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>What he lerned &yogh;ow in lente &middot; leue &thorn;ow none other,</L>
<L>And what he lent &yogh;ow of owre lordes good &middot; to lette &yogh;ow fro synne."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>Corruptly made into two lines in</I> COB.</P><P>And what he lente yow of his goode &middot; to wite yow fro synne,</P><P>For he sholde helpe yow &middot; of oure lordes goode C.</P></NOTE></L>
</LG>
