<L N="304">&para; Now bigynneth glotoun &middot; for to go to schrifte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">GULA] LWCOC<SUB>2</SUB>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kaires hym to-kirke-ward &middot; his coupe to schewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kaires</I>] karie&thorn; WB. <I>kirke</I>] cherche R. <I>coupe</I>] culpe B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac Beton &thorn;e brewestere &middot; bad hym good morwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And W; An C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And axed of hym with &thorn;at &middot; whiderward he wolde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>axed</I>] asked WR. <I>of</I>] at W. <I>hym</I>] B <I>om. whiderward</I>] whider B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="308">&para; "To holi cherche," quod he &middot; "forto here masse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cherche</I>] kirke O. <I>forto</I>] to CB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="74, B-text"></L>
<L>And sithen I wil be shryuen &middot; and synne namore."</L>
<L>&para; "I haue gode ale, gossib," quod she &middot; "glotown, wiltow assaye?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wiltow</I>] woltow W; wilt &thorn;ou OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Hastow au&yogh;te in &thorn;i purs &middot; any hote spices?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>purs</I>] purs, quod he W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="312">&para; "I haue peper and piones," quod [s]he &middot; "and a pounde of garlike,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>piones</I>] pionus C; pioyne R; greynes B. <I>she</I>] <I>so in</I> W; sche OR; he LCB; <I>see</I> l. 310.</NOTE></L>
<L>A ferthyngworth of fenel-seed &middot; for fastyngdayes."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A</I>] And a W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne goth glotoun in &middot; and grete othes after;</L>
<L>Cesse &thorn;e souteresse &middot; sat on &thorn;e benche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>souteresse</I>] sowestere B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="316">Watte &thorn;e warner &middot; and his wyf bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>warner</I>] waryner B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tymme &thorn;e tynkere &middot; and tweyne of his prentis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Tymme</I>] Symme CRB. <I>prentis</I>] prentices WCO; prentys R; prenti&yogh; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hikke &thorn;e hakeneyman &middot; and hughe &thorn;e nedeler,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="61"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hughe</I>] howe R; hue O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Clarice of cokkeslane &middot; and &thorn;e clerke of &thorn;e cherche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cokkeslane</I>] cockislane B. <I>&thorn;e clerke</I>] clerc C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">Dawe &thorn;e dykere &middot; and a dozeine other;<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>transposes these lines</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sire Piers of Pridie &middot; and Peronelle of Flaundres,<MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>transposes these lines</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sire</I>] And sire R. <I>Pridie</I>] Pride C. <I>Peronelle</I>] Pernele W.</NOTE></L>
<L>A ribibour, a ratonere &middot; a rakyer of chepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rakyer</I>] Raker COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>A ropere, a redyngkyng &middot; and Rose &thorn;e dissheres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>redyngkyng</I>] Rydyngkyng C. <I>dissheres</I>] disshere B; dyssheres dou&yogh;ter R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="324">Godfrey of garlekehithe &middot; and gryfin &thorn;e walshe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>garlekehithe</I>] garlek-hethe R. <I>gryfin</I>] grifyth R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And vpholderes an hepe &middot; erly bi &thorn;e morwe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>erly</I>] herly R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Geuen glotoun with glad chere &middot; good ale to hansel.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Geuen</I>] Gyuen C. <I>glad</I>] good COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Clement &thorn;e cobelere &middot; cast of his cloke,</L>
<L N="328">And atte new faire &middot; he nempned it to selle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>atte</I>] at &thorn;e WCOB; to &thorn;e R. <I>he</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hikke &thorn;e hakeneyman &middot; hitte his hood after,</L>
<L>And badde bette &thorn;e bochere &middot; ben on his side.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben</I>] to ben R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere were chapmen y-chose &middot; &thorn;is chaffare to preise;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>were</I>] R. <I>om. y-chose</I>] chosen CB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="75, B-text"></L>
<L N="332">Who-so haueth &thorn;e hood &middot; shuld haue amendes of &thorn;e cloke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Who-so</I>] That whoso W. <I>haueth</I>] haue CB; hadde WO. <I>shuld</I>] shul CR. <I>haue</I>] han W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Two risen vp in rape &middot; and rouned togideres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Two</I>] &thorn;o R. <I>vp</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And preised &thorn;ese penyworthes &middot; apart bi hem-selue;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ese</I>] &thorn;e R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei couth nou&yogh;te bi her conscience &middot; acorden in treuthe,</L>
<L N="336">Tyl Robyn &thorn;e ropere &middot; arose bi &thorn;e southe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi</I>] R <I>om</I> (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>And nempned hym for a noumpere &middot; &thorn;at no debate nere,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="62"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>noumpere</I>] nounpere W; noun|pier C. <I>nere</I>] were R.</NOTE></L>
<L>[For to trye &thorn;is chaffare &middot; bitwixen hem &thorn;re.]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> O; <I>also in</I> CBC<SUB>2</SUB>; LWR <I>omit</I>. Crowley <I>has the line, but puts</I> there <I>for</I> &thorn;re.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Hikke &thorn;e hostellere &middot; hadde &thorn;e cloke,</L>
<L N="340">In couenaunte &thorn;at Clement &middot; shulde &thorn;e cuppe fille,</L>
<L>And haue Hikkes hode hostellere &middot; and holde hym yserued;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yserued</I>] serued CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And who-so repented rathest &middot; shulde arise after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>who-so</I>] who &thorn;at COB. <I>rathest</I>] rather COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And grete sire glotoun &middot; with a galoun ale.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sire</I>] wele C; wel B; wel sire O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="344">&para; &THORN;ere was laughyng and louryng &middot; and "let go &thorn;e cuppe,"</L>
<L>And seten so til euensonge &middot; and songen vmwhile,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seten so</I>] sitten so R; so setyn &thorn;ey C; so &thorn;ei seten B; so seten O. <I>songen</I>] syngen R. <I>vmwhile</I>] vmb|while R; o&thorn;er while O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tyl glotoun had y-globbed &middot; a galoun an a Iille.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-globbed</I>] y-glubbed W; glubbed O; globed C; swelwid B. <I>an</I>] and WCROB. <I>Iille</I>] gille WCROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>His guttis gunne to [gothely] &middot; as two gredy sowes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gunne</I>] gonne R; bigonne WC; bigune O. [<I>gothely</I> C] gurle, <I>corrected to</I> gotheli O; go&thorn;elen W; grouly B; godly LR; <I>but in</I> L, <I>the line is marked for correction</I>. Crowley <I>prints</I> gothlen. <I>gredy</I>] guedy R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="348">He pissed a potel &middot; in a pater-noster while,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>potel</I>] potel and more B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And blew his rounde ruwet &middot; at his rigge-bon ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] He R. <I>ruwet</I>] rowet R; rewet C; ruet B. <I>rigge-bon</I>] rigges boun C; ruggebones W; rigges|bones R; rigge-bonys O; riegbones B.</NOTE></L>
<L>That alle &thorn;at herde &thorn;at horne &middot; held her nose after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at herde</I>] R <I>om. nose</I>] noses W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wissheden it had be wexed &middot; with a wispe of firses.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wexed</I>] waxed COB. <I>wispe</I>] wips R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="76, B-text"></L>
<L N="352">&para; He my&yogh;te neither steppe ne stonde &middot; er he his staffe hadde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] no C.</NOTE></L>
