<L N="583">Ne-none-of-her-seruauntes- &middot; &thorn;at-noyen-hem-my&yogh;te.<MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>noyen</I>] anoien B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke &yogh;e breke no bowes &thorn;ere &middot; but if it be &yogh;owre owne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>] &thorn;ow R. <I>&yogh;owre</I>] on &yogh;oure R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Two stokkes &thorn;ere stondeth &middot; ac stynte &yogh;e nou&yogh;te &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stondeth</I>] stonde CB. <I>ac</I>] and C.</NOTE></L>
<L>They [hatte] stele-nou&yogh;te, ne-slee-nou&yogh;te &middot; stryke forth by bothe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hatte</I> CR] hatten OB; hi&yogh;te W; hat L. <I>ne</I>] &amp; W. <I>by bothe</I>] bifore COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And leue hem on &thorn;i left halfe &middot; and loke nou&yogh;te &thorn;ere|after;</L>
<L N="588">And holde wel &thorn;yne haliday &middot; heighe til euen.</L>
<L>Thanne shaltow blenche at a berghe &middot; bere-no-false|witnesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>blenche</I>] <I>written more like</I> bleuche <I>in</I> L; blenche W. Cf. Text A. <I>berghe</I>] beruh R; beru&yogh; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>He is frithed in with floreines &middot; and other [fees] many;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="71"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He</I>] R <I>om. frithed in</I>] florischid wi&thorn;-Inne B. [<I>fees</I> WCRB] foes L; foos O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ow plukke no plante &thorn;ere &middot; for peril of &thorn;i soule.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ow</I>] &yogh;e R. <I>&thorn;i soule</I>] &yogh;oure soules R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="89, B-text"></L>
<L N="592">&para; &THORN;anne shal &yogh;e se sey-soth- &middot; so-it-be-to-done|<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>se</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-no-manere-ellis-nau&yogh;te- &middot; for-no-mannes-biddynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>] none RB; good W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne shaltow come to a courte &middot; as clere as &thorn;e sonne,</L>
<L N="595">&THORN;e mote is of mercy &middot; &thorn;e manere aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e mote</I>] &thorn;at moot hit B. <I>of</I>] O <I>om. manere</I>] Manoir W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e wallis ben of witte &middot; to holden wille oute;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kerneled with crystendome &middot; man-kynde to saue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kerneled</I>] I-carneled R. <I>man|kynde</I>] &thorn;at kende R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Boterased with bileue-so- &middot; or-&thorn;ow-beest-nou&yogh;te-ysaued.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Boterased</I>] Botrased W; Bi|trased C; I-buterased R; Bretaskid B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And alle &thorn;e houses ben hiled &middot; halles and chambres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] O <I>om. hiled</I>] I-hyled R; helied B. <I>halles</I>] halle B. <I>chambres</I>] chambere C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="600">Wit[h] no lede, but with loue &middot; and lowe-speche-as-bre|theren.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>With</I>] Wit L; <I>but the line is marked for correction</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e brugge is of bidde-wel- &middot; &thorn;e-bette-may-&thorn;ow-spede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brugge</I>] brygge COB. <I>may</I>] maist B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eche piler is of penaunce &middot; of preyeres to seyntes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Eche</I>] Ilke C. <I>preyeres</I>] prayer C; preyer O; preiere B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of almes dedes ar &thorn;e hokes &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e gates hangen on.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>almes dedes</I>] almeis dede C. <I>&thorn;e</I> (1)] &thorn;o B. <I>&thorn;at</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="604">&para; Grace hatte &thorn;e gateward &middot; a gode man for sothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hatte</I>] hoti&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys man hatte amende-&yogh;ow &middot; for many man him knoweth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hatte</I>] hoti&thorn; B. <I>for</I>] R <I>om. man</I>] men WB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Telleth hym &thorn;is tokene &middot; &thorn;at treuthe wite &thorn;e sothe;</L>
<L>'I parfourned &thorn;e penaunce &middot; &thorn;e preest me enioyned,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>parfourned</I>] parfournied R; performed B. <I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] &thorn;at &thorn;e W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="608">And am ful sori for my synnes &middot; and so I shal euere,</L>
<L>Whan I &thorn;inke &thorn;ere-on &middot; &thorn;eighe I were a pope.'</L>
<L>&para; Biddeth amende-&yogh;ow meke him &middot; til his maistre ones,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="72"></L>
<L>To wayne vp &thorn;e wiket &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e womman shette,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wayne</I>] wayne OB; wayne <I>or</I> wayue LRC; waynen <I>or</I> wayuen (<I>printed</I> wayven) W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="612">Tho Adam and Eue &middot; eten apples vnrosted;<Q><I>Per euam cun[c]tis clausa est, &amp; per mariam virginem [iterum] patefacta est;</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>iterum</I>] <I>in</I> R <I>only</I>. See note.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="90, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; For he hath &thorn;e keye and &thorn;e [cliket] &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e kynge slepe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] scho C. [<I>cliket</I> WCB] clikat LR. <I>&thorn;ou&yogh;</I>] &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And if grace graunte &thorn;e &middot; to go in in &thorn;is wise,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in in</I>] in WCROB; <I>but see</I> Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ow shalt see in &thorn;i-selue &middot; treuthe sitte in &thorn;ine herte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sitte</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="616">In a cheyne of charyte &middot; as &thorn;ow a childe were,</L>
<L>To suffre hym and segge nou&yogh;te &middot; a&yogh;ein &thorn;i sires wille.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>segge</I>] saye C. <I>segge nou&yogh;te</I>] to segge (!) R. <I>&thorn;i sires</I>] thy eires C; &thorn;yn heiris B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac bewar &thorn;anne of wrath-&thorn;e &middot; &thorn;at is a wikked shrewe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And WC. <I>wrath-&thorn;e</I>] Wratthe CB. <I>shrewe</I>] sherewe W.</NOTE></L>
<L>He hath enuye to hym &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;ine herte sitteth;<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] til COB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="620">And pukketh for&thorn; pruyde &middot; to prayse &thorn;i-seluen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pukketh</I>] pukkes C; pucketh R; pouke&thorn; O; poke&thorn; WB. <I>for&thorn;</I>] for C; R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e boldnesse of &thorn;i bienfetes &middot; maketh &thorn;e blynde &thorn;anne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bienfetes</I>] benefetes R; bien|faittes CB; beenfetis O. <I>maketk</I>] make C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;anne worstow dryuen oute as dew &middot; and &thorn;e dore closed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;anne</I>] O <I>om. worstow</I>] worst &thorn;ou B; wor&thorn;est &thorn;ou O. <I>dryuen</I>] dryues C. <I>dew</I>] deuh R; a dew CB. <I>closed</I>] I-closed R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kayed and [cliketed] &middot; to kepe &thorn;e with-outen;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Kayed</I>] I-cayed R; Keyed WCOB. [<I>cliketed</I> CB] clikated L; cliketted W; I-clycated R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="624">Happily an hundreth wyntre &middot; ar &thorn;ow eft entre.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hundreth</I>] hundred WOB. <I>ar</I>] er WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;us myght &thorn;ow lesen his loue &middot; to late wel by &thorn;i-selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myght &thorn;ow</I>] my&yogh;tist &thorn;ou O; my&yogh;testow W; mi&yogh;tow R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And neuere happiliche efte entre &middot; but grace &thorn;ow haue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>but</I>] til O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;ere [aren] seuene sustren &middot; &thorn;at seruen treuthe euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And WC. [<I>aren</I> R] are W; ar L; been O; ben B; be C; <I>see next line. sustren</I>] sistren O; systers C; &yogh;iftes (!) R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="628">And aren porteres of &thorn;e posternes &middot; that to &thorn;e place longeth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aren</I>] arn W; been O; ben B; be C. <I>porteres</I>] portes C. <I>of</I>] ouer R. <I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at one hat abstenence &middot; and humilite an other,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>humilite</I>] vmblete R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Charite and chastite &middot; ben his chief maydenes,
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="91, B-text"></L>
<L>Pacience and pees &middot; moche poeple &thorn;ei helpeth,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="73"></L>
<L N="632">Largenesse &thorn;e lady &middot; heo let in ful manye;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heo</I>] he R; she WOB; sho C. <I>in</I>] out (!) O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo hath hulpe a &thorn;ousande oute &middot; of &thorn;e deueles pon|folde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Heo</I>] Sche OB; Sho C. <I>hulpe</I>] <I>so in</I> R.; holpe WCO; holpen B. <I>ponfolde</I>] pondfolde R; punfolde WB; pounfolde C; pynfold O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And who is sibbe to &thorn;is seuene &middot; so me god helpe!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>who</I>] who so CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>He is wonderliche welcome &middot; and faire vnderfongen.</L>
<L N="636">And but if &yogh;e be syb &middot; to summe of &thorn;ise seuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>] if &thorn;at R. <I>&yogh;e</I>] he B.</NOTE></L>
<L>It is ful harde bi myne heued," quod Peres &middot; "for any of &yogh;ow alle</L>
<L>To geten ingonge at any gate &thorn;ere &middot; but grace be &thorn;e more."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ingonge</I>] ingong O; Ingange C; in-going WB. <I>any</I>] &thorn;e COB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="639">&para; "Now, bi cryst," quod a cutpurs &middot; "I haue no kynne &thorn;ere!"</L>
<L>"Ne I," quod an apewarde &middot; "bi au&yogh;te &thorn;at I knowe!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ne</I>] Nor WCB; Nou O. <I>I</I> (2)] I kan W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Wite god," quod a wafrestre &middot; "wist I &thorn;is for sothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wite god</I>] God wot B. <I>wa|frestre</I>] waferer OB. <I>for</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shulde I neuere ferthere a fote &middot; for no freres prechynge."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Shulde</I>] Shul C. <I>freres</I>] frere R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="643">&para; "&YOGH;us," quod Pieres &thorn;e plowman &middot; and pukked hem alle to gode,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;us</I>] &yogh;is B; &yogh;is WC. <I>pukked</I>] poukede O; poked WRB; pute C. <I>hem</I>] the (<I>miswritten for</I> them) C; O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Mercy is a maydene &thorn;ere &middot; hath my&yogh;te ouer hem alle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] as C. <I>hath</I>] and ha&thorn; B. <I>hem</I>] WCOB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And she is syb to alle synful &middot; and her sone also;</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh;e &thorn;e helpe of hem two &middot; (hope &thorn;ow none other),</L>
<L>&thorn;ow my&yogh;te gete grace &thorn;ere &middot; bi so &thorn;ow go bityme."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ere bi</I>] &thorn;ere &middot; bi LO; &thorn;ere &middot; be R; &thorn;ere W; &thorn;erby CB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="648">&para; "By seynt Poule," quod a pardonere &middot; "perauenture I be nou&yogh;te knowe &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>knowe &thorn;ere</I>] welcome R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="92, B-text"></L>
<L>I wil go fecche my box with my breuettes &middot; and a bulle with bisshopes lettres!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>go</I>] COB <I>om. fecche</I>] fette B. <I>bisshopes</I>] bisshope C.</NOTE></L>
<L>"By cryst," quod a comune womman &middot; "&thorn;i companye wil I folwe,</L>
<L N="651">&THORN;ow shalt sey I am &thorn;i sustre &middot; I ne wot where &thorn;ei bicome."
</L>
</LG>

