<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000375.tif" N="93, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS VI.</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. Passus Sextus LOB; C <I>adds</I>, de visione; WR <I>add</I>, de visione, vt supra.</NOTE><I>Passus Sextus</I>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"This were a wikked way &middot; but who-so hadde a gyde<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="74"></L>
<L>That wolde folwen vs eche a fote;" &middot; &thorn;us &thorn;is folke hem mened.</L>
<L>Quat&yogh; Perkyn &thorn;e plouman &middot; "bi seynt Peter of Rome,<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>omit</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">I haue an half acre to erye &middot; bi &thorn;e heighe way;<MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hadde I eried &thorn;is half acre &middot; and sowen it after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eried</I>] hered R. <I>sowen</I>] I-sowen R.</NOTE></L>
<L>I [wolde] wende with &yogh;ow &middot; and &thorn;e way teche."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolde</I> WOB] wil LR; wyl C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;is were a longe lettynge" &middot; quod a lady in a sklayre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> (3)] <I>retained in</I> W (<I>but omitted in the printed edition</I>). <I>sklayre</I>] Scleyre W; slaire C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">"What sholde we wommen &middot; worche &thorn;ere whiles?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>omit. &thorn;ere whiles</I>] <I>so in</I> R; &thorn;e whyles O; &thorn;e while W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Somme shal sowe [&thorn;e] sakke," quod Piers &middot; "for shedyng of &thorn;e whete;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shal</I>] schal R; shul WC; shullen B. [<I>&thorn;e</I> WCROB] L <I>om. &thorn;e whete</I>] whete CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;e, louely ladyes &middot; with &yogh;oure longe fyngres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ladyes</I>] lady B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e han silke and sendal &middot; to sowe, whan tyme is,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>han</I>] haue WRCB. <I>sendal</I>] sandel WC.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">Chesibles for chapelleynes &middot; cherches to honoure.</L>
<L>&para; Wyues and wydwes &middot; wolle &amp; flex spynneth,
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="94, B-text"></L>
<L>Maketh cloth, I conseille &yogh;ow &middot; and kenneth so &yogh;owre dou&yogh;tres;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Maketh</I>] Make C. <I>kenneth so</I>] kennes C; kenny&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e nedy and &thorn;e naked &middot; nymmeth hede how hij liggeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nymmeth</I>] takes C. <I>hij lig|geth</I>] &thorn;ei ligge&thorn; W; &thorn;ey ligge COB; a lyggeth R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="16">And casteth hem clothes &middot; for so comaundeth treuthe.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="75"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>casteth</I>] castes C. <I>hem</I>] hym R. <I>comaundeth</I>] biddi&thorn; O; com|aunde C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For I shal lene hem lyflode &middot; but &yogh;if &thorn;e londe faille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lene</I>] <I>so in</I> LOB; lene <I>or</I> leue RC; lenen <I>or</I> leuen (<I>printed</I> leven) W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Flesshe and bred bothe &middot; to riche and to pore,</L>
<L>As longe as I lyue &middot; for &thorn;e lordes loue of heuene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] oure O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&para; And alle manere of men &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;orw mete and drynke lybbeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lybbeth</I>] lyues C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Helpith hym to worche wi&yogh;tliche &middot; &thorn;at wynneth &yogh;owre fode."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Helpith</I>] Helpes C. <I>wynneth</I>] wynnes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Bi crist," quod a kny&yogh;te &thorn;o &middot; "he kenneth vs &thorn;e best;</L>
<L>Ac on &thorn;e teme trewly &middot; tau&yogh;te was I neuere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>tau&yogh;te</I>] caught (<I>so miswritten</I>) C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">Ac kenne me," quod &thorn;e kny&yogh;te &middot; "and, bi cryst, I wil assaye!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] But W; And C. <I>bi cryst</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Bi seynt Poule," quod Perkyn &middot; "&yogh;e profre &yogh;ow so faire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I shal swynke and swete &middot; and sowe for vs bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sowe</I>] saw C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er laboures do for &thorn;i loue &middot; al my lyf tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>laboures</I>] laboreres R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">In couenaunt &thorn;at &thorn;ow kepe &middot; holikirke and my-selue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin of</I> O&mdash;&thorn;e lyuyng of trewe kny&yogh;tis. <I>my</I>] &thorn;y C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro wastoures and fro wykked men &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde struyeth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fro</I>] COB <I>om. struyeth</I>] strueth R; struthes C; stroyen O; stroie&thorn; B; destruye&thorn; W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And go hunte hardiliche &middot; to hares and to foxes,</L>
<L>To bores and to brockes &middot; &thorn;at breketh adown myne hegges,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="76"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brockes</I>] bukkes R. <I>adown</I>] doun W. <I>myne</I>] men B.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="95, B-text"></L>
<L N="32">And go affaite &thorn;e faucones &middot; wilde foules to kille;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>go</I>] so W. <I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;i WR; &thorn;y C. <I>foules</I>] foweles W; bestis O.</NOTE></L>
<L>For suche cometh to my croft &middot; and croppeth my whete."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>suche</I>] swiche WR; swilce C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Curteislich &thorn;e kny&yogh;te &thorn;anne &middot; comsed &thorn;ise wordes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ise</I>] hise O.</NOTE></L>
<L>"By my power, Pieres," quod he &middot; "I pli&yogh;te &thorn;e my treuthe</L>
<L N="36">To fulfille &thorn;is forward &middot; &thorn;ow&yogh; I fi&yogh;te sholde;</L>
<L>Als longe as I lyue &middot; I shal &thorn;e mayntene."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Als</I>] Al-so B; As CR.</NOTE></L>
