<L>And be fayne, bi my feith &middot; his phisik to lete,</L>
<L>And lerne to laboure with londe &middot; for lyflode is swete;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lerne</I>] lere CO; to lere B. <I>laboure</I>] labori R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For morthereres aren mony leches &middot; lorde hem amende!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] R <I>om. morthereres&mdash;leches</I>] many lechis ben mor&thorn;ereris B; &thorn;er aren mo morareres (<I>sic</I>) &thorn;an leches R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="276">&THORN;ei do men deye &thorn;orw here drynkes &middot; ar destine it wolde."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do men</I>] maken men to B. <I>drynkes</I>] drynkyngis B. <I>destine</I>] here desteny B. <I>it</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "By seynt Poule," quod pieres &middot; "&thorn;ise aren profit|able wordis!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pieres</I>] Piers W; perkyn CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wende now, hunger, whan &thorn;ow wolt &middot; &thorn;at wel be &thorn;ow euere!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be &thorn;ow</I>] &thorn;ow be R; be &thorn;ee O; be &thorn;e B.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;is is a louely lessoun &middot; lorde it &thorn;e for-&yogh;elde!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="280">&para; "By-hote god," quod hunger &middot; "hennes ne wil I wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>By-hote</I>] I bihote B. <I>ne wil I</I>] wol I nat COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til I haue dyned bi &thorn;is day &middot; and ydronke bothe."</L>
<L>&para; "I haue no peny," quod peres &middot; "poletes forto bigge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>forto</I>] to W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne neyther gees ne grys &middot; but two grene cheses,<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>omit. gees</I>] goos O. <I>grys</I>] grijs O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="284">A fewe cruddes and creem &middot; and an hauer cake,
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="108, B-text"></L>
<L>And two loues of benes and bran &middot; y-bake for my fauntis.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="89"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bran</I>] of bran B. <I>y-bake</I>] I take CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;et I sey, by my soule &middot; I haue no salt bacoun,</L>
<L N="287">Ne no kokeney, bi cryst &middot; coloppes forto maken.</L>
<L>Ac I haue percil and porettes &middot; and many kole-plantes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>percil</I>] percile WR; percelle C; persoly B. <I>porettes</I>] porett R; porete B. <I>kole-plantes</I>] cale-plantes C; queynte herbes R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And eke a cow and a kalf &middot; and a cart-mare</L>
<L>To drawe a-felde my donge &middot; &thorn;e while &thorn;e drought lasteth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a-felde</I>] on feld B. <I>&thorn;e</I> (1)] B <I>om. &thorn;e</I> (2)] C <I>om. drought last|eth</I>] weder is drye COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bi &thorn;is lyflode we mot lyue &middot; til lammasse tyme;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>til&mdash;tyme</I>] to heruest tyme CB; til heruest tyme come O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="292">And bi &thorn;at, I hope to haue &middot; heruest in my croft;</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne may I di&yogh;te &thorn;i dyner &middot; as me dere liketh."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>liketh</I>] likes C; lykede B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e pore peple &thorn;o &middot; pesecoddes fetten,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fetten</I>] to fette B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Benes and baken apples &middot; &thorn;ei brou&yogh;te in her lappes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Only one line in</I> CB; <I>thus</I>&mdash;Benes, Chibolles, and cherueles &middot; and many o&thorn;er herbes.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lappes</I>] lappe R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="296">Chibolles and cheruelles &middot; and ripe chiries manye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Only one line in</I> CB; <I>thus</I>&mdash;Benes, Chibolles, and cherueles &middot; and many o&thorn;er herbes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And profred peres &thorn;is present &middot; to plese with hunger.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And&mdash;&thorn;is</I>] To make Piers a COB. <I>with</I>] with his COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Al hunger eet in hast &middot; and axed after more.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Al</I>] An C; Ac B. <I>axed</I>] asked C; aski&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;anne pore folke for fere &middot; fedde hunger &yogh;erne</L>
<L N="300">With grene poret and pesen &middot; to poysoun hunger &thorn;ei &thorn;ou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>poret</I>] porettes COB. <I>and</I>] and wi&thorn; B. <I>to&mdash;hunger</I>] to poisone hym W; hunger &thorn;ey CB. <I>&thorn;ou&yogh;te</I>] sou&yogh;te B.</NOTE></L>
<L>By &thorn;at it neighed nere heruest &middot; newe corne cam to chepynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it&mdash;nere</I>] neighed C; ney&yogh;hede it O; hit neighed B. <I>newe</I>] &amp; newe W; CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;anne was folke fayne &middot; and fedde hunger with &thorn;e best,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="90"><NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits. hunger with</I>] hem of CO.</NOTE></L>
<L>With good ale, as glotoun tau&yogh;te &middot; and gerte hunger go slepe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>omit. gerte</I>] garte W.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="109, B-text"></L>
<L N="304">&para; And &thorn;o wolde wastour nou&yogh;t werche &middot; but wandren aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolde&mdash;nou&yogh;t</I>] ne wolde no wastour R; wolde nou&yogh;t (<I>omitting</I> wastour) C; &thorn;ei wolden no&yogh;t B. <I>wandren</I>] wandred COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no begger ete bred &middot; &thorn;at benes Inne were,<MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But of coket or clerematyn &middot; or elles of clene whete;<NOTE PLACE="foot">But of coket or clene whete &middot; and drynke of &thorn;e beste ale C; B <I>the same, with</I> or of <I>for</I> or.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I> (1)] or of R; and W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne none halpeny ale &middot; in none wise drynke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">But of coket or clene whete &middot; and drynke of &thorn;e beste ale C; B <I>the same, with</I> or of <I>for</I> or.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>halpeny</I>] <I>so also in</I> RO; half|peny W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="308">But of &thorn;e best and of &thorn;e brounest &middot; &thorn;at in borghe is to selle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I> (2)] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Laboreres &thorn;at haue no lande &middot; to lyue on but her handes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>haue</I>] hadde O. <I>to&mdash;but</I>] but lyue wi&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Deyned nou&yogh;t to dyne a-day &middot; ny&yogh;t-olde wortes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wolden ete no ny&yogh;t olde wortis &middot; ne drynke no peny ale OC<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>nou&yogh;t</I>] R <I>om</I>. (<I>by mistake</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>May no peny ale hem paye &middot; ne no pece of bakoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">308&mdash;311. CB <I>omit</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Wolden ete no ny&yogh;t olde wortis &middot; ne drynke no peny ale OC<SUB>2</SUB>. <I>nou&yogh;t</I>] R <I>om</I>. (<I>by mistake</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="312">But if it be fresch flesch other fische &middot; fryed other bake,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if it be</I>] COB <I>om. bake</I>] y-bake WB; baken O.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fryed&mdash;chaud</I>] R <I>om. or</I>] and W. <I>here</I>] his R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at <I>chaude</I> or <I>plus chaud</I> &middot; for chillyng of here mawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fryed&mdash;chaud</I>] R <I>om. or</I>] and W. <I>here</I>] his R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And but if he be heighlich huyred &middot; ellis wil he chyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>] CO <I>om. heighlich</I>] hye O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at he was werkman wrou&yogh;t &middot; waille &thorn;e tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">COB <I>omit</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="316">A&yogh;eines catones conseille &middot; comseth he to iangle:&mdash;<Q><I>Paupertatis onus pacienter ferre memento</I>.</Q></L>
<L>&para; He greueth hym a&yogh;eines god &middot; and gruccheth a&yogh;eines resoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gruccheth</I>] grucchede B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;anne curseth he &thorn;e kynge &middot; and al his conseille after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] R <I>om. &thorn;anne&mdash;he</I>] he corses &thorn;e C; he curse&thorn; &thorn;e O; he cursed &thorn;e B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="319">Suche lawes to loke &middot; laboreres to greue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>loke</I>] look C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="110, B-text"></L>
<L N="320">Ac whiles hunger was her maister &middot; &thorn;ere wolde none of hem chyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And COB. <I>&thorn;ere&mdash;hem</I>] wolde &thorn;ey nat COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne stryue a&yogh;eines his statut &middot; so sterneliche he loked.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="91"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I>] &thorn;e B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac I warne &yogh;ow, werkemen &middot; wynneth while &yogh;e mowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hunger hide[r]ward &middot; hasteth hym faste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hiderward</I>] <I>so in</I> WCROB; hideward L. <I>faste</I>] ful faste R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="324">He shal awake with water &middot; wastoures to chaste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>water</I>] wat R. <I>chaste</I>] chastie C; chastise OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ar fyue [&yogh;ere] be fulfilled &middot; suche famyn shal aryse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fyue</I>] fewe B. [<I>&yogh;ere</I> R] &yogh;eer OB; LWC <I>om.;</I> Crowley <I>has</I> yere. <I>suche</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thorwgh flodes and &thorn;ourgh foule wederes &middot; frutes shul faille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ourgh</I>] CROB <I>om. foule wederes</I>] foule werdis O; foolis wordis B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="327">And so sayde saturne &middot; and sent &yogh;ow to warne:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sent</I>] sende B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan &yogh;e se &thorn;e sonne amys &middot; and two monkes hedes,</L>
<L>And a Mayde haue &thorn;e maistrie &middot; and multiplie bi eight,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>multiplie</I>] <I>so in</I> WCOB; LR <I>have</I> multiplied; Crowley <I>has</I> mul|tiply. <I>bi</I>] be R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;anne shal deth withdrawe &middot; and derthe be iustice,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ll. 329,330. Transposed in</I> B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dawe &thorn;e dyker &middot; deye for hunger,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deye</I>] shal dye B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="332">But if god of his goodnesse &middot; graunt vs a trewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>But</I>] And R. <I>if</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000393.tif" N="111, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS VII.</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. <I>So in</I> LWCRB; Passus 7 <I>us</I> O.</NOTE><I>Passus vij</I><SUP>us.</SUP> <I>de visione, vt supra</I>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Treuthe herde telle her-of &middot; and to peres he sent,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="92"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her-of</I>] her-of (<I>printed</I> her) W. <I>he</I>] O <I>om. sent</I>] wente B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To taken his teme &middot; and tulyen &thorn;e erthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>taken</I>] maken W. <I>tulyen</I>] <I>so in</I> LR; tilien WCB; tilie O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And purchaced hym a pardoun &middot; <I>a pena &amp; a culpa</I></L>
<L N="4">For hym, and for his heires &middot; for euermore after.</L>
<L>And bad hym holde hym at home &middot; and eryen his leyes,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at halpe hym to erie &middot; to sette or to sowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>halpe</I>] holpen WOB; holpe R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or any other myster &middot; &thorn;at my&yogh;te pieres auaille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myster</I>] mestier W; mester R; mynysterye B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pardoun with pieres plowman &middot; treuthe hath ygraunted.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pieres</I>] peres &thorn;e R; pieris &thorn;e B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="9">&para; Kynges and kny&yogh;tes &middot; &thorn;at kepen holycherche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cherche</I>] cherches R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ry&yogh;tfullych in reumes &middot; reulen &thorn;e peple,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>reumes</I>] reames C; Remes W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Han pardoun thourgh purgatorie &middot; to passe ful ly&yogh;tly,<MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Han</I>] And (!) R. <I>ly&yogh;tly</I>] lighte COB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">With patriarkes and prophetes &middot; in paradise to be felawes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>felawes</I>] felawe WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Bisshopes yblessed &middot; &yogh;if &thorn;ei ben as &thorn;ei shulden,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shulden</I>] mowe amende B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Legistres of bothe &thorn;e lawes &middot; &thorn;e lewed &thorn;ere-with to preche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (1)] WRB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in as moche as &thorn;ei mowe &middot; amende alle synful,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="93"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="112, B-text"></L>
<L>Aren peres with &thorn;e apostles &middot; [&thorn;is] pardoun Piers sheweth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>&thorn;is</I> WCOB] &thorn;us LR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="17">And at &thorn;e day of dome &middot; atte heigh deyse to sytte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deyse</I>] deys WCOB; dayes R. <I>to</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Marchauntz in &thorn;e margyne &middot; hadden many &yogh;eres,</L>
<L>Ac none <I>a pena &amp; a culpa</I> &middot; &thorn;e Pope nolde hem graunte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>none&mdash;pena</I>] no <I>pena</I> R. <I>a</I> (2)] O <I>om. Pope</I>] pape C. <I>nolde hem</I>] wald hem nau&yogh;t R; wolde hem B.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ei holde nou&yogh;t her halidayes &middot; as holicherche techeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holde</I>] held C. <I>halidayes</I>] halyday R. <I>techeth</I>] telleth R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="21">And for &thorn;ei swere by her soule &middot; and 'so god moste hem helpe,'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by&mdash;soule</I>] ofte R. <I>and</I>] R <I>om. moste</I>] mote B; R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;ein clene conscience &middot; her catel to selle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>catel</I>] chaffare B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac vnder his secret seel &middot; treuthe sent hem a lettre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And CB. <I>his</I>] her O. <I>seel</I>] sehel O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">That &thorn;ey shulde bugge boldely &middot; &thorn;at hem best liked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] what B. <I>best liked</I>] likede best O; best liketh R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sithenes selle it a&yogh;ein &middot; and saue &thorn;e wynny[n]ge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it</I>] it vs R. <I>wynnynge</I>] wyn|nynges R; <I>miswritten</I> wynnyge L.</NOTE></L>
<L>And amende <I>mesondieux</I> &thorn;ere-myde &middot; and myseyse folke helpe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ere-myde</I>] &thorn;er-with CRB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wikked wayes &middot; wi&yogh;tlich hem amende;<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>om. hem</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">And do bote to brugges &middot; &thorn;at to-broke were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brugges</I>] brugges (<I>altered to</I> brygges) C; briegges B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Marien maydenes &middot; or maken hem nonnes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maken</I>] to make B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pore peple and prisounes &middot; fynden hem here fode,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="94"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] or R. <I>prisounes</I>] prisones RCO; prisons W; prisoneris B. <I>fode</I>] liflode CB; lijflode O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sette scoleres to scole &middot; or to somme other craftes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>somme</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">Releue Religioun &middot; and renten hem bettere;&mdash;</L>
<L>"And I shal sende &yogh;ow my-selue &middot; seynt Michel myn archangel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no deuel shal &yogh;ow dere &middot; ne fere &yogh;ow in &yogh;owre deyinge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deyinge</I>] deynge R; doynge (<I>sic</I>) COB, <I>and</I> Crowley.</NOTE></L>
<L>And witen &yogh;ow fro wanhope &middot; if &yogh;e wil &thorn;us worche,
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="113, B-text"></L>
<L N="36">And sende &yogh;owre sowles in safte &middot; to my seyntes in ioye."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sende</I>] sente C. <I>in</I> (1)] in-to O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne were Marchauntz mery &middot; many wepten for ioye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Marchauntz&mdash;wepten</I>] manye marchauntz &middot; &thorn;at wopen R. <I>many</I>] &amp; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And preyseden pieres &thorn;e plowman &middot; &thorn;at purchaced &thorn;is bulle.</L>
<L N="39">&para; Men of lawe lest pardoun hadde &middot; &thorn;at pleteden for Mede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Two lines in</I> R; <I>the first ends at</I> hadde; <I>the second is eked out by adding</I> for &thorn;at craft is schrewed.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e sauter saueth hem nou&yogh;te &middot; such as taketh &yogh;iftes,</L>
<L>And namelich of innocentz &middot; &thorn;at none yuel ne kunneth;<Q><I>Super innocentem munera non accipies</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne kunneth</I>] konnes C; kunnen OB. R <I>omits the Latin</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pledoures shulde peynen hem &middot; to plede for such, an helpe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peynen</I>] pyne CO; pynen B. <I>an</I>] and WCROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Prynces and prelates &middot; shulde paye for her trauaille;<Q><I>A regibus &amp; pryncipibus erit merces eorum</I>.</Q></L>
<L N="44">&para; Ac many a iustice an iuroure &middot; wolde for Iohan do more,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>a iustice</I>] Iustices COB. <I>iuroure</I>] Iurour CO; Iur|rouris B. <I>Iohan</I>] ion O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an <I>pro dei pietate</I> &middot; leue &thorn;ow none other!<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="95"></L>
<L>Ac he &thorn;at spendeth his speche &middot; and speke&thorn; for &thorn;e pore<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>spendeth</I>] speneth R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is Innocent and nedy &middot; and no man appeireth,</L>
<L N="48">Conforteth hym in &thorn;at cas &middot; with-oute coueytise of &yogh;iftes,<MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Conforteth</I>] And conforteth R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And scheweth lawe for owre lordes loue &middot; as he it hath lerned,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lerned</I>] I-lerned R; y-lerned W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal no deuel at his ded-day &middot; deren hym a my&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ded-day</I>] dede-day C; dee&thorn;-day WB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne worth sauf and his sowle &middot; &thorn;e sauter bereth witnesse;<Q><I>Domine, quis habitabit in tabernaculo tuo, &amp;c</I>.</Q>
