</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000405.tif" N="[unnumbered], B-text">
<HEAD>Visio ejusdem de Do-wel, Do-bet, et Do-best, secundum Wit et Resoun.</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="[unnumbered], B-text">

<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="125, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS VIII. (INCIPIT DO-WEL.)<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>TITLE. [<I>Petri&mdash;Dobest</I>] <I>so in</I> R (<I>but with the spelling</I> Plowhman); &amp; primus de dowel LW; vt supra C; vt supra; Et hic incipit primus de do|wel, &amp;c., B. O <I>merely has</I> Passus octauus. <I>See the</I> Note.</P><P>OBS. <I>From this point mere varia|tions of spelling and inflexion will not so often be given, as they can be well ascertained from the foregoing part</I>.</P></NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD><I>Passus octauus de visione</I> [<I>Petri Plowman. Incipit Dowel, Dobet, &amp; Dobest</I>.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THus yrobed in russet &middot; I romed aboute<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="103"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>romed</I> WCRO] romed me B; <I>spelt</I> rowmed <I>in</I> L, <I>but the line is marked</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al a somer sesoun &middot; for to seke dowel,</L>
<L>And frayned ful oft &middot; of folke &thorn;at I mette,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>frayned</I>] asked C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">If ani wi&yogh;te wiste &middot; where dowel was at Inne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>was</I>] were R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And what man he mi&yogh;te be &middot; of many man I axed.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>] men B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Was neuere wi&yogh;te, as I went &middot; &thorn;at me wisse couthe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Was&mdash;went</I>] And was neuere in &thorn;is worlde R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where &thorn;is lede lenged &middot; lasse ne more;<NOTE PLACE="foot">O <I>omits. lenged</I>] logged was B. <I>ne</I>] o&thorn;ur B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">&para; Tyl it bifel on a fryday &middot; two freres I mette,</L>
<L>Maistres of &thorn;e Menoures &middot; men of grete witte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Maistres</I>] And maistres R.</NOTE></L>
<L>I hailsed hem hendely &middot; as I hadde lerned,</L>
<L>And preyed hem par charitee &middot; ar &thorn;ei passed forther,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>par</I>] for CR; pur OB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">If &thorn;ei knewe any contre &middot; or costes, as &thorn;ei went,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>contre</I>] courte R. <I>as</I>] &thorn;er R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where &thorn;at dowel dwelleth &middot; doth me to wytene.
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="126, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ei ben men on &thorn;is molde &middot; &thorn;at moste wyde walken,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyde</I>] wilde COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And knowen contrees, and courtes &middot; and many kynnes places,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>contrees and courtes</I>] townes and contreis B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="16">Bothe prynces paleyses &middot; and pore mennes cotes,</L>
<L>And do-wel and do-yuel &middot; where &thorn;ei dwelle bothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">14&mdash;17. R <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Amonges vs," quod &thorn;e Menours &middot; "&thorn;at man is dwellynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e Menours</I>] a menoures (<I>sic</I>) R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euere hath, as I hope &middot; and euere shal here-after."<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="104"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>euere</I> (2)] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&para; "Contra," quod I as a clerke &middot; and comsed to dis|puten,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>comsed</I>] by-gane C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide [hem] sothli, "<I>sepcies &middot; in die cadit iustus;</I><MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hem</I> WCOB] LR <I>om. sothli</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seuene sythes, seith &thorn;e boke &middot; synneth &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seith</I>] on &thorn;e day sei&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And who-so synneth," I seyde &middot; "doth yuel, as me &thorn;inketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I seyde</I>] he saide CO; seide he B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dowel and do-yuel &middot; mow nou&yogh;t dwelle togideres.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dowel&mdash;do-yuel</I>] do-yuel and do-wel CB. O <I>omits this line</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25"><I>Ergo</I>, he nys nau&yogh;t alway &middot; amonge &yogh;ow freres;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nys</I>] is CROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>He is otherwhile ellis where &middot; to wisse &thorn;e peple."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "I shal sey &thorn;e, my sone" &middot; seide &thorn;e frere &thorn;anne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shal</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"How seuene sithes &thorn;e sadman &middot; on &thorn;e day synneth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] a WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="29">By a forbisene," quod &thorn;e frere &middot; "I shal &thorn;e faire shewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a forbisene</I>] an ensample B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Lat brynge a man in a bote &middot; amydde a brode water,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> (3)] &thorn;e WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wynde and &thorn;e water &middot; and &thorn;e bote waggynge</L>
<L>Maketh &thorn;e man many a tyme &middot; to falle and to stonde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] a O. <I>a</I>] RO <I>om. and</I>] &thorn;an B. <I>stonde</I>] stumble O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="33">For stonde he neuere so styf &middot; he stombleth &yogh;if he moeue;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] B <I>om. stombleth</I>] tumble&thorn; B. <I>moeue</I>] meue WR; moue&thorn; O; meuy&thorn; B.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="127, B-text"></L>
<L>Ac &yogh;it is he sauf and sounde &middot; and so hym bihoueth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &yogh;if he ne arise &thorn;e rather &middot; and rau&yogh;te to &thorn;e stiere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stiere</I>] steere W; stere COB; sterne R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wynde wolde, wyth &thorn;e water &middot; &thorn;e bote ouerthrowe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyth</I>] and R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="37">And &thorn;anne were his lyf loste &middot; &thorn;ourgh lacchesse of hym-self.</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;us it falleth," quod &thorn;e frere &middot; "bi folke here on erthe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e water is likned to &thorn;e worlde &middot; &thorn;at wanyeth and wexeth,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="105"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wanyeth</I>] wanes C; wanti&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e godis of &thorn;is grounde aren like &middot; to &thorn;e grete wawes,</L>
<L N="41">&THORN;at as wyndes and wederes &middot; walweth aboute.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>walweth</I>] walke&thorn; WRB; walkes C; walken O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bote is likned to owre body &middot; &thorn;at brutel is of kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>body</I>] bodyes CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;orugh &thorn;e fende and [&thorn;e] flesshe &middot; and &thorn;e frele worlde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] And B. [<I>&thorn;e</I> WCOB] &thorn;i LR. <I>&thorn;e</I> (3)] &thorn;is R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">Synneth &thorn;e sadman &middot; a day, seuene sythes.</L>
<L>&para; Ac dedly synne doth he nou&yogh;t &middot; for dowel hym kepith,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is charite &thorn;e champioun &middot; chief help a&yogh;ein synne;</L>
<L>For he strengtheth man to stonde &middot; and stereth mannes soule,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>] men W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;owgh &thorn;i body bow &middot; as bote doth in &thorn;e water,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] &thorn;at R. <I>&thorn;owgh</I>] doi&thorn; B. <I>&thorn;i</I>] &thorn;e W. <I>&thorn;e</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ay is &thorn;i soule sauf &middot; but [if] &thorn;i-self wole<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>if</I> WCOB] LR <I>om. &thorn;i-self wole</I>] &thorn;ow wole &thorn;i-selue W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Do a dedly synne &middot; and drenche so &thorn;i soule;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so</I>] CB <I>om. soule</I>] selue R.</NOTE></L>
<L>God wole suffre wel &thorn;i sleuthe &middot; &yogh;if &thorn;i-self lyketh.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sleuthe</I>] soule R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">For he &yogh;af &thorn;e to &yogh;eres&yogh;yue &middot; to &yogh;eme wel &thorn;i-selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I> (1)] a W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at is witte a[nd] fre wille &middot; to euery wy&yogh;te a por|cioun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] L <I>has</I> a, <I>but the line is marked for correction;</I> and WCROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To fleghyng foules &middot; to fissches &amp; to bestes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp;</I>] and also COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac man hath moste &thorn;erof &middot; and moste is to blame,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>] &thorn;anne, <I>altered to</I> men R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="128, B-text"></L>
<L>But if he worche wel &thorn;er-with &middot; as dowel hym techeth."</L>
<L N="57">&para; "I haue no kynde knowyng," quod I &middot; "to conceyue alle &yogh;owre wordes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;owre</I>] &thorn;i R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac if I may lyue and loke &middot; I shal go lerne bettere."</L>
<L>"I bikenne &thorn;e cryst, [quod he] &middot; &thorn;at on &thorn;e crosse deyde."<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>quod he</I> W] quod &thorn;ei R; LCOB <I>om. on &thorn;e</I>] on W; vppon &thorn;e B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">And I seyde, "&thorn;e same &middot; saue &yogh;ow fro myschaunce,</L>
<L>And &yogh;iue &yogh;ow grace on &thorn;is grounde &middot; good men to worthe."<MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;us I went wide-where &middot; walkyng myne one,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myne</I>] bi myn B.</NOTE></L>
<L>By a wilde wildernesse &middot; and bi a wode-syde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wode-syde</I>] wodes side WCB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">Blisse of &thorn;o briddes &middot; [abyde me made,]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Blisse</I>] &thorn;e blisse B. <I>&thorn;o</I>] &thorn;e WCOB. [<I>abyde me made</I> R] brou&yogh;te me aslepe LWCOB. <I>But see the three next lines; and cf</I>. Text A.</NOTE></L>
<L>And vnder a lynde vppon a launde &middot; lened I a stounde,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="106"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> (1)] RB <I>om. vppon</I>] vnder B. <I>I</I>] y me B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To lythe &thorn;e layes &middot; &thorn;e louely foules made.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lythe</I>] hiren B. <I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] &thorn;at &thorn;o B; &thorn;at &thorn;e R. <I>louely</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Murthe of her mouthes &middot; made me &thorn;ere to slepe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>slepe</I>] sleple W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e merueillousest meteles &middot; mette me &thorn;anne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] R <I>om. merueillousest</I>] Merueylokest R; merueilous B. <I>mette me</I>] Mette I me O; me mette B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at euer dremed wy&yogh;te &middot; in worlde, as I wene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">L <I>repeats</I> dremed, <I>but the line is marked</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; A moche man, as me &thorn;ou&yogh;te &middot; and lyke to my-selue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moche</I>] mykil C. <I>me</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Come and called me &middot; by my kynde name.</L>
<L N="72">"What artow," quod I &thorn;o &middot; "&thorn;at &thorn;ow my name knowest?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;at &thorn;ow wost wel," quod he &middot; "and no wy&yogh;te bettere."</L>
<L>&para; "Wote I what &thorn;ow art?" &middot; "&thorn;ought," seyde he &thorn;anne,</L>
<L>"I haue suwed &thorn;e &thorn;is seuene &yogh;ere &middot; sey &thorn;ow me no rather?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sey</I>] seye W; sey&yogh; O; sawe C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">&para; "Art &thorn;ow thought?" quod I &thorn;o &middot; "&thorn;ow couthest me wisse<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>couthest&mdash;wisse</I>] kannes me wisse C; knowest, y-wysse B; coud|est me wisse where R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="129, B-text"></L>
<L>Where &thorn;at dowel dwelleth &middot; and do me &thorn;at to knowe?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I> (2)] hym R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Dowel and dobet &middot; and dobest &thorn;e thridde," quod he,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Aren three faire vertues &middot; and beth nau&yogh;te fer to fynde.</L>
<L>Who-so is trewe of his tonge &middot; and of his two handes,</L>
<L N="81">And &thorn;orugh his laboure or &thorn;orugh his londe &middot; his lyflode wynneth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>] and B. <I>&thorn;orugh</I> (2)] COB <I>om. londe</I>] londes COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And is trusti of his tailende &middot; taketh but his owne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>om. his tailende</I>] taylyng O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And is nou&yogh;t dronkenlew ne dedeignous &middot; dowel hym folweth.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="107"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] is (<I>printed</I> his) W. <I>dronk|enlew</I>] dronkelew R; dronkelewe (<I>printed</I> dronklewe) WB; dronklewe C; drunklew O. <I>dedeignous</I>] deygn|ous CB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="84">Dobet doth ry&yogh;t &thorn;us &middot; ac he doth moche more;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>doth</I> (1)] does C; do B. <I>he</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>He is as low as a lombe &middot; and loueliche of speche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as</I> (1)] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And helpeth alle men &middot; after &thorn;at hem nedeth;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bagges and &thorn;e bigurdeles &middot; he hath to-broken hem alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to-broken</I>] to-brook C; broken B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at &thorn;e Erl auarous &middot; helde, and his heires;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;us with Mammonaes [moneie] &middot; he hath made hym frendes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;us</I>] R <I>om. Mammonaes</I>] Mamondes C. [<I>moneie</I> WCOB] mone LR. <I>hath</I>] had B. <I>made</I>] ymade R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And is ronne in-to Religioun &middot; and hath rendred &thorn;e bible,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in-to</I>] to WCOB. <I>bible</I>] bille (!) R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And precheth to &thorn;e poeple &middot; seynt Poules wordes,<Q><I>Libenter suffertis insipientes, cum sitis ipsi sapientes,</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>precheth</I>] preched CR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="92">'And suffreth &thorn;e vnwise &middot; with &yogh;ow for to libbe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In one line</I>&mdash;And to &thorn;e vn|wise ye do goode &middot; for so god yow beddis C; B <I>the same, but with</I> hoti&thorn; <I>for</I> beddis.</NOTE></L>
<L>And with gladde wille doth hem gode &middot; for so god &yogh;ow hoteth.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In one line</I>&mdash;And to &thorn;e vn|wise ye do goode &middot; for so god yow beddis C; B <I>the same, but with</I> hoti&thorn; <I>for</I> beddis.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000412.tif" N="130, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; Dobest is aboue bothe &middot; and bereth a bisschopes crosse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bothe</I>] hem bo&thorn;e O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is hoked on &thorn;at one ende &middot; to halie men fro helle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Is</I>] And is B. <I>hoked</I>] an hoke R.</NOTE></L>
<L>A pyke is on &thorn;at potente &middot; to pulte adown &thorn;e wikked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A</I>] And a B. <I>is</I>] R <I>om. on&mdash;potente</I>] on &thorn;e potente CO; in &thorn;e poynt B. <I>pulte</I>] pelte R; pilte O; putte WCB. <I>wikked</I>] helle B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="97">&THORN;at wayten any wikkednesse &middot; dowel to tene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wikkednesse</I>] wickednesse to do B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dowel and dobet &middot; amonges hem ordeigned<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> (2)] ha&thorn; B. <I>ordeigned</I>] ordeyneden O; ordeyne&thorn; B; han or|deyned W.</NOTE></L>
<L>To croune one to be kynge &middot; to reule hem bothe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>one</I>] and R. R <I>omits from</I> to reule (<I>l</I>. 99) <I>to</I> kynge <I>in l</I>. 104.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at &yogh;if dowel or dobet &middot; did a&yogh;ein dobest,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>did</I>] do&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;anne shal &thorn;e kynge come &middot; and casten hem in yrens,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="108"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>casten</I>] putte B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And but if dobest bede for hem &middot; &thorn;ei to be &thorn;ere for euere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bede</I>] did C; dyde B; bidde O. <I>hem</I>] hym CB. <I>&thorn;ei&mdash;&thorn;ere</I>] &thorn;ei be &thorn;er O; &thorn;er to be B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thus dowel and dobet &middot; and dobest &thorn;e thridde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dobest</I>] best C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="104">Crouned one to be kynge &middot; to kepen hem alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>] be (<I>printed</I> the) W; &thorn;e B. <I>kepen</I>] <I>so in</I> WCOR; <I>spelt</I> kepin L; B <I>has</I> helpe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to reule &thorn;e Reume &middot; bi her thre wittes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;i O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And none other-wise &middot; but as &thorn;ei thre assented."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>none</I>] in non B. <I>assented</I>] assentes C; assente&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I thonked thou&yogh;t &thorn;o &middot; &thorn;at he me &thorn;us tau&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;us</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">"Ac &yogh;ete sauoureth me nou&yogh;t &thorn;i seggyng &middot; I coueite to lerne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac &yogh;ete</I>] Ac R; And yet C; And ari&yogh;t B. <I>seggyng</I>] seying W; sayeng C; segge B. <I>lerne</I>] lere B.</NOTE></L>
<L>How dowel, dobet, and dobest &middot; don amonges &thorn;e peple."</L>
<L>&para; "But witte conne wisse &thorn;e," quod &thorn;ou&yogh;t &middot; "where &thorn;o thre dwelle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>quod</I>] C <I>om. &thorn;o</I>] &thorn;ei B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ellis wote I none &thorn;at can &middot; &thorn;at now is alyue."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>can</I>] can &thorn;e telle B. <I>is alyue</I>] lyue&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="112">&para; &THORN;ou&yogh;te and I thus &middot; thre days we &yogh;eden,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>we</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Disputyng vppon dowel &middot; day after other,
<PB REF="00000413.tif" N="131, B-text"></L>
<L>And ar we were ywar &middot; with witte gan we mete.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>we</I> (1)] y B. <I>were ywar</I>] were war WB; war were R. <I>we</I> (2)] I O.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was longe and lene &middot; liche to none other,</L>
<L>Was no pruyde on his apparaille &middot; ne pouerte noyther,</L>
<L N="117">Sadde of his semblaunt &middot; and of soft chiere.</L>
<L>I dorste meue no matere &middot; to make hym to iangle,</L>
<L>But as I bad &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;o &middot; be mene bitwene,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="109"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>] to be B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And put forth somme purpos &middot; to prouen his wittes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>somme</I>] his R.</NOTE></L>
<L>What was dowel fro dobet &middot; and dobest fram hem bothe.</L>
<L N="122">&para; &THORN;anne &thorn;ou&yogh;t in &thorn;at tyme &middot; seide &thorn;ise wordes,</L>
<L>"Where dowel, dobet &middot; and dobest ben in londe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Where</I>] Whether R. <I>dobet</I>] and dobet B. <I>ben</I>] was CB; R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here is wille wolde ywyte &middot; yif witte couthe teche hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] R <I>om. ywyte</I>] wite WCOB; Iwitt R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">And whether he be man or [no] man &middot; &thorn;is man fayne wolde aspye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>no man</I>] <I>so in</I> RCB; L <I>omits</I> no, <I>but the line is marked;</I> WO <I>have</I> womman, <I>which is probably corrupt. fayne</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And worchen as &thorn;ei thre wolde &middot; &thorn;is is his entente."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>] thus W.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000414.tif" N="132, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS IX. (DO-WEL I.)</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. Passus nonus LO; Passus Nonus de visione, vt supra CR; <I>to which</I> W <I>adds</I> et primus de Do-bet (<I>an obvious mistake</I>); B <I>adds</I>, et se|cundus de Dowel. <I>But</I> Crowley <I>has the correct title</I>.</NOTE><I>Passus nonus</I> [<I>de visione; et primus de dowel</I>.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sire dowel dwelleth," quod witte &middot; "nou&yogh;t a day hennes,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="110"></L>
<L>In a castel &thorn;at kynde made &middot; of foure kynnes &thorn;inges;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kynnes</I>] maner R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of erthe and eyre is it made &middot; medled togideres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eyre</I>] of Eyr WB; heyer R. <I>is it</I>] is it (<I>printed</I> it is) W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">With wynde and with water &middot; witterly enioyned.</L>
<L>Kynde hath closed &thorn;ere-Inne &middot; craftily with-alle,</L>
<L>A lemman &thorn;at he loueth &middot; like to hym-selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>like</I>] y-liche R.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Anima</I> she hatte &middot; ac enuye hir hateth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hatte</I>] hatteth R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">A proude pryker of Fraunce &middot; <I>prynceps huius mundi</I>,</L>
<L>And wolde winne hir awey &middot; with wyles, and he my&yogh;te.<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; Ac kynde knoweth &thorn;is wel &middot; and kepeth hir &thorn;e bettere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And CR.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hath do hir with sire dowel &middot; is duke of &thorn;is marches.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And&mdash;do</I>] And hath I-do R; As does C; And doo&thorn; W; As do&thorn; B. <I>sire</I>] R <I>om. &thorn;is</I>] &thorn;e R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">Dobet is hir damoisele &middot; sire doweles dou&yogh;ter,</L>
<L>To serue &thorn;is lady lelly &middot; bothe late and rathe.</L>
<L>Dobest is aboue bothe &middot; a bisschopes pere;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="111"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboue</I>] aboute R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he bit, mote be do &middot; he reuleth hem alle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I>] don B; doon O. <I>reuleth</I>] reule C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="16"><I>Anima</I> &thorn;at lady &middot; is ladde bi his lerynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lerynge</I>] lernyng R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="133, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;e constable of &thorn;at castel &middot; &thorn;at kepeth al &thorn;e wacche,</L>
<L>Is a wys kni&yogh;te with-al &middot; sire Inwitte he hatte,</L>
<L>And hath fyue feyre sones &middot; bi his first wyf;</L>
<L N="20">Sire sewel and saywel &middot; and herewel &thorn;e hende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>herewel</I>] sire here-wel R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sire worche-wel-wyth-&thorn;ine-hande &middot; a wi&yogh;te man of strengthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sire</I>] And CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sire godfrey gowel &middot; gret lordes for sothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gret lordes</I>] a grete lord R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ise fyue ben sette &middot; to saue &thorn;is lady <I>anima</I>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>saue</I>] kepe W. <I>lady</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">Tyl kynde come or sende &middot; to saue hir for euere."</L>
<L>&para; "What kynnes thyng is kynde," quod I &middot; "canstow me telle?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kynnes</I>] kynne R; COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Kynde," quod witte, "is a creatour &middot; of alle kynnes &thorn;inges;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>creatour</I>] creature COB. <I>alle kynnes</I>] alkynge C; alkynne R; alkyns O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fader and fourmour &middot; of al &thorn;at euere was maked;</L>
<L N="28">And &thorn;at is &thorn;e gret god &middot; gynnynge had neuere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at&mdash;gret</I>] &thorn;e get (<I>sic</I>) R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lorde of lyf and of ly&yogh;te &middot; of lysse and of peyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lysse</I>] blisse RB.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Transposed in</I> B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Angeles and al &thorn;ing &middot; aren at his wille.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Transposed in</I> B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac man is hym moste lyke &middot; of marke and of schafte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym moste</I>] most hym R. <I>schafte</I>] schape C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;orugh &thorn;e worde &thorn;at he spake &middot; wexen forth bestes,<Q><I>Dixit, &amp; facta sunt;</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wexen</I>] <I>so in</I> LRO; woxen WCB. <I>Dixit</I>] Et dixit B. <I>sunt</I>] sunt, &amp;c. CB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="33">&para; And made man likkest &middot; to hym-self one,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="112"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>likkest</I>] I-likest R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Eue of his ribbe-bon &middot; with-outen eny mene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mene</I>] mede B.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he was synguler hym-self &middot; and seyde <I>faciamus</I>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>As who seith, 'more mote here-to &middot; &thorn;an my worde one;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mote here-to</I>] mut &thorn;erto O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="37">My my&yogh;te mote helpe &middot; now with my speche.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>now</I>] for&thorn; W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;te as a lorde sholde make lettres &middot; and hym lakked parchemyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] C <I>om</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="134, B-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;ough he couth write neuere so wel &middot; &yogh;if he had no penne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>] a CB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">&THORN;e lettre[s] for al &thorn;e lordship &middot; I leue were neuere ymaked.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lettres</I> O] lettre LWCRB; Crowley <I>has</I> letters; <I>see l</I>. 38.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And so it semeth bi hym &middot; as &thorn;e bible telleth,&THORN;ere he seyde, <Q><I>dixit, &amp; facta sunt;</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>semeth</I>] semed R. <I>bible</I>] book COB. <I>he seyde</I>] it sayes C; hit sei&thorn; B; he sey&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>He moste worche with his worde &middot; and his witte shewe.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is manere was man made &middot; &thorn;orugh my&yogh;te of god almi&yogh;ti,</L>
<L N="44">With his worde and werkemanschip &middot; and with lyf to laste.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us god gaf hym a goost &middot; of &thorn;e godhed of heuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] &thorn;oru&yogh; W. <I>godhed</I>] godded R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of his grete grace &middot; graunted hym blisse,<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at is lyf &thorn;at ay shal last &middot; to al [his] lynage after.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>his</I> WR] LCOB <I>om. lynage</I>] lynages CO.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;at is &thorn;e castel &thorn;at kynde made &middot; <I>caro</I> it hatte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;is R. <I>castel</I>] catel (!) RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And is as moche to mene &middot; as man with a soule;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] &thorn;at is O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;t with werke &middot; and with worde bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>worde</I>] his wordes R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orugh my&yogh;te of &thorn;e maieste &middot; man was ymaked.</L>
<L N="52">&para; Inwit and alle wittes &middot; closed ben &thorn;er-inne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inwit</I>] In-wyttis B. <I>closed</I>] I-clothed R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;e lady <I>anima</I> &middot; &thorn;at lyf is ynempned;</L>
<L>Ouer al in mannes body &middot; he walketh and wandreth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>omit</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac in &thorn;e herte is hir home &middot; and hir moste reste.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And WC. <I>hir</I> (1)] his C; B <I>om. hir</I> (2)] his CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac Inwitte is in &thorn;e hed &middot; and to the herte he loketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inwitte</I>] wytt B. <I>he</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="57">What <I>anima</I> is lief or loth &middot; he lat hir at his wille;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>] &amp; O. <I>his</I>] hire R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For after &thorn;e grace of god &middot; &thorn;e grettest is Inwitte.</L>
<L>&para; Moche wo worth &thorn;at man &middot; &thorn;at mys-reuleth his In|witte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>] wi&yogh;t R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at be glotouns globbares &middot; her god is her wombe;
<PB REF="00000417.tif" N="135, B-text"><Q><I>Quorum deus venter est</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>globbares</I>] glubberes WO; glob|bers C; clobberis B. <I>venter</I>] venter eorum B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="61">For &thorn;ei seruen sathan &middot; her soule shal he haue;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>soule</I>] <I>so in</I> R; soules WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at liueth synful lyf here &middot; her soule is liche &thorn;e deuel.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>soule</I>] soules C. <I>deuel</I>] deuelis O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at lyuen good lyf &middot; aren like god almi&yogh;ti,<Q><I>Qui manet in caritate, in deo manet, &amp;c</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>like</I>] lik to WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Allas! &thorn;at drynke shal for-do &middot; &thorn;at god dere bou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bou&yogh;te</I>] abou&yogh;te COB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">And doth god forsaken hem &middot; &thorn;at he shope to his lik|nesse;<Q><I>Amen dico vobis, nescio vos: &amp; alibi: et dimisi eos secundum desideria eorum</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he shope</I>] schope hem R. <I>&amp; alibi&mdash;eorum</I>] R <I>om. eorum</I>] &amp;c. CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Foles &thorn;at fauten Inwitte &middot; I fynde &thorn;at holicherche<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="113"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fauten</I>] faylen B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shulde fynden hem &thorn;at hem [fauteth] &middot; and faderelees children;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I> (2)] R <I>om</I>. [<I>fauteth</I> RCOB] fauted LW; <I>marked in</I> L.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">And wydwes &thorn;at han nou&yogh;te wher-with &middot; to wynnen hem her fode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>omit</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Madde men, and maydenes &middot; &thorn;at helplees were;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ise lakken Inwitte &middot; and lore bihoueth.</L>
<L>&para; Of &thorn;is matere I my&yogh;te &middot; make a longe tale,</L>
<L>And fynde fele witnesses &middot; amonges &thorn;e foure doctours,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>witnesses</I>] witnesse CR.</NOTE></L>
<L N="73">And &thorn;at I lye nou&yogh;t of &thorn;at I lere &thorn;e &middot; luke bereth wit|nesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of&mdash;&thorn;e</I>] I lerethe (<I>sic</I>) R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Godfader and godmoder &middot; &thorn;at sen her godchildren<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Godfader</I>] Godfadir OB; God|fadres W. <I>godmoder</I>] godmodir OB; godmodres W.</NOTE></L>
<L>At myseise and at mischief &middot; and mowe hem amende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>At</I>] &thorn;at is R. <I>at</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">Shal haue penaunce in purgatorie &middot; but &yogh;if &thorn;ei hem helpe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;if</I>] if COB; W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For more bilongeth to &thorn;e litel barne &middot; ar he &thorn;e lawe knowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an nempnyng of a name &middot; and he neuere &thorn;e wiser!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] CB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shulde no crystene creature &middot; crien atte &yogh;ate,
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="136, B-text"></L>
<L N="80">Ne faille payn ne potage &middot; and prelates did as &thorn;ei shulden.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ne</I>] And R.</NOTE></L>
<L>A Iuwe wolde nou&yogh;te se a Iuwe &middot; go iangelyng for de|faute,</L>
