<L>And if &thorn;ei leden &thorn;us her lyf &middot; it [like&thorn;] god almi&yogh;ti;<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] But CB. <I>leden</I>] ledden R. [<I>like&thorn;</I> WOB] likes C; liked LR.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he made wedloke firste &middot; and him-self it seide;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="121"><Q><I>Bonum est vt unusquisque vxorem suam habeat, propter fornicacionem</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>propter, &amp;c</I>.] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="192">&para; And &thorn;ei &thorn;at o&thorn;ergatis ben geten &middot; for gedelynges ben holden,</L>
<L>As false folke fondelynges &middot; faitoures and lyars;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As</I>] And RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vngracious to gete goode &middot; or loue of &thorn;e poeple,</L>
<L>Wandren and wasten &middot; what &thorn;ei cacche mowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei</I>] &thorn;e C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="142, B-text"></L>
<L N="196">A&yogh;eines dowel &thorn;ei don yuel &middot; and &thorn;e deuel serue,</L>
<L>And after her deth-day &middot; shulle dwelle with &thorn;e same,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shulle dwelle</I>] soule dwelles C; &thorn;e soule shal dwelle B. <I>same</I>] deuel R.</NOTE></L>
<L>But god gyue hem grace here &middot; hem-self to amende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] hym C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Dowel, my frende, is &middot; to don as lawe techeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] CB <I>om. as</I>] as &thorn;e COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To loue &thorn;i frende and &thorn;i foo &middot; leue me, &thorn;at is dobet.</L>
<L N="201">To &yogh;iuen and to &yogh;emen &middot; bothe &yogh;onge and olde,</L>
<L>To helen and to helpen &middot; is dobest of alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">199&mdash;202. R <I>omits</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And dowel is to drede god &middot; and dobet to suffre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dowel is</I>] &thorn;us is dowel R. <I>to</I>] (2)] is to COB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="204">And so cometh dobest of bothe &middot; and bryngeth adoun &thorn;e mody,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is wikked wille &middot; &thorn;at many werke shendeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werke</I>] a werk W; werkes R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dryueth away dowel &middot; &thorn;orugh dedliche synnes."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dryueth</I>] dryue C. <I>&thorn;orugh</I>] with CB. <I>synnes</I>] syne COB.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000425.tif" N="143, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS X. (DO-WEL II.)</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. &amp;&mdash;<I>dowel</I>] vt supra CR; &amp; tercius de dowel B; et ijus de Dowel W; &amp; ijus dowel L. O <I>has merely</I> Passus decimus.</NOTE><I>Passus decimus de visione, &amp; secundus</I> [<I>de</I>] <I>dowel</I>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THanne hadde witte a wyf &middot; was hote dame studye,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="122"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hote</I>] called R. <I>was</I>] &thorn;at was B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at lene was of lere &middot; and of liche bothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lere</I>] lire CB. <I>liche</I>] lichee R.</NOTE></L>
<L>She was wonderly wroth &middot; &thorn;at witte me &thorn;us tau&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wroth</I>] wrou&yogh;t B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">And al starynge dame studye &middot; sternelich seyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seyde</I>] loked W.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Wel artow wyse," quod she to witte &middot; "any wysdomes to telle</L>
<L>To flatereres or to folis &middot; &thorn;at frantyk ben of wittes!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>frantyk</I>] frenetike WO; frentik CRB. <I>wittes</I>] wytte B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And blamed hym and banned hym &middot; and badde hym be stylle,</L>
<L N="8">With suche wise wordes &middot; to wissen any sottes;</L>
<L>And seyde, "<I>noli mittere</I>, man &middot; margerye perlis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>] CB <I>om. margerye</I>] magerie RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amanges hogges, &thorn;at han &middot; hawes at wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei don but dryuele &thorn;er-on &middot; draffe were hem leuere</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;an al &thorn;e precious perre &middot; &thorn;at in paradys wexeth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] C <I>om. perre</I>] perree W; pere B. <I>wexeth</I>] vexes (<I>sic</I>) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>I sey it bi suche," quod she &middot; "&thorn;at sheweth bi her werkes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hem were leuer londe &middot; and lordship on erthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on erthe</I>] here R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or ricchesse or rentis &middot; and reste at her wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I>] Other R; Of B. <I>or</I>] other R; and of B.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="144, B-text"></L>
<L N="16">&THORN;an alle &thorn;e sothe sawes &middot; &thorn;at salamon seyde euere.</L>
<L>&para; Wisdome and witte now &middot; is nou&yogh;t worth a carse,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="123"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>carse</I>] <I>so in</I> R; kerse WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>But if it be carded with coueytise &middot; as clotheres kemben here wolle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it be</I>] he B. <I>kemben</I>] kemen B. <I>here</I>] CROB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Who-so can contreue deceytes &middot; an conspire wronges,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>can contreue</I>] kan troue C. <I>de|ceytes</I>] desaytise C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">And lede forth a loue-day &middot; to latte with treuthe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to&mdash;with</I>] and letten &thorn;e R.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;at suche craftes can &middot; to conseille is clepid;<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ei lede lordes with lesynges &middot; and bilyeth treuthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lordes</I>] lordynges C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Iob &thorn;e gentel &middot; in his gestes witnesseth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gestes</I>] gestes &middot; gretely COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wikked men, &thorn;ei welden &middot; &thorn;e welthe of &thorn;is worlde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei</I>] COB <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">And &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben lordes of eche a londe &middot; &thorn;at oute of lawe libbeth;<Q><I>Quare impij viuunt? bene est omnibus, qui preuaricantur &amp; inique agunt?</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of&mdash;a</I>] of ech COB; in vch a R. <I>lawe</I>] C <I>om</I>. (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e sauter seyth &thorn;e same &middot; bi suche &thorn;at don ille,<Q><I>Ecce ipsi peccatores habundantes; in seculo optinuerunt diuicias</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>habundantes</I>] &amp; habundantes O. <I>diuicias</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>'Lo!' seith holy letterrure &middot; 'whiche lordes beth &thorn;is shrewes!'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holy</I>] &thorn;e holy O. <I>letterrure</I>] lecture B. <I>lordes</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ilke &thorn;at god moste gyueth &middot; leste good &thorn;ei deleth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moste gyueth</I>] most greueth CR; gyue&thorn; moost W; moost good gyue&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And moste vnkynde to &thorn;e comune &middot; &thorn;at moste catel weldeth;<Q><I>Que perfecisti, destruxerunt; iustus autem</I> [<I>quid fecit?</I>]</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>quid fecit</I>] <I>supplied from</I> The Vulgate; <I>not in the</I> MSS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Harlotes for her harlotrye &middot; may haue of her godis,</L>
<L>And iaperes and iogeloures &middot; and iangelers of gestes.</L>
<L N="32">&para; Ac he &thorn;at hath holy writte &middot; ay in his mouth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin of</I> O <I>is</I> Nota: how good carpyng is not loued.</NOTE></L>
<L>And can telle of Tobye &middot; and of &thorn;e twelue apostles,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] W <I>om</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="145, B-text"></L>
<L>Or prechen of &thorn;e penaunce &middot; &thorn;at pilat wrou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] COB <I>om. pilat</I>] Pilat wikkedly W.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Ihesu &thorn;e gentil &middot; &thorn;at Iewes to-drowe:&mdash;</L>
<L N="36">Litel is he loued &middot; &thorn;at suche a lessoun scheweth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Litel</I>] Ful litel B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or daunted or drawe forth &middot; I do it on god hym-self!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>daunted&mdash;drawe</I>] daunte&thorn; or drawi&thorn; B. <I>god</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; But &thorn;o &thorn;at feynen hem folis &middot; and with faityng libbeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>] &thorn;ei B; &thorn;oo W.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;ein &thorn;e lawe of owre lorde &middot; and lyen on hem-selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lorde</I>] C <I>omits, by mistake</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Spitten and spewen &middot; and speke foule wordes,</L>
<L>Drynken and dryuelen &middot; and do men for to gape,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dryuelen</I>] drauelen O. <I>for</I>] for (<I>printed</I> fer) W. <I>gape</I>] Iape B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lickne men and lye on hem &middot; &thorn;at leneth hem no &yogh;iftes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lickne</I>] Likkene RO; Lykene C. <I>&yogh;iftes</I>] gestes CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei conne namore mynstralcye &middot; ne musyke, men to glade,</L>
<L N="44">Than Munde &thorn;e mylnere &middot; of <I>multa fecit deus!</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mylnere</I>] mulenere R; melner C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne were here vyle harlotrye &middot; haue god my treuthe,</L>
<L>Shulde neuere Kyng ne kni&yogh;t &middot; ne chanoun of seynt Poules<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chanoun</I>] canoun R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yue hem to her &yogh;eres&yogh;iue &middot; &thorn;e &yogh;ifte of a grote!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;eres&yogh;iue</I>] yeresgyfte C. <I>&yogh;ifte</I>] worth R; value O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac murthe and mynstralcye &middot; amonges men is nouthe</L>
<L N="49">Leccherye, losengerye &middot; and loseles tales;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Leccherye</I>] But lecherie B. <I>losengerye</I>] and losengerie RCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Glotonye and grete othes &middot; &thorn;is murthe &thorn;ei louieth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac if &thorn;ei carpen of cryst &middot; &thorn;is clerkis and &thorn;is lewed,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="124"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>carpen</I>] harpen C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">Atte mete in her murthes &middot; whan mynstralles ben stille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her</I>] COB <I>om. murthes</I>] mur&thorn;e W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;anne telleth &thorn;ei of &thorn;e trinite &middot; a tale other tweyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tweyne</I>] tweye W; tweyen O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bringen forth a balled resoun &middot; and taken Bernard to witnesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>forth</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And putten forth a presumpsioun &middot; to preue &thorn;e sothe.
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="146, B-text"></L>
<L N="56">&THORN;us &thorn;ei dryuele at her deyse &middot; &thorn;e deite to knowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deyse</I>] deys WCOB; dayes R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gnawen god with &thorn;e gorge &middot; whan her gutte is fulle.<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gutte&mdash;fulle</I>] guttis is fulle (<I>sic</I>) C; guttis been fulle OB; guttes fullen W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;e careful may crye &middot; and carpen atte &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>Bothe afyngred and a-thurst &middot; and for chele quake;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>afyngred</I>] a-fyngerd C; an|hungred O; a-hungred B. <I>a-thurst</I>] a-furst W; a-&thorn;rist O; a-thrust CB. <I>chele</I>] chelde C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Is none to nymen hym nere &middot; his noye to amende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Is</I>] Is &thorn;er WB. <I>noye</I>] nuye R; anoy W. <I>to</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>But [hoen] on hym as an hounde &middot; and hoten hym go &thorn;ennes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hoen on</I>] <I>so in</I> R; heon on LC; howen on O; howlen on B; hunten W. <I>In</I> L, <I>the line is marked for correction</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Litel loueth he &thorn;at lorde &middot; &thorn;at lent hym al &thorn;at blisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;us parteth with &thorn;e pore &middot; a parcel whan hym nedeth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] hem O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">Ne were mercy in mene men &middot; more &thorn;an in riche,</L>
<L>Mendinant&yogh; meteles &middot; mi&yogh;te go to bedde.</L>
<L>God is moche in &thorn;e gorge &middot; of &thorn;ise grete maystres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gorge</I>] gorges R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac amonges mene men &middot; his mercy and his werkis;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">And so seith &thorn;e sauter &middot; I haue yseye it ofte,<Q><I>Ecce audiuimus eam in effrata, inuenimus eam in campis silue</I>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] Ich R. <I>yseye</I>] sei&yogh;en WB; seyn O; seen C. <I>inuenimus</I>] &amp; inuenimus CB. <I>eam</I> (2)] eum R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Clerkes and other kynnes men &middot; carpen of god faste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kynnes</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">And haue [hym] moche in &thorn;e mouthe &middot; ac mene men in herte.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="125"><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hym</I> WCROB] L <I>om. &thorn;e</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Freres and faitoures &middot; han founde suche questiouns</L>
<L>To plese with proude men &middot; sithen &thorn;e pestilence tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sithen</I>] syn W; si&thorn; O. <I>&thorn;e</I>] C <I>om. tyme</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And prechen at seint poules &middot; for pure enuye of clerkis,</L>
<L N="74">&THORN;at folke is nou&yogh;te fermed in &thorn;e feith &middot; ne fre of her goodes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] been O. <I>feith</I>] fayit C</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="147, B-text"></L>
<L>Ne sori for her synnes &middot; so is pryde waxen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is pryde</I>] pruyde is R. <I>waxen</I>] woxen RWB; vaxen C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">In religioun and in alle &thorn;e rewme &middot; amonges riche &amp; pore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alle</I>] C <I>om. rewme</I>] Reme W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at preyeres haue no power &middot; &thorn;e pestilence to lette.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>&thorn;e <I>pestilence</I>] &thorn;is pestilences R. <I>Here</I> R <I>has two extra lines, belonging to the C-text</I>.</P><P>For god is def now a dayes &middot; and deyneth his heres to opne,</P><P>&thorn;at gerles for here gyltes &middot; he for|grynt hem alle.</P><P><I>For</I> deyneth <I>we should read</I> deyneth not.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;ette &thorn;e wrecches of &thorn;is worlde &middot; is none ywar bi other,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wrecches</I>] wrycches C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne for drede of &thorn;e deth &middot; withdrawe nou&yogh;t her pryde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nou&yogh;t</I>] no&yogh;t of B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne beth plentyuous to &thorn;e pore &middot; as pure charite wolde,</L>
<L N="81">But in gaynesse and in glotonye &middot; for-glotten her goode hem-selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I> (2)] CB <I>om. for-glotten</I>] forglutten WCO; for-gutten B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And breken nou&yogh;te to &thorn;e beggar &middot; as &thorn;e boke techeth,<Q><I>Frange esurienti panem tuum, &amp;c</I>.</Q></L>
<L>And &thorn;e more he wynneth and welt &middot; welthes &amp; ricchesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>welt</I>] weldi&thorn; B. <I>ricchesse</I>] richesses RB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="84">And lordeth in londes &middot; &thorn;e lasse good he deleth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] Euere as he R. <I>And&mdash;londes</I>] And lord of leedis and londis B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thobye telleth &yogh;ow nou&yogh;t so &middot; take hede, &yogh;e riche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hede, &yogh;e</I>] he &thorn;e C (<I>sic</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>How &thorn;e boke bible &middot; of hym bereth witnesse:<Q><I>Si tibi sit copia, habundanter tribue; si autem exiguum, illud impertiri stude libenter:</I>&mdash;</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bible</I>] of &thorn;e bibile C; of &thorn;e bible B. <I>hym</I>] hem CB. <I>sit copia</I>] copia sit COB. <I>illud</I>] COB <I>om. im|pertiri&mdash;libenter</I>] inpertire libenter stude R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Who-so hath moche, spene manliche &middot; so meneth Thobie,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spene</I>] spende WO. <I>manliche</I>] muche C. <I>meneth</I>] sei&thorn; W. B <I>is corrupt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">And who-so litel weldeth &middot; reule him &thorn;er-after;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] B <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For we haue no lettre of owre lyf &middot; how longe it shal dure.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dure</I>] endure B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Suche lessounes lordes shulde &middot; louie to here,
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="148, B-text"></L>
<L>And how he my&yogh;te moste meyne &middot; manliche fynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he my&yogh;te</I>] &thorn;ei my&yogh;ton B. <I>meyne</I>] meynee W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="92">&para; Nou&yogh;t to fare as a fitheler or a frere &middot; for to seke festes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nou&yogh;t</I>] And nou&yogh;t C; And how no&yogh;t B; Ac not O. <I>or</I>] or as R. <I>for</I>] R <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Homelich at other mennes house[s] &middot; and hatyen her owne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>houses</I>] <I>so in</I> WCROB; house L.</NOTE></L>
<L>Elyng is &thorn;e halle &middot; vche daye in &thorn;e wyke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Elyng</I>] Elenge WCOB. <I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;at B. <I>wyke</I>] weke RC.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;e lorde ne &thorn;e lady &middot; liketh nou&yogh;te to sytte.<MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] and COB. <I>to</I>] O <I>om</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="96">Now hath vche riche a reule &middot; to eten bi hym-selue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vche</I>] ech WB; ich O; elk (<I>sic</I>) C. <I>hymselue</I>] hem-selue C.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a pryue pa[r]loure &middot; for pore mennes sake,</L>
<L>Or in a chambre with a chymneye &middot; and leue &thorn;e chief halle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> (1)] B <I>om. with</I>] by R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was made for meles &middot; men to eten Inne;</L>
<L>And al to spare to spille &middot; &thorn;at spende shal an other.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I>] O <I>om. to spille</I>] to spende W; and to spille (<I>badly</I>) CB. <I>spende</I>] spene R; spille W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="101">&para; I haue yherde hiegh men &middot; etyng atte table,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yherde</I>] herd CRB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Carpen as &thorn;ei clerkes were &middot; of cryste and of his mi&yogh;tes,</L>
<L>And leyden fautes vppon &thorn;e fader &middot; &thorn;at fourmed vs alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vppon</I>] on CB.</NOTE></L>
