<L>And who tau&yogh;te hem on trees &middot; to tymbre so heighe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere noither buirn ne beste &middot; may her briddes rechen.<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>noither</I>] nei&thorn;er WB; no&thorn;er R. <I>buirn</I>] burn W; barne C; barn OB. <I>may</I>] ne may R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="354">&para; And sythen I loked vpon &thorn;e see &middot; and so forth vpon &thorn;e sterres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vpon</I> (1)] on COB. <I>see</I>] sehe O. <I>forth vpon</I>] on COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many selcouthes I seygh &middot; ben nought to seye nouthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben</I>] beth R; &thorn;at ben B. <I>seye</I>] segge R; seyn B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I seigh floures in &thorn;e fritthe &middot; and her faire coloures,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] of R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And how amonge &thorn;e grene grasse &middot; grewe so many hewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>grewe</I>] greu&yogh; R; growed W; grewen B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And somme soure and some swete &middot; selcouthe me &thorn;ou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Of her kynde and her coloure &middot; to carpe it were to longe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her</I> (2)] of here R.</NOTE></L>
