<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000474.tif" N="192, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS XII (DO-WEL IV).</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. Passus xij <I>us</I> LW; Passus Duodecimus CO; <I>wrongly called</I> Passus xj <I>us</I> de visione, vt <I>supra</I> R; <I>also</I> B <I>wrongly adds</I> et quintus [<I>read</I> quartus] de dowel.</NOTE><I>Passus duodecimus.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I am ymagynatyf," quod he &middot; "Idel was I neuere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;e I sitte bi my-self &middot; in sikenesse ne in helthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] nor W; and COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>I haue folwed &thorn;e in feithe &middot; &thorn;is fyue and fourty wyntre,</L>
<L N="4">And many tymes haue moeued &thorn;e &middot; to &thorn;inke on &thorn;ine ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moeued</I>] meued WRB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And how fele fern&yogh;eres are faren &middot; and so fewe to come,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fern&yogh;eres</I>] fernyers C; ferneres R. <I>are</I>] be R; an (!) C; arn B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;i wylde wantounesse &middot; &thorn;o &thorn;ow &yogh;onge were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] B <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To amende it in &thorn;i myddel age &middot; lest mi&yogh;te &thorn;e faylled<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>faylled</I>] faile RB; faille C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">In &thorn;yne olde elde &middot; &thorn;at yuel can suffre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>elde</I>] eelde R. <I>yuel</I>] so yuel CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pouerte or penaunce &middot; or preyeres bidde;<Q><I>Si non in prima vigilia, nec in secunda, &amp;c.</I><MILESTONE N="49b" UNIT="folio"></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bidde</I>] to bidde W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amende &thorn;e while &thorn;ow my&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;ow hast ben warned ofte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>while</I>] &thorn;e while R. <I>ben</I>] be CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>With poustees of pestilences &middot; with pouerte and with angres;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] and CB. <I>pestilences</I>] pesti|lence C; penaunce R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">And with &thorn;ise bitter baleyses &middot; god beteth his dere childeren,<Q><I>Quem diligo, castigo.</I></Q>
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="193, B-text"></L>
<L>And dauid in &thorn;e sauter seith &middot; of suche &thorn;at loueth Ihesus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>omits this line, and the quo|tation.</I></NOTE><Q>'<I>Virga tua &amp; baculus tuus, ipsa me consolata sunt, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ipsa</I>] ipse C. <I>consolata</I>] consolata (<I>printed</I> consolati) W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al-&thorn;ough &thorn;ow stryke me with &thorn;i staffe &middot; with stikke or with &yogh;erde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or with</I>] other CO; o&thorn;er wi&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>It is but murth as for me &middot; to amende my soule.'</L>
<L N="16">And &thorn;ow medlest &thorn;e with makynges &middot; and my&yogh;test go sey &thorn;i sauter,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>makynges</I>] makynge R; mais|tries CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bidde for hem &thorn;at &yogh;iueth &thorn;e bred; &middot; for &thorn;ere ar bokes ynowe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;iueth</I>] geues C; &yogh;euen B. <I>&thorn;e</I>] me B. <I>ar</I>] ben O. <I>ynowe</I>] y-knowe W; O <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To telle men what dowel is &middot; dobet, and dobest bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>men</I>] me O. <I>is</I>] CB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And prechoures to preue what it is &middot; of many a peyre freres."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>preue</I>] proue CB. <I>a</I>] C <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&para; I seigh wel he sayde me soth &middot; and, somwhat me to excuse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] ac R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seid[e], "catoun conforted his sone &middot; &thorn;at, clerke &thorn;ough he were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Seide</I>] Seid L; And seide R; Seide W; Saide C. <I>conforted</I>] con|forted me W; to conforte CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To solacen hym sum tyme &middot; as I do whan I make;<Q><I>Interpone tuis interdum gaudia curis, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as</I>] and R. <I>I</I>] ich R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">&para; And of holy men I herde," quod I &middot; "how &thorn;ei other|while<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] R <I>om. herde</I>] here R; hard C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pleyden, &thorn;e parfiter to be &middot; in many places.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>places</I>] a place R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac if &thorn;ere were any wight &middot; &thorn;at wolde me telle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac if</I>] And if C; &yogh;if R. <I>wight</I>] wit R.</NOTE></L>
<L>What were dowel and dobet &middot; and dobest atte laste,</L>
<L>Wolde I neuere do werke &middot; but wende to holicherche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do werke</I>] worche B; wyrke C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ere bydde my bedes &middot; but whan ich eet or slepe."
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="194, B-text"></L>
<L N="30">&para; "Poule in his pistle," quod he &middot; "preueth what is dowel;<Q><I>Fides, spes, caritas; &amp; maior horum, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Poule</I>] With poule R. <I>pistle</I>] pistles R. <I>preueth</I>] proues C. &amp;] R <I>om. horum</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Feith, hope, and charitee &middot; and alle ben good,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> (2)] R <I>om. good</I>] goed R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">And sauen men sundry tymes &middot; ac none so sone as charite.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>] and C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he doth wel with-oute doute &middot; &thorn;at doth as lewte techeth;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is, if &thorn;ow be man maried &middot; &thorn;i make &thorn;ow louye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ow</I>] he CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lyue forth as lawe wole &middot; while &yogh;e lyuen bothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] R <I>om. while</I>] &thorn;e while R. <I>bothe</I>] here COB.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">&para; Ri&yogh;t so if &thorn;ow be Religious &middot; renne &thorn;ow neuere ferther<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ferther</I>] &thorn;e fer&thorn;er B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Rome ne to Rochemadore &middot; but as &thorn;i reule techeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rochemadore</I>] Rochemadour CROB; Rochemador W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And holde &thorn;e vnder obedyence &middot; &thorn;at heigh wey is to heuene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heigh</I>] &thorn;e hi&yogh;e B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And if &thorn;ow be mayden to marye &middot; and mi&yogh;te wel contynue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mayden</I>] mayde &amp; R. <I>con|tynue</I>] contene O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Seke &thorn;ow neuere seynt forther &middot; for no soule helthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>neuere</I>] nere R. <I>no</I>] thy CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>For what made Lucyfer &middot; to lese &thorn;e heigh heuene,</L>
<L>Or salamon his sapience &middot; or sampson his strengthe?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>] other R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Iob &thorn;e Iewe his ioye &middot; dere he it abou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">C <I>omits. dere he it</I>] dere it he O; dere he B; ful deere W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">Arestotle and other mo &middot; ypocras, &amp; virgyle;</L>
<L>Alisaundre &thorn;at al wan &middot; elengelich ended.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Alisaundre</I>] Alexander C. <I>ended</I>] endeden O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Catel and kynde witte &middot; was combraunce to hem alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>combraunce</I>] a combraunce B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Felyce hir fayrnesse &middot; fel hir al to sklaundre;</L>
<L N="48">And Rosamounde ri&yogh;t so &middot; reufully bysette,<MILESTONE N="50" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>reufully</I>] reuful B. <I>bysette</I>] besette R; to bileue W.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000477.tif" N="195, B-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bewte of hir body &middot; in badnesse she dispended.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>badnesse she</I>] badd vse R; wickednesse she B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of many suche I may rede &middot; of men and of wommen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I may</I>] men may I R. <I>may</I>] mi&yogh;te COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wyse wordes wolde shewe &middot; and worche &thorn;e contrarye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolde shewe</I>] can say CB; kun seye O. <I>worche</I>] werchen R. <I>con|trarye</I>] contrarye L (<I>by mistake</I>). CB <I>place</I> bene <I>after</I> virtute.</NOTE></L>
<L N="52"><I>Sunt homines nequam bene de virtute loquentes.</I></L>
<L>&para; And riche renkes ri&yogh;t so &middot; gaderen and sparen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>renkes</I>] men &thorn;enken B. <I>gaderen</I>] &thorn;at gadren B; gadderand C. <I>sparen</I>] sparynge C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;o men &thorn;at &thorn;ei moste haten &middot; mynistren it atte laste;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>] to C. <I>atte</I>] at &thorn;e WCOB. <I>laste</I>] leste C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, for &thorn;ei suffren &amp; se &middot; so many nedy folkes,</L>
<L>And loue hem nou&yogh;t as owre lorde byt &middot; lesen her soules;<Q><I>Date &amp; dabitur vobis, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>owre lorde</I>] god CB. <I>byt</I>] bit WCRO; bytt B; <I>badly spelt</I> bytte <I>in</I> L. <I>lesen</I>] &thorn;ei lesen W; and lesen B. <I>her</I>] &yogh;oure R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="57">[So catel and kende wit &middot; acombreth ful many;</L>
<L>Wo is hym &thorn;at hem weldeth &middot; but if he hem [wel] despende;<Q><I>Scientes et non facientes varijs flagellis vapula|bunt;</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>[<I>wel</I>] <I>so in</I> Cotton MS.; R <I>has</I> wil</P><P><I>Scientes&mdash;vapulabunt</I>] R <I>has</I>&mdash;Scienti et non facienti varijs flagellis vapulabit. <I>I correct it by the</I> Cotton MS.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>Sapience, seith &thorn;e boke &middot; swelleth a mannes soule,<Q><I>Sapiencia inflat, &amp;c.;</I>]</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot">57&mdash;59. <I>In</I> R <I>only; but necessary to the sense; cf.</I> C-Text.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">&para; And ricchesse ri&yogh;t so &middot; but if &thorn;e Rote be trewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ricchesse</I>] riche C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac grace is a grasse &thorn;er-of &middot; &thorn;o greuaunces to abate.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;er-of</I>] &thorn;ere-fore R. <I>&thorn;o gre|uaunces</I>] the greuance COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac grace ne groweth nou&yogh;te &middot; but amonges lowe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] B <I>om. lowe</I>] &thorn;e lowe O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pacience and pouerte &middot; &thorn;e place is &thorn;ere it groweth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pacience</I>] Of pacience R. <I>is</I>] hi&yogh;te W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">And in lele lyuynge men &middot; and in lyf holy,</L>
<L>And &thorn;orugh &thorn;e gyfte of &thorn;e holygoste &middot; as &thorn;e gospel telleth,
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="196, B-text"><Q><I>Spiritus vbi vult spirat, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (1)] R <I>om. gyfte</I>] si&yogh;t B. <I>vult</I>] wlt R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Clergye and kynde witte &middot; comth of si&yogh;te and tech|ynge,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e boke bereth witnesse &middot; to buirnes &thorn;at can rede,<Q><I>Quod scimus, loquimur; quod vidimus, testamur.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As</I>] And CB. <I>buirnes</I>] burnes WO; barnes CRB. <I>can</I>] konne C; kun O; kunnen B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">Of <I>quod scimus</I> cometh clergye &middot; and connynge of heuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] a R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of <I>quod vidimus</I> cometh kynde witte &middot; of si&yogh;te of dyue[r]se peple.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] C <I>om. quod</I>] B <I>om. dyuerse] miswritten</I> dyuese <I>in</I> L; diuerse WCROB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac grace is a gyfte of god &middot; and of gret loue spryngeth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Knewe neuere clerke how it cometh forth &middot; ne kynde witte &thorn;e weyes,<Q><I>Nescit aliquis vnde venit, aut quo vadit, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Knewe</I>] Know C. <I>ne</I>] &thorn;e (!) O. <I>&thorn;e</I>] his R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac &yogh;it is clergye to comende &middot; and kynde witte bothe,</L>
<L N="73">And namely clergye, for crystes loue &middot; &thorn;at of clergye is rote.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] B <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>For Moyses witnesseth &thorn;at god wrote &middot; for to wisse &thorn;e peple,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>witnesseth</I>] witnesse C. <I>wrote</I>] wroot WC. <I>wisse</I>] wise R.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e olde lawe, as &thorn;e lettre telleth &middot; &thorn;at was &thorn;e lawe of iewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at what woman were in auoutrie taken &middot; were she riche or pore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I> WCROB] L <I>has the word in the margin. auoutrie</I>] deuoutrie R. <I>were she</I>] were he R; COB <I>om. or</I>] other COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>With stones men shulde hir stryke &middot; and stone hir to deth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stones</I>] stanes C. <I>stryke</I>] striken R. <I>stone</I>] stonen RB; stonye C. <I>deth</I>] dede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>A womman, as we fynden &middot; was gulty of &thorn;at dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>omits. we fynden</I>] I fynde W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac cryste of his curteisye &middot; &thorn;orw clergye hir saued;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;orw</I>] and &thorn;oru&yogh; R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="197, B-text"></L>
<L N="80">For &thorn;orw carectus &thorn;at cryst wrot &middot; &thorn;e iewes knewe hem|seluen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] And W. <I>carectus&mdash;wrot</I>] cristes carectus R; carrectis &thorn;at crist wrou&yogh;te CO.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gultier as afor god &middot; and gretter in synne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Gultier</I>] Giltier WCO; Gilty B. <I>gretter in</I>] in gretter O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e woman &thorn;at &thorn;ere was &middot; and wenten awey for schame.</L>
<L>&THORN;e clergye &thorn;at &thorn;ere was &middot; conforted &thorn;e womman.</L>
<L N="84">Holykirke knoweth &thorn;is &middot; &thorn;at crystes writyng saued;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kirke</I>] cherche R. <I>knoweth</I>] knew B. <I>saued</I>] saued hire W.</NOTE></L>
<L>So clergye is conforte &middot; to creatures &thorn;at repenten,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;at hem B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to mansed men &middot; myschief at her ende<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mansed</I>] mased C; manasid B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; For goddes body my&yogh;te nou&yogh;te be &middot; of bred, with|outen clergye,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e which body is bothe &middot; bote to &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] is bote to B. <I>bote</I>] boote WC; B <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And deth and dampnacioun &middot; to hem &thorn;at dyeth yuel.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dyeth</I>] dyen CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>As crystes carecte conforted and bothe &middot; coupable shewed<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>carecte</I>] carrectes C; caractes O; carectes B; carette R. <I>con|forted</I>] counforteden O. <I>coupable</I>] coupile C; couple B. <I>shewed</I>] scheweden O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e womman &thorn;at &thorn;e iewes brou&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;at Ihesus &thorn;ou&yogh;te to saue;<Q><I>Nolite iudicare, et non iudicabimini, &amp;c.</I><MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio"></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] R <I>om. brou&yogh;te</I>] bou&yogh;te R. <I>non</I>] non (<I>printed</I> not) W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="92">Ri&yogh;t so goddes body, bretheren &middot; but it be worthily taken,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>body</I>] B <I>om. but</I>] but if W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dampneth vs atte daye of dome &middot; as &thorn;e carectes dede &thorn;e iewes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Dampneth</I>] Dampned R. <I>carectes</I>] caractes W. <I>&thorn;e&mdash;dede</I>] dede &thorn;e carette R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I conseille &thorn;e for cristes sake &middot; clergye &thorn;at &thorn;ow louye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at &thorn;ow</I>] to COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>For kynde witte is of his kyn &middot; and neighe cosynes bothe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>neighe</I>] ny&yogh; B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="96">To owre lorde, leue me; &middot; for-&thorn;i loue hem, I rede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] hym C.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="198, B-text"></L>
<L>For bothe ben as miroures &middot; to amenden owre defautes,</L>
<L>And lederes for lewed men &middot; and for lettred bothe.</L>
<L>&para; For-&thorn;i lakke &thorn;ow neuere logyke &middot; lawe, ne his cus|tumes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lawe</I>] is lawe B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">Ne countreplede clerkes &middot; I conseille &thorn;e for eure.</L>
<L>For as a man may nou&yogh;t se &middot; &thorn;at mysseth his eyghen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eyghen</I>] si&yogh;te R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Namore can no klerke &middot; but if he cau&yogh;t it first &thorn;orugh bokes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>] C <I>om. cau&yogh;t</I>] cacche O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al-&thorn;ough men made bokes &middot; god was &thorn;e maistre,</L>
<L N="104">And seynt spirit &thorn;e saumplarye &middot; and seide what men sholde write.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] his COB. <I>men</I>] man R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t as sy&yogh;te serueth a man &middot; to se &thorn;e heighe strete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">W <I>omits. Found in</I> LCROB C2.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so ledeth letterure &middot; lewed men to resoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ledeth</I>] lereth R. <I>letterure</I>] clergie CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as a blynde man in bataille &middot; bereth wepne to fi&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And as</I>] As as (<I>sic</I>) C. <I>bereth</I>] bere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hath none happ with his axe &middot; his enemye to hitte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I>] C <I>om. enemye</I>] enmy C; enemyes O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="109">Namore kan a kynde witted man &middot; but clerkes hym teche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kynde witted</I>] kende wedded R. <I>but</I>] but if O. <I>clerkes</I>] clergie CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Come for al his kynde witte &middot; to crystendome and be saued;</L>
