<L>Alle &thorn;e clerkes vnder cryst &middot; ne couthe &thorn;e skil assoille;<Q><I>Quare placuit, quia voluit.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] R <I>om. assoille</I>] telle R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="205, B-text"></L>
<L N="217">And so I sey by &thorn;e &middot; &thorn;at sekest after &thorn;e whyes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>whyes</I>] whaies C; wyes B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And aresonedest resoun &middot; a rebukyng as it were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aresonedest</I>] resonedest CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;e floures in &thorn;e fryth &middot; and of her feire hewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>inserts these lower down, after l.</I> 222.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her</I>] C <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Where-of &thorn;ei cacche her coloures &middot; so clere and so bri&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>inserts these lower down, after l.</I> 222.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cacche</I>] caughte C; lau&yogh;te B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="221">And willest of briddes and of bestes &middot; and of hire bredyng to knowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I> (2)] WRO; CB <I>om.; very faint in</I> L. <I>to</I>] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Why somme be alowe and somme alofte &middot; &thorn;i lykyng it were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>] so CB. <I>alowe</I>] alou&yogh; W; lowe CB; low R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;e stones and of &thorn;e sterres &middot; &thorn;ow studyest, as I leue,<MILESTONE N="52" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (1)] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="224">How euere beste or brydde &middot; hath so breme wittes:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>euere</I>] euery B. <I>or</I>] ou&thorn;er W; other R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Clergye ne kynde witte &middot; ne knewe neuere &thorn;e cause,</L>
<L>Ac kynde knoweth &thorn;e cause hym-selue &middot; [and] no creature elles.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>hym-selue</I>] CB <I>om.</I> [<I>and</I> WCOB] LR <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>He is &thorn;e pyes patroun &middot; and putteth it in hire ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] his C. <I>pyes patroun</I>] pye patroen R. <I>putteth</I>] put R. <I>it</I>] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ere &thorn;e &thorn;orne is thikkest &middot; to buylden and brede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] W <I>om. &thorn;ere</I>] CB <I>om. to</I>] &thorn;ere to R. <I>buylden</I>] byggen C; bilden in B. <I>and</I>] and to C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="229">And kynde kenned &thorn;e pecok &middot; to cauken in swich a kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kenned</I>] kenneth COB. <I>pecok</I>] pakok C; pocok O. <I>cauken</I>] kauken COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And kenned Adam &middot; to knowe his pryue membres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kenned</I>] kende kenned R. <I>knowe</I>] knowen R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tau&yogh;te hym and Eue &middot; to hylien hem with leues.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hylien</I>] helien WCRB; hilen O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Lewed men many tymes &middot; maistres &thorn;ei apposen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ei</I>] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="233">Why Adam ne hiled nou&yogh;t firste &middot; his mouth &thorn;at eet &thorn;e apple,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I>] COB <I>om. hiled</I>] huled R; hilled C; heliede B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rather &thorn;an his lykam a-low &middot; lewed axen &thorn;us clerkes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lykam</I>] likame W; likham CR. <I>a-low</I>] alogh W. <I>lewed</I>] &thorn;e lewid B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kynde knoweth whi he dede so &middot; ac no clerke elles.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>] and COB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="206, B-text"></L>
<L N="236">Ac of briddes and of bestes &middot; men by olde tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ensamples token and termes &middot; as telleth &thorn;is poetes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>token</I>] toke R. <I>&thorn;is</I>] <I>so also in</I> R; thise CB; &thorn;e WO.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e fairest foule &middot; foulest engendreth,</L>
<L>And feblest foule of flyght is &middot; &thorn;at fleegheth or swym|meth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fleegheth</I>] flee&thorn; W; fleth R; flieth CB; flye&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">And &thorn;at is &thorn;e pekok &amp; &thorn;e pohenne &middot; proude riche men &thorn;ei bitokneth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] W <I>om. pekok</I>] pokok O; pacok C. <I>pohenne</I>] <I>so in</I> COB; Pehen W; pohen R. <I>proude</I>] CB <I>om. &thorn;ei</I>] W <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e pekok, and men pursue hym &middot; may nou&yogh;te fleighe heighe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pecok</I>] pocok O; pacok C. <I>pursue</I>] pursuen R. <I>may</I>] ne may R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e traillyng of his taille &middot; ouertaken is he sone,</L>
<L>And his flesshe is foule flesshe &middot; and his feet bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I> (2)] is C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="244">And vnlouelich of ledene &middot; and laith for to here.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] on O. <I>ledene</I>] cryeng C. <I>laith</I>] loo&thorn; W; laithe R; loth C; lay&thorn; O; lo&thorn;ly B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ri&yogh;t so &thorn;e riche &middot; if he his ricchesse kepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I>] is C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And deleth it nou&yogh;t tyl his deth day &middot; &thorn;e taille of al sorwe.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e pennes of &thorn;e pecok &middot; [peyneth] hym in his fli&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>as</I>] so as W. <I>as</I>] so CB. <I>pecok</I>] pocok O; pacok C. [<I>peyneth</I> WOB] payned LR; peyned C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="248">So is possessioun payne &middot; of pens and of nobles<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] or CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To alle hem &thorn;at it holdeth &middot; til her taille be plukked.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough &thorn;e riche repente &thorn;anne &middot; and birewe &thorn;e tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>repente</I>] repente hym O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at euere he gadered so grete &middot; and gaf &thorn;ere-of so litel,</L>
<L>&THORN;ough he crye to cryst &thorn;anne &middot; with kene wille, I leue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kene</I>] clen CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>His ledne be in owre lordes ere &middot; lyke a pyes [chiteryng].<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>] is COB. <I>lyke</I>] yliche O; lyl (<I>sic</I>) R. [<I>chiteryng</I> W] LCROB <I>om.; but the line is marked in</I> L.</NOTE></L>
<L>And whan his caroigne shal come &middot; in caue to be buryed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I>] is C. <I>caue</I>] graue C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">I leue it flaumbe ful foule &middot; &thorn;e folde al aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>flaumbe</I>] flawme WRO; flambe CB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="207, B-text"></L>
<L N="256">And alle &thorn;e o&thorn;er &thorn;er it lyth &middot; [enuenyme&thorn;] &thorn;orgh his attere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] CB <I>om. o&thorn;er</I>] er&thorn;e O; schere B. [<I>enuenyme&thorn;</I> WCOB] en|uenymed LR. <I>attere</I>] attre W; atter RCO; attir B.</NOTE></L>
<L>By &thorn;e [po feet] is vnderstonde &middot; as I haue lerned in auynete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>po feet</I> WR] poo feet CO; pownes feet B; profeet (!) L. <I>vnder|stonde</I>] vnderstande W; vnderstonded R. <I>haue</I>] COB <I>om. auynete</I>] auy|nettes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Excecutoures, fals frendes &middot; &thorn;at fulfille nou&yogh;t his wille<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at fulfille&mdash;witnesse</I>] C <I>om. witnesse</I>] witnesses R. <I>ri&yogh;t</I>] COB <I>om. it</I>] he R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was writen, and &thorn;ei witnesse &middot; to worche ri&yogh;t as it wolde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at fulfille&mdash;witnesse</I>] C <I>om. witnesse</I>] witnesses R. <I>ri&yogh;t</I>] COB <I>om. it</I>] he R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">&THORN;us &thorn;e poete preues &thorn;at &thorn;e pecok &middot; for his fetheres is reuerenced,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] O <I>om. pecok</I>] pocok O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so is &thorn;e riche &middot; bi resoun of his godis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>riche</I>] riche man B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e larke, &thorn;at is a lasse foule &middot; is more louelich of ledne,</L>
<L>And wel awey of wenge &middot; swifter &thorn;an &thorn;e pecok,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wenge</I>] wynge WCO; whenge B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="264">And of flesch, by fele folde &middot; fatter and swetter.</L>
<L>To lowe lybbyng men &middot; &thorn;e larke is resembled;</L>
<L>Arestotle &thorn;e grete clerke &middot; suche tales he telleth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Arestotle</I>] For aristotel R; Aristole C. <I>he</I>] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Thus he lykneth in his logyk &middot; &thorn;e leste foule oute.<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>logyk</I>] glosinge R. <I>leste</I>] leeste W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="268">And where he be sauf or nou&yogh;t sauf &middot; &thorn;e sothe wote no clergye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>where</I>] whei&thorn;er W. <I>sauf</I> (1)] saue C. <I>sauf</I> (2)] COB <I>om. no</I>] &thorn;e (!) O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne of sortes ne of salamon &middot; no scripture can telle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I> (2)] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ac god is so good, I hope &middot; &thorn;at sitth he gaf hem wittis</L>
<L>To wissen vs weyes &thorn;ere-with &middot; (&thorn;at wissen vs to be saued,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>weyes</I>] wayes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e better for her bokes) &middot; to bidden we ben holden,</L>
<L N="273">&THORN;at god for his grace &middot; gyue her soules reste;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>soules</I>] soule R.</NOTE></L>
<L>For lettred men were lewed men &yogh;ut &middot; ne were lore of her bokes."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>men</I> (2)] CB <I>om. &yogh;ut</I>] yet WO; yit CB. <I>ne were</I>] nere CB; ner O. <I>lore</I>] loore W. <I>her</I>] &thorn;e R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="208, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; "Alle &thorn;ise clerkes," quod I &thorn;o &middot; "&thorn;at on cryst leuen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>quod</I>] quo B. <I>on</I>] in W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seggen in her sarmones &middot; &thorn;at noyther sarasenes ne iewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Seggen</I>] Seyen W; Sayand C. <I>noyther sarasenes</I>] no sarazyns C; no Sarsyn B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="277">Ne no creature of cristes lyknesse &middot; with-outen crysten|dome worth saued."</L>
<L>&para; "<I>Contra</I>," quod ymagynatyf &thorn;o &middot; and comsed for to loure, And seyde,<Q> <I>"saluabitur vix iustus in die iudicij.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>comsed</I>] bygane C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; <I>Ergo saluabitur</I>," quod he &middot; and seyde namore latyne.</L>
<L N="280">"Troianus was a trewe kny&yogh;te &middot; and toke neuere cristen|dome,</L>
<L>And he is sauf, so seith &thorn;e boke &middot; and his soule in heuene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] R <I>om. sauf</I>] saaf W; O <I>om. so</I>] as COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ere is fullyng of fonte &middot; and fullyng in blode shedynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] Ac R. <I>fonte</I>] founte C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;orugh fuire is fullyng &middot; and &thorn;at is ferme bileue;<Q><I>Aduenit ignis diuinus, non comburens, sed illuminans, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fuire</I>] fuir R; fir WO; fier B; fire C. <I>sed</I>] set C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="284">&para; Ac trewth &thorn;at trespassed neuere &middot; ne transuersed a&yogh;eines his lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>transuersed</I>] <I>so also in</I> R; trauersed WCOB. <I>a&yogh;eines</I>] a&yogh;en R.</NOTE></L>
<L>But lyueth as his lawe techeth &middot; and leueth &thorn;ere be no bettere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyueth</I>] lyued R. <I>techeth</I>] tau&yogh;te R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And if &thorn;ere were, he wolde amende &middot; and in suche wille deyeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>] B <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ne wolde neuere trewe god &middot; but treuth were allowed;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>treuth</I>] trewe treuthe R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="288">And where it worth or worth nou&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;e bileue is grete of treuth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>where</I>] whei&thorn;er W; were RCOB. <I>it</I>] it be W. <I>worth nou&yogh;t</I>] worth nau&yogh;te R; no&yogh;t wor&thorn; W; nou&yogh;t C; no&yogh;t B; not O.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="209, B-text"></L>
<L N="289">And an hope hangyng &thorn;er-inne &middot; to haue a Mede for his treuthe. For,<Q> <I>Deus dicitur quasi dans vitam eternam suis, hoc est, fidelibus; et alibi: si ambulauero in medio vmbre mortis</I>, [<I>&amp;c.</I>]</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] CB <I>om. for</I>] B <I>om. For</I>] Quia COB. [<I>&amp;c</I> CROB] LW <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e glose graunteth vpon &thorn;at ver &middot; a gret mede to treuthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>treuthe</I>] trewe R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And witt and wisdome," quod &thorn;at wye &middot; "was somme tyme tresore,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wye</I>] weye R.</NOTE></L>
<L>To kepe with a comune &middot; no katel was holde bettere,</L>
<L N="293">And moche murth and manhod:"&mdash;and ri&yogh;t with &thorn;at he vanesched.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>manhod</I>] manhede R; manhed C. <I>with</I>] myd R.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

