<L N="404">And more mete ete and dronke &middot; &thorn;en kende mi&yogh;t defie&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kende</I>] <I>such is the usual spell|ing in</I> R, <I>wherever</I> L <I>has</I> kynde.</NOTE></L>
<L>"And kau&yogh;te seknesse sum-tyme &middot; for my sorfetes ofte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sorfetes</I>] <I>miswritten</I> forfetes; <I>but sense and alliteration decide it.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;anne I dradde to deye &middot; in dedlich synne"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at in-to wanhope he [worthe] &middot; and wende nau&yogh;t to be saued,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>worthe</I>] <I>miswritten</I> wrathe <I>in</I> R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="408">&THORN;e whiche is sleuthe so slow &middot; &thorn;at may no slithes helpe it,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>slithes</I>] <I>a better spelling is</I> slei&yogh;tes ( = sleights); <I>cf.</I> l. 365.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000514.tif" N="232, B-text"></L>
<L>Ne no mercy amenden &middot; &thorn;e man &thorn;at so deyeth.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">400&mdash;409. <I>In</I> R <I>only, and the text is corrupt. The reason for inserting it is given in the</I> Critical Note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="410">&para; Which ben &thorn;e braunches &middot; &thorn;at bryngeth a man to sleuth?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Which</I>] Ac whiche R. <I>bryng|eth</I>] bryngen WOB; brynges C.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Is whanne a man] morneth nou&yogh;te for his mysdedes &middot; ne maketh no sorwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Is whanne a man</I> O] Is whan man B; He &thorn;at W; LRC <I>have the extraordinary false reading</I> His wo|man; <I>but, fortunately, the</I> C-Text <I>helps us out.</I> (Is = it is, <I>as else|where.</I>) <I>mysdedes</I>] dedis O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac penaunce &thorn;at &thorn;e prest enioigneth &middot; perfourneth yuel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And WRC. <I>enioigneth</I>] enioyned B. <I>perfourneth yuel</I>] per|forme hij nylle&thorn; B; parfourned C.</NOTE></L>
<L N="413">Doth none almes-dede &middot; dret hym of no synne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Doth</I>] Doos C. <I>almes-dede</I>] almesse W. <I>dret</I>] drat R; dred W; drede CB; dredi&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lyueth a&yogh;ein &thorn;e bileue &middot; and no lawe holdeth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holdeth</I>] haldes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vch day is haliday with hym &middot; or an heigh ferye;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vch&mdash;is</I>] Ilce day or Ilc C; Eche day or eche B. <I>is</I>] is an O. <I>with hym</I>] O <I>om. or</I>] &amp; O; as B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="416">And if he au&yogh;te wole here &middot; it is an harlotes tonge.</L>
<L>Whan men carpeth of cryst &middot; or of clennesse of soule,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Whan</I>] And whanne O. <I>carp|eth</I>] carpen WCOB. <I>of</I> (2)] COB <I>om. soule</I>] saule C; soules W.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wexeth wroth &amp; wil nou&yogh;te here &middot; but wordes of myrthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wexeth</I>] waxes C; waxi&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Penaunce and pore men &middot; and &thorn;e passioun of seyntes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> (1)] of W. <I>&thorn;e</I>] O <I>om. passioun</I>] possessioun C.</NOTE></L>
