<L>And called me &thorn;e fote of his faith &middot; his folke forto saue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e fote</I>] &thorn;e for&thorn; O; stot CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And defende hem fro &thorn;e fende &middot; folke &thorn;at on me leueden.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] hym C. <I>leueden</I>] bileueden B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;us haue I ben his heraude &middot; here and in helle,</L>
<L N="248">And conforted many a careful &middot; &thorn;at after his comynge wayten.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] COB <I>om. wayten</I>] wait|eden W.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000583.tif" N="301, B-text"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us I seke hym," he seide &middot; "for I [herde] seyne late<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>herde</I> WCROB] L <I>omits, but the line is marked.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Of a barne &thorn;at baptised hym &middot; Iohan Baptiste was his name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to patriarkes and to prophetes &middot; and to other peple in derknesse<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I> (2)] CB <I>om. to</I> (3)] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="252">Seyde &thorn;at he seigh here &middot; &thorn;at sholde saue vs alle;<Q><I>Ecce agnus dei, &amp;c.</I>"</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seigh</I>] seyde R. <I>here</I>] hir C; hym O. <I>sholde</I>] shul C. <I>vs</I>] hem R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; I hadde wonder of his wordes &middot; and of his wyde clothes;</L>
<L>For in his bosome he bar a thyng &middot; &thorn;at he blissed euere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] And R. <I>&thorn;at</I>] and &thorn;at R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And I loked on his lappe &middot; a lazar lay <I>&thorn;ere</I>-Inne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] in W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amonges patriarkes and profetes &middot; pleyande togyderes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">CB <I>om. pleyandc</I>] pleyinge WYO; pleyede R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="257">"What awaytestow?" quod he &middot; "and what woldestow haue?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>awaytestow</I>] art &thorn;ou B.</NOTE></L>
<L>"I wolde wyte," quod I &thorn;o &middot; "what is in &yogh;owre lappe?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] is &thorn;is O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Loo!" quod he, and lete me se &middot; "lorde, mercy!" I seide,</L>
<L N="260">"&THORN;is is [a] present of moche prys &middot; what Prynce shal it haue?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>a</I> WCROB] L <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>"It is a preciouse present," quod he &middot; "ac &thorn;e pouke it hath attached,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>] and C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And me &thorn;ere-myde," quod &thorn;at man &middot; "may no wedde vs quite,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ere-myde</I>] &thorn;ere-with RC. <I>man</I>] weye R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne no buyrn be owre borwgh &middot; ne bryng vs fram his daungere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>buyrn</I>] barne CO.</NOTE></L>
<L N="264">Oute of &thorn;e poukes pondfolde &middot; no meynprise may vs fecche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>omits. pondfolde</I>] ponfold CY; pynfold OB. <I>no</I>] ne no CB. <I>may</I>] O <I>om.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000584.tif" N="302, B-text"></L>
<L N="265">Tyl he come &thorn;at I carpe of &middot; cryst is his name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shal delyure vs some daye &middot; out of &thorn;e deueles powere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>some daye</I>] O <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And bettere wedde for vs legge &middot; &thorn;an we ben alle worthy,</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;at is, lyf for lyf &middot; or ligge &thorn;us euere</L>
<L>Lollynge in my lappe &middot; tyl such a lorde vs fecche."</L>
<L>&para; "Allas!" I seyde, "&thorn;at synne &middot; so longe shal lette</L>
<L>&THORN;e my&yogh;te of goddes mercy &middot; &thorn;at my&yogh;t vs alle amende!"</L>
<L N="272">I wepte for his wordes &middot; with &thorn;at sawe I an other</L>
<L>Rapelich renne forth; &middot; &thorn;e ri&yogh;te waye he went.<NOTE PLACE="foot">270&mdash;273. R <I>has</I>&mdash;Allas, thou&yogh;te I &thorn;o &middot; &thorn;at is a longe a-bydynge, And sued hym &middot; for he softe &yogh;ede, &THORN;at he toek vs as tit &middot; ac, trewly to telle.</NOTE></L>
<L>I affrayned hym fyrste &middot; fram whennes he come,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>affrayned</I>] fraynede O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">And what he hi&yogh;te &amp; whider he wolde &middot; and wightlich he tolde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] R <I>om. wightlich</I>] whith-liche R.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000585.tif" N="303, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS XVII. (DO-BET II.)</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. Passus xvijus OCYB; Passus xvjus de visione vt supra R; W <I>adds</I> &mdash;et ijus de Do-bet; B <I>adds</I> &mdash; et tercius de dobet.</NOTE><I>Passus xvij</I><SUP>us</SUP>, <I>et secundus de do-bet.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"<B>I</B> am <I>spes</I>," quod he, "a spye &middot; and spire after a kny&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>quod</I>&mdash;<I>spye</I>] a spie, quod he R. <I>and spire</I>] spere R.</NOTE></L>
<L>That toke me a maundement &middot; vpon &thorn;e mounte of synay,</L>
<L>To reule alle rewmes with; &middot; I bere &thorn;e writte here."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>] &thorn;ere-with R. <I>&thorn;e writte</I>] it writen O; it write Y.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">"Is it asseled?" I seyde &middot; "may men se &thorn;i lettres?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>asseled</I>] enseled W. <I>&thorn;i</I>] the COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Nay," he sayde, "I seke hym &middot; &thorn;at hath &thorn;e sele to kepe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] W <I>om. &thorn;e sele</I>] &thorn;eal (!) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;at is, crosse and crystenedome &middot; And cryst &thorn;ere-on to hange.<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And whan it is asseled so &middot; I wote wel &thorn;e sothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>asseled</I>] enseled W. <I>I</I>&mdash;<I>sothe</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at Lucyferes lordeship &middot; laste shal no lenger."<NOTE PLACE="foot">R <I>has</I>&mdash;Sathanas power schal last no lenger, And &thorn;us my lettre meneth. <I>See</I> Critical Note.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Late se &thorn;i lettres," quod I &middot; "we mi&yogh;te &thorn;e lawe knowe."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;i lettres</I>] &thorn;at lettre R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne plokked he forth a patent &middot; a pece of an harde roche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;anne</I>&mdash;<I>he</I>] A plucked R. <I>patent</I>] pauntelet B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher-on [were] writen two wordes &middot; on &thorn;is wyse y|glosed, <Q><I>Dilige deum &amp; proximum tuum, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>were</I> WCBY] weren O; was LR.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000586.tif" N="304, B-text"></L>
<L N="12">&THORN;is was &thorn;e tixte trewly &middot; I toke ful gode &yogh;eme;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;eme</I>] gome R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e glose was gloriousely writen &middot; with a gilte penne, <Q><I>In hijs duobus mandatis tota lex pendet &amp; pro|phetia.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>writen</I>] I-write R. <I>mandatis</I>] R <I>om. tota&mdash;pendet</I>] pendet tota lex R. <I>prophetia</I>] prophete CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "[Ben] here alle &thorn;i lordes lawes?" quod I &middot; "&yogh;e, leue me wel," he seyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Ben</I> WCBY] Been O; Is LR. <I>leue</I>] lef R. <I>wel</I>] wille C; R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="15">"And who so worcheth after &thorn;is writte &middot; I wil vnder|taken,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] COB <I>om. &thorn;is writte</I>] my wit R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal neuere deuel hym dere &middot; ne deth in soule greue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deth</I>] dette COB; deet Y.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ough I seye it my-self &middot; I haue saued with &thorn;is charme</L>
<L>Of men &amp; of wommen &middot; many score &thorn;ousandes."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I> (2)] CB <I>om. &thorn;ousandes</I>] &thorn;ousand W.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "He seith soth," seyde &thorn;is heraud &middot; "I haue yfounde it ofte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He seith</I>] Ye seien W. <I>seyde &thorn;is</I>] sayed &thorn;e C; seide &thorn;e B; sei&thorn; &thorn;e O. <I>yfounde</I>] founded CBY; founden O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">Lo here in my lappe &middot; &thorn;at leued on &thorn;at charme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] of R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Iosue and Iudith &middot; and Iudas Macabeus,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e, and sexty &thorn;ousande bisyde forth &middot; &thorn;at ben nou&yogh;t seyen here."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;owre wordes aren wonderful," quod I tho &middot; "which of &yogh;ow is trewest,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aren</I>] be C; ben B; been O. <I>tho</I>] CB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="24">And lelest to leue on &middot; for lyf and for soule?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] so W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Abraham seith &thorn;at he seigh &middot; holy &thorn;e Trinite,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holy</I>] hoolly W.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thre persones in parcelles &middot; departable fro other,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>departable</I>] despartable B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;re but o god &middot; &thorn;us Abraham me tau&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="28">And hath saued &thorn;at bileued so &middot; and sory for her synnes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &thorn;at I CB. <I>bileued</I>] bi|leueth R. <I>synnes</I>] synne COB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000587.tif" N="305, B-text"></L>
<L>He can nou&yogh;te segge &thorn;e somme &middot; and some aren in his lappe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He</I>] I O. <I>and some</I>] of &thorn;o &thorn;at B. <I>his</I>] my O.</NOTE></L>
<L>What neded it &thorn;anne &middot; a newe lawe to bigynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>neded it</I>] nedi&thorn; &thorn;ee O; nedes it C; nedi&thorn; it B. <I>bigynne</I>] bringe R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sith &thorn;e fyrst sufficeth &middot; to sauacioun &amp; to blisse?</L>
<L N="32">&para; And now cometh <I>spes</I>, and speketh &middot; &thorn;at hath aspied &thorn;e lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cometh</I>] bigynne&thorn; OY; bi|cometh CB. <I>hath</I>] W <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And telleth nou&yogh;te of &thorn;e Trinitee &middot; &thorn;at toke hym his lettres,</L>
<L>'To byleue and louye &middot; in o lorde almy&yogh;ty,</L>
<L>And sitthe ri&yogh;t as my-self &middot; so louye alle peple.'</L>
<L N="36">&para; &THORN;e gome &thorn;at goth with o staf &middot; he semeth in gretter hele<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gome</I>] mane C. <I>goth</I>] gaes C. <I>o</I>] a COB. <I>in</I>] in a B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an he &thorn;at goth with two staues &middot; to sy&yogh;te of vs alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>goth</I>] gos C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ri&yogh;te so, by &thorn;e Rode! &middot; resoun me sheweth,</L>
<L>It is ly&yogh;ter to lewed men &middot; a lessoun to knowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>It</I>] That it W. <I>a</I>] o W. <I>knowe</I>] lere B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">&THORN;an for to techen hem two &middot; and to harde to lerne &thorn;e leest!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lerne</I>] lere C; here B. <I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;e (<I>printed</I> to the) W.</NOTE></L>
<L>It is ful harde for any man &middot; on abraham byleue,</L>
<L>And welawey worse &yogh;it &middot; for to loue a shrewe!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>welawey</I>] waylawey C; wel awey W; weiloway B.</NOTE></L>
<L>It is li&yogh;ter to leue &middot; in &thorn;re louely persones<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>li&yogh;ter</I>] <I>written</I> li&yogh;tor; <I>cf.</I> l. 39.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">&THORN;an for to louye and leue &middot; as wel lorelles as lele.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leue</I>] leue <I>or</I> lene (<I>uncertain in the</I> MSS.) <I>lele</I>] lelles O; leles CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Go &thorn;i gate," quod I to <I>spes</I> &middot; "so me god helpe!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I>] <I>erased in</I> B. <I>to</I>] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at lerneth &thorn;i lawe &middot; wil litel while vsen it!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">36&mdash;46. R <I>omits.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wil</I>] wol W; wel B; O <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And as we wenten &thorn;us in &thorn;e weye &middot; wordyng togyderes,<MILESTONE N="73" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wenten</I>] wente vs B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">&THORN;anne seye we a samaritan &middot; sittende on a mule,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sittende</I>] <I>so in</I> R; sittynge WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rydynge ful rapely &middot; &thorn;e ri&yogh;t weye we &yogh;eden,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rydynge</I>] Ryden R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000588.tif" N="306, B-text"></L>
<L>Comynge fro a cuntre &middot; &thorn;at men called Ierico;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Comynge</I>] Com CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>To a iustes in iherusalem &middot; he chaced awey faste.</L>
<L N="52">Bothe &thorn;e heraud and hope &middot; and he mette at ones<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] CB <I>om. and</I> (2)] B <I>om. he</I>] <I>glossed by</I> .i. xpc. (<I>meaning</I> id est Christus) <I>in</I> LWR.</NOTE></L>
<L>Where a man was wounded &middot; and with &thorn;eues taken.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wounded</I>] I-wounded R.</NOTE></L>
<L>He my&yogh;te neither steppe ne stonde &middot; ne stere fote ne handes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He</I>] A R. <I>stere</I>] stire C; sterie B. <I>handes</I>] hand B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Ne helpe hym-self sothely &middot; for semiuyf he semed,</L>
<L>And as naked as a nedle &middot; and none helpe aboute hym.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Feith had first si&yogh;te of hym &middot; ac he flegh on syde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] on R. <I>ac</I>] and C. <I>flegh</I>] fled C. <I>on</I>] a W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And nolde nou&yogh;t neighen hym &middot; by nyne londes lengthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nolde</I>] walde C. <I>by</I>] B <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Hope cam hippyng after &middot; &thorn;at hadde so ybosted,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] &amp; O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">How he with Moyses maundement &middot; hadde many men y-holpe;</L>
<L>Ac whan he hadde si&yogh;te of &thorn;at segge &middot; a-syde he gan hym drawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>segge</I>] grome C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dredfully, by &thorn;is day! as duk &middot; doth fram &thorn;e faucoun.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Dredfully</I>] Dredful B. <I>duk</I>] doke WCRO; a doke B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac so sone so &thorn;e samaritan &middot; hadde si&yogh;te of &thorn;is lede,</L>
<L>He li&yogh;te adown of lyard &middot; and ladde hym in his hande,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] B <I>om. ladde</I>] CB <I>om. hande</I>] handes R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">And to &thorn;e wye he went &middot; his woundes to biholde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to &thorn;e</I>] with &thorn;at R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And parceyued bi his pous &middot; he was in peril to deye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi</I>] in R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And but if he hadde recourere &thorn;e rather &middot; &thorn;at rise shulde he neure;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>if</I>] &yogh;if R; WB <I>om. recourere</I>] recouerer WOY; recouered B; socur C. <I>rather</I>] rapelier W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="68">[And breyde to his boteles &middot; and bothe he atamede;]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In</I> R <I>only; but see</I> C-text.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth wyn &amp; with oyle &middot; his woundes he wasshed,</L>
<L>Enbawmed hym and bonde his hed &middot; &amp; in his lappe hym layde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I> (2)] he CB.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000589.tif" N="307, B-text"></L>
<L>And ladde hym so forth on lyard &middot; to <I>lex christi</I>, a graunge,</L>
<L N="72">Wel six myle or seuene &middot; biside &thorn;e newe market;</L>
<L>Herberwed hym at an hostrye &middot; and to &thorn;e hostellere called,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hostrye</I>] ostrie COB. <I>to</I>] R <I>om. hostellere</I>] ostiler CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sayde, "haue, kepe &thorn;is man &middot; til I come fro &thorn;e iustes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>haue</I>] <I>there is a point after this word in</I> C <I>and</I> O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lo here syluer," he seyde &middot; "for salue to his woundes."</L>
<L N="76">And he toke hym two pans &middot; to lyflode as it were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pans</I>] pens WCO.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide, "what he speneth more &middot; I make &thorn;e good here-after;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>speneth</I>] spende&thorn; WB; spendes C.</NOTE></L>
<L>For I may nou&yogh;t lette," quod &thorn;at leode &middot; &amp; lyarde he bistrydeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lette</I>] O <I>om.</I> (!) <I>bistrydeth</I>] bistroode C; bistrode OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And raped hym to-iherusalem-ward &middot; &thorn;e ri&yogh;te waye to ryde.</L>
<L N="80">&para; Faith folweth after faste &middot; and fonded to mete hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>folweth</I>] folwede WCOB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And <I>spes</I> spaklich hym spedde &middot; spede if he my&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spaklich</I>] sparkliche R; scharpli B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To ouertake hym and talke to hym &middot; ar &thorn;ei to toun come.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I> (2)] til COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And whan I sey&yogh; &thorn;is, I soiourned nou&yogh;te &middot; but shope me to renne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] C <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="84">And suwed &thorn;at samaritan &middot; &thorn;at was so ful of pite,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I> (1)] &thorn;e R. <I>pite</I>] piete C.</NOTE></L>
<L>And graunted hym to ben his grome &middot; "gramercy," he seyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>grome</I>] gome R. <I>gramercy</I>] graunt mercy WCRO.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ac &thorn;i frende and &thorn;i felawe," quod he &middot; "&thorn;ow fyndest me at nede."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>quod he</I>] he saide CB; O <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&para; And I thanked hym &thorn;o &middot; and sith I hym tolde,
<PB REF="00000590.tif" N="308, B-text"></L>
<L>How &thorn;at feith fleigh awey &middot; and <I>spes</I> his felaw bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fleigh</I>] fleed C; fle&yogh; R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="89">For si&yogh;te of &thorn;e sorweful man &middot; &thorn;at robbed was with &thorn;eues.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;at W.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Haue hem excused," quod he &middot; "her help may litel auaille;<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
