<L>&THORN;at sholde brynge in better wode &middot; or blowe it til it brende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it</I> (1)] B <I>om. brende</I>] brenne BC2Y.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ise thre &thorn;at I telle of &middot; ben &thorn;us to vnderstonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ben &thorn;us</I>] &thorn;us ben R. <I>to</I>] CR <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="328">The wyf is owre wikked flesshe &middot; &thorn;at wil nou&yogh;t be chasted,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I>] &thorn;re B. <I>&thorn;at</I>] R <I>om. chasted</I>] chastised WB; schastisid C2.</NOTE></L>
<L>For kynde cleueth on hym euere &middot; to contrarie &thorn;e soule.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cleueth</I>] clyue&thorn; W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;owgh it falle, it fynt skiles &middot; [&thorn;at] frelete it made,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>&thorn;at</I> WCRC2BY] &thorn;e L. <I>it</I>] is CC2Y.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at is li&yogh;tly for&yogh;euen &middot; and for&yogh;eten bothe,</L>
<L N="332">To man &thorn;at mercy asketh &middot; and amende &thorn;enketh.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>amende</I>] to amende hym B; to amende C2.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; The reyne &thorn;at reyneth &middot; &thorn;ere we reste sholde,</L>
<L>Ben sikenesses &amp; sorwes &middot; &thorn;at we suffren oft,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sikenesses</I>] siknesse WCC2Y. <I>&amp;</I>] and other R. <I>oft</I>] ou&yogh;te R.</NOTE></L>
<L>As Powle &thorn;e Apostle &middot; to &thorn;e peple tau&yogh;te,<Q><I>Virtus in infirmitate perficitur, &amp;c.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] <I>retained in</I> MS. W. <I>per|ficitur</I>] C <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;owgh &thorn;at men make &middot; moche deol in her angre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deol</I>] doel WC2RY; dole C; dol B. <I>her</I>] C <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="337">And [ben] inpacient in here penaunce &middot; pure resoun knoweth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>ben</I> W] be R; LCC2YB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei han cause to contrarie &middot; by kynde of her syke|nesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cause</I>] resoun R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And li&yogh;tlich owre lorde &middot; at her lyues ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>li&yogh;tlich</I>] ful li&yogh;tli B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="340">Hath mercy on suche men &middot; &thorn;at so yuel may suffre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">96&mdash;340. <I>Here</I> MS. O <I>has lost three leaves; this portion is collated with</I> MSS. C2 <I>and</I> Y.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so</I>] CB <I>om. Here collation with</I> O <I>recommences, and with</I> C2 <I>and</I> Y <I>ceases.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;e smoke and &thorn;e smolder &middot; &thorn;at smyt in owre eyghen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And C. <I>smyt</I>] smitte R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is coueityse and vnkyndenesse &middot; &thorn;at quencheth goddes mercy.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I> (1)] COB <I>om. is</I>] R <I>om. &thorn;at</I> (2)] R <I>om.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000603.tif" N="321, B-text"></L>
<L>For vnkyndenesse is &thorn;e contrarie &middot; of alkynnes resoun;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere nys syke ne sori &middot; ne non so moche wrecche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moche</I>] yuele a O. <I>wrecche</I>] werche (!) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne may louye, &amp; hym lyke &middot; and lene of his herte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lene</I>] lene <I>or</I> leue <I>in the</I> MSS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Goed wille &amp; good worde &middot; bothe wisshen and willen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp;</I>] R <I>om. bothe</I>] and W. <I>willen</I>] wilnen R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="347">Alle manere men &middot; mercy &amp; for&yogh;ifnesse,</L>
<L>And louye hem liche hym-self &middot; and his lyf amende.&mdash;</L>
<L>I may no lenger lette," quod he &middot; and lyarde he pryked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyarde&mdash;pryked</I>] harde priked CB; harde prikede for&thorn; O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And went away as wynde &middot; and &thorn;ere-with I awaked.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>away</I>] O <I>om. awaked</I>] wakede R; awaki&thorn; B.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000604.tif" N="322, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS XVIII (DO-BET III).</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. Passus decimus octauus CO; <I>to which</I> W <I>adds</I>&mdash;&amp;c. et iijus de dobet, <I>and</I> B (<I>wrongly</I>) <I>adds</I>&mdash;et quartus de dobet; R has&mdash;Passus xvijus de visione, vt supra.</NOTE><I>Passus xviij</I><SUP>us</SUP>, <I>et tercius de dobet.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wolleward and wete-shoed &middot; went I forth after,<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As a reccheles renke &middot; &thorn;at of no wo reccheth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As a</I>] And as a CB; And as O. <I>renke</I>] freek B. <I>wo</I>] C <I>om. reccheth</I>] roughte WB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;ede forth lyke a lorel &middot; al my lyf tyme,</L>
<L>Tyl I wex wery of &thorn;e worlde &middot; and wylned eft to slepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wylned</I>] wilnes C. <I>eft to</I>] efte R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">And lened me to a lenten &middot; and longe tyme I slepte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>slepte</I>] slepe B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of crystes passioun and penaunce &middot; &thorn;e peple &thorn;at of-rau&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;er B. <I>&thorn;at of-rau&yogh;te</I>] &thorn;at of taughte C; ofte tau&yogh;te O; &thorn;er-of tau&yogh;te B. <I>This line is perhaps mis|placed, and should follow l.</I> 8.</NOTE></L>
<L>[Reste] me &thorn;ere, and rutte faste &middot; tyl <I>ramis palmarum;</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Reste</I>] <I>so in</I> WCOY; I reste B; Rested LR; (<I>but</I> reste <I>is the A.S. form</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">Of gerlis &amp; of <I>gloria laus</I> &middot; gretly me dremed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp;</I>] O <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And how <I>osanna</I> by orgonye &middot; olde folke songen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>osanna</I>] Osanna (<I>printed</I> ho|sanna) W. <I>orgonye</I>] Organye WC; orgene R; organ B. <I>folke</I>] folkes CB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; One semblable to &thorn;e samaritan &middot; &amp; some del to Piers &thorn;e plowman,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] CB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Barfote on an asse bakke &middot; botelees cam pryk[y]e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] and oon C; &amp; on OB. <I>cam</I>] <I>so in</I> WR; gan COBY. <I>prykye</I>] prikye WO; prekie B; pryke LC; prikynge R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">Wyth-oute spores other spere &middot; spakliche he loked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>other</I>] or O. <I>spakliche</I>] sprac|liche R; sharpliche B.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000605.tif" N="323, B-text"></L>
<L>As is &thorn;e kynde of a kny&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;at cometh to be dubbed,<NOTE PLACE="foot">B <I>omits. be</I>] C <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To geten hem gylte spores &middot; or galoches ycouped.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>geten</I>] geute B. <I>or</I>] and COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne was faith in a fenestre &middot; and cryde "<I>a! fili dauid!</I>"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cryde</I>] crie C. <I>a</I> (2)] B <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="16">As doth an Heraude of armes &middot; whan [auntrous] cometh to iustes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>auntrous</I> RO] aunterous C; Auentrous W; aduenturus B; aun|turos L.</NOTE></L>
<L>Olde iuwes of ierusalem &middot; for ioye &thorn;ei songen,<Q><I>Benedictus qui venit in nomine domini.</I></Q></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne I frayned at faith &middot; what al &thorn;at fare be-ment[e],<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;anne</I>] That C. <I>be-mente</I>] <I>so in</I> RO; bymente WCB; bement L.</NOTE></L>
<L>And who sholde iouste in Iherusalem &middot; "Ihesus," he seyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sholde</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="20">"And fecche &thorn;at &thorn;e fende claymeth &middot; Piers fruit &thorn;e plowman."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fecche</I>] feccheth R; fecche out B.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Is Piers in &thorn;is place?" quod I &middot; &amp; he preynte on me,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>] &thorn;at B. <I>I</I>] C <I>om. preynte</I>] twynclid B; prent R.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;is ihesus of his gentrice &middot; wole iuste in piers armes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>] &thorn;us B. <I>gentrice</I>] gentries WC; gentrie RB.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his helme &amp; in his haberioun &middot; <I>humana natura.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in his</I>] hise C; his B; O <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at cryst be nou&yogh;t biknowe here &middot; for consu[m]matus <I>deus</I>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>biknowe</I>] yknowe C; yknowen O; knowe B. <I>consummatus</I>] <I>so in</I> WROBY; consumatus LC. <I>Cf.</I> l. 57. <I>deus</I>] est COB. B <I>places</I> l. 24 <I>after</I> l. 25.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Piers paltok &thorn;e plowman &middot; &thorn;is priker shal ryde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>priker</I>] prikiere W.</NOTE></L>
<L>For no dynte shal hym dere &middot; as <I>in deitate patris.</I>"</L>
<L>"Who shal iuste with ihesus?" quod I &middot; "iuwes or scribes?"</L>
<L N="28">&para; "Nay," quod he, "&thorn;e foule fende &middot; and fals dome &amp; deth.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] faith R. <I>&thorn;e</I>] but &thorn;e R. <I>foule</I>] R <I>om. &amp; deth</I>] to deye R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Deth seith he shal fordo &middot; and adown brynge</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at lyueth or loketh &middot; in londe or in watere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I> (1)] and WR. <I>or</I> (2)] and W.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000606.tif" N="324, B-text"></L>
<L>Lyf seyth &thorn;at he likth &middot; and leyth his lif to wedde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] C <I>om. likth</I>] <I>so in</I> R; L <I>really has</I> likthe (<I>but the</I> e <I>is not wanted</I>); lie&thorn; WCO; li&yogh;e&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at for al &thorn;at deth can do &middot; with-in &thorn;re dayes,</L>
<L>To walke and fecche fro &thorn;e fende &middot; piers fruite &thorn;e plowman,</L>
<L>And legge it &thorn;ere hym lyketh &middot; and lucifer bynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>legge</I>] lede B.</NOTE></L>
<L>And forbete and adown brynge &middot; bale [&amp;] deth for euere:<Q><I>O mors, ero mors tua!</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>forbete</I>] forbite R; for to bete COB. <I>adown</I>] doun R. [<I>&amp;</I> OY] of B; LWCR <I>om.; but it seems neces|sary. ero&mdash;tua</I>] mors tua ero R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">&para; &THORN;anne cam <I>pilatus</I> with moche peple &middot; <I>sedens pro tribunali</I>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moche</I>] COB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To se how doughtilich deth sholde do &middot; &amp; deme her botheres ri&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her botheres</I>] here beither R; hir brotheres (!) CB. <I>ri&yogh;te</I>] my&yogh;t O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e iuwes and &thorn;e iustice &middot; a&yogh;eine ihesu &thorn;ei were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] B <I>om. iustice</I>] Iustices COB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al her courte on hym cryde &middot; <I>crucifige</I> sharpe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her</I>] here R; &thorn;e WCOB. <I>hym</I>] ihesu R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Tho put hym forth a piloure &middot; bifor pilat, &amp; seyde,<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Tho</I>] to B.</NOTE></L>
<L>"This ihesus of owre iewes temple &middot; iaped &amp; dispised,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>This</I>] &thorn;us B. <I>iewes</I>] R <I>om. temple</I>] peple CB. <I>iaped</I>] ha&thorn; Iaped W. <I>Here</I> B <I>adds the probably spurious line</I>&mdash;and seide he wolde felle a-doun &thorn;e temple &middot; &thorn;at is so strong.</NOTE></L>
<L>To fordone it on o day &middot; and in thre dayes after<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To</I>] and B. <I>on o</I>] in a R; in o B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Edefye it eft newe &middot; (here he stant &thorn;at seyde it)<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seyde it</I>] it seide B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">And &yogh;it maken it as moche &middot; in al manere poyntes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;it</I>] &yogh;ut to B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bothe as longe and as large &middot; bi loft &amp; by grounde."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi</I>] a R; on B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Cru[ci]fige," quod a cacchepolle &middot; "I warante hym a wicche!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Crucifige</I>] <I>miswritten</I> Crufige L.</NOTE></L>
<L>"<I>Tolle, tolle!</I>" quod an other &middot; and toke o[f] kene &thorn;ornes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] <I>so in</I> WCROB; o L; <I>see next line.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="48">And bigan of kene thorne &middot; a gerelande to make,
<PB REF="00000607.tif" N="325, B-text"></L>
<L>And sette it sore on his hed &middot; and seyde in envye,</L>
<L>"<I>Aue, rabby!</I>" quod &thorn;at Ribaude &middot; and &thorn;rew redes at hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at Ribaude</I>] &thorn;e ribaudes R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nailled hym with &thorn;re nailles &middot; naked on &thorn;e Rode,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nailled</I>] &thorn;ei nailid B. <I>&thorn;re</I>] thre (<I>with</I> foure <I>written in margin</I>) R. <I>on</I>] vp-on R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">And poysoun on a pole &middot; &thorn;ei put vp to his lippes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>on</I>] vppon B. <I>vp</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And bede hym drynke his deth-yuel &middot; his dayes were ydone.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deth-yuel</I>] euyl dee&thorn; B. <I>ydone</I>] doon C; done OB.</NOTE></L>
<L>"And &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ow sotil be &middot; help now &thorn;i-seluen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>] CB <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>If &thorn;ow be cryst, &amp; kynges sone &middot; come downe of &thorn;e Rode;</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;anne shul we leue &thorn;at lyf &thorn;e loueth &middot; and wil nou&yogh;t lete &thorn;e deye!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>shul</I>] shulde B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "<I>Consummatum est</I>," quod cryst &middot; &amp; comsed forto swowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>swowe</I>] <I>so in</I> OB; swowen C; swoune W; swowne R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pitousliche and pale &middot; as a prisoun &thorn;at deyeth;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pitousliche</I>] Ful pitousliche B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e lorde of lyf &amp; of li&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;o leyed his eyen togideres.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The lorde</I>] Til lore R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e daye for drede with-drowe &middot; and derke bicam &thorn;e sonne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bicam</I>] bigan O.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wal wagged and clef &middot; and al &thorn;e worlde quaued.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wal</I>] wallis of &thorn;e temple B. <I>worlde</I>] word C. <I>quaued</I>] quakid B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ded men for that dyne &middot; come out of depe graues,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dyne</I>] dene WR; dee&thorn; B. <I>depe</I>] here R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tolde whi &thorn;at tempest &middot; so longe tyme dured.</L>
<L N="64">"For a bitter bataille" &middot; &thorn;e ded bodye sayde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bodye</I>] bodies B.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Lyf and deth in &thorn;is derknesse &middot; her one-fordoth her other;</L>
<L>Shal no wi&yogh;te wite witterly &middot; who shal haue &thorn;e maystrye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wite</I>] wit C; witte R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="67">Er sondey aboute sonne rysynge" &middot; &amp; sank with &thorn;at til erthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sonne</I>] &thorn;e sunne OB. <I>til</I>] in-to B.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000608.tif" N="326, B-text"></L>
<L>Some seyde &thorn;at he was goddes sone &middot; &thorn;at so faire deyde,<Q><I>Vere filius dei erat iste, &amp;c.</I></Q></L>
<L>And somme saide he was a wicche &middot; "good is &thorn;at we assaye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at we</I>] R <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Where he be ded or nou&yogh;te ded &middot; doun er he be taken."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I> (1)] B <I>om. ded</I> (2)] B <I>om. doun</I>] a-doun B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="71">&para; Two theues also &middot; tholed deth &thorn;at tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deth</I>] dede R.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vppon a crosse bisydes cryst &middot; so was &thorn;e comune lawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] B <I>om. bisydes</I>] biside C.</NOTE></L>
<L>A cacchepole cam forth &middot; and craked bothe her legges,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A</I>] Ac a R.</NOTE></L>
<L>And her armes after &middot; of eyther of &thorn;o theues.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her</I>] &thorn;e W. <I>of eyther</I>] B <I>om. &thorn;o</I>] the C; &thorn;o two B.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac was no boy so bolde &middot; goddes body to touche;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>was</I>] &thorn;er was B. <I>boy</I>] body W.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">For he was kny&yogh;te &amp; kynges sone &middot; kynde for&yogh;af &thorn;at tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tyme</I>] throwe R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at non harlot were so hardy &middot; to leyne hande vppon hym.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hande</I>] an hand R.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Ac &thorn;ere cam forth a kny&yogh;te &middot; with a kene spere ygrounde,</L>
<L>Hi&yogh;te <I>longeus</I>, as &thorn;e lettre telleth &middot; and longe had lore his si&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hi&yogh;te</I>] &thorn;at hi&yogh;te B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Bifor pilat &amp; other peple &middot; in &thorn;e place he houed;</L>
<L>Maugre his many tethe &middot; he was made &thorn;at tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Maugre</I>] and magre B. <I>his many</I>] he (!) B.</NOTE></L>
<L>To take &thorn;e spere in his honde &middot; &amp; iusten with ihesus;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;ei were vnhardy &middot; &thorn;at houed on hors or stode,<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I>] &amp; COB. <I>stode</I>] stede R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="84">To touche hym or to taste hym &middot; or take hym down of Rode.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I> (1)] R <I>om. or to</I>] or COB. <I>hym</I> (3)] W <I>om. of</I>] of &thorn;e B; on (!) C.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;is blynde bacheler &thorn;anne &middot; bar hym &thorn;orugh &thorn;e herte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;anne</I>] &thorn;at R; WO <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e blode spronge down by &thorn;e spere &middot; &amp; vnspered &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes eyen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> (1)] &thorn;at B. <I>spronge</I>] ran B. <I>vnspered</I>] opned R. <I>&thorn;e kni&yogh;tes</I>] hise CO; his B.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000609.tif" N="327, B-text"></L>
