<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000626.tif" N="344, B-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS XIX (PROLOGUE TO DOBEST).</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. Passus decimus nonus YO; <I>to which</I> B <I>adds</I>&mdash;et quintus de dobet. W <I>agrees with</I> L.</NOTE><I>Passus xix</I><SUP>us</SUP>; <I>&amp; explicit dobet, &amp; incipit dobest.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THus I awaked &amp; wrote &middot; what I had dremed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dremed</I>] ydremed WC.</NOTE></L>
<L>And di&yogh;te me derely &middot; &amp; dede me to cherche,</L>
<L>To here holy &thorn;e masse &middot; &amp; to be houseled after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holy &thorn;e</I>] &thorn;e holi B.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp; to be&mdash;masse</I>] COBY <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="4">In myddes of &thorn;e masse &middot; &thorn;o men &yogh;ede to offrynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp; to be&mdash;masse</I>] COBY <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>I fel eftsones a-slepe &middot; &amp; sodeynly me mette,<NOTE PLACE="foot">COBY <I>omit.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>That Pieres &thorn;e plowman &middot; was paynted al blody,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>That</I>] &thorn;anne O.</NOTE></L>
<L>And come in with a crosse &middot; bifor &thorn;e comune peple,</L>
<L N="8">And ri&yogh;te lyke in alle lymes &middot; to owre lorde ihesu;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lymes</I>] &thorn;ynges W.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;anne called I conscience &middot; to kenne me &thorn;e sothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] CBY <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>"Is &thorn;is ihesus &thorn;e iuster?" quod I &middot; "&thorn;at iuwes did to deth?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>did</I>] diden B; diden hym O.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or it is Pieres &thorn;e plowman! &middot; who paynted hym so rede?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it is</I>] <I>so in</I> WCOBY; is it <I>in</I> Crowley.</NOTE></L>
<L>Quod conscience, &amp; kneled &thorn;o &middot; "&thorn;ise aren Pieres armes,</L>
<L N="13">His coloures &amp; his cote-armure &middot; ac he &thorn;at cometh so blody<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>] and C.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is cryst with his crosse &middot; conqueroure of crystene."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Is</I>] Wi&thorn; B.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000627.tif" N="345, B-text"></L>
<L>&para; "Why calle &yogh;e hym cryst?" quod I &middot; "sithenes iuwes calle hym ihesus?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>] W <I>om. calle</I> (2)] called CBY; calleden O.</NOTE></L>
<L N="16">Patriarkes &amp; prophetes &middot; prophecyed bifore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alkyn creatures &middot; shulden knelen &amp; bowen,</L>
<L>Anon as men nempned &middot; &thorn;e name of god Ihesu.</L>
<L><I>Ergo</I> is no name &middot; to &thorn;e name of ihesus,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] &thorn;er is B. <I>&thorn;e</I>] &thorn;at B. <I>of</I>] CBY <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ne none so nedeful to nempne &middot; by ny&yogh;te ne by daye.</L>
<L N="21">For alle derke deuelles &middot; aren adradde to heren it,</L>
<L>And synful aren solaced &middot; &amp; saued bi &thorn;at name.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e callen hym cryst &middot; for what cause, telleth me?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>] thay C. <I>callen</I>] callid B.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">Is cryst more of my&yogh;te &middot; &amp; more worthy name</L>
<L>&THORN;an ihesu or ihesus &middot; &thorn;at al owre ioye come of?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>come</I>] come&thorn; B.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Thow knowest wel," quod conscience &middot; "and &thorn;ow konne resoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>konne</I>] canst O.</NOTE></L>
<L>That kny&yogh;te, kynge, conqueroure &middot; may be o persone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">O <I>puts</I> kynge <I>before</I> kny&yogh;te. <I>kynge</I>] kyng and B. <I>o</I>] a B; of oo Y.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">To be called a kni&yogh;te is faire &middot; for men shal knele to hym;</L>
<L>To be called a Kynge is fairer &middot; for he may kny&yogh;tes make;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To</I>] And to O. <I>is</I>] O <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ac to be conquerour called &middot; &thorn;at cometh of special grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>] And CYB.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of hardynesse of herte &middot; &amp; of hendenesse [bothe],<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>bothe</I> COBY] LW <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="32">To make lordes of laddes &middot; of londe &thorn;at he wynneth,</L>
<L>And fre men foule thralles &middot; &thorn;at folweth nou&yogh;t his lawes.<MILESTONE N="82" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; The iuwes, &thorn;at were gentil men &middot; ihesu &thorn;ei dispised,</L>
<L>Bothe his lore &amp; his lawe &middot; now ar &thorn;ei lowe cherlis.</L>
<L N="36">As wyde as &thorn;e worlde is &middot; wonyeth &thorn;ere none<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As</I>] Also B. <I>wonyeth&mdash;none</I>] noon of hem &thorn;er wonye&thorn; W.</NOTE></L>
<L>But vnder tribut &amp; taillage &middot; as tykes &amp; cherles.</L>
