<L>Among wyues and wodewes &middot; ich am ywoned sitte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyues</I>] &thorn;e wyues F. <I>ich am</I>] am i M. <I>ywoned</I>] wont to IFS; wonet to M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">Yparroked in puwes; &middot; &thorn;e person hit knoweth<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e&mdash;hit</I>] as our parsoun F.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000941.tif" N="103, C-text"></L>
<L>How lytel ic louye &middot; letice at &thorn;e style;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ic louye</I>] it is &thorn;at I loue F. <I>at &thorn;e</I>] atte FI.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hue hadde haly bred er ich &middot; myn herte by-gan to chaunge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-gan</I>] gan IS.</NOTE></L>
<L>After-ward after mete &middot; hue and ich chidde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>After-ward&mdash;mete</I>] After mete aftirward I. <I>hue&mdash;ich</I>] Annot &amp; heo F.</NOTE></L>
<L N="148">And ich, wratth, was war &middot; and wroth on hem bo&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>war</I>] i-war MF. <I>wroth</I>] wor&thorn; M; war&thorn; I; wax F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til ai&thorn;er [cleped o&thorn;ere 'hore'] &middot; and of with &thorn;e clo&thorn;es,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>cleped&mdash;hore</I> IMFSG] cleped ei&thorn;er o&thorn;er (<I>sic</I>) E; cliped o&thorn;ere P. <I>of&mdash;clo&thorn;es</I>] cast of here hoodus F; on wi&thorn; &thorn;e clawes I.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til bo&thorn;e here heuedes were bar &middot; and blody here chekes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here</I>] M <I>om. here</I> (2)] bo&thorn;e F.</NOTE></L>
<L>A-mong monkes myght ich be &middot; ac meny tyme ich spare,<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="66"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myght&mdash;be</I>] I mighte be I. <I>ich be</I>] S <I>om. ac</I>] and M. <I>myght&mdash;spare</I>] I am &middot; many a tyme &amp; ofte F.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;er be&thorn; meny felle frekus &middot; myne afferes to aspye;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] M <I>om. &thorn;er be&thorn;</I>] &thorn;er arn IMS; &thorn;ei ar F. <I>meny felle</I>] felle fers F. <I>myne&mdash;to</I>] her ferus i F. <I>aspye</I>] spie M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="153">&THORN;at ys, &thorn;e priour and &thorn;e suppriour &middot; and oure <I>pater abbas.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] I <I>om.</I> (<I>twice</I>). <I>oure</I>] o&thorn;er M. F <I>has</I>&mdash;&amp; put hem to &thorn;e priour &middot; or ellus to pater abbas.</NOTE></L>
<L>And yf ich telle eny tales &middot; thei taken hem to-geders,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yf</I>] ES <I>om. hem</I>] E <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And don me faste fridaies &middot; to bred and to water.</L>
<L N="156">&YOGH;ut am ich chalenged in chapitele-hous &middot; as ich a childe were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chapitele</I>] oure chapitre I; &thorn;e chapitele M; chapitre E.</NOTE></L>
<L>And baleysed [on] &thorn;e bar ers &middot; and no breche by|twyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>baleysed</I>] bylasched E; bete G. [<I>on</I> IMFSG] in PE.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich haue no lust, leyue me &middot; to lenge a-mong monkes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leyue</I>] leue IME; lef S. <I>lenge</I>] longe I; lyue M; dwelle E.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000942.tif" N="104, C-text"></L>
<L>For hij ete&thorn; more fisch &thorn;an flesh &middot; and feble ale drynken.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hij ete&thorn;</I>] I ete I. <I>drynken</I>] drenken P; <I>but see</I> l. 166.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">Ac o&thorn;er-while whanne wyn come&thorn; &middot; and whenne ich drynke late,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>while whanne</I>] wile wanne P. <I>whenne</I>] wenne P. <I>drynke</I>] drenke P. <I>late</I>] late an eue I.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich haue a flux of a foul mouth &middot; wel fyf dayes after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] or MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at ich wiste wickede &middot; by eny of oure couent,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Al</I>] And alle I. <I>wickede</I>] wikke I.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich cowede hit vp in oure cloistre &middot; &thorn;at al &thorn;e Couent wot hit."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cowede</I>] cou&yogh;hede S; schewede M; cou&thorn;e I. <I>hit</I>] M <I>om. &thorn;e</I>] oure MS.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>154&mdash;163. <I>For these</I>, F <I>has</I>&mdash;</P><P>With-oute loue or leaute &middot; &amp; lye on hem with talus,</P><P>&amp; make hem euer ete flesch &middot; for ech of hem ete o&thorn;ur.</P><P>&THORN;e wikkednesse &thorn;at I wiste &middot; by any of &thorn;e route,</P><P>I cowhed it up in our cloistre &middot; &thorn;at al &thorn;e couent wist it.</P><P>&amp; &yogh;it I spak no speche &middot; it swal so my breste,</P><P>&THORN;at I chewed it as a cowe &middot; &thorn;at code chewith ofte.</P><P>&THORN;an was I chalanged in chapitre &middot; as I childe were,</P><P>&amp; balised on &thorn;e bare ers &middot; &amp; no brech bitwene.</P></NOTE></L>
<L N="164">"Now repente &thorn;e," qua&thorn; repentaunce &middot; "and reherce neuere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] I <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>What counsail &thorn;at &thorn;ow knowest &middot; by contenaunce ne by speche.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>What</I>] &thorn;at M; I <I>om. &thorn;at</I>] S <I>om. ne by</I>] no F.</NOTE></L>
<L>And drynk nat ouer delicatliche &middot; ne to depe nei&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot">F <I>omits. depe</I>] dupe P. <I>nei&thorn;er</I>] no&thorn;er ES.</NOTE></L>
