<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>CONFESSIO LUXURIE.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thenne seide lecherie 'alas!' &middot; and to oure lady cryede,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="55"><MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="60"></L>
<L>"Lady, to &thorn;y leue sone &middot; lowte for me nouthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] for M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="172">That he haue pyte on me putour &middot; of hus pure grace and mercy,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>putour</I>] putrour I; F <I>om. of</I>] for MF. <I>grace and</I>] IMFS <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>With &thorn;at ich shal," quath &thorn;at shrewe &middot; "saterdayes, for &thorn;y loue,<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="61"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>With</I>] Whit P. <I>saterdayes</I>] saturday F. <I>&thorn;y loue</I>] &thorn;y moder loue I; euere F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Drynke bote with &thorn;e douke &middot; and dyne bote ones.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bote</I> (1)] M <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ich, gulty in gost &middot; to god ich me shryue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ich</I>] For i F.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000943.tif" N="105, C-text"></L>
<L N="176">As in lykynge of lecherie &middot; my licames gultes,</L>
<L>In wordes, in wedes &middot; in waitynge of eyen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wordes</I>] worde and I. <I>in</I> (3)] on I.</NOTE></L>
<L>To eche maide &thorn;at ich mette &middot; ich made hure a sygne<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="228"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To eche</I>] To eche a F; For ich a I. <I>hure</I>] to hure P; <I>but</I> IMF SE <I>omit</I> to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Semynge to synne-warde &middot; and somme gan ich taste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gan ich</I>] I gan I.</NOTE></L>
<L>A-boute &thorn;e mouthe, and by-nythe &middot; by-gan ich to grope,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] F <I>om. by-gan</I>] gan S.</NOTE></L>
<L N="181">Til oure bo&thorn;ers wil was on; &middot; to werke we &yogh;eden<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oure bo&thorn;ers</I>] bo&thorn;e oure IM. <I>bo&thorn;ers</I>] bei&thorn;ur F; beyres E; bo&thorn;e IMS. <I>to</I>] &amp; to S; and to &thorn;e I.</NOTE></L>
<L>As wel fastyngdaies [as] frydaies &middot; and heye-feste euenes,<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="229"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As wel</I>] F <I>om.</I> [<I>as</I> IE] and PFSG. <I>as frydaies</I>] M <I>om. heye</I>] eye P; heie I; hi M; hye F. <I>euenes</I>] eues MFE.</NOTE></L>
<L>As luf in lente as oute of lente &middot; alle tymes liche&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As</I>] And M. <I>luf</I>] lef E; lief I; leef FS; wel M. <I>tymes</I>] tyme IM. <I>liche</I>] yliche IMS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Suche werkus with ous &middot; were neuere out of seson&mdash;</L>
<L>Til we myghte no more; &middot; &thorn;anne hadde we murye tales</L>
<L N="186">Of puterie and of paramours &middot; and proueden &thorn;orw speches,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> (1)] F <I>om. proueden &thorn;orw</I>] perelous F. <I>speches</I>] speche IM.</NOTE></L>
<L>Handlynge and halsynge &middot; and al-so &thorn;orw cussynge<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Handlynge</I>] And handelyng I. <I>also&mdash;cussynge</I>] hory kissyngus F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Excitynge oure ai&thorn;er o&thorn;er &middot; til oure olde synne;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oure</I> (1)] ous S; IM <I>om. oure</I> (2)] I <I>om. olde</I> IFSE] elde M; holde P.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sotilede songes &middot; and sende out olde baudes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sende</I>] sente IMF.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">For to wynne to my wil &middot; wommen with gyle;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] I <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>By sorcerye som tyme &middot; and som tyme by maistrye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>som&mdash;maistrye</I>] alle suche slei&yogh;tus F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich lay by &thorn;e louelokeste &middot; and loued hem neuere after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hem</I>] hir I.</NOTE></L>
<L N="193">Whenne ich was old and hor &middot; and hadde lore &thorn;at kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lore</I>] y-lore I; i-lorn M; lost F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich had lykynge to lauhe &middot; of [lecherous] tales.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lauhe</I>] lau&yogh;e E; lau&yogh;&yogh;e S; li&yogh;e M; lithe I. [<I>lecherous</I> MF] lecherye PIES; lecheryes G.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now, lord, for &thorn;y leaute &middot; of lechours haue mercy!"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I>] of S. <I>of</I>] on IMF.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000944.tif" N="106, C-text">
<HEAD>CONFESSIO AUARICIE.<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="58"><MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="67"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="196">Thenne cam couetyse &middot; ich can nat hym discryue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Thenne</I>] And &thorn;anne F.</NOTE></L>
<L>So hongerliche and so holwe &middot; heruy hym-self lokede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hongerliche</I>] hongri MF. <I>and</I>] an P; I <I>om. so</I>] IMFS <I>om. heruy hym-self</I>] <I>sir</I> heruy him I; syr heruy he F. <I>heruy&mdash;lokede</I>] heruy was his name M.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was bytelbrowed and baberlupped &middot; with two blery eyen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He was</I>] F <I>om. bytelbrowed</I>] Bittur-browed F. <I>with</I>] whit P. <I>two</I>] tueye I. <I>blery</I>] blered IMFS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as a le&thorn;erene pors &middot; lollid hus chekus,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>] S <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="200">[Wel] sydder &thorn;an hys chyn &middot; ychiueled for elde:<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>Wel</I> IMFSEG] Al P. <I>hys</I>] ys P. <I>ychiueled</I>] he chyuelede F; i-reueled M.</NOTE></L>
<L>As bondemenne bacon &middot; hus berd was yshaue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As</I>] As a M; And as a I. <I>bondemenne</I>] bedemones M.</NOTE></L>
<L>With hus hod on his heued &middot; and hus hatte bo&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>With</I>] Whit P.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a toren tabarde &middot; of twelue wynter age;</L>
<L N="204">[But &yogh;if a lous cou&thorn;e lepe &middot; I leue hit, as y trowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> S; <I>also in</I> IMFG; PE <I>omit.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cou&thorn;e</I>] I <I>om. hit</I>] IM <I>om. as</I>] I <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>He scholde not wandre on &thorn;at welch &middot; so was hit &thorn;rede-bare.]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>From</I> S; <I>also in</I> IMFG; PE <I>omit.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>not</I>] I <I>om. wandre</I>] walke M. <I>on</I>] vp I. <I>welch</I>] walk I; wel&thorn;e F; clo&thorn; G.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ich haue be coueitous," qua&thorn; &thorn;is caityf &middot; "Ich by|know hit here.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is caityf</I>] &thorn;at caitijf M; &thorn;e caytif E; heo F.</NOTE></L>
<L N="207">For som tyme ich serued &middot; symme at &thorn;e style,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>at &thorn;e</I>] atte F; at S.</NOTE></L>
<L>And was his prentys yplyght &middot; hus profyt to waite.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>his</I>] is P. <I>yplyght</I>] tru&thorn;e|plith M. <I>waite</I>] awayte S.</NOTE></L>
<L>Furst ich lerned to lye &middot; a lesyng o&thorn;er tweye;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lesyng</I>] lees I. <I>a&mdash;tweye</I>] and leuyng al tru&thorn;e M.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wickedliche to weye &middot; was my furst lesson.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] for to F. <I>weye</I>] wynne M. <I>furst</I>] S <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To wy and to winchestre &middot; ich wente to &thorn;e faire<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="68"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wy</I>] &thorn;e weo M. <I>ich wente</I>] went i F. <I>wente</I>] wende E.</NOTE></L>
<L N="212">With many [maner] marchandises &middot; as my [maister] heghte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>maner</I> MIFSEG] P <I>om. marchandises</I>] marchandise IF. [<I>maister</I> MIFSEG] maistres P.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000945.tif" N="107, C-text"></L>
<L>Ne hadde &thorn;e grace of gyle &middot; gon among my ware,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I>] F <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Hit hadde ben vnsold &thorn;ys seuen &yogh;er &middot; so me god helpe!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hadde&mdash;vnsold</I>] nad be sold F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich drow me among drapers &middot; my donet to lerne,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="59"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ich drow me</I>] &THORN;an drogh I me I. <I>among</I>] to F. <I>lerne</I>] lere I.</NOTE></L>
