<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000996.tif" N="158, C-text">
<HEAD>PASSUS X.</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. <I>So</I> PEG; Hic incipit pas|sus decimus de uisione M; Passus Nonus, vt prius I.</NOTE><I>Incipit passus decimus.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TReuthe herde telle here-of &middot; and to peers sente<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="92"><MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="111"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here-of</I>] &thorn;er-of M.</NOTE></L>
<L>To take hus teeme &middot; and tulye &thorn;e erthe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tulye</I>] tilie E; tylien IG; teli&yogh;e M.</NOTE></L>
<L>And purchased hym a pardon &middot; <I>&aacute; pena et &aacute; culpa</I>,</L>
<L N="4">For hym and for hus heyres &middot; for euere to be asoiled;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I> (3)] G <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And bad [hym] halde hym at home &middot; and erye hus leyes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hym</I> IG] PEM <I>om. at home</I>] a-tom G.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at hulpe hym to erye &middot; to setten o&thorn;er to sawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alle</I>] &thorn;o M. <I>hulpe</I>] holpe I; holpen M; helpi&thorn; G. <I>hym</I>] E <I>om. sawe</I>] sowe IMEG.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er eny manere myster &middot; &thorn;at myght peers a-vayle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>myster</I> MEG] meester P.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">Pardon with peers plouhman &middot; perpetual he graunte&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>perpetual</I>] perpetuelly GI. <I>he</I>] I <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Kynges and knyghtes &middot; &thorn;at holy [kirke] defenden,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>kirke</I> I] churche PEG; chirche M.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ryghtfulliche in reames &middot; ruelen &thorn;e comune,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ryghtfulliche</I>] ryghtfulleche P.</NOTE></L>
<L>Han pardon &thorn;orw purgatorie &middot; to passy ful lyghtliche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to passy</I>] passen M.</NOTE></L>
<L>With patriarkes and prophetes &middot; in paradyse to sitte.</L>
<L N="13">Bisshopes yblessed &middot; if &thorn;ei ben as &thorn;ei sholde,</L>
<L>Leel and ful of loue &middot; and no lord dreden,<NOTE PLACE="foot">G <I>omits. no lord</I>] none lordes M.</NOTE></L>
<L>Merciable to meek &middot; and mylde to &thorn;e goode,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>meek</I>] &thorn;e meke G; meke men E.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000997.tif" N="159, C-text"></L>
<L>And bytynge on badde men &middot; bote yf &thorn;ei wolde amende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bytynge</I>] biter G. <I>on</I>] to G; in I. <I>wolde</I>] wole GI; wollen M.</NOTE></L>
<L>And drede&thorn; nat for no de&thorn; &middot; to distruye, by here powere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] I <I>om. nat</I>] MG <I>om. here</I>] &thorn;i M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="18">Lecherie a-mong lordes &middot; and hure lu&thorn;er customes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>customes</I> MI] custymes PE; custumes G.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sitthen lyue as &thorn;ei lere&thorn; men &middot; oure lord treuthe hem graunte&thorn;</L>
<L N="20">To be peeres to a-posteles &middot; alle puple to ruele,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="93"><MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="112"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] of &thorn;e G; M <I>om. a-posteles</I>] &thorn;apostles I. <I>alle</I>] al &thorn;e MG.</NOTE></L>
<L>And deme with hem at domes day &middot; bo&thorn;e quike and ded.</L>
<L>Marchans in &thorn;e margine &middot; hadden menye &yogh;eres,</L>
<L>Ac <I>&aacute; pena &amp; &aacute; culpa</I> &middot; treuthe nolde hem graunte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac a</I>] Ac no I. <I>treuthe nolde</I>] no treu&thorn;e wolde I.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">For thei holden nat here halydaies &middot; as holychurche teche&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>daies</I>] day IG. <I>teche&thorn;</I>] hem hote&thorn; I.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for &thorn;ei swere by here saule &middot; and 'so god me mote helpe!'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so</I>] I <I>om. god&mdash;mote</I>] mot god hem G; god mote hem I. <I>god&mdash;helpe</I>] helpe hem god al-my&yogh;ti M.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;ens clene conscience &middot; for couetyse of wynnynge.</L>
<L>Ac vnder his secre seel &middot; treuthe sente [hem] a lettere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>secre</I>] secrete IE. [<I>hem</I> MIEG] hym P.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">And bad [hem] bygge baldly &middot; what [hem] best lykede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hem</I> MEIG] hym P (<I>twice</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>And sitthen sellen hit a-&yogh;eyn &middot; and saue &thorn;e wynnynges,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sellen</I>] to sellen M. <I>saue</I>] haue E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amenden <I>meson-dieux &thorn;er</I>-with &middot; and myseyse men fynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">G <I>omits. Amenden&mdash;dieux</I>] And to amende &thorn;i mysdedes M.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wikkede weyes &middot; with here good amende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here</I>] &yogh;ore G.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">And brygges to-broke &middot; by &thorn;e heye weyes<NOTE PLACE="foot">E <I>omits. to-broke</I>] to-brokene I. <I>weyes</I>] wei&yogh;e M. <I>weyes</I>] weyes amende P (<I>by mistake</I>); <I>but</I> IMG <I>omit</I> amende; <I>see next line.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Amende in som manere wise &middot; and maydenes helpen;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maydenes</I> IMG] maydones PE.</NOTE></L>
<L>Poure puple bedredene &middot; and prisones in stockes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bedredene</I>] bedrede M.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fynde hem for Godes loue &middot; and fauntekynes to scole;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="94"></L>
<L N="36">Releue religion &middot; and renten hem bettere;
<PB REF="00000998.tif" N="160, C-text"></L>
<L>'And ich shal sende &yogh;ow my-selue &middot; seynt Michel myn Angel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Angel</I>] archangel I.</NOTE></L>
<L>That no deuel shal &yogh;ow dere &middot; ne despeir in &yogh;oure deyinge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>despeir in</I>] despeire &yogh;ow in M; dispise G. <I>deyinge</I>] deyenge P; doyng G.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sende &yogh;oure soules &middot; &thorn;er ich my-self dwelle,<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="113"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sende</I>] sitthe sende I. <I>dwelle</I>] sitte M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">And &thorn;ere a-byde body and soule &middot; in blisse for euere.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ere</I> M] &thorn;er EI; <I>miswritten</I> &thorn;e (<I>for &thorn;ere</I>) P; G <I>om. body</I>] in bodi EM. <I>&thorn;ere&mdash;blisse</I>] abide &thorn;er in my blisse &middot; body and soule I.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tho were merchauns murye &middot; somme wepte for ioye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>somme wepte</I>] meny wepen I.</NOTE></L>
<L>And preyde for peers plouhman &middot; &thorn;at purchasede hem &thorn;is bulle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peers</I>] peres &thorn;e I. <I>hem &thorn;is</I>] &thorn;e G.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e puple hadde pardon ynow &middot; &thorn;at parfytliche lyueden;</L>
<L N="44">Men of lawe hadde lest &middot; that loth were to plede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lest</I>] leest G; left (!) E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ei <I>pre manibus</I> were payed &middot; for pledyng atte barre.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>atte</I>] at &thorn;e MEG.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac he &thorn;at spene&thorn; hus speche &middot; and speke&thorn; for &thorn;e poure<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="95"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spene&thorn;</I>] spende&thorn; M.</NOTE></L>
<L>That innocent and nedy is &middot; and no man harme wolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nedy</I> IMEG] nudy P.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">And conforte&thorn; suche in eny cas &middot; and coueyte&thorn; nat here &yogh;iftes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">G <I>omits. And</I>] &THORN;at MI. <I>&yogh;iftes</I> IME] &yogh;eftes P.</NOTE></L>
<L>And for &thorn;e loue of oure lorde &middot; lawe for hem declare&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">G <I>omits. hem</I>] hym E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shal haue grace of God ynow &middot; and a gret ioye after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>God</I>] good M. <I>God ynow</I>] good ende G; a good ende I. <I>a</I>] MIG <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Be&thorn; ywar, &yogh;e wise men &middot; and witty of &thorn;e lawe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wise men</I> IMEG] wismen P. <I>&thorn;e</I>] G <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="52">For whenne &yogh;e drawe&thorn; to &thorn;e de&thorn; &middot; and indulgence wolde haue,<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="114"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>] M <I>om. whenne</I>] wenne P. <I>indulgence</I>] indulgences MI.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hus pardon is ful petit &middot; at hus partynge hennes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hus</I>] &thorn;e M.</NOTE></L>
<L>That mede of mene men &middot; for here motynge take&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mene</I>] &thorn;e mene E; meny G.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000999.tif" N="161, C-text"></L>
<L>For hit is symonye, to sulle &middot; &thorn;at send is of grace;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>send</I>] sent I. <I>send&mdash;of</I>] is i-sent bi M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="56">That is, witt and water &middot; wynd, and fuyr &thorn;e furthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>That</I>] And &thorn;at I. <I>wynd</I>] and wynde I.</NOTE></L>
<L>These foure sholden be fre &middot; to alle folk &thorn;at hit [nede&thorn;.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>nede&thorn;</I> IME] nedi&thorn; G; needede P.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle lybbynge laborours &middot; &thorn;at lyuen with here handes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lybbynge</I>] libbynde G; truwe M. <I>laborours</I>] laberours P.</NOTE></L>
<L>Leelyche and lawefulliche &middot; oure lord treuthe hem graunte&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lawefulliche</I>] lawefulleche P. <I>hem</I>] G <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Pardon perpetuel &middot; ryght as peers plouhman.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peers</I>] peres &thorn;e I; to peres G.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beggers and bydders &middot; be&thorn; nat in [&thorn;at] bulle<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>&thorn;at</I> IMEG] &thorn;e P. <I>bulle</I>] bille I.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e suggestion be soth &middot; &thorn;at shape&thorn; hem to begge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>suggestion</I>] sugestion P. <I>shape&thorn;</I>] shappe&thorn; P. <I>hem</I>] him I.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he &thorn;at beggeth o&thorn;er bydde&thorn; &middot; bote yf [he] haue nede,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="96"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] hy G. [<I>he</I> MI] hi G; &thorn;ei P; &thorn;ey E.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">He ys fals and faitour &middot; and defraunde&thorn; &thorn;e [nedy,]<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>nedy</I> IMEG] neede P.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also gyle&thorn; hym &thorn;at gyue&thorn; &middot; and take&thorn; ageyns hus wyl.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>] MG <I>om. gyle&thorn;</I>] bi-gile&thorn; M.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he &thorn;at gyue&thorn; for Godes loue &middot; wolde nat gyue, hus &thorn;ankus,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ankus</I>] &thorn;onkes E; &thorn;ankes IMG.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &thorn;er he wyste hit were &middot; wel gret neede to gyuen,<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="115"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hit</I>] I <I>om. wel</I>] G <I>om. to gyuen</I>] to geue hit M; I <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="68">And most meritorie to men &middot; &thorn;at he &yogh;eue&thorn; for.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>most</I>] mest PE; <I>but see</I> l. 71. <I>for</I> EG] fore PI; hit fore M.</NOTE></L>
<L>Caton a-corde&thorn; &thorn;er-with &middot; <I>cui des uideto;</I></L>
<L>Wot no man, as ich wene &middot; who is worthy to haue.</L>
<L>The most needy aren oure neighebores &middot; and we nyme good hede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aren</I>] arn M; ar G; be&thorn; E.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">As prisones in puttes &middot; and poure folke in Cotes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>folke</I>] men G.</NOTE></L>
<L>Charged with children &middot; and chef lordes rente,</L>
<L>That &thorn;ei [wi&thorn;] spynnynge may spare &middot; spenen hit in hous-hyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>wi&thorn;</I> MIG] PE <I>om. spenen</I> E] spene IG; spende M; <I>miswritten</I> spynen P; <I>but see</I> l. 46. <I>in</I>] on IG.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001000.tif" N="162, C-text"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in mylk and in mele &middot; to make with papelotes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] wi&thorn; G (<I>twice</I>). <I>papelotes</I>] her papelotes <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="76">To a-glotye with here gurles &middot; &thorn;at greden after fode.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To</I>] Forte M. <I>a-glotye</I>] glotye I.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al-so hem-selue &middot; suffren muche hunger,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Al-so</I>] &amp; al-so GM. <I>Al-so hem-selue</I>] And hem-seluen also I.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wo in winter-tyme &middot; with wakynge a nyghtes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in</I>] on G. <I>tyme</I>] tymes I. <I>with</I>] and I; on G. <I>wakynge</I>] walkynge G. <I>a</I>] in I; on MG<I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To ryse to &thorn;e ruel &middot; to rocke &thorn;e cradel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ryse</I>] arisen M. <I>ruel</I>] <I>so</I> PM; rewel I; rule EG. <I>to</I>] and to M. <I>cradel</I>] childes cradel <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to karde and to kembe &middot; to clouten and to wasche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kembe</I>] combe wolle <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="81">To rubbe and to rely &middot; russhes to pilie,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rubbe</I>] ribbe IMG. <I>and</I>] G <I>om. rely</I>] <I>so</I> PE; rele IG<I>I</I>; reole M. <I>russhes</I>] &amp; rissches G; and resshes <I>I. pilie</I>] pili&yogh;e M; pyl <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at reuthe is to rede &middot; o&thorn;ere in ryme shewe</L>
<L>The wo [of] &thorn;ese women &middot; &thorn;at wonye&thorn; in Cotes;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>of</I> IG] &thorn;at PEM; <I>but see next line. &thorn;ese</I>] &thorn;eese P; <I>and in</I> ll. 96, 164, 183. <I>women</I>] women han E; woman ha&thorn; M. <I>wonye&thorn;&mdash;Cotes</I>] in Cote wonen <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="84">And of meny o&thorn;er men &middot; &thorn;at muche wo suffren,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>men</I>] mo <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e a-fyngrede and a-furst &middot; to turne &thorn;e fayre out|warde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a-fyngrede</I>] a-fyngred E; a|fingred G; of-hungret M; an-hungred I. <I>a-furst</I>] <I>so</I> PG; a&thorn;urst EI; of-&thorn;erst M; in harde thurst <I>I. fayre</I>] fairest M<I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And beth abasshed for to begge &middot; and wolle nat be aknowe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>] &thorn;ey <I>I. aknowe</I> EMG] aknowen I; byknowen <I>I;</I> yknowe P.</NOTE></L>
<L>What hem neede&thorn; at here neihebores &middot; at non and at euen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>at</I> (1)] att P; of M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">This ich wot witerly &middot; as &thorn;e worlde teche&thorn;,</L>
<L>What o&thorn;er by-houe&thorn; &middot; &thorn;at hath meny children,</L>
<L>And hath no catel bote hus crafte &middot; to clo&thorn;y hem and to fede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fede</I>] foode G.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fele to fonge &thorn;er-to &middot; and fewe pans take&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pans</I>] pens IM.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther is payn and peny-ale &middot; as for a pytaunce y-take,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ale</I>] ale also E. <I>as</I>] M <I>om.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00001001.tif" N="163, C-text"></L>
<L N="93">Colde flessh and cold fyssh &middot; for veneson ybake;<NOTE PLACE="foot">M <I>omits. Colde</I>] And colde I. <I>cold</I>] I <I>om. for</I>] as I. <I>ybake</I>] were y-bake I.</NOTE></L>
<L>Frydayes and fastyng-dayes &middot; [a] ferthyng-worth of muscles<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>a</I> IMEG] P <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Were a feste for suche folke &middot; o&thorn;er so fele Cockes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I>] wi&thorn; I. <I>folke</I>] a folke P; <I>but</I> IMEG <I>omit</I> a. <I>so fele</I>] as fele of M. <I>Cockes</I>] <I>so</I> PEM; cokkys G; cokeles I.</NOTE></L>
<L N="96">These were almes, to helpe &middot; &thorn;at han suche charges,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>were</I>] are I. <I>helpe&mdash;charges</I>] ese &middot; and also many o&thorn;er <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And to comfortie suche cotyers &middot; and crokede men and blynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>] M <I>om. cotyers</I>] coterels IG. <I>and&mdash;and</I>] &thorn;e croked and &thorn;e <I>I.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ac beggers with bagges &middot; &thorn;e whiche brewhouses ben here churches,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>with</I>] wi&thorn; here G. <I>&thorn;e whiche</I>] &thorn;e wiche P; swiche M.</NOTE></L>
