<HEAD>PASSUS XI. (DO-WEL I.)</HEAD>
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="foot">TITLE. <I>So</I> PEG; M <I>prefixes</I> Hic. <I>Willelmi</I>] FI <I>om.</I></NOTE><I>Incipit uisio eiusdem Willelmi de dowel.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THus robed in russett &middot; ich romede a-boute,<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="103"><MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="125"></L>
<L>Al a somer seson &middot; for to seke dowel,</L>
<L>[And] frainede ful ofte &middot; of folke &thorn;at ich mette,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>And</I> IMGF] PE <I>om. frainede</I>] a-frainede M. <I>folke</I>] men G.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">Yf eny wiht wist &middot; wher dowel was at ynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wiht</I>] with P; <I>but see</I> l. 6. <I>wher</I>] wer P.</NOTE></L>
<L>And what man he myghte be &middot; of meny man ich askede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I> (2)] men E.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was neuere wiht in &thorn;is worlde &middot; &thorn;at wisse me couthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;is</I>] &thorn;e I. <I>wisse me</I>] me wisse IG.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher &thorn;at he longede &middot; lasse ne more;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at he</I>] &thorn;is I. <I>longede</I>] lengede F; logget E; wonede G. <I>ne</I>] no I.</NOTE></L>
<L N="8">Til hit by-ful on a frydaye &middot; two freres ich mette,</L>
<L>Maisteres of [&thorn;e] menours &middot; men of grete witte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>&thorn;e</I> IEF] PMS <I>om. menours</I>] menour (<I>sic</I>) I; mynours E; menow|rus &amp; F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich hailsede hem hendilyche &middot; as ich hadde ylerned,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hailsede</I>] hailede M; askede G. <I>ylerned</I> E] ylernede P; i-lered M; lered IGF.</NOTE></L>
<L>And prayede pur charite &middot; ar &thorn;ei passede for&thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>prayede</I>] prayed hem I. <I>pur</I>] par E; for M. <I>ar</I>] er I; or MFEG.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">Yf &thorn;ei knew eny contreie &middot; o&thorn;er costes a-boute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>contreie</I>] contreis EG.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher &thorn;at dowel dwelle&thorn;&mdash; &middot; "dere frendes, telle&thorn; me;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dwelle&thorn;</I>] dwellede I. <I>telle&thorn; me</I>] me telle&thorn; E; &yogh;e me telle F.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &yogh;e aren men of &thorn;ys molde &middot; &thorn;at most wide walken,<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="126"></L>
<L>And knowen contreies and courtes &middot; and menye kynne places,</L>
<L N="16">Bo&thorn;e princes paleis &middot; and poure menne Cotes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>menne</I>] men IE; menes M.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dowel and do-vuele &middot; wher &thorn;ei dwellen bo&thorn;e."
<PB REF="00001018.tif" N="180, C-text"></L>
<L>"Sothliche," seide &thorn;e frere &middot; "he soiourne&thorn; with ous freres,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>freres</I>] bo&thorn;e G.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ay hath, as ich hope &middot; and [euer] wol her-after."<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="104"><NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>euer</I> FGI] &yogh;ut M; PE <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="20">"<I>Contra</I>," qua&thorn; ich as a clerke &middot; and comsede to dis|pute,</L>
<L>And seide sothliche &middot; "<I>septies in die cadit iustus</I>,</L>
<L>Fallynge fro ioye &middot; iesus wot &thorn;e sothe!</L>
<L>'Seuene sythes,' seith &thorn;e bok &middot; 'synge&thorn; day by day<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sythes</I> EMF] sythe PI; <I>see</I> l. 31. <I>synge&thorn;</I>] synege&thorn; G; synne&thorn; ME; man synneth F. <I>by day</I>] and nyth M.</NOTE></L>
<L>The al&thorn;er-ryghtfulleste renk &middot; &thorn;at regne&thorn; vpon erthe.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al&thorn;er</I>] alder M; I <I>om. vpon</I>] on I; on &thorn;e G.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ho so synge&thorn;," ich seide &middot; "certys, do&thorn; nat wel;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>synge&thorn;</I>] synne&thorn; IMEF; synegi&thorn; G. <I>do&thorn;</I>] he do&thorn; I.</NOTE></L>
<L N="26">For ho so synge&thorn; &middot; sikerliche do&thorn; vuele,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>synge&thorn;</I>] synne&thorn; IME; synege&thorn; PG; <I>but see</I> ll. 23, 25.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dowel and do-vuele &middot; may nat dwelle to-gederes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dwelle</I>] stonde G.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ergo</I>, he ys nat al-way &middot; at hom among &yogh;ow Freres;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ys</I>] nys G. <I>at&mdash;among</I>] a-tom wi&thorn; M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="29">He is som while elles-wher &middot; to wisse &thorn;e puple."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] his P. <I>som while</I>] vm|while G; vm-whilus F; vmbiwhile M; o&thorn;er-while I.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ich shal sei &thorn;e, my sone," &middot; seide &thorn;e frere &thorn;enne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sone</I>] self M.</NOTE></L>
<L>"How seuene sithes &thorn;e sadde man &middot; synge&thorn; on &thorn;e day.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>synge&thorn;</I>] synne&thorn; IMFE; singe&thorn; G. <I>on</I>] in G.</NOTE></L>
<L N="32">By a forbusene," qua&thorn; &thorn;e frere &middot; "ich shal &thorn;e faire shewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>forbusene</I>] forbisne I; forbisme (<I>sic</I>) G; for-bisen M; forbisen F. <I>qua&thorn;</I>] seide M. <I>&thorn;e</I> (2)] &yogh;ow G.</NOTE></L>
<L>Let brynge a man in a bot &middot; in-myddes a brode water;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in myddes</I>] amyddes I; amyd F; in G.</NOTE></L>
<L>The wynde and &thorn;e water &middot; and waggynge of &thorn;e bote<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>waggynge</I>] &thorn;e waggyng MFG. <I>bote</I>] vessel F.</NOTE></L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;e man meny tyme &middot; to stomble, yf he stande;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tyme</I>] tymes I; a tyme F. <I>stomble</I>] tombly G.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">Stonde he neuere so styfliche &middot; &thorn;orgh sterynge of &thorn;e bote<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Stonde</I>] For stonde I. <I>styfliche</I>] stillich E. <I>sterynge</I>] streng&thorn;e EM. <I>bote</I>] barge F.</NOTE></L>
<L>He bende&thorn; and bowe&thorn; &middot; &thorn;e body is vnstable,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I>] is so I; his P.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001019.tif" N="181, C-text"></L>
<L>Ac &yogh;ut he is saf and sounde; &middot; so fareth hit by &thorn;e ryght|ful.<MILESTONE UNIT="B page" N="127"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>saf</I>] sad M. <I>so</I>] and so I. <I>hit</I>] G <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;auh he falle, he falle&thorn; nat &middot; bote as ho fulle in a bote,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>falle</I>] faile MF. <I>as</I>] I <I>om. ho</I>] who so I; hoso F; he MG.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ay is saf and sounde &middot; &thorn;at sitte&thorn; with-ynne &thorn;e borde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>saf</I>] sad M. <I>&thorn;at</I>] and I. <I>sitte&thorn;</I>] sitte I; sit M.</NOTE></L>
<L N="41">So hit fare&thorn;," qua&thorn; &thorn;e frere &middot; "by ryghtful mannes fallynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by</I>] by &thorn;e I.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;awe he &thorn;orgh fondinge falle &middot; he falle&thorn; nat out of charite;<NOTE PLACE="foot">40&mdash;42. G <I>omits.</I></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;orgh</I>] &thorn;orghe P. <I>fondinge</I>] fondynges I.</NOTE></L>
<L>So dedliche synne do&thorn; he nat &middot; for dowel hym helpe&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>] I <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="44">The water ys likned to &thorn;e worlde &middot; &thorn;at wanye&thorn; and wexe&thorn;;<MILESTONE UNIT="A page" N="105"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>likned</I> IF] liknyd G; likened EM; liknede P. <I>wanye&thorn;&mdash;wexe&thorn;</I>] wexe&thorn; and wanye&thorn; M.</NOTE></L>
<L>The godes of [&thorn;is] grounde aren lyke &middot; to &thorn;e grete wawes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>] on M. [<I>&thorn;is</I> IMFEG] &thorn;e P. <I>aren</I>] ben E. <I>to</I>] I <I>om. &thorn;e</I>] MEFG <I>om.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>[&THORN;at] as wyndes and wederes &middot; walwen a-boute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>&THORN;at</I> I] For F; PEGM <I>om.; cf.</I> B-text. <I>walwen</I>] wawen E; wa|we&thorn; M; wawen &thorn;ei F.</NOTE></L>
