<TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Richard the redeles.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="prologue">

<PB REF="00001307.tif" N="469, C-text">
<HEAD>[Prologus.]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>In these foot-notes, the reader will find the rejected readings of the MS., corrections in which have been but very sparingly made.</I></P><P><I>Besides these, all the more impor|tant parallel passages from the</I> "Vision" <I>are cited, with proper references. Thus, at l.</I> 12, <I>a quota|tion is given from l.</I> 261 <I>of</I> Passus iv. <I>of the</I> C-text, <I>as denoted by</I> C. 4. 261. <I>The</I> C-text <I>has been chosen for refer|ence</I> (<I>where possible</I>) <I>because the reader has it in his hand, and has only to turn back till he finds the passage cited.</I></P></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as I passid in my preiere &middot; &thorn;er prestis were at messe,<MILESTONE N="107b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In a blessid borugh &middot; &thorn;at bristow is named,</L>
<L>In a temple of &thorn;e trinite &middot; &thorn;e toune euen amyddis,</L>
<L N="4">That cristis chirche is cleped &middot; amonge &thorn;e comune peple,</L>
<L>Sodeynly &thorn;er sourdid &middot; selcou&thorn;e &thorn;ingis,</L>
<L>A grett wondir to wyse men &middot; as it well my&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And dowtes ffor to deme &middot; ffor drede comynge after.</L>
<L N="8">So sore were &thorn;e sawis &middot; of bothe two sidis,</L>
<L>Of Richard &thorn;at Regned &middot; so Riche and so noble,</L>
<L>That whyle he werrid be west &middot; on &thorn;e wilde yrisshe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>whyle;</I> MS. wyle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Henrri was entrid &middot; on the est half,</L>
<L N="12">Whom all &thorn;e londe loued &middot; in leng&thorn;e and in brede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> He had be lord of &thorn;at <I>londe &middot; in lengthe and in brede;</I> C. 4. 261.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ros with him rapely &middot; to ri&yogh;tyn his wronge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Two <I>rysen rapliche</I> &middot; and rounede to-geders; C. 7. 383. For <I>ros,</I> the MS. has <I>rosse.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>ffor he shullde hem serue &middot; of &thorn;e same after.
<PB REF="00001308.tif" N="470, C-text"></L>
<L>Thus tales me troblid &middot; ffor &thorn;ey trewe were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>were;</I> MS. <I>where.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="16">And amarride my mynde rith moche &middot; and my wittis eke:</L>
<L>ffor it passid my parceit &middot; and my preifis also,</L>
<L>How so wondirffull werkis &middot; wolde haue an ende.</L>
<L>But in sothe whan &thorn;ey sembled &middot; some dede repente,</L>
<L N="20">As knowyn is in cumpas &middot; of Cristen londis,</L>
<L>That rewthe was, if reson &middot; ne had reffourmed</L>
<L>The myssecheff &amp; &thorn;e mysserule &middot; &thorn;at men &thorn;o in endurid.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>endurid;</I> no doubt a corruption of <I>durede,</I> the true old form.</NOTE></L>
<L>I had pete of his passion &middot; &thorn;at prince was of Walis,</L>
<L>And eke oure crouned kynge &middot; till crist woll no lenger;</L>
<L N="25">And as a lord to his liage &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; I lite hade,</L>
<L>All myn hoole herte was his &middot; while he in helthe regnid.</L>
<L>And ffor I wuste not witterly &middot; what shulde ffall,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wuste;</I> MS. <I>wost;</I> but see Pass. i. ll. 49 and 64, below.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whedir god wolde &yogh;eue him grace &middot; sone to amende,</L>
<L N="29">To be oure gioure a&yogh;eyn &middot; or graunte it ano&thorn;er,</L>
<L>This made me to muse &middot; many tyme and ofte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>Cf. Musynge</I> on &thorn;is meteles &middot; a myle-wey ich &yogh;eode.</P><P>And <I>meny tymes</I> this me|teles &middot; <I>made me</I> to studie; C. 10. 296.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>For to written him a writte &middot; to wissen him better,</L>
<L N="32">And to meuve him of mysserewle &middot; his mynde to reffresshe,</L>
<L>ffor to preise &thorn;e prynce &middot; &thorn;at paradise made,</L>
<L>To ffullfill him with ffeith &middot; and ffortune aboue,</L>
<L>And not to grucchen a grott &middot; a&yogh;eine godis sonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> On <I>god,</I> whenne me greued ouht &middot; and <I>grucched of hus sonde;</I> C. 7. 111.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">But mekely to suffre &middot; what so him sente were.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if him list to loke &middot; a leef o&thorn;er tweyne,<MILESTONE N="108" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> First I lerned to lye &middot; <I>a leef other tweyne;</I> B. 5. 203.</NOTE></L>
<L>That made is to mende him &middot; of his myssededis,</L>
<L>And to kepe him in confforte &middot; in crist and nou&yogh;t ellis,
<PB REF="00001309.tif" N="471, C-text"></L>
<L N="40">I wolde be gladde &thorn;at his gost &middot; my&yogh;te glade be my wordis,</L>
<L>And grame if it greued him &middot; be god &thorn;at me bou&yogh;te!</L>
<L>Ther nys no gouernour on &thorn;e grounde &middot; ne sholde gye him &thorn;e better&mdash;</L>
<L>And euery Cristen kyng &middot; &thorn;at ony [croune] bereth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>croune;</I> MS. <I>grounde,</I> an ob|vious error, copied from l. 42.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">So he were lerned on &thorn;e langage &middot; my lyff durst I wedde&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Ich dorst haue <I>leid my lyue</I> &middot; and no lasse <I>wedde;</I> C. 4. 260.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if he waite well &thorn;e wordis, and so werche &thorn;erafter;</L>
<L>ffor all is tresour of &thorn;e trinite &middot; &thorn;at turneth men to gode.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Ther treuthe is, &thorn;e trone &middot; &thorn;at <I>trinite</I> ynne sitte&thorn; . . Than treuthe &amp; trewe loue &middot; ys no <I>tresour</I> bettere; C. 2. 134&mdash;136.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as my body &amp; my beste &middot; ou[&yogh;]te to be my liegis,</L>
<L N="48">So rithffully be reson &middot; my rede shulde also,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf. &mdash;bi Reson,</I> And <I>Rihtful|iche,</I> &amp;c.; A. 1. 92, 93; <I>also,</I> For <I>ryhtfulliche reson;</I> C. 2. 50.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor to conceill, and I couthe &middot; my kyng and &thorn;e lordis;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>couthe;</I> MS. <I>cou&yogh;the.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er-ffor I ffondyd &middot; with all my ffyue wyttis<NOTE PLACE="foot">For <I>ffondyd,</I> MS. had <I>ffordyd,</I> but it has been altered to <I>ffondyd.</I> Mr Wright prints <I>ffordyd,</I> but see B. 15. 327; and cf. C. 2. 15.</NOTE></L>
<L>To traueile on &thorn;is tretis &middot; to teche men &thorn;er-after</L>
<L N="52">To be war of wylffulnesse &middot; lest wondris arise.</L>
<L>And if it happe to &yogh;oure honde &middot; beholde &thorn;e book onys,</L>
<L>And redeth on him redely &middot; rewis an hundrid,</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e sauere sum dell &middot; se it fforth ouere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &yogh;ut <I>sauere&thorn;</I> me nat &thorn;i sawe; C. 11. 107.</NOTE></L>
<L N="56">ffor reson is no repreff &middot; be the rode of chester!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf. bi &thorn;e Rode of chestre;</I> B. 5. 467.</NOTE></L>
<L>And if &yogh;e ffynde ffables &middot; or ffoly &thorn;er amonge,</L>
<L>Or ony ffantasie yffeyned &middot; &thorn;at no ffrute is in,</L>
<L>Lete &yogh;oure conceill corette it &middot; and clerkis to-gedyr,</L>
<L N="60">And amende &thorn;at ys amysse &middot; and make it more better:</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it it is secrette &middot; and so it shall lenger,
<PB REF="00001310.tif" N="472, C-text"></L>
<L>Tyll wyser wittis &middot; han waytid it ouere,</L>
<L>That it be lore laweffull &middot; and lusty to here.</L>
<L N="64">ffor witterly, my will is &middot; &thorn;at it well liked</L>
<L>&YOGH;ou and all &yogh;ouris &middot; and yonge men leueste,</L>
<L>To be-nyme hem her noyes &middot; &thorn;at neweth hem ofte.</L>
<L N="67">ffor and &thorn;ey mvse &thorn;eron &middot; to &thorn;e myddwardis,</L>
<L>They shall [fynde] ffele ffawtis &middot; ffoure score and odde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The word <I>fynde</I> has obviously been omitted here; it is not in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>That yough[th]e weneth alwey &middot; &thorn;at it be witte euere.</L>
<L>And thou&yogh; &thorn;at elde opyn it &middot; o&thorn;er-while amonge,</L>
<L>And poure on it preuyly &middot; and preue it well after,</L>
<L N="72">And constrewe ich clause &middot; with &thorn;e culorum,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &thorn;e <I>culorum</I> of &thorn;is <I>clause</I>; A. 3. 264; C. 12. 248.</NOTE></L>
<L>It shulde not apeire hem a peere &middot; a prynce &thorn;ou&yogh; he were,</L>
<L>Ne harme no&thorn;er hurte &middot; &thorn;e hyghest of &thorn;e rewme,</L>
<L>But to holde him in hele &middot; and helpe all his ffrendis.<MILESTONE N="108b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And if ony word write be &middot; &thorn;at wrothe make myghte</L>
<L N="77">My souereyne, &thorn;at suget &middot; I shulde to be,</L>
<L>I put me in his power &middot; and preie him, of grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>Cf.</I> Thenne knelede ich on my knees and criede hure <I>of grace,</I></P><P>And <I>preide hure</I> pytously; C. 2. 76, 77.</P></NOTE></L>
<L>To take &thorn;e entent of my trou&thorn;e &middot; &thorn;at thou&yogh;te non ylle.</L>
<L N="80">ffor to wrath no wyght &middot; be my wyll neuere,</L>
<L>As my soule be saff &middot; ffrom synne at myn ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e story is of non estate &middot; &thorn;at stryuen with her lustus,</L>
<L>But &thorn;o &thorn;at ffolwyn her fflessh &middot; and here ffrelle &thorn;ou&yogh;tis;</L>
<L N="84">So if my conceyll be clere &middot; I can saie no more,</L>
<L>But ho be greued in his gost &middot; gouerne him better,</L>
<L>And blame not &thorn;e berne &middot; &thorn;at the book made,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e wickyd will &middot; and &thorn;e werkis after.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00001311.tif" N="473, C-text">
<HEAD>[Passus Primus.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pass. i. 4. <I>y-lyfte;</I> so in MS. Mr Wright prints <I>y-lyste.</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now, Richard &thorn;e redeles &middot; reweth on &yogh;ou self,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lawelesse leddyn &yogh;oure lyf &middot; and &yogh;oure peple o&thorn;e;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;oru &thorn;e wyles and wronge &middot; and wast in &yogh;oure tyme,</L>
<L N="4">&YOGH;e were lyghtlich y-lyfte &middot; ffrom &thorn;at &yogh;ou leef &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And ffrom &yogh;oure willffull werkis &middot; &yogh;oure will was chaungid,</L>
<L>And rafte was &yogh;oure riott &middot; and rest, ffor &yogh;oure daiez</L>
<L>Weren wikkid &thorn;oru &yogh;oure cursid counceill &middot; &yogh;oure karis weren newed,</L>
<L N="8">And coueitise hath crasid &middot; &yogh;oure croune ffor euere!<Q><I>Radix omnium malorum cupiditas.</I></Q></L>
<L>Of alegeaunce now lerneth &middot; a lesson o&thorn;er tweyne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Furst I <I>leornede</I> to ly&yogh;e &middot; <I>a lessun or tweyne;</I> A. 5. 117.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher-by it standith &middot; and stablithe moste&mdash;</L>
<L>By drede, or be dyntis &middot; or domes vntrewe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>drede;</I> MS. dride, <I>but altered to</I> drede.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">Or by creaunce of coyne &middot; ffor castes of gile,</L>
<L>By pillynge of &yogh;oure peple &middot; &yogh;oure prynces to plese;</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &yogh;oure wylle were wrou&yogh;te &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; wisdom it nolde;&mdash;</L>
<L>Or be tallage of &yogh;oure townes &middot; without ony werre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>townes;</I> MS. towunes <I>or</I> townnes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="16">By rewthles routus &middot; &thorn;at ryffled euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>routus;</I> MS. routus, <I>altered to</I> routes, <I>unnecessarily.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>By preysinge of polaxis &middot; &thorn;at no pete hadde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Or Poule &thorn;e apostle &middot; <I>&thorn;at no pitec hadde;</I> B. 10. 424; C. 12. 268.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or be dette ffor &thorn;i dees &middot; deme as &thorn;ou ffyndist;
<PB REF="00001312.tif" N="474, C-text"></L>
<L>Or be ledinge of lawe &middot; with loue well ytemprid.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And <I>lede&thorn; &thorn;e lawe</I> as hure lust &middot; and <I>louedayes</I> make&thorn;; C. 4. 196.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Though &thorn;is be derklich endited &middot; ffor a dull nolle,</L>
<L N="21">Miche nede is it not &middot; to mwse &thorn;er-on,</L>
<L>ffor as mad as I am &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; I litill kunne,</L>
<L>I cowde it discryue &middot; in a ffewe wordys;<MILESTONE N="109" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24">ffor legiance without loue &middot; litill &thorn;inge availith.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Lawe <I>with-outen loue</I> &middot; leye &thorn;ere a bene! B. 11. 165.</NOTE></L>
<L>But graceles gostis &middot; gylours of hem-self,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gostis;</I> so in MS.; printed <I>gestis</I> by Mr Wright.</NOTE></L>
<L>That neuere had harnesse &middot; ne hayle schouris,</L>
<L>But walwed in her willis &middot; ffor-weyned in here youthe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And lete no wynnynge <I>for|wene</I> hem &middot; <I>&thorn;e while &thorn;ei ben &yogh;onge;</I> C. 6. 138.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ey sawe no manere si&yogh;th &middot; saff solas and ese,</L>
<L>And cowde no mysse amende &middot; whan mysscheff was vp,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &thorn;i <I>myschief is vppe;</I> B. 4. 72.</NOTE></L>
<L>But sorwed ffor her lustus &middot; of lordsch[i]pe &thorn;ey hadde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lustus;</I> altered to <I>lustes</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And neuere ffor her trespas &middot; oo tere wolde &thorn;ey lete!</L>
<L N="32">&YOGH;e come to &yogh;oure kyngdom &middot; er &yogh;e &yogh;oure-self knewe,</L>
<L>Crouned with a croune &middot; &thorn;at kyng vnder heuene</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;te not a better &middot; haue bou&yogh;te, as I trowe;</L>
<L>So ffull was it ffilled &middot; with vertuous stones,</L>
<L N="36">With perlis of pris &middot; to punnysshe &thorn;e wrongis,</L>
<L>With rubies rede &middot; &thorn;e ri&yogh;th for to deme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">33&mdash;37. <I>Cf.</I> And <I>coroned with a corone</I> &middot; &thorn;e <I>kynge hath no betere;</I> . . . And &thorn;er-on <I>rede rubies</I> &middot; and o&thorn;er <I>riche stones;</I> C. 3. 11, 13.</NOTE></L>
<L>With gemmes and Iuellis &middot; Ioyned to-gedir,</L>
<L>And pees amonge &thorn;e peple &middot; ffor peyne of &thorn;i lawis.</L>
<L>It was ffull goodeliche ygraue &middot; with gold al aboute;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te,</I> both here and in ii. 2, 15, and 102. <I>Cf. gold al a-boute;</I> C. 3. 158.</NOTE></L>
<L N="41">The braunchis aboue &middot; boren grett charge;</L>
<L>With diamauntis derne &middot; y-doutid of all<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And <I>diamantz</I> of derrest pris &middot; and double manere <I>safferes;</I> B. 2. 13; <I>see the whole passage. y|doutid;</I> written <I>y-douutid</I> in MS.; so in l. 46 the MS. has <I>Y-pouudride.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>That wrou[&yogh;]te ony wrake &middot; within or withoute;
<PB REF="00001313.tif" N="475, C-text"></L>
<L N="44">With lewte and loue &middot; yloke to &thorn;i peeris,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Ac <I>loue</I> and louhnesse &middot; and <I>leaute</I> to-gederes; C. 4. 447.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sapheris swete &middot; &thorn;at sou&yogh;te all wrongis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And <I>diamantz</I> of derrest pris &middot; and double manere <I>safferes;</I> B. 2. 13; <I>see the whole passage. y|doutid;</I> written <I>y-douutid</I> in MS.; so in l. 46 the MS. has <I>Y-pouudride.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ypoudride wyth pete &middot; &thorn;er it be ou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note to l. 42, above.</NOTE></L>
<L>And traylid with trou&thorn;e &middot; and treste al aboute;</L>
<L N="48">ffor ony cristen kynge &middot; a croune well ymakyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But where &thorn;is croune bicome &middot; a clerk were &thorn;at wuste;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> I <I>ne wot where &thorn;ei bicome;</I> B. 5. 651.</NOTE></L>
<L>But so as I can &middot; declare it I thenke,</L>
<L>And nempne no name; &middot; but &thorn;o &thorn;at nest were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nest;</I> MS. <I>nest</I> or <I>neft.</I> Mr Wright prints <I>neft,</I> but leaves it un|explained, there being no such word; <I>nest</I> is <I>nighest.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="52">ffull preuyly &thorn;ey pluckud &middot; &thorn;y power awey,</L>
<L>And reden with realte &middot; &yogh;oure rewme &thorn;oru-oute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>reden;</I> so in MS., though afterwards altered to <I>ryden.</I> Yet <I>reden</I> may stand, as it occurs in the Lansdowne MS. of Chaucer; Prol. l. 825. See also C. 2. 91.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as tyrauntis, of tiliers &middot; token what hem liste,</L>
<L N="55">And paide hem on her pannes &middot; whan her penyes lacked.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> the account of how "Pees" came by his "<I>panne</I> blody;" C. 5. 74.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor non of &yogh;oure peple &middot; durste pleyne of here wrongis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> For <I>pore men der nat pleyne</I> &middot; ne here pleinte shewe; C. 4. 214; <I>see the whole passage.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>ffor drede of &yogh;oure dukys &middot; &amp; of here double harmes.</L>
<L>Men my&yogh;tten as well haue huntyd &middot; an hare with a tabre,<MILESTONE N="109b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As aske ony mendis &middot; ffor &thorn;at &thorn;ei mysdede,</L>
<L N="60">Or of ony of her men &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; men wulde plete,</L>
<L>ffor all was ffelawis and ffelawschepe &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e with fferde,</L>
<L>And no soule persone &middot; to punnyshe &thorn;e wrongis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at maddid &thorn;i men &middot; as &thorn;ei nede muste.</L>
<L N="64">ffor wo, &thorn;ey ne wuste &middot; to whom ffor to pleyne.</L>
<L>ffor, as it is said &middot; by elderne dawis,</L>
<L>'&THORN;er gromes and the goodmen &middot; beth all eliche grette,</L>
<L>Woll wo beth &thorn;e wones &middot; and all &thorn;at woneth &thorn;er-in!'
<PB REF="00001314.tif" N="476, C-text"></L>
<L N="68">&THORN;ey ladde &yogh;ou with loue &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;oure lawe dradde,</L>
<L>To deme &yogh;oure dukys myssdedis &middot; so derne &thorn;ei were.</L>
<L>Thus was &yogh;oure croune crasid &middot; till he was cast newe,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru partinge of &yogh;oure powere &middot; to &yogh;oure paragals.</L>
<L N="72">Thus lacchide &thorn;ey with laughinge &middot; and lourid longe after,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &THORN;ere was <I>laughyng</I> and <I>louryng;</I> B. 5. 344.</NOTE></L>
<L>But ffrist sawe they it not &middot; ne youre-self no&thorn;er;</L>
<L>ffor all was wisliche ywrou&yogh;te &middot; as &yogh;oure witte demed,</L>
<L N="75">And no ffautis y-ffounde &middot; till ffortune aperid.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fautis;</I> MS. <I>fauutis.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>But had &yogh;oure croune be kepte &middot; &thorn;at comons it wiste,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nadde morder ne mysscheff &middot; be amonge &thorn;e grette.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nadde;</I> glossed in the MS. by <I>had nat.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Thus &yogh;oure cautell to the comoune &middot; hath combred &yogh;ou all,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cautell;</I> glossed in the MS. by <I>crafte.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>That, but if god helpe &middot; &yogh;oure heruest is ynne.</L>
<L N="80">Wyteth it not &yogh;oure counceill &middot; but wyteth it more &yogh;oure-self,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wyteth;</I> misspelt <I>Wytteth</I> (alt. to <I>Wyteth</I>) the first time, and <I>wyteh</I> the second time, in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>The ffortune &thorn;at ffallyn is &middot; to ffeitheles peple;</L>
<L>And wayte well my wordis &middot; and wrappe hem to|gedir,</L>
<L>And constrwe [&thorn;oru] clergie &middot; &thorn;e clause in &thorn;in herte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The word <I>&thorn;oru</I> (= through) must be supplied; <I>cf. Clerkus</I> &thorn;at were confessours &middot; couplede hem to|gederes <I>To construe this clause;</I> C. 5. 146, 147.</NOTE></L>
<L N="84">Of maters &thorn;at I thenke &middot; to meve ffor the best<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> I dorste <I>meue</I> no <I>matere;</I> C. 11. 118.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor kyngis and kayseris &middot; comynge here-after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Kayseris;</I> badly spelt <I>Kayse|ceris</I> in the MS., with the gloss <I>lordes, rulers;</I> cf. <I>Kynges</I> and knyghtes &middot; <I>caysers</I> and popes; C. 23. 101.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whane &yogh;e were sette in &yogh;oure se &middot; as a sir aughte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sir;</I> glossed in the MS. by <I>lorde.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Ther Carpinge comynliche &middot; of conceill arisith,</L>
<L N="88">The cheuyteyns cheef &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e chesse euere,</L>
<L>Weren all to yonge of &yogh;eris &middot; to yeme swyche a rewme;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yeme;</I> glossed in the MS. by <I>guyde or rule.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00001315.tif" N="477, C-text"></L>
<L>O&thorn;er hobbis &yogh;e hadden &middot; of hurlewaynis kynne,</L>
<L>Reffusynge the reule &middot; of realles kynde.<MILESTONE N="110" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="92">And whane &yogh;oure counceill I-knewe &middot; &yogh;e come so at ones,</L>
<L>ffor to leue on her lore &middot; and be led be hem,</L>
<L>ffor drede &thorn;at they had &middot; of demynge &thorn;er-after,</L>
<L>And ffor curinge of hem-self &middot; cried on &yogh;ou euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>curinge;</I> MS. somewhat indis|tinct. Mr. Wright prints <I>caringe.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="96">ffor to hente hele &middot; of her owen greues,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an ffor wurschepe &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ey to &yogh;ou owed,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey made &yogh;ou to leue &middot; &thorn;at regne &yogh;e ne my&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>my&yogh;te;</I> MS. <I>myste.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Withoute busshinge adoune &middot; of all &yogh;oure best ffrendis,</L>
<L N="100">Be a ffals colour &middot; her caris to wayve,</L>
<L>And to holde hem in hele &middot; if it happe my&yogh;te.</L>
<L>ffor trosti&thorn; rith treuly &middot; and in no tale better,</L>
<L N="103">All &thorn;at &thorn;ey moued &middot; or mynged in &thorn;at mater,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at;</I> Mr. Wright prints <I>the.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Was to be sure of hem-self &middot; and siris to ben y-callid;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at was all her werchinge &middot; in worde and in dede.</L>
<L>But had &yogh;e do duly &middot; and as a duke oughte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ffrist &thorn;at &yogh;ou fformed &middot; to &thorn;at ffals dede,</L>
<L N="108">He shulde have hadde hongynge &middot; on hie on &thorn;e fforckis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &yogh;oure brother y-born &middot; had be &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>Than wolde o&thorn;er boynardis &middot; haue ben abasshyd,</L>
<L>To haue meved &yogh;ou to ony maters &middot; &thorn;at myss[c]heff had ben ynne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maters;</I> printed <I>mals</I> by Mr Wright, owing to the indistinctness of the mark of contraction; but see l. 84, above; and also l. 103.</NOTE></L>
<L N="112">But ffor &yogh;e cleued to knavis &middot; In &thorn;is cas I avowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at boldid &thorn;i burnes &middot; to belde vppon sorowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>burnes;</I> glossed by <I>barons</I> in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And stirid &yogh;ou stouttely &middot; till &yogh;e stombled all.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00001316.tif" N="478, C-text">
<HEAD>Passus secundus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pass. ii. 2. <I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te;</I> cf. note above to i. 40. So also in l. 15.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But moche now me merueilith &middot; and well may I in sothe,</L>
<L>Of &yogh;oure large leuerey &middot; to leodis aboute,</L>
<L>That &yogh;e so goodliche &yogh;af &middot; but if gile letted,</L>
<L N="4">As hertis y-heedyd &middot; and hornyd of kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As;</I> misprinted <I>And</I> by Mr Wright.</NOTE></L>
<L>So ryff as &thorn;ey ronne &middot; &yogh;oure rewme &thorn;oru-oute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ronne;</I> printed <I>roune</I> by Mr Wright.</NOTE></L>
<L>That non at &yogh;oure nede &middot; &yogh;oure name wolde nempne</L>
<L>In ffersnesse ne in ffoltheed &middot; but ffaste ffle away-ward,</L>
<L N="8">And some stode astonyed &middot; and stared ffor drede,</L>
<L>ffor eye of the Egle &middot; &thorn;at oure helpe brou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brou&yogh;te;</I> written <I>brouute</I> in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And also in sothe &middot; &thorn;e seson was paste</L>
<L>ffor hertis y-heedid &middot; so hy and so noble</L>
<L N="12">To make ony myrthe &middot; ffor mowtynge &thorn;at nyghed.</L>
<L>That bawtid &yogh;oure bestis &middot; of here bolde chere;<MILESTONE N="110b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey seuerid and sondrid &middot; ffor somere hem ffaylid,</L>
<L>And fflowen in-to fforest &middot; and ffeldis aboute,</L>
<L N="16">All &thorn;e hoole herde &middot; &thorn;at helde so to-gedir;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I>- in <I>to-gedir</I> is supplied in the MS. in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &yogh;et &thorn;ey had hornes &middot; half a &yogh;ere after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> is supplied in the MS. in a later hand; cf. "half a &yogh;ere" in C. 3. 238.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now liste me to lerne &middot; ho me lere coude,</L>
<L>What kynnes conceyll &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng had,</L>
<L N="20">Or meued him most &middot; to merke his liegis,</L>
<L>Or serue hem with signes &middot; &thorn;at swarmed so thikke
<PB REF="00001317.tif" N="479, C-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;oru-oute his lond &middot; in leng&thorn;e and in brede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Prol. l. 12.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ho so had hobblid &middot; &thorn;oru holtes and tounes,</L>
<L N="24">Or y-passid &thorn;e patthis &middot; &thorn;er the prynce dwellyd,</L>
<L>Of hertis or hyndis &middot; on hassellis brestis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Of;</I> MS. <I>Or</I> (wrongly).</NOTE></L>
<L>Or some lordis leuere &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe stried,</L>
<L N="27">He shulde haue y-mette &middot; mo &thorn;an y-nowe.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ey acombrede &thorn;e contre &middot; and many curse seruid,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seruid;</I> glossed <I>deserved</I> in the MS.; correctly.</NOTE></L>
<L>And carped to &thorn;e comounes &middot; with &thorn;e kyngys mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Or with &thorn;e lordis &middot; &thorn;er &thorn;ey be-lefte were,</L>
<L>That no renke shulde rise &middot; reson to schewe.</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;ey plucked the plomayle &middot; ffrom &thorn;e pore skynnes,</L>
<L>And schewed her signes &middot; ffor men shulde drede</L>
<L>To axe ony mendis &middot; ffor her mys-dedis.</L>
<L>Thus leuerez ouere-loked &middot; &yogh;oure liegis ichone;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ichone;</I> MS. <I>ichonne.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="36">ffor &thorn;o &thorn;at had hertis &middot; on hie on her brestis</L>
<L>ffor the more partie &middot; I may well avowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf. ich may it wel avowe;</I> C. 4. 315.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey bare hem the bolder &middot; ffor her gay broches,</L>
<L>And busshid with her brestis &middot; and bare adoune the pouere,</L>
<L N="40">Lieges &thorn;at loued &yogh;ou &thorn;e lesse &middot; ffor her yuell dedis.</L>
<L>So, trouthe to telle &middot; as toune men said,</L>
<L>ffor on &thorn;at &yogh;e merkyd &middot; &yogh;e myssed ten schore</L>
<L>Of homeliche hertis &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e harme hente.</L>
<L N="44">Thane was it ffoly &middot; in ffeith, as me thynketh,</L>
<L>To sette siluer in signes &middot; &thorn;at of nou&yogh;t serued.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Bere no <I>suluer</I> ouer see &middot; &thorn;at kynges <I>sygne</I> shewe&thorn;; C. 5. 126.</NOTE></L>
<L>I not what &yogh;ou eylid &middot; but if it ese were;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Ich <I>wot</I> wel, quath hunger &middot; <I>what</I> syknesse <I>&yogh;ow aile&thorn;;</I> C. 9. 271.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor ffrist at &yogh;oure anoyntynge &middot; alle were &yogh;oure owene,</L>
<L N="48">Bothe hertis and hyndis &middot; and helde of non o&thorn;er;<MILESTONE N="111" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No lede of &yogh;oure lond &middot; but as a liege aughte,</L>
<L>Tyl &yogh;e, of &yogh;oure dulnesse &middot; deseueraunce made,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Tyl;</I> MS. <I>Ty,</I> altered to <I>Tyl.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00001318.tif" N="480, C-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;oru &yogh;oure side signes &middot; &thorn;at shente all &thorn;e browet,</L>
<L N="52">And cast adoun &thorn;e crokk &middot; &thorn;e Colys amyd.<Q><I>Omne regnum in se diuisum desolabitur; luce xj</I><SUP>o</SUP>. <I>c</I><SUP>o</SUP>.</Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &THORN;at cast for to kele a <I>crokke</I> &middot; and saue &thorn;e fatte aboue; C. 20. 280.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it am I lewde &middot; and litill good schewe,</L>
<L>To coueyte knowliche &middot; of kyngis wittis,</L>
<L>Or wilne to witte &middot; how was &thorn;e mevynge,</L>
<L N="56">That [ladde] &yogh;ou to lykynge &middot; &yogh;oure liegis to merke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Here <I>ladde</I> seems required.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at loued &yogh;ou full lelly &middot; or leuerez beganne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>begynne,</I> altered to <I>beganne.</I> Cf. And to <I>loue</I> me <I>lelly;</I> B. 1. 78.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as redy to ride &middot; or renne at &yogh;oure heste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &yogh;emen &middot; to <I>rennen</I> and to <I>ryde;</I> C. 4. 271.</NOTE></L>
<L>As wyghte myghte wilne &middot; wonnynge vppon erthe,</L>
<L N="60">Tyll leuerez hem lette &middot; and lordyns wrongis,</L>
<L>As &yogh;oure-self ffonde well &middot; whane ffortune &yogh;ou ffolwyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffolwyd;</I> the word <I>ffayled</I> is written above, and is perhaps a better reading.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor whan &yogh;e list to lene &middot; to &yogh;oure owen lymmes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey were so ffeble and ffeynte &middot; ffor ffaute of &yogh;oure lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>faute;</I> spelt <I>fau&yogh;te</I> in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">And so ffeble and wayke &middot; wexe in &thorn;e hammes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey had no myghte &middot; to amende &yogh;oure greues,</L>
<L>Ne to bere byrthen &middot; &yogh;oure banere to helpe.</L>
<L>But it longith to no liegeman &middot; his lord to anoye,</L>
<L N="68">No&thorn;er in werk ne in word &middot; but if his witt ffayle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> As <I>in workes</I> and <I>in wordes;</I> C. 3. 94.</NOTE></L>
<L>"No, redely," quod reson &middot; "&thorn;at reule I alowe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> For&thorn;y, <I>reson, redelyche;</I> C. 5. 184.</NOTE></L>
<L>Displese not &thorn;i demer &middot; in dede ne in wordis,</L>
<L>But if &thorn;e liste ffor to lede &middot; &thorn;i lyf in dissese.</L>
<L N="72">But &yogh;if god haue grauntyd &thorn;e &middot; grace ffor to knowe</L>
<L>Ony manere mysscheff &middot; &thorn;at my&yogh;tte be amendyd,</L>
<L>Schewe &thorn;at to &thorn;i souereyne &middot; to schelde him ffrom harmes;</L>
<L>ffor, and he be blessid &middot; &thorn;e better &thorn;e be-tydyth</L>
<L N="76">In tyme ffor to telle him &middot; ffor &thorn;i trewe herte."
<PB REF="00001319.tif" N="481, C-text"></L>
<L>Now, ffor to telle trouthe &middot; &thorn;us &thorn;an me thynketh,</L>
<L>That no manere meyntenour &middot; shulde merkis bere,</L>
<L>Ne haue lordis leuere &middot; &thorn;e lawe to apeire,</L>
<L N="80">Nei&thorn;er bragger ne boster &middot; ffor no bremme wordis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.&mdash;braggynge &middot; abosted,</I> &amp;c.; C. 9. 152.</NOTE></L>
<L>But ho so had kunnynge &middot; and conscience bothe,</L>
<L>To stonde vnstombled &middot; and stronge in his wittis,<MILESTONE N="111b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> to <I>stomble,</I> yf he <I>stande;</I> C. 11. 35.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lele in his leuynge &middot; leuyd be his owen,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at no manere mede &middot; shulde make him wrye,</L>
<L>ffor to trien a trouthe &middot; be-twynne two sidis,</L>
<L>And lette ffor no lordschep &middot; &thorn;e lawe to susteyne,</L>
<L>Whane &thorn;e pore pleyned &middot; that put were to wrongis.</L>
<L N="88">And I were of conceill &middot; by crist &thorn;at me bou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>He shuld haue a signe &middot; and sum-what be &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>ffor to kepe his contre &middot; in quiete and in reste.</L>
<L>This were a good grounde &middot; so me god helpe!</L>
<L N="92">And a trewe tente &middot; to take and to &yogh;eue,</L>
<L>And ony lord of this londe &middot; &thorn;at leuerez vsith.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And;</I> read <I>To</I> or <I>For?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>But how the gayes han y-gon &middot; god wotte &thorn;e sothe<NOTE PLACE="foot">A <I>d</I> is written over <I>g</I> in <I>gayes,</I> as if to alter it to <I>dayes;</I> but the alliteration requires <I>gayes;</I> see Note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amonge my&yogh;tfull men &middot; alle these many &yogh;eris;</L>
<L N="96">And, whedir &thorn;e grounde of &yogh;ifte &middot; were good o&thorn;er ille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ifte;</I> printed <I>&yogh;iste</I> by Mr Wright.</NOTE></L>
<L>Trouthe ha&thorn;e determyned &middot; &thorn;e tente to &thorn;e ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Til <I>trew&thorn;e hadde ytermenyd</I> &middot; here trespas <I>to &thorn;e ende;</I> C. 2. 93.</NOTE></L>
<L>And reson hath rehersid &middot; &thorn;e resceyte of all.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it, I trowe, &yogh;oure entente &middot; at &thorn;e ffrist tyme,</L>
<L N="100">Was, as I wene, &yogh;if I well thenke &middot; in multitude of peple,</L>
<L>That &yogh;e were &thorn;e more my&yogh;tier &middot; ffor the many signes</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e and &yogh;oure seruauntis &middot; aboute so thikke sowid;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> badly spelt <I>abou&yogh;te</I> in the MS. <I>sowid;</I> glossed by <I>shewed</I> in the MS.; wrongly.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ey were more tristi &middot; and trewer &thorn;an o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="104">To loue &yogh;ou ffor &thorn;e leuere &middot; &thorn;at legeaunce stroied;
<PB REF="00001320.tif" N="482, C-text"></L>
<L N="105">Or ellis ffor a skylle &middot; &thorn;at skathed &yogh;oure-self,</L>
<L>&THORN;at comounes of contre &middot; in costis aboute<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in;</I> Mr Wright prints <I>and,</I> but MS. has <I>had</I> altered to <I>in.</I> For <I>aboute,</I> the MS. has the false spelling <I>abou&yogh;te.</I> Cf. Yf &thorn;ei knew eny <I>countreie</I> &middot; o&thorn;er <I>costes aboute;</I> C. 11. 12.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sholde knowe be hir quentise &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng loued hem</L>
<L N="108">ffor her priuy prynte &middot; passinge ano&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at was &yogh;oure purpos &middot; it passith my wittis</L>
<L>To deme discrecioun &middot; of &yogh;oure well-doynge!</L>
<L>&THORN;us were &yogh;e disceyued &middot; &thorn;oru &yogh;oure duble hertis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere weren to truste &middot; so god saue my soule!</L>
<L N="113">But had &thorn;e good greehonde &middot; be not agreued,</L>
<L>But cherischid as a cheffeteyne &middot; and cheff of &yogh;oure lese,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e hadde had hertis ynowe at &yogh;oure wille &middot; to go and to ride.</L>
<L N="116">And also in serteyne &middot; &thorn;e so&thorn;e ffor to telle,</L>
<L>I wondir not hyly &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; heed-dere &thorn;ou ffailid;<MILESTONE N="112" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor litill on &yogh;oure lyf &middot; &thorn;e list ffor to rewe</L>
<L>On rascaile &thorn;at rorid &middot; with ribbis so lene,</L>
<L N="120">ffor ffaute of her ffode &middot; &thorn;at fflater[er]is stelen,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffaute;</I> misspelt <I>ffau&yogh;te</I> in the MS., as in l. 63.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euere with here wylis &amp; wast &middot; ofte &thorn;ey hem anoyed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at pouerte hem prickid &middot; ffull preuyliche to pleyne,</L>
<L>But where, &thorn;ey ne wyste &middot; ne ho it wolde amende!</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;us &yogh;e derid hem vnduly &middot; with droppis of anger,</L>
<L>And stonyed hem with stormes &middot; &thorn;at stynted neuere,</L>
<L>But plucked and pulled hem &middot; anon to &thorn;e skynnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at the ffresinge ffrost &middot; ffreted to here hertis.</L>
<L>So whanne &yogh;oure hauntelere dere &middot; were all ytakyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>were;</I> MS. <I>where,</I> badly; see <I>were</I> in ll. 101, 103.</NOTE></L>
<L N="129">Was non of &thorn;e rasskayle &middot; aredy ffull growe,</L>
<L>To bere ony bremme heed &middot; as a best aughte,</L>
<L>So wyntris wedir &middot; hem wessh with &thorn;e snowis,</L>
<L N="132">With many derke mystis &middot; &thorn;at maddid her eyne.
<PB REF="00001321.tif" N="483, C-text"></L>
<L>ffor well mowe &yogh;e wyttyn &middot; &amp; so mowe we all,</L>
<L>&THORN;at harde is &thorn;e somer &middot; &thorn;er sonne schyneth neuere.</L>
<L N="135">&YOGH;e ffostrid and ffodid &middot; a ffewe of &thorn;e best,</L>
<L>And leyde on hem lordschipe &middot; aleyne vppon o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>And bereued &thorn;e raskall &middot; &thorn;at rith wolde &thorn;ei hadde,</L>
<L N="138">And knewe not &thorn;e caris &middot; ne cursis &thorn;at walkyd;</L>
<L>But mesure is a meri mene &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; men moche yerne:&mdash;<Q><I>Deus exaudit clamorem pauperum, et iudicat Causam eorum; dauid in psalmis.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Mesure is</I> medcyne &middot; <I>&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ow moche &yogh;erne;</I> B. 1. 35; C. 2. 33.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">&THORN;us be &thorn;e rotus &middot; &yogh;oure raskall endurid,</L>
<L>Tyll &thorn;e blessid bredd &middot; brodid his wyngis,</L>
<L>To couere hem ffrom colde &middot; as his kynde wolde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. <I>as hus kynde wolde;</I> C. 4. 129; and 9. 161.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rith as &thorn;e hous-hennes &middot; vppon londe hacchen,</L>
<L>And cherichen her chekonys &middot; ffro chele of &thorn;e wynter,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cherichen;</I> glossed <I>cherissheth. chele;</I> glossed <I>colde.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="145">Ryth so &thorn;e hende Egle &middot; &thorn;e heyere of hem all,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>heyere;</I> MS. <I>Eyere;</I> but see iii. 74.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hasteth him in heruest &middot; to houyn his bryddis,</L>
<L>And besieth him besely &middot; to breden hem ffeedrin,</L>
<L N="148">Tyll her ffre ffedris &middot; be ffulliche y-pynned,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey heue wynge at her wyll &middot; to wonne vppon hille,</L>
<L>ffor venym on &thorn;e valeye &middot; hadde ffoule with hem ffare,</L>
<L>Tyll trouthe &thorn;e triacle &middot; telde somme her sothes.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> For <I>treuthe</I> telle&thorn; &thorn;at loue &middot; ys <I>tryacle</I> for synne; C. 2. 147.</NOTE></L>
<L N="152">Thus baterid &thorn;is bred &middot; on busshes aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te.</I> So also in ll. 157, 182, 186.</NOTE></L>
<L>And gaderid gomes on grene &middot; &thorn;er as &thorn;ey walkyd,<MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e schroff and schroup &middot; sondrid ffrom o&thorn;er.</L>
<L N="155">He mellid so &thorn;e matall &middot; with &thorn;e hand-molde,</L>
<L>That [&thorn;ey] lost [of &thorn;eir] lemes &middot; &thorn;e leuest &thorn;at &thorn;ey had.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Supply <I>&thorn;ey</I> and <I>of &thorn;eir.</I> They lost the liefest of their limbs; i. e. their <I>heads.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Thus ffoulyd this ffaukyn &middot; on ffyldis aboute,</L>
<L>And cau&yogh;te of the kytes &middot; a cartfull at ones,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kytes;</I> MS. <I>kuyttis,</I> with <I>kytes</I> written above; see l. 161.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001322.tif" N="484, C-text"></L>
<L>That rentis and robis &middot; with raveyn euere lau&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>raveyn;</I> so I read it. Mr Wright prints <I>rabeyn,</I> as it may also be read. <I>lau&yogh;te;</I> glossed <I>caught.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="160">&YOGH;it was not &thorn;e ffawcon &middot; ffull ffed at his likynge,</L>
<L>ffor it cam him not of kynde &middot; kytes to loue.</L>
<L>Than bated he boldeliche &middot; as a brid wolde,</L>
<L>To plewme on his pray &middot; &thorn;e pol ffro &thorn;e nekk;</L>
<L N="164">But &thorn;e blernyed boynard &middot; &thorn;at his bagg stall,</L>
<L>Where purraile-is pulter &middot; was pynnyd ffull ofte,</L>
<L>Made &thorn;e ffawcon to ffloter &middot; and fflussh ffor anger,</L>
<L>That &thorn;e boy hadd be bounde &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e bagge kepte.</L>
<L N="168">But sone &thorn;er-after &middot; in a schorte tyme,</L>
<L>As ffortune ffolwith &middot; ech ffode till his ende,</L>
<L>This lorell &thorn;at ladde &middot; &thorn;is loby awey<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ladde;</I> MS. <I>hadde;</I> but ob|serve the alliteration and the sense.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouere ffrithe and fforde &middot; ffor his ffals dedis,</L>
<L N="172">Lyghte on &thorn;e lordschepe &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e brid longid,</L>
<L>And was ffelliche ylau&yogh;te &middot; and luggid ffull ylle,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;te to &thorn;e brydd &middot; and his blames rehersid</L>
<L>Preuyly at &thorn;e parlement &middot; amonge all &thorn;e peple.</L>
<L N="176">Thus hawkyd &thorn;is Egle &middot; and houed aboue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, as god wolde &middot; &thorn;at gouerneth all &thorn;ingis,</L>
<L>Ther nas kyte ne krowe &middot; &thorn;at kareyne hantid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne with his lynage &middot; ne louyd ffull sone.</L>
<L N="180">ffor wher so &thorn;ey fferde &middot; be ffryth or be wones,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wones;</I> Mr Wright prints <I>woves,</I> but in his glossary says "<I>qu.</I> wones." <I>Cf.</I> Lorde, who shal <I>wonye</I> in &thorn;i <I>wones?</I> B. 3. 234. And see Pass. iii. 220, below.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was non of hem all &middot; &thorn;at him hide my&yogh;th,</L>
<L>But cam with him a reclayme &middot; ffro costis aboute,</L>
<L>And ffell with her ffetheris &middot; fflat vppon &thorn;e erthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> platte hure to &thorn;e erthe; C. 7. 3.</NOTE></L>
<L N="184">As madde of her mynde &middot; and mercy be-sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey my&yogh;te not aschonne &middot; &thorn;e sorowe &thorn;ey had serued.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>serued;</I> glossed <I>deserved.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>So lymed leues &middot; were leyde all aboute,</L>
<L>And panteris preuyliche &middot; pight vppon &thorn;e grounde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Here follow the catchwords&mdash;With grennes of good here.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001323.tif" N="485, C-text"></L>
<L>With grennes of good heere &middot; &thorn;at god him-self made,<MILESTONE N="113" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>grennes;</I> glossed <I>greyhoundes.</I> This is entirely wrong; for a <I>gren</I> is a <I>gin</I> or snare; and "a gren of good heere" is a snare made of fine hair. Observe the context.</NOTE></L>
<L N="189">&THORN;at where so &thorn;ey walkid &middot; &thorn;ey waltrid dounwardis;</L>
<L>And euere houed &thorn;e Egle &middot; on hie on &thorn;e skyes,</L>
<L>And kenned clerliche &middot; as his kynde axith,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> ri&yogh;te <I>as kynde axeth;</I> B. 2. 27.</NOTE></L>
<L N="192">Alle &thorn;e preuy poyntis &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e pies wrou&yogh;th.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00001324.tif" N="486, C-text">
<HEAD>Passus Tercius.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pass. iii. 9. <I>Cf. &THORN;e moste myschif on molde</I> &middot; Mounte&thorn; vp faste; C. 1. 65.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now leue we &thorn;is beu brid &middot; till I restore,</L>
<L>ffor mater &thorn;at my mynde &middot; is meued in now,</L>
<L>That whi &thorn;e hie hertis &middot; her hele so mysside,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at pasture axid &middot; rith to here pure wombis;</L>
<L>I wolle schewe as I sawe &middot; till I se better,</L>
<L>And if I walke out of the wey &middot; I wolle me repente.</L>
<L>Now herkeneth, hende men &middot; how &thorn;at me thynkyth,</L>
<L N="8">Sauynge souereynes &middot; and sages avise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e moste myscheff &middot; vppon molde on</L>
<L>Is demed &thorn;e dede &middot; y-do a&yogh;eins kynde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it clereth &thorn;is clause &middot; no &thorn;inge my wittis,</L>
<L N="12">With-out more mater &middot; what it mene wolde.</L>
<L>I mene of &thorn;e hertis &middot; &thorn;at hautesse of &yogh;eris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at pasture prikkyth &middot; and her preuy age;</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ey han hoblid on &thorn;e holte &middot; an hundrid of &yogh;eris,</L>
<L N="16">That &thorn;ey ffeblen in ffleissh &middot; in ffelle, and in bones,</L>
<L>Her kynde is to keuere &middot; if &thorn;ey cacche my&yogh;th</L>
<L>Adders &thorn;at harmen &middot; alle hende bestis;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>harmen;</I> MS <I>armen,</I> with <I>h</I> supplied above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;oru busschis and bromes &middot; &thorn;is beste, of his kynde,</L>
<L N="20">Secheth and sercheth &middot; &thorn;o schrewed wormes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at steleth on &thorn;e stedis &middot; to stynge hem to deth;</L>
<L>And whanne it happeth &thorn;e herte &middot; to hente &thorn;e edder,</L>
<L>He putyth him to peyne &middot; as his pray asketh,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf. as</I> &thorn;e worlde <I>aske&thorn;;</I> C. 1. 21.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">And ffedith him on &thorn;e venym &middot; his ffelle to anewe,
<PB REF="00001325.tif" N="487, C-text"></L>
<L>To leue at more lykynge &middot; a longe tyme after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf. a longe tyme after;</I> C. 8. 203.</NOTE></L>
<L>This is clergie, hir kynde &middot; coltis nat to greue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nat</I> is supplied above the line; it is clearly wanted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne to hurlle with haras &middot; no hors well atamed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no;</I> MS. <I>ne.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="28">Ne to stryue with swan &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; it sholle werre,</L>
<L>Ne to bayten on the bere &middot; ne bynde him no&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Ne to wilne to woo &middot; &thorn;at were hem ny sibbe,</L>
<L>Ne to liste ffor to loke &middot; &thorn;at her alie bledde;</L>
<L N="32">This was a&yogh;eins kynde &middot; as clerkis me tolde:<Q><I>Propter ingratitudinem liber homo reuocatur in seruitutem, ut in stimulo compunccionis, et in lege Ciuili.</I></Q><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>homo;</I> MS. h<SUP>o</SUP>; Mr Wright prints <I>hic,</I> wrongly; see the Preface. <I>seruitutem;</I> MS. seruititem, by a mere slip.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;erffor &thorn;e hertis &middot; here hele so myssid,<MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And my&yogh;te nat passe &thorn;e poynte &middot; of her prime age.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Whoso <I>passe&thorn;</I> &thorn;at <I>poynt;</I> C. 2. 98.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now constrew ho so kunne &middot; I can saie no more,</L>
<L N="36">But ffare I wolle to &thorn;e ffowle &middot; &thorn;at I beffore tolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Off all billid breddis &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e bough spareth,</L>
<L>&THORN;e propirte of partriche &middot; to preise me lusti&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e somer seson &middot; whane sittinge nyeth,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> In a <I>somer sesoun;</I> C. l. 1.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at ich ffoule with his ffere &middot; ffolwith his kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;is brid be a bank &middot; bildith his nest,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Briddes I bihelde &middot; &thorn;at in buskes made nestes; B. ll. 336; and compare the whole passage in B. ll. 318&mdash;353 with the context.</NOTE></L>
<L>And heipeth his eiren &middot; and hetith hem after.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eiren;</I> MS. <I>heires,</I> which is obviously a blunder; for see l. 50, below. <I>Heires</I> = heirs; but <I>ciren</I> = eggs.</NOTE></L>
<L>And whane &thorn;e dame hath ydo &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e dede longith,</L>
<L N="44">And hopith ffor to hacche &middot; or heruest begynne,</L>
<L>Thanne cometh &thorn;er a congioun &middot; with a grey cote,</L>
<L>As not of his nolle &middot; as he &thorn;e nest made,</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er proud partriche &middot; and precyth to &thorn;e nest,</L>
<L N="48">And preuylich pirith &middot; till &thorn;e dame passe,</L>
<L>And sesith on hir sete &middot; with hir softe plumes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sete;</I> MS. <I>Cete,</I> altered to <I>sete.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00001326.tif" N="488, C-text"></L>
<L>And houeth &thorn;e eyren &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e hue laide,</L>
<L>And with hir corps keuereth hem &middot; till &thorn;at &thorn;ey kenne,</L>
<L N="52">And ffostrith and ffodith &middot; till ffedris schewe,</L>
<L>And cotis of kynde &middot; hem keuere all aboute.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>But as sone as &thorn;ey styffe &middot; and &thorn;at &thorn;ey steppe kunne,</L>
<L>&THORN;an cometh and crieth &middot; her owen kynde dame,</L>
<L N="56">And &thorn;ey ffolwith &thorn;e vois &middot; at &thorn;e ffrist note,</L>
<L>And leueth &thorn;e lurker &middot; &thorn;at hem er ladde,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e schrewe schrapid &middot; to selde ffor her wombis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at her lendys were lene &middot; and leued with hunger.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leued;</I> altered to <I>lyued.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="60">But &thorn;an &thorn;e dewe dame &middot; dineth hem swythe,</L>
<L>And ffostrith hem fforthe &middot; till &thorn;ey ffle kunne.</L>
<L>"What is &thorn;is to mene, man?" &middot; maiste &thorn;ou axe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf. what is &thorn;is to mene;</I> B. 1. 11.</NOTE></L>
<L>"ffor it is derklich endited &middot; ffor a dull panne;</L>
<L N="64">Wherffore I wilne &middot; &yogh;if it &thorn;i will were,</L>
<L>&THORN;e partriche propurtes &middot; by whom &thorn;at &thorn;ou menest?"</L>
<L>A! hicke heuyheed! &middot; hard is &thorn;i nolle</L>
<L>To cacche ony kunnynge &middot; but cautell bigynne!</L>
<L N="68">Herdist &thorn;ou not with eeris &middot; how &thorn;at I er tellde,</L>
<L>How &thorn;e egle in &thorn;e est &middot; entrid his owene,<MILESTONE N="114" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And cried and clepid &middot; after his owen kynde briddis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren anoyed in his nest &middot; and norished ffull ille,</L>
<L N="72">And well ny yworewid &middot; with a wronge leder?</L>
<L>But &thorn;e nedy nestlingis &middot; whan &thorn;ey &thorn;e note herde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hende Egle &middot; &thorn;e heyer of hem all,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hende;</I> MS. <I>ende,</I> altered to <I>hende.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei busked ffro &thorn;e busches &middot; and breris &thorn;at hem noyed,</L>
<L>And burnisched her beekis &middot; and bent to-him-wardis,</L>
<L>And ffolowid him ffersly &middot; to ffighte ffor &thorn;e wrongis;</L>
<L N="78">&THORN;ey bablid with her billis &middot; how &thorn;ei bete were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And so I <I>babeled</I> on my bedes; B. 5. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tenyd with twiggis &middot; two and twenty &yogh;eris.</L>
<L>Thus lafte &thorn;ey &thorn;e leder &middot; &thorn;at hem wrong ladde,</L>
<L N="81">And tymed no twynte &middot; but tolled her cornes,
<PB REF="00001327.tif" N="489, C-text"></L>
<L>And gaderid &thorn;e grotus &middot; with gyle, as I trowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ffolwid &thorn;ey her ffre ffader &middot; as good ffeith wolde,</L>
<L N="84">That he hem ffede shulde &middot; and ffostre fforther,</L>
<L>And bringe hem out of bondage &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ey were brou&yogh;th inne.</L>
<L>Thanne sighed &thorn;e swymmers &middot; ffor the swan ffailid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin is written&mdash;"y<SUP>e</SUP> Swan."</NOTE></L>
<L>And ffolwid &thorn;is ffaucoun &middot; &thorn;oru ffeldus and tounes,</L>
<L N="88">With many ffaire ffowle &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey ffeynte were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffowle;</I> MS. <I>ffoole,</I> with <I>ffowle</I> written above.</NOTE></L>
<L>And heuy ffor &thorn;e hurte &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e hors hadde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hurte;</I> MS. <I>hirte,</I> with <I>u</I> above the <I>i.</I> In the margin&mdash;"ye Horse."</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it &thorn;ey fferkyd hem fforth &middot; as ffaste as &thorn;ey my&yogh;te,</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e Egles helpe &middot; of harme &thorn;at &thorn;ey hadde;</L>
<L N="92">ffor he was heed of hem all &middot; and hieste of kynde,</L>
<L>To kepe &thorn;e Croune &middot; as cronecle tellith.</L>
<L>He blythid &thorn;e beere &middot; and his bond braste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bond;</I> MS. <I>broud</I> or <I>brond;</I> Mr Wright prints <I>broud,</I> but surely it is merely <I>bond,</I> misspelt <I>brond</I> owing to the influence of the following word <I>braste.</I> In the margin &mdash; "The Beare."</NOTE></L>
<L>And lete him go at large &middot; to lepe where he wolde.</L>
<L N="96">But &thorn;o all &thorn;e berlingis &middot; brast out at ones,</L>
<L>As ffayne as &thorn;e ffoule &middot; &thorn;at fflieth on &thorn;e skyes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>As fayne as;</I> MS. <I>As fayne was;</I> but I venture on the correction on the strength of the parallel passage &mdash; &THORN;anne was I <I>also fayne &middot; as foule</I> of faire morwe; B. 10. 153; C. 12. 103.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at bosse was vnbounde &middot; and brou&yogh;te to his owene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brou&yogh;te;</I> MS. <I>brouute.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey gaderid hem to-gedir &middot; on a grette route,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>route;</I> MS. <I>rou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="100">To helpe &thorn;e heeris &middot; &thorn;at had many wrongis;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey gaglide fforth on &thorn;e grene &middot; ffor &thorn;ey greued were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at her ffrendis were ffalle &middot; &thorn;oru ffelouns castis.</L>
<L>They mornyd ffor &thorn;e morthir &middot; of manffull kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>That many a styff storme &middot; with-stode ffor &thorn;e comunes;<MILESTONE N="114b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e[y] monside &thorn;e marchall &middot; ffor his myssedede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>monside;</I> MS. <I>monside</I> or <I>mouside.</I> Mr Wright prints <I>mouside,</I> but does not explain it; <I>monside</I> (i. e. cursed) is only another spelling of <I>mansed,</I> which see in C. 3. 41.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at euell coude his Craft &middot; whan he clo&thorn;ed &thorn;e stede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>clo&thorn;ed;</I> so in MS. Mr Wright prints <I>cloped,</I> which he ex|plains by <I>clipped.</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00001328.tif" N="490, C-text"></L>
<L>And euere as &thorn;ey ffolwide &middot; &thorn;is ffaucoun aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="108">At iche mevinge ffotte &middot; venyaunce &thorn;ey asked</L>
<L>On all &thorn;at assentid &middot; to &thorn;at synfull dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A rere now to Richard &middot; and reste here awhile,</L>
<L>ffor a preuy poynt &middot; &thorn;at persith my wittis.</L>
<L N="112">Of ffautis I ffynde &middot; &thorn;at ffrist dede engendre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fautis;</I> MS. <I>fauutis.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Cursidnesse and combraunce &middot; amonge &thorn;e yonge lordis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wikkid werchinge &middot; &thorn;at walmed in her daies,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it woll here-after &middot; but wisdome it lette.</L>
<L>That were a lord of lond &middot; &thorn;at lawe hathe in honde,</L>
<L N="117">&THORN;at to lyghtliche leueth &middot; or lewte apere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tale of a trifflour &middot; in turmentours wede,</L>
<L>That neuere reed good rewle &middot; ne resons bookis!</L>
<L N="120">ffor ben &thorn;ey rayed arith &middot; &thorn;ey recchith no fforther,</L>
<L>But studieth all in stroutynge &middot; and stireth amys euere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stroutynge;</I> MS. <I>strouutynge,</I> here and in l. 134; but see l. 189, and Chaucer, C. T. 3315.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor all his witte in his wede &middot; ys wrappid ffor sothe,</L>
<L>More &thorn;an in mater to amende &middot; &thorn;e peple &thorn;at ben mys-led.</L>
<L>ffor I say ffor my-self &middot; and schewe, as me thynchith,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. <I>Ich seye it for my-selue;</I> C. 5. 134. <I>thynchith;</I> MS. thynthith; but this writing of <I>c</I> like <I>t</I> is common enough.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">That ho is riall of his ray &middot; that light reede him ffol|with;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it swiche ffresshe ffoodis &middot; beth ffeet in-to chambris,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> and <I>brou&yogh;te</I> hir <I>in-to chaumbre;</I> B. 3. 10.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ffor her dignesse endauntid &middot; of dullisshe nollis,</L>
<L N="128">And, if &thorn;ou well waite &middot; of no wight ellis:<Q><I>Qui mollibus vestiuntur in domibus regum sunt: in Euangelio.</I></Q></L>
<L>&THORN;an waite mo wayes &middot; how &thorn;e while turneth</L>
<L>With gyuleris, Ioyffull &middot; ffor here gery Iaces,</L>
<L N="131">And ffor her wedis so wyde &middot; wise beth y-holde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ey casteth hem to creaunce &middot; &thorn;e courte ffor to plese,</L>
<L>And hopen to be hied &middot; in hast, yif &thorn;ey my&yogh;the,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru swiche stif stroutynge &middot; &thorn;at stroyeth &thorn;e rewme;
<PB REF="00001329.tif" N="491, C-text"></L>
<L>But here wey is all wronge &middot; &thorn;er wisdom is ynned,</L>
<L N="136">[For] &thorn;ey lepith als lygh[t]ly &middot; at &thorn;e longe goynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For;</I> MS. <I>But,</I> wrongly re|peated.</NOTE></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e domes carte &middot; as he &thorn;at &thorn;roff neuere.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ey kepeth no coyne &middot; &thorn;at cometh to here hondis,<MILESTONE N="115" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But chaunchyth it ffor cheynes &middot; &thorn;at in chepe hangith,</L>
<L N="140">And settith all her siluer &middot; in semitis and hornes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>semitis;</I> or <I>seimtis,</I> or <I>seitu|tis;</I> indistinct and uncertain.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ffor-doth &thorn;e coyne &middot; and many o&thorn;er craftis,</L>
<L>And make&thorn; &thorn;e peple ffor pens lac &middot; in pointe ffor to wepe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peple;</I> miswritten <I>pephe.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;ey beth ytake fforth &middot; and her tale leued,</L>
<L N="144">And ffor her newe nysete &middot; nexte to &thorn;e lordis.</L>
<L>Now, be &thorn;e lawe of lydfford &middot; in londe [&amp;] in water<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&amp;;</I> MS. <I>ne,</I> which seems to have been written over an erasure; <I>&amp;</I> is better.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ilke lewde ladde &middot; ou&yogh;te euyll to &thorn;ryue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hongith on his hippis &middot; more &thorn;an he wynneth,</L>
<L N="148">And douteth no dette &middot; so dukis hem preise,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>douteth;</I> MS. <I>dou&yogh;teth.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>But beggith and borwith &middot; of burgeis in tounes</L>
<L>ffurris of ffoyne &middot; and o&thorn;er ffelle-ware,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ware;</I> misspelt <I>whare</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And not &thorn;e better of a bene &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ey boru euere.</L>
<L N="152">And, but if &thorn;e slevis &middot; slide on &thorn;e erthe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei woll be wroth as &thorn;e wynde &middot; and warie hem &thorn;at it made;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> As <I>wroth as &thorn;e wynd;</I> C. 4. 486.</NOTE></L>
<L>And [but] &yogh;if it were elbowis &middot; adoun to the helis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Supply <I>but;</I> as in l. 152.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or passinge &thorn;e knee &middot; it was not acounted.</L>
<L N="156">And if pernell preisid &middot; &thorn;e plytis bihynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> He preide <I>purnele</I> &middot; here porfil to leue; C. 6. 129. Observe that <I>felice</I> is mentioned only three lines lower down, in C. 6. 132; whilst she is mentioned here also, four lines lower. <I>plytis;</I> glossed by <I>pleytes.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>The costis were acountid &middot; paye whan he my&yogh;th.</L>
<L>&THORN;e leesinge so likyde &middot; ladies and o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>That &thorn;ey Ioied of &thorn;e Iette &middot; and gyside hem &thorn;er-vnder;</L>
<L>And if ffelice ffonde ony ffaute &middot; &thorn;enne of &thorn;e makynge,
<PB REF="00001330.tif" N="492, C-text"></L>
<L N="161">Yt was y-sent sone &middot; to shape of &thorn;e newe.</L>
<L>But now &thorn;er is a gyse &middot; &thorn;e queyntest of all</L>
<L>A wondir coriouse crafte &middot; y-come now of late,</L>
<L N="164">That men clepith kerving &middot; &thorn;e clo&thorn;e all to pecis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seuene goode sowers &middot; sixe wekes after</L>
<L>Moun not sett &thorn;e seemes &middot; ne sewe hem a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>But &thorn;er is a proffit in &thorn;at pride &middot; &thorn;at I preise euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a proffit:</I> MS. <I>aprffith</I> (<I>sic</I>), with <I>a profett</I> written above it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="168">ffor &thorn;ei ffor &thorn;e pesinge paieth &middot; pens ten duble</L>
<L>That &thorn;e clo&thorn;e costened &middot; &thorn;e craft is so dere.</L>
<L>Now if I sothe shall saie &middot; and shonne side tales,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is as moche good witte &middot; in swyche gomes nollis,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou shuldist mete of a myst &middot; ffro morwe tyll euen!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &THORN;ow my&yogh;t bet <I>mete &thorn;e myst;</I> C. l. 163.</NOTE></L>
<L N="173">&YOGH;it blame I no burne &middot; to be, as him ou&yogh;te,<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In comliche clo&thorn;inge &middot; as his statt axith;</L>
<L>But to ledyn her lust &middot; all here lyff-daies</L>
<L N="176">In quentise of clo&thorn;inge &middot; ffor to queme sir pride,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> In cuntinaunce <I>of clo&thorn;inge &middot; queinteliche</I> de-gyset; A. pr. 24.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euere-more stroutynge &middot; and no store kepe,</L>
<L>And iche day a newe deuyse &middot; it dullith my wittis</L>
<L>&THORN;at ony lord of a lond &middot; shulde leue swiche &thorn;ingis,</L>
<L N="180">Or clepe to his conceill &middot; swiche manere cotis,</L>
<L>That loueth more her lustis &middot; &thorn;an &thorn;e lore of oure lord.</L>
<L>And if a lord his leuere &middot; lyste ffor to &yogh;eue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leuere;</I> MS. leuere, altered to lyuerey. It is a trisyllable word.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther may no gome ffor goodnesse &middot; gette &thorn;er-of but lite,</L>
<L>ffor curtesie, ffor comlynesse &middot; ne ffor his kynde herte,</L>
<L>But rather ffor his rancour &middot; and rennynge ouere peple,</L>
<L N="186">ffor braggynge and ffor bostynge &middot; and beringe vppon oilles,</L>
<L>ffor cursidnes of conscience &middot; and comynge to &thorn;e assises.</L>
<L>This makyth men mysdo &middot; more &thorn;an ou&yogh;te ellis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And <I>make&thorn; men mys-do</I> meny score tymes; C. 4. 159.</NOTE></L>
<L>And to stroute and to stare &middot; and stryue a&yogh;eyn vertu.</L>
<L N="190">So [be] clergie, &thorn;e cause &middot; comsith in grette,</L>
<L>Of all manere mysscheff &middot; &thorn;at men here vsyn.
<PB REF="00001331.tif" N="493, C-text"></L>
<L N="192">ffor wolde &thorn;ey blame &thorn;e burnes &middot; &thorn;at brou&yogh;te newe gysis,</L>
<L>And dryue out &thorn;e dagges &middot; and all &thorn;e duche cotis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> let <I>dagge</I> hus clo&thorn;es; C. 23. 143.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sette hem a-side &middot; and scorte of hem telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scorte;</I> so in MS.; glossed by <I>scorne.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And lete hem pleye in &thorn;e porche &middot; and presse non ynnere,</L>
<L N="196">Ne no proude peniles &middot; with his peynte sleve;</L>
<L>And eke repreue robbers &middot; and riffleris of peple,</L>
<L>fflater[er]is and ffals men &middot; &thorn;at no ffeith vseth,</L>
<L>And alle deabolik doeris &middot; dispise hem ichone,</L>
<L>And coile out &thorn;e kny&yogh;tys &middot; &thorn;at knowe well hem-self,</L>
<L N="201">&THORN;at were sad of her sawis &middot; and suffre well coude,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>coude;</I> MS. <I>couude.</I> So also in l. 219.</NOTE></L>
<L>And had traueilid in her tyme &middot; and temprid hem-self,</L>
<L>And cherliche cheriche hem &middot; as cheff in &thorn;e halle,</L>
<L N="204">ffor to ordeyne officeris &middot; and all o&thorn;er thyngis;</L>
<L>Men shuld wete in a while &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e world wolde amende,</L>
<L>So vertue wolde fflowe &middot; whan vicis were ebbid.</L>
<L>But now to &thorn;e mater &middot; &thorn;at I be-ffore meved,<MILESTONE N="116" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="208">Of &thorn;e gomes so gay &middot; &thorn;at grace hadde affendid,</L>
<L>And how stille &thorn;at steddeffaste stode &middot; amonge &thorn;is reccheles peple,</L>
<L>&THORN;at had awilled his wyll &middot; as wisdom him taughte:</L>
<L>ffor he drough him to an herne &middot; at &thorn;e halle ende,</L>
<L N="212">Well homelich yhelid &middot; in an holsume gyse,</L>
<L>Not ouerelonge, but ordeyned &middot; in &thorn;e olde schappe,</L>
<L>With grette browis y-bente &middot; and a berde eke,</L>
<L>And y-wounde in his wedis &middot; as &thorn;e wedir axith;</L>
<L N="216">He wondrid in his wittis &middot; as he well my&yogh;the,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>well;</I> MS. <I>will,</I> altered to <I>well.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e hie housinge &middot; herborowe ne myghte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>housinge;</I> MS. <I>houusinge.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Halfdell &thorn;e houshould &middot; but hales hem helped;</L>
<L>But ffor crafte &thorn;at he coude &middot; caste &thorn;enne or be-&thorn;enke,</L>
<L>He my&yogh;te not wonne in &thorn;e wones &middot; ffor witt &thorn;at he vsid;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Lorde, who shal <I>wonye in</I> &thorn;i <I>wones;</I> B. 3. 234.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001332.tif" N="494, C-text"></L>
<L N="221">But, aroutyd ffor his ray &middot; and rebuked ofte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aroutyd;</I> MS. <I>arouutyd.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>He had leue of &thorn;e lord &middot; and of ladies alle,</L>
<L>ffor his good gouernaunce &middot; to go or he drank!</L>
<L>&THORN;er was non of &thorn;e mene &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ey ne merueilid moche,</L>
<L N="225">How he cam to &thorn;e courte &middot; and was not y-knowe;</L>
<L>But als sone as &thorn;ey wiste &middot; &thorn;at witt was his name,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng knewe him not &middot; ne non of his kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="228">He was halowid and y-huntid &middot; and y-hote trusse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Ouer-al houted out &middot; <I>and yhote trusse;</I> C. 3. 228. For <I>y-hote,</I> MS. has <I>y-hotte,</I> with the gloss <I>bydden</I> above it.</NOTE></L>
<L>And his dwellinge ydemed &middot; a bowe-drawte ffrom hem,</L>
<L>And ich man y-charchid &middot; to schoppe at his croune,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he nyhed hem ony nere &middot; &thorn;an &thorn;ey had him nempned.</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;e portir with his pikis &middot; &thorn;o put him vttere,</L>
<L>And warned him &thorn;e wickett &middot; while &thorn;e wacche durid:</L>
<L>"Lete sle him!" quod &thorn;e sleues &middot; &thorn;at slode vppon &thorn;e erthe,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e berdles burnes &middot; bayed on him euere,</L>
<L N="236">And schorned him, ffor his slaueyn &middot; was of &thorn;e olde schappe.</L>
<L>&THORN;us malaperte was my&yogh;tffull &middot; and maister of hous,</L>
<L>And euere wandrid wisdom &middot; without &thorn;e &yogh;atis.</L>
<L>"By him &thorn;at wrou&yogh;te &thorn;is world!" &middot; quod wisdom in wrath,</L>
<L>"But &yogh;if &yogh;e woll sumtyme &middot; I walke in amonge &yogh;ou,</L>
<L N="241">I shall fforbede &yogh;ou burnes &middot; &thorn;e best on &thorn;is erthe,<MILESTONE N="116b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>burnes;</I> MS. <I>burnesse,</I> which is merely a bad spelling of the same word. Other instances of confusion between the endings -<I>es</I> and -<I>esse</I> are occasionally found in the MS. Thus we have <I>rosse</I> for <I>ros</I> in Prol. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is, gouernance of gettinge &middot; and grace &thorn;at him ffollwith;</L>
<L>ffor these two trewly &middot; twynned &yogh;et neuere."</L>
<L N="244">And so it ffell on hem, in ffeith &middot; ffor ffautis &thorn;at &thorn;ey vsid,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffautis;</I> MS. <I>ffau&yogh;tis.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at her grace was a-goo &middot; ffor grucchinge chere,
<PB REF="00001333.tif" N="495, C-text"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e wronge &thorn;at &thorn;ey wrou&yogh;te &middot; to wisdom affore.</L>
<L>ffor tristith, als trewly &middot; as tyllinge us helpeth,</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at iche rewme vndir roff &middot; of &thorn;e reyne-bowe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> &thorn;e richest <I>rewme</I> &middot; &thorn;at <I>reyne</I> ouer houeth; B. 3. 207.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sholde stable and stonde &middot; be &thorn;ese &thorn;re degres:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> gan <I>stable and stynte;</I> B. l. 120.</NOTE></L>
<L>By gouernaunce of grete &middot; and of good age;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Before l. 250 is prefixed the figure 1; before l. 251, the figure 2; and before l. 253, the figure 3. These refer to the "thre degres," viz. 1. <I>Oratores</I> (here Counsellors); 2. <I>Bella|tores</I> (Warriors); and 3. <I>Laboratores</I> (Labourers); according to the old threefold division. In l. 253, <I>be</I> = <I>by.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>By styffnesse and strengthe &middot; of steeris well y-yokyd,</L>
<L N="252">&THORN;at beth my&yogh;thffull men &middot; of &thorn;e mydill age;</L>
<L>And be laboreris of lond &middot; &thorn;at lyfflode ne ffayle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And lerne to <I>labore with londe &middot; lest lyflode hym faile;</I> C. 9. 295.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thanne wolde [right dome] reule &middot; if reson were amongis us,<NOTE PLACE="foot">We must supply <I>right dome,</I> i. e. just judgment, or some such words. In the margin is written&mdash;"Agaynste yonnge Counsaylours."</NOTE></L>
<L>That ich leode lokide &middot; what longid to his age,</L>
<L N="256">And neuere ffor to passe more &middot; oo poynt ffor&thorn;er,</L>
<L>To vsurpe &thorn;e service &middot; &thorn;at to sages bilongith,</L>
<L>To be-come conselleris &middot; er &thorn;ey kunne rede,</L>
<L>In schenshepe of souereynes &middot; and shame at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L N="260">ffor it ffallith as well to ffodis &middot; of xxiiij &yogh;eris,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The abbreviation <I>xxiiij</I> is to be read <I>four and twenty,</I> not <I>twenty|four.</I> Cf. l. 79, above.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or yonge men of yistirday &middot; to &yogh;eue good redis,</L>
<L>As be-cometh a kow &middot; to hoppe in a cage!</L>
<L>It is not vnknowen &middot; to kunnynge leodis,</L>
<L N="264">That rewlers of rewmes &middot; around all &thorn;e erthe</L>
<L>Were not yffoundid &middot; at &thorn;e ffrist tyme</L>
<L>To leue al at likynge &middot; and lust of &thorn;e world,</L>
<L>But to laboure on &thorn;e lawe &middot; as lewde men on plowes,</L>
<L N="268">And to merke meyntenourz &middot; with maces ichonne,</L>
<L>And to strie strouters &middot; &thorn;at sterede a&yogh;eine rithis,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e myssedoers &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;te ffynde,</L>
<L>To put hem in preson &middot; a peere &thorn;ou&yogh; he were;
<PB REF="00001334.tif" N="496, C-text"></L>
<L>And [not] to rewle as reremys &middot; and rest on &thorn;e daies,</L>
<L N="273">And spende of &thorn;e spicerie &middot; more &thorn;an it nedid,</L>
<L>Bothe wexe and wyn &middot; in wast all aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>With deyntes y-doublid &middot; and daunsinge to pipis,</L>
<L N="276">In myrthe with moppis &middot; myrrours of synne.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it fforbede I no burne &middot; to be blithe sum while;</L>
<L>But all thinge hath tyme &middot; ffor to tempre glees:<MILESTONE N="117" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor caste all &thorn;e countis &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng holdith,</L>
<L N="280">And loke how &thorn;ese lordis &middot; loggen hem-self,</L>
<L>And euere shall &thorn;ou ffynde &middot; as ffer as &thorn;ou walkiste,</L>
<L>That wisdom and ouere-wacche &middot; wonneth ffer asundre;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>That;</I> MS. <I>What,</I> probably by mistake. In the margin is "nota, nota, nota" in the same hand-writing as the text; another hand has added &mdash;"Over-watchynge."</NOTE></L>
<L>But whane &thorn;e gouernaunce goth &thorn;us &middot; with &thorn;o &thorn;e hous gie shulde,</L>
<L>And letith lyghte of &thorn;e lawe &middot; and lesse of &thorn;e peple,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And <I>let lyght of &thorn;e lawe</I> &middot; <I>and lasse of &thorn;e</I> knyght; C. 9. 165.</NOTE></L>
<L N="285">And herkeneth all to honour &middot; and to ese eke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ich wyght with his witte &middot; waite on him euere,</L>
<L>To do hem reuerence aright &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e rigge brest,</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;is warmnesse in welth &middot; with wy vppon erthe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wy;</I> glossed by <I>man;</I> cor|rectly. So also in l. 297.</NOTE></L>
<L>My&yogh;te not longe dure &middot; as doctourz us tellith.</L>
<L>ffor ho so &thorn;us leued &middot; his lyff to the ende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leued;</I> MS. <I>leued,</I> altered to <I>lyved.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Euere wrappid in welle &middot; and with no wo mette,</L>
<L N="292">My&yogh;te seie &thorn;at he sawe &middot; &thorn;at seie was neuere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heuene were vnhonge &middot; out of &thorn;e hookis,</L>
<L>And were boun at his bidding &middot; &yogh;if it be my&yogh;te!</L>
<L>But clerkis kne[w] I non &yogh;ete &middot; &thorn;at so coude rede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>knew;</I> MS. <I>kne. coude;</I> MS. <I>couude.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="296">In bokis y-bounde &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; &yogh;e brou&yogh;te alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at ony wy welldith &middot; wonnynge vppon erthe;</L>
<L>ffor in well and in woo &middot; &thorn;e werld euere turneth,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it &thorn;er is kew-kaw &middot; &thorn;ou&yogh; he come late,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin&mdash;"kew kaw;" to which substantive <I>he</I> obviously refers.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001335.tif" N="497, C-text"></L>
<L N="300">A new &thorn;ing &thorn;at noyeth &middot; nedy men and o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Whanne realles remeveth &middot; and ridith &thorn;oru tounes,</L>
<L>And carieth ouere contre &middot; &thorn;er comunes dwelleth,</L>
<L>To preson &thorn;e pillourz &middot; &thorn;at ouere &thorn;e pore renneth;</L>
<L N="304">For &thorn;at were euene in her weye &middot; if &thorn;ey well ride.</L>
<L>But &yogh;it &thorn;er is a ffoule ffaute &middot; &thorn;at I ffynde ofte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ffaute;</I> MS. <I>ffau&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey prien affter presentis &middot; or pleyntis ben y-clepid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin&mdash;"Takynge of presentes."</NOTE></L>
<L>And abateth all &thorn;e billis &middot; of &thorn;o &thorn;at nou&yogh;th bringith;</L>
<L>And ho so grucche or grone &middot; a&yogh;eins her grette willes,</L>
<L N="309">May lese her lyff lyghtly &middot; and no lesse weddis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> Ich dorst haue leid <I>my lyue</I> &middot; <I>and no lasse wedde;</I> C. 4. 260.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thus is the lawe louyd &middot; &thorn;oru my&yogh;hty lordis willys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin&mdash;"maynten|aunce."</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at meyneteyne myssdoers &middot; more &thorn;an o&thorn;er peple.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> To <I>meyntene mysdoers</I> &middot; Mede &thorn;ei take; B. 3. 246.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor mayntenaunce many day &middot; well more is &thorn;e reuthe!</L>
<L N="313">Hath y-had mo men &middot; at mete and at melis,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ony &middot;cristen kynge &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e knewe euere;<MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor, as reson and rith &middot; rehersid to me ones,</L>
<L>Tho ben men of this molde &middot; &thorn;at most harme worchen.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> For &thorn;ise aren <I>men on &thorn;is molde</I> &middot; <I>&thorn;at moste harme worcheth;</I> B. 3. 80.</NOTE></L>
<L N="317">ffor chyders of chester &middot; were chose many daies<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>were;</I> MS. <I>where.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To ben of conceill ffor causis &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e court hangid,</L>
<L>And pledid pipoudris &middot; alle manere pleyntis.</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;ey cared ffor no coyffes &middot; &thorn;at men of court vsyn,</L>
<L>But meved many maters &middot; &thorn;at man neuer thou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And ffeyned ffalshed &middot; till &thorn;ey a ffyne had,</L>
<L>And knewe no manere cause &middot; as comunes tolde.</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;ei had non o&thorn;er signe &middot; to schewe &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>But a preuy pallette &middot; her pannes to kepe,</L>
<L>To hille here lewde heed &middot; in stede of an houe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>houe.</I> Mr Wright prints <I>hone,</I> but does not explain it. See "<I>houes</I> of silke" in C. l. 159.</NOTE></L>
<L>They constrewed quarellis &middot; to quenche &thorn;e peple,</L>
<L N="328">And pletid with pollaxis &middot; and poyntis of swerdis,
<PB REF="00001336.tif" N="498, C-text"></L>
<L>And at the dome-&yogh;euynge &middot; drowe out &thorn;e bladis,</L>
<L>And lente men leuere &middot; of her longe battis.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leuere;</I> MS. leuere, altered to leuerey. It is a trisyllable word, equivalent here to <I>delivery,</I> in the sense of <I>delivering a blow;</I> see l. 182.</NOTE></L>
<L>They lacked alle vertues &middot; &thorn;at a Iuge shulde haue;</L>
<L>ffor, er a tale were ytolde &middot; &thorn;ey wolde trie &thorn;e harmes,</L>
<L N="333">Without ony answere &middot; but ho his lyf hatid.</L>
<L>And ho so pleyned to &thorn;e prince &middot; &thorn;at pees shulde kepe,</L>
<L>Of these mystirmen &middot; medlers of wrongis,</L>
<L>He was lyghtliche y-lau&yogh;te &middot; and y-luggyd of many,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyghliche</I> in MS. <I>Cf.</I> Lor|kynge &thorn;orw lones &middot; <I>to-logged of menye;</I> C. 3. 226.</NOTE></L>
<L N="337">And y-Mummyd on &thorn;e mouthe &middot; and manaced to &thorn;e deth.</L>
<L>They leid on &thorn;i leigis, Richard &middot; lasshis y-now,</L>
<L>And drede neuere a dele &middot; &thorn;e dome of &thorn;e lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas Rial of &thorn;e rewme &middot; &thorn;at hem durste rebuke,</L>
<L N="341">Ne Iuge, ne Iustice &middot; &thorn;at Iewis durste hem deme</L>
<L>ffor oute &thorn;at &thorn;ei toke &middot; or trespassid to &thorn;e peple.</L>
<L>This was a wondir world &middot; ho so well lokyd,</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;at gromes ouere-grewe &middot; so many grette maistris;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is was &thorn;e rewle in &thorn;is rewme &middot; while &thorn;ey here regnyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; I satte seuenenyght &middot; and slepte ffull selde,</L>
<L>[I mi&yogh;te not reche redili &middot; to rekene &thorn;e nombre]<NOTE PLACE="foot">A line lost; supplied by guess.</NOTE></L>
<L N="348">Of many mo wrongis &middot; &thorn;an I write coude;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>coude;</I> MS. <I>Couude.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>ffor selde were &thorn;e sergiauntis &middot; sou&yogh;te ffor to plete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>serigauntis.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Or ony prentise of courte &middot; preied of his wittis,<MILESTONE N="118" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e while &thorn;e degonys domes &middot; weren so endauntid.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>degonys;</I> MS. <I>dogonys;</I> see l. 362, below.</NOTE></L>
<L N="352">Tille oure sire in his see &middot; aboue &thorn;e vij<SUP>ne</SUP> sterris,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> by <I>the seuen sterres;</I> C. 18. 98.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sawe &thorn;e many mysscheuys &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ese men dede,</L>
<L>And no mendis ymade &middot; but menteyned euere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>menteyned;</I> MS. <I>menteyne it,</I> absurdly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at was hiest &middot; y-holde for to kepe
<PB REF="00001337.tif" N="499, C-text"></L>
<L N="356">His liegis in lawe &middot; and so her loue gette.</L>
<L>He sente ffor his seruantis &middot; &thorn;at sembled many,</L>
<L>Of baronys and baccheleris &middot; with many bri&yogh;th helmes,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e comunes [of] &thorn;e contres &middot; &thorn;ey cam all at ones;</L>
<L N="360">And as a duke dou&yogh;ty &middot; in dedis of armes,</L>
<L>In full reall aray &middot; he rood vppon hem euere,</L>
<L>Tyll degon and dobyn &middot; &thorn;at mennys doris brastyn,</L>
<L>And were y-dubbid of a duke &middot; ffor her while domes,</L>
<L N="364">Awakyd ffor wecchis &middot; and wast &thorn;at &thorn;ey vsid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wrongly inserts <I>And</I> at the beginning of this line.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ffor her breme blastis &middot; buffettis henten.</L>
<L>&THORN;an gan it to calme &middot; and clere all aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at iche man my&yogh;te &middot; ho so mynde hadde,</L>
<L N="368">Se, be &thorn;e sonne &middot; &thorn;at so bri&yogh;te schewed,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mone at &thorn;e mydday &middot; meve, and &thorn;e sterris,</L>
<L>ffolwinge ffelouns &middot; ffor her ffalse dedis,</L>
<L>Devourours of vetaile &middot; &thorn;at ffou&yogh;ten er &thorn;ei paide.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00001338.tif" N="500, C-text">
<HEAD>Passus quartus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pass. iv. 4. <I>ffautis;</I> MS. <I>ffau&yogh;tis.</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For where was euere ony cristen kynge &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e euere knewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at helde swiche an household &middot; be &thorn;e half-delle</L>
<L>As Richard in &thorn;is rewme &middot; &thorn;oru myserule of o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at alle his ffynys ffor ffautis &middot; ne his ffee ffermes,</L>
<L>Ne ffor-ffeyturis ffele &middot; &thorn;at ffelle in his daies,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e nownagis &middot; &thorn;at newed him euere,</L>
<L>As marche and moubray &middot; and many mo o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="8">Ne alle &thorn;e issues of court &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e kyng longid,</L>
<L>Ne sellynge, &thorn;at sowkid &middot; siluer rith ffaste,</L>
<L>Ne alle the prophete of &thorn;e lond &middot; &thorn;at the prince owed,</L>
<L>Whane &thorn;e countis were caste &middot; with &thorn;e custum of wullus,</L>
<L N="12">My&yogh;te not areche &middot; ne his rent no&thorn;er,</L>
<L>To paie &thorn;e pore peple &middot; &thorn;at his puruyours toke,</L>
<L>Withoute preiere at a parlement &middot; a poundage biside,<MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And a fifteneth &middot; and a dyme eke,</L>
<L N="16">And with-all &thorn;e custum of &thorn;e clo&thorn;e &middot; &thorn;at cometh to ffayres?</L>
<L>And &yogh;et, ne had creaunce Icome &middot; at &thorn;e last ende,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e comunes curse &middot; &thorn;at cleued on hem euere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey had be drawe to &thorn;e deuyll &middot; ffor dette &thorn;at &thorn;ey owed.</L>
<L N="20">And whanne &thorn;e reot and &thorn;e reeuell &middot; &thorn;e rent &thorn;us passid,</L>
<L>And no &thorn;ing y-lafte &middot; but &thorn;e bare baggis,
<PB REF="00001339.tif" N="501, C-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;an ffelle it afforse &middot; to ffille hem a&yogh;eyne,</L>
<L>And ffeyned sum ffolie &middot; &thorn;at ffailid hem neuer,</L>
<L N="24">And cast it be colis &middot; with her conceill at euene,</L>
<L>To haue preuy parlement &middot; for profit of hem-self,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>profit.</I> The spelling in the MS. is indeed odd, being pproffitt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lete write writtis &middot; all in wex closid,</L>
<L>ffor peeris and prelatis &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ei apere shuld,</L>
<L N="28">And sente side sondis &middot; to schreuys aboute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>To chese swiche cheualleris &middot; as &thorn;e charge wold,</L>
<L>To schewe ffor &thorn;e schire &middot; in company with &thorn;e grete.</L>
<L>And whanne it drowe to &thorn;e day &middot; of &thorn;e dede-doynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at souereynes were semblid &middot; and &thorn;e schire-kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Than, as her fforme is, ffrist &middot; &thorn;ey begynne to declare</L>
<L>&THORN;e cause of her comynge &middot; and &thorn;an &thorn;e kyngis will.</L>
<L>Comliche a clerk &thorn;an &middot; comsid &thorn;e wordis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. <I>Corteysliche</I> &thorn;e kny&yogh;t <I>&thorn;en &middot; comsede &thorn;ese wordes;</I> C. 9. 32.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">And pronouncid &thorn;e poyntis &middot; aparte to hem alle,</L>
<L>And meved ffor mony &middot; more than ffor out ellis,</L>
<L>In glosinge of grette &middot; lest greyues arise.</L>
<L>And whanne &thorn;e tale was tolde &middot; anon to &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L N="40">A-morwe thei must, affore mete &middot; mete to-gedir,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;tis of &thorn;e comunete &middot; and carpe of &thorn;e maters,</L>
<L>With Citiseyns of shiris &middot; y-sent ffor &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>To reherse &thorn;e articlis &middot; and graunte all her askynge.</L>
<L N="44">But &yogh;it ffor &thorn;e manere &middot; to make men blynde,</L>
<L>Somme argued a&yogh;ein rith &middot; &thorn;en a good while,</L>
<L>And said, "we beth seruantis &middot; and sallery ffongen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>sallere,</I> altered to <I>sallery,</I> with the gloss <I>wages.</I> The word meant is <I>salarye,</I> for which see C. 8. 39. <I>ffongen;</I> glossed by <I>taken.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And y-sent ffro &thorn;e shiris &middot; to shewe what hem greueth,</L>
<L N="48">And to parle ffor her prophete &middot; and passe no fferthere,<MILESTONE N="119" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>parle;</I> glossed by <I>speake.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And to graunte of her gold &middot; to &thorn;e grett wattis</L>
<L>By no manere wronge way &middot; but if werre were;</L>
<L>And if we ben ffals &middot; to &thorn;o us here ffyndyth,</L>
<L N="52">Euyll be we worthy &middot; to welden oure hire."
<PB REF="00001340.tif" N="502, C-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;an satte summe &middot; as siphre doth in awgrym,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noteth a place &middot; and no &thorn;ing availith;</L>
<L>And some had ysoupid &middot; with Symond ouere euen,</L>
<L N="56">And schewed ffor &thorn;e shire &middot; and here schew lost;</L>
<L>And somme were tituleris &middot; and to &thorn;e kyng wente,</L>
<L>And fformed him of foos &middot; &thorn;at good ffrendis weren,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bablid ffor &thorn;e best &middot; and no blame serued</L>
<L N="60">Of kynge ne conceyll &middot; ne of &thorn;e comunes no&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Ho so toke good kepe &middot; to &thorn;e <I>culorum.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">For <I>culorum,</I> see C. 4. 436.</NOTE></L>
<L>And somme slombrid and slepte &middot; and said but a lite;</L>
<L>And somme mafflid with &thorn;e mou&thorn; &middot; and nyst what &thorn;ey mente;</L>
<L N="64">And somme had hire &middot; and helde &thorn;er-with euere,</L>
<L>And wolde no fforther affoot &middot; ffor ffer of her maistris;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> That I ne my&yogh;te <I>ferther a-foot;</I> B. 5. 6.</NOTE></L>
<L>And some were so soleyne &middot; and sad of her wittis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er they come to &thorn;e clos &middot; acombrid &thorn;ey were,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at &thorn;ei &thorn;e conclucioun &thorn;an &middot; constrewe ne cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>No burne of &thorn;e benche &middot; of borowe no&thorn;er ellis,</L>
<L>So blynde and so ballid &middot; and bare was &thorn;e reson.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Cf.</I> And brynge forth <I>ballede resones;</I> C. 12. 38.</NOTE></L>
<L>And somme were so ffers &middot; at &thorn;e ffrist come,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at they bente on a bonet &middot; and bare a topte saile<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bonet; bouet</I> in Mr Wright's edition. It is the name of a small sail. See l. 81, below.</NOTE></L>
<L>Affor &thorn;e wynde ffresshely &middot; to make a good ffare.</L>
<L>&THORN;an lay &thorn;e lordis a-lee &middot; with laste and with charge,</L>
<L>And bare aboute &thorn;e barge &middot; and blamed &thorn;e maister,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aboute;</I> MS. <I>abou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at knewe not &thorn;e kynde cours &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e crafte longid,</L>
<L>And warned him wisely &middot; of &thorn;e wedir-side.</L>
<L>Thanne &thorn;e maste in &thorn;e myddis &middot; at &thorn;e mon&thorn;e ende,</L>
<L>Bowid ffor brestynge &middot; and brou&yogh;te hem to lond;</L>
<L N="80">ffor ne had &thorn;ei striked a strake &middot; and sterid hem &thorn;e better,</L>
<L>And abated a bonet &middot; or &thorn;e blast come,
<PB REF="00001341.tif" N="503, C-text"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey had be &thorn;rowe ouere &thorn;e borde &middot; backewarde ichonne.</L>
<L>And some were acombrid &middot; with &thorn;e conceill be-ffore,<MILESTONE N="119b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="84">And wiste well y-now &middot; how it sholde ende,</L>
<L>Or some of &thorn;e semble &middot; shulde repente.</L>
<L>Some helde with &thorn;e mo &middot; how it euere wente,</L>
<L>And somme dede rith so &middot; and wolld go no ffor&thorn;er.</L>
<L N="88">Some parled as perte &middot; as prouyd well after,</L>
<L>And clappid more ffor &thorn;e coyne &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng oweth hem<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oweth;</I> MS. <I>owen,</I> an obvious error for <I>oweth</I> or <I>owed;</I> the true <I>past</I> tense, however, would be <I>ou&yogh;te.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Thanne ffor comfforte of &thorn;e comyne &middot; &thorn;at her cost paied,</L>
<L>And were be-hote hansell &middot; if &thorn;ey helpe wold</L>
<L N="92">To be seruyd sekirly &middot; of &thorn;e same siluere.</L>
<L>And some dradde dukis &middot; and do-well ffor-soke;<NOTE PLACE="foot">The poem terminates abruptly with the eleventh line on fol. 119 <I>b</I>. The rest of the page is blank.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
