<PB REF="00001361.tif" N="523, C-text">
<HEAD>The Crowned King.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[THIS piece has been inserted because it is an early specimen of the several poems that have been written in imitation of Piers the Plowman. The first 27 lines were printed by Percy in his "Reliques;" but the <I>whole</I> poem is now printed for the first time. As it has no title, I have given it that of <I>The Crowned King,</I> because this expression occurs <I>four</I> times; see ll. 1, 35, 51, 141; note especially l. 35. Short as it is, we can decide with sufficient accuracy many points in connection with it. The general form of it, especially that part where the dream begins, is enough to shew that it is, as above-said, an imitation of Piers the Plowman; and this will appear more clearly if the passages mentioned in the foot-notes be examined. The language is somewhat simpler and later, and the author has caught the manner of his original but imperfectly, so that the result is, as a whole, weaker and milder. In this respect, it supplies a most useful contrast to the poem of "Richard the Redeless," in which the exact style and spirit of Piers the Plowman is perfectly maintained throughout. The happiest imitations are perhaps to be found in ll. 61&mdash;72, 81&mdash;83, 86&mdash;89, 111, 118, 124, 131, 132, and especially l. 134, which is perfect. Instead of <I>metels</I> (a dream) we find the later form <I>metyng.</I> In l. 116, the alliteration breaks down badly; the writer had no business to link <I>speche</I> with <I>small</I> (thus alliterating <I>sp</I> with <I>sm</I>), and then leave out the chief-letter. The unique copy here printed is to be found in MS. Douce 95, the writing being of the middle of the fifteenth century. The MS. contains several other pieces, and on leaf 12 the date 1439 is mentioned. If we accept the various indications of date afforded by the allusions in it&mdash;and we in fairness ought to do so, because otherwise the whole poem becomes meaningless&mdash;we may very easily determine all that is necessary to be known about it. It really amounts to a letter of advice addressed to a youthful yet not incompetent king, who can be no other than Henry V. Such a line as l. 77&mdash; Thi peres in parlement &middot; pull hem to-geders&mdash; is quite inapplicable to Henry VI., who succeeded to the throne as a mere infant, and would have been entirely superfluous if addressed to Henry IV.; whilst the language is too late for the first few years of Richard II., and the writing too early for Edward IV. As addressed to Henry V., however, the poem is at once intelligible, and has adequate reasons for existence. I have little hesitation in fixing the date of composition as being probably the month of June, 1415. The author says he had just been with some friends on 
<PB REF="00001362.tif" N="524, C-text"> Corpus Christi Eve, i. e. on the Wednesday after Trinity Sunday, which answered, in 1415, to the 29th of May. He plainly speaks of an imminent war, to be waged against a foreign country, in which there were castles to be won by adventurers (l. 97). This is an evident allusion to the coming cam|paign in France, and it is worthy of note that the expedition set sail from Southampton (cf. l. 20) in the month of August. Henry had declared for war some time before. Fabian gives June 18 as the date when Henry rode through London to go to Southampton, and Walsingham gives June 24 as the date when he was expected to arrive there. The "subsidie" mentioned in l. 36 is the very large grant which Henry had obtained (Nov. 19, 1414) of no less than two tenths and two fifteenths; for though no war was then declared, it was doubtless well understood that it was to come. The suggestion in ll. 95 and 96, that all prisoners should be for the benefit of their captors, is exactly parallel to the arrangement that "all prisoners were to belong to their captors," to which Lingard draws special attention, with a reference to Rymer, ix. 223&mdash;239, as having been made on this very occasion. The knowledge that the king was coming to Southampton would naturally suggest a poem of the present form to a poet resident there; and its brevity may have been intended to give it a better chance of attention. All who remember the story of Henry and Chief Justice Gascoigne will see the ap|plication of l. 53, and those following; whilst l. 75 well expresses the favour in which the young king was held. Neither are the exhortations (ll. 122&mdash;124) to a display of personal prowess out of place; for it was now twelve years since the battle of Shrewsbury (July 21, 1403), and there was little to shew that Henry would again display such bravery as he then exhibited. Further points I leave to the reader's consideration, with the remark that, when read in the light thus thrown upon it, the poem is not without interest, and very fairly expresses the public opinion of the time.]</P><P>[<I>Douce MS.</I> 95; <I>leaf</I> 4.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Crist, crowned kyng &middot; that on cros didest,</L>
<L>And art comfort of all care &middot; &thorn;ow kynd go out of cours,</L>
<L>With thi halwes in heuen &middot; heried mote thu be,</L>
<L N="4">And thy worshipfull werkes &middot; worshiped euere,</L>
<L>That suche sondry signes &middot; shewest vnto man,</L>
<L>In dremyng, in drecchyng &middot; &amp; in derk swevenes,</L>
<L>Wherwith that thei ben ware &middot; &amp; witterly knowen</L>
<L N="8">Of care and of comfort &middot; &thorn;at comyng is here-after!</L>
<L>This i sey be my-self &middot; (so saue me our lord!)</L>
<L>Be a metyng that y met &middot; in a morowe slepe,</L>
<L>Hevy &amp; hidows &middot; y hight you forsoth,</L>
<L N="12">And the most merveylous &middot; that y met euere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. prol. 11; C. 1. 9.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001363.tif" N="525, C-text"></L>
<L>And ye like to lere &middot; &amp; listen a while,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lere</I>] <I>a better spelling than</I> leer, <I>as in the</I> MS.; <I>see</I> l. 113.</NOTE></L>
<L>As y may in my mynde &middot; this metyng reherce,</L>
<L>Sekerly and shortly &middot; &thorn;e soth y shall you shewe</L>
<L N="16">Of this dredefull dreme &middot; deme as you likes!</L>
<L>Ones y me ordeyned &middot; as y haue ofte doon,</L>
<L>With frendes and felawes &middot; fremde men and other,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fremde men</I>] <I>written</I> frende men; <I>but</I> fremde <I>must be meant.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And caught me in a company &middot; on Corpus Christi even,</L>
<L N="20">Six other vij myle &middot; oute of Suthampton,</L>
<L>To take melodye and mirthes &middot; among my makes,</L>
<L>With redyng of romaunces &middot; and reuelyng among.</L>
<L>The dym of the derkenesse &middot; drowe into the west,</L>
<L N="24">And began for to spryng &middot; in the grey day;</L>
<L>Than lift y vp my lyddes &middot; &amp; loked in the sky,</L>
<L>And knewe by the kende cours &middot; hit clered in &thorn;e Est.</L>
<L>Blyve y busked me doun &middot; And to bed went,</L>
<L N="28">For to comfort my kynde &middot; And cacche a slepe.</L>
<L>Swythe y swyed in a sweem &middot; &thorn;at y swet after,</L>
<L>So my spirit in a spaas &middot; so sore was y-set.</L>
<L>Me thought that y houed &middot; an high on an hill<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an</I>] <I>the second stroke of the</I> n <I>is missing.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="32">And loked doun on a dale &middot; deppest of othre;</L>
<L>Ther y sawe in my sight &middot; a selcouthe peple,</L>
<L>The multitude was so moche &middot; it myght not be noum|bred.<NOTE PLACE="foot">31&mdash;34. Cf. B. prol. 13&mdash;18; C. 1. 14&mdash;20.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>noumbred</I>] written <I>noumbrerd.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Me thought y herd a crowned kyng &middot; of his comunes axe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. prol. 112; C. 1. 139.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">A soleyn subsidie &middot; to susteyne his werres,<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To be rered in the reaume &middot; as reson requyred</L>
<L>Of suche as were seemly &middot; to suffre the charge;</L>
<L>That they that rekened were riche &middot; be reson and skyle</L>
<L N="40">Shuld pay a parcell &middot; for here pouere neighbowres;
<PB REF="00001364.tif" N="526, C-text"></L>
<L>This ordenaunce he made &middot; in ease of his peple.</L>
<L>With that a Clerke kneled a-doun &middot; &amp; carped these wordes;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. prol. 123, 124; C. 1. 147, 148.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Liege lord, yif it you like &middot; to listen a while,</L>
<L N="44">Sum sawes of Salomon &middot; y shall you shew sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. 3. 93, 94; C. 4. 121, 122.</NOTE></L>
<L>Besechyng you of your souerainte &middot; that y myght be suffred</L>
<L>To shewe you my sentence &middot; in singuler noumbre;</L>
<L>To peynte it with pluralitee &middot; my prose wolde faile,</L>
<L N="48">To pike a thonke with plesaunce &middot; my profit were but simple."</L>
<L>Than the kyng of his curtesie &middot; comaunded hym to ryse,</L>
<L>To stonde and sey what hym semed &middot; and knele no lenger.</L>
<L>Than he seid, "sir crowned kyng &middot; thou knowest well &thorn;y-self,</L>
<L N="52">Thi-self hast lyfe, lyme &middot; and lawes for to keep.</L>
<L>Yif &thorn;ou be chief Iustice &middot; Iustifie the truthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. 4. 136&mdash;142; C. 5. 133&mdash;139.</NOTE></L>
<L>And rule the be resoun &middot; and vp-right sitte;</L>
<L>For that is a poynt principall &middot; preve it who so will,</L>
<L N="56">To be dred for thy domes &middot; and dowted for thy myght.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and dowted</I>] <I>written</I> an dowte.</NOTE></L>
<L>For ther is neither lered ne lewed &middot; &thorn;at lyveth vpon erthe,</L>
<L>That wyssheth after worshipe &middot; his wit is full feble,</L>
<L>But yif he wite be his werkes &middot; he hath well deserued,</L>
<L>And of his well doyng his dedes &middot; to deme the same.</L>
<L N="61">The loue of thi liegemen &middot; that to thi lawe are bounde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. 4. 148; C. 5. 145. <I>liegemen</I>] <I>written</I> liegmen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Take hit for a tresour &middot; of hem that are true,</L>
<L>That may the more availl &middot; in a myle-wey
<PB REF="00001365.tif" N="527, C-text"></L>
<L N="64">Thanne moche of thy mukke &middot; &thorn;at manhode loue&thorn; neuere.</L>
<L>The playnt of the pouere peple &middot; put &thorn;ou not behynde,</L>
<L>For they swope and swete &middot; and swynke for thy fode;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>they</I>] <I>miswritten</I> the; <I>but see</I> l. 67.</NOTE></L>
<L>Moche worshipe they wynne the &middot; in this worlde riche,</L>
<L N="68">Of thy gliteryng gold &middot; and of thy gay wedes,</L>
<L>Thy proude pelure and palle &middot; with preciouse stones,</L>
<L>Grete Castels and stronge &middot; and styff-walled Townes;<MILESTONE N="5" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And yit the most preciouse plente &middot; &thorn;at apparaill passeth,</L>
<L N="72">Thi pouere peple with here ploughe &middot; pike oute of the erthe.</L>
<L>And they yeve here goodes &middot; to gouerne hem euen;</L>
<L>And yit the peple ben well a-paid &middot; to plese &thorn;e Allone,</L>
<L>Suche loue is on the leid &middot; of lordes and of lower,</L>
<L N="76">And grete is thi grace &middot; that god hath the lent.</L>
<L>Thi peres in parlement &middot; pull hem to-geders,</L>
<L>Worche after wysdom &middot; &amp; worshipe will folowe.</L>
<L>For as a lord is a lord &middot; and ledeth the peple,</L>
<L N="80">So shuld prowesse in &thorn;i persone &middot; passe o&thorn;er mennes wittes;</L>
<L>The wittyest and wylyest &middot; and worthiest in Armes,</L>
<L>All is but wast wele &middot; and he wronge vse,</L>
<L>And vnsemely for a souerain &middot; (so saue me our lord!)</L>
<L N="84">And hevy for his name &middot; that hyndren will ever.</L>
<L>Sir, &thorn;ou most be worldly wys &middot; &amp; ware &thorn;e be-tymes,</L>
<L>And kepe the fro glosyng &middot; of gylers mowthes,</L>
<L>That speken to the spiritually &middot; with spiritual tonges,</L>
<L>Momelyn with here mouthes moche &middot; and malys in hert,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. 5. 21; C. 6. 124.</NOTE></L>
<L N="89">And of a mys menyng &middot; maketh a faire tale;</L>
<L>Vnder flateryng and fair speche &middot; falsehede foloweth,</L>
<L>And yif they myght with here moustres &middot; to marre &thorn;e for euere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>moustres</I>] moustres <I>or</I> monstres <I>in the</I> MS; <I>see</I> C. 7. 260.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00001366.tif" N="528, C-text"></L>
<L N="92">With disceit of here derknesse; &middot; &thorn;e deuell hem a|drenche!</L>
<L>Be kende to thi clergi &middot; and comfort &thorn;e pouere;</L>
<L>Cherissh thy champyons &middot; and chief men of Armes;</L>
<L>And suche as presoners mowe pike &middot; with poyntes of werre,</L>
<L N="96">Lete hem welde that they wynne &middot; &amp; wor&thorn;yly hem &thorn;onke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>welde</I>] <I>miswritten</I> wilde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And suche as castels mowe cacche &middot; or eny clos tounes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. C. 4. 251&mdash;253.</NOTE></L>
<L>Geve hem as gladly &middot; than shalt &thorn;ou gete hertes.</L>
<L>For god in his gospell &middot; asketh no thyng elles</L>
<L N="100">But oonly loue for love &middot; and let hym be levest.</L>
<L>Also he that is stronge &middot; strokes for to dele,</L>
<L>Make hym thy marchall &middot; and maner his maistre,</L>
<L>That for his doughtynesse &middot; men mowe hym drede,</L>
<L>And for his wysdom and witte &middot; the better to be ware.<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="105">Knyghtes of thy counseill &middot; connyng in armes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>connyng</I>] <I>miswritten</I> comyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>That been seker at asay &middot; and sober to thy frendes,</L>
<L>Suche thou shuldest comfort &middot; be cours of thy kende,</L>
<L N="108">That lede here lyves &middot; in labour for thy loue.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou haue suche a man &middot; that loueth not to lye,</L>
<L>A faithfull Philosofre &middot; &thorn;at flater woll never;</L>
<L>For he that fareth as a faane &middot; folowyng &thorn;y wille,</L>
<L N="112">Worche &thorn;ou well or woo &middot; he woll &thorn;e not amende.</L>
<L>Lere lettrewre in &thorn;y youthe &middot; as a lord befalleth,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ou to parlement shall passe &middot; &thorn;ere lordes shull pere;</L>
<L>For to her of thy wysdom &middot; &thorn;ey woll awayte after,</L>
<L N="116">And though her speche be but small &middot; &thorn;e more be here &thorn;oughtes.</L>
<L>For yif &thorn;ou haue no science &middot; to shewe of thy-self,</L>
<L>But as a Brokour to go Borowe &middot; pore mennes wittes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Brokour</I>] <I>miswritten</I> Brogour; <I>see</I> B. 2. 65.</NOTE></L>
<L>That were most myscheef &middot; &thorn;at myght a lord befalle,
<PB REF="00001367.tif" N="529, C-text"></L>
<L N="120">Ther as wyse men haue wrapped &middot; her wittes to|gidre.</L>
<L>Sir, they it come to &thorn;e of kynde &middot; a kyng to be called,</L>
<L>Yit must &thorn;ou knowe of corage &middot; what knyghthood befalle&thorn;;</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at Armes shall haunte &middot; in you&thorn;e he must begynne,</L>
<L N="124">Of all Artes vnder heven &middot; vse is a maistre.</L>
<L>Sir, more-ouere be not gredy &middot; gyftes to grype;</L>
<L>Rather &thorn;ou shalt yeve hem &middot; &thorn;at fele hem agreved:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. 3. 208&mdash;211; C. 4. 266&mdash;269.</NOTE></L>
<L>So shall thy hawtesse &middot; highlich be honoured,</L>
<L N="128">And prudence in thy principaltee &middot; y-preised for euere,</L>
<L>For an ensample y shall you shewe &middot; that soth is knowe.</L>
<L>A kyng shuld not of curtesie &middot; couetouse be holde;</L>
<L>For there as couetyse is knowe &middot; in A kynges brest,</L>
<L N="132">Ther is corage out of kende &middot; when mukke is his maistre.</L>
<L>The condicion of a kyng &middot; shuld comfort his peple;</L>
<L>For suche laykes ben to love &middot; &thorn;ere leedes laghen alle.</L>
<L>My liege lord, of this mater &middot; y meve you no more,</L>
<L>But euere in your mynde &middot; haue hym &thorn;at you made;</L>
<L N="137">And taketh a siker ensample &middot; &thorn;at crist hym-self sheweth,</L>
<L>Of all the seyntes in heven &middot; that for hym deth suffred;<MILESTONE N="6" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For his loue thei were so large &middot; her lyves they lost,</L>
<L N="140">And for loue of that lord &middot; a-loft now they dwelle</L>
<L>With that crowned kyng &middot; that on cros dyed;</L>
<L>Ther crist in his kyngdom &middot; comfort vs euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cf. B. prol. 105; C. 1. 133.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of his high grace &middot; graunte vnto vs alle</L>
<L N="144">Prosperite and pees; &middot; pursue we therafter!"</L>
<TRAILER><I>Explicit.</I></TRAILER>
</LG>
